INSERT INTO `paper` VALUES (10,'IJSFM#10',6,'Basic Concepts and Physical Relationships of Fluid Motion','(flow patterns  velocity vectors, streamlines, pathlines, streaklines -, local and convective acceleration, relative motion, continuity relationship, vorticity, circulation, rotational and irrotational flow, flow net)','flow patterns, velocity vectors','paper.docx','2013-07-30 16:37:35','1','submitted','0','36','55','','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(11,'IJORO#11',4,'Integrated Inventory Model of a Differential Items Sold form Two Shops under Single Management with Shortages','In this paper, integrated models have been developed for both non-defective and defective units purchased in a lot and selling separately at two different shops under a single management. In primary shop, non-defective units were sold with a profit. And the defective units, which are continuously transferred to the adjacent secondary shop, were sold after some re-work or repair at a reduced price even incurring a loss. Here, shortages are allowed in both shops. It is also assumed that the rate of replenishment of units for the primary shop is infinite. In the secondary shop, the defective units are continuously transferred from the primary shop with variable rates.\r\n','Integrated models, shortages and replenishment','Shalley Gupta.docx','2020-11-04 07:08:26','79','published','0','32','48','','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(12,'ITAS#12',2,'Eventually Stabilization of Impulsive Functional Differential Equations by using piecewise continuous Lyapunov functions','In this paper, by using piecewise continuous Lyapunov functions, criteria of eventual stability for system of impulsive functional differential equations is investigated. The sufficient conditions that are obtained significantly depend on the moments of impulses.An example is provided to illustrate the effectiveness and the advantages of the results obtained.\r\n','Impulsive functional differential equations; Eventual stability; Lyapunov functions.','evntual stability.pdf','2013-09-17 13:28:08','272','submitted','0','35','56','','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(14,'IJEAS#13',7,'Maternal Employment and Academic Achievement of Adolescent Students','The main purpose of the present investigation was to study the academic achievement of adolescent students of working and non-working mothers. Further the study compared assigned groups (on the basis of gender & maternal status) of adolescent students of working and non-working mothers on the measures of academic achievement. The sample of the study consisted of 100 higher secondary school adolescents (25 male students working mothers, 25 female students of working mothers, 25 male students of non-working mothers & 25 female students of non-working mothers) of the age group 16 to 18 years  belonging to different localities selected randomly from different educational institutions of district Pulwama, Jammu & Kashmir. Data was collected by using Personal Information Sheet developed by the researcher to elicit information regarding the subjects age, sex, family type, single parent or both parent, mother whether working or non-working, kind of work, number of working hours, educated/uneducated etc. Marks obtained in the last qualifying examination served as an index of academic achievement. The data so collected was analyzed statistically by employing Z score, mean, SD and t-test. The findings of the study revealed (i) no significant difference in academic achievement between adolescent students of working and non-working mothers. (ii) Female students of working mothers possess higher academic achievement than other three groups (male students of working mothers, male students o','Maternal Employment, Academic Achievement, Adolescent Students','Maternal Employment and Academic Achievement of Adolescent Students.docx','2013-10-09 08:27:43','317','submitted','0','27','42','','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(15,'IJSFM#15',6,'Double Diffusive Convection in a Layer of Maxwell Visco- Elastic  Fluid in Porous Medium with Cross Diffusion Effects','Double Diffusive convection in a horizontal layer of Maxwell visco- elastic  fluid in porous medium in the presence of temperture gradient (Soret effects) and concentration gradient (Dufour effects) is investigated. For the porous medium Darcy model is considered. A linear stability analysis based upon normal mode analysis is used to find solution of the fluid layer confined between two free-free boundaries. The stability criterion for stationary and oscillatory convection have been derived and graphs have been plotted to study the  effects of the Dufour parameter, Soret parameter on stationary convection. ','Maxwell visco-elastic fluid, Dufour parameter, Soret parameter, Rayleigh number','RCGC.doc','2013-12-17 12:49:37','368','submitted','0','36','55','','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(16,'ITHSS#16',3,'A STUDY ON SOCIO- ECONOMIC AND ENVIRONMENTAL CAUSES OF MENTAL RETARDATION','Mental retardation (MR) is a generalized disorder appearing before adulthood, characterized by significantly impaired cognitive functioning and deficits in two or more adaptive behavior. It has historically been defined as an Intelligence Quotient score under 70. Once focused almost entirely on cognition, the definition now includes both a component relating to mental functioning and one relating to individuals\' functional skills in their environment. As a result, a person with a Below-Average Intelligence Quotient (BAIQ) may not be considered mentally retarded. Syndromic mental retardation is intellectual deficits associated with other medical and behavioral signs and symptoms. Non-syndrome mental retardation refers to intellectual deficits that appear without other abnormalities.\r\nThe study has been undertaken at government Doon Hospital in Dehradun and it the psychology clinic running in room no 56 of the hospital. Research method chosen for this study was a interview method  and home visits. The data was collected for 50 patients. The patients are between the age group of 3 to 25 yrs have been included in the study. Among them are the patients who came to the clinic for  IQ assessment. \r\nThe study said that 54% of the parents in the hills having special need children are from the low income group. The data reveals that 70% of the parents are not aware of the special schools and doctor for the special need children. They do not consult any doctor and wanted to hide the cas','Mental Retardation, Socio-economic, Post-natal, Awareness and Immunization','persons with disability.docx','2014-01-13 06:48:02','397','submitted','0','28','46','','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(17,'IJORO#17',4,'Economic Buffer Capacity in Designing Manufacturing Production Lines','The analysis and design of production lines is one of the oldest problems in manufacturing.  The major problem that the designer faces in a tandem production line is what should be the size of buffer and where it should be placed within the line. In literature it is referred the Buffer Allocation Problem (BAP). This paper focuses on BAP in manufacturing line consisting of two workstation separated by finite buffer space.  Processing times of workstations are exponentially distributed and arrivals are considered as Poisson. Even though problem looks trivial it presents major complexity due to the fact that variable buffer size affects probability states and also the number of equations to be solved at steady state. This makes it almost impossible to generate close form solution for buffer size. Thus procedure to find optimal buffer size is developed as alternate approach. Use of computer programs for applying this procedure to real life problems is recommended. Developed procedure finds application in design of production line manufacturing sector and with some modification can also be applied for service industry problems.','Optimization, Buffer size, M/M/1/k system and Blocking probabilities','Buffer Paper_IJORO submission.pdf','2020-11-04 07:07:22','533','accepted','0','39','61','','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(18,'IJEAS#18',7,'A STUDY OF ATTITUDE TOWARDS TEACHING PROFESSION OF B.ED. AND SPECIAL B.T.C. PROSPECTIVE TEACHERS','The present study was undertaken to assess and compare the attitude towards teaching profession of B.Ed. and Special B.T.C. prospective teachers. A sample of 400 B.Ed. prospective teachers and 200 Special B.T.C. prospective teachers was drawn by using stratified random-sampling technique from 3 district of Rohilkhand regions. When attitude towards teaching profession of prospective teachers was considered as the dependent variable, the variable like gender, academic background and economic status were considered as independent variable. Attitude towards teaching profession was assessed by Teacher Attitude Inventory developed and standardized by S. P. Ahluwalia (2006). Mean, SD, and t-test were used for the analysis of the data. Research findings revealed that there is no significant difference in the attitude of B.Ed. and Special B.T.C. prospective teachers towards teaching profession on controlling their gender/ economic status or total. But on controlling academic background, B.Ed. prospective teacher of science stream had show better attitude towards teaching profession than their respective counterparts. No meaningful difference was found between the B.Ed. and Special B.T.C. prospective teacher of arts and commerce stream.','ATTITUDE TOWARDS TEACHING PROFESSION,B.ED.,SPECIAL B.T.C.,PROSPECTIVE TEACHERS','A STUDY OF ATTITUDE TOWARDS TEACHING PROFESSION OF B.odt','2014-03-21 15:17:11','579','submitted','0','27','42','','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(19,'IJEAS#19',7,'A STUDY OF ATTITUDE TOWARDS TEACHING PROFESSION OF B.ED. AND SPECIAL B.T.C. PROSPECTIVE TEACHERS','The present study was undertaken to assess and compare the attitude towards teaching profession of B.Ed. and Special B.T.C. prospective teachers. A sample of 400 B.Ed. prospective teachers and 200 Special B.T.C. prospective teachers was drawn by using stratified random-sampling technique from 3 district of Rohilkhand regions. When attitude towards teaching profession of prospective teachers was considered as the dependent variable, the variable like gender, academic background and economic status were considered as independent variable. Attitude towards teaching profession was assessed by Teacher Attitude Inventory developed and standardized by S. P. Ahluwalia (2006). Mean, SD, and t-test were used for the analysis of the data. Research findings revealed that there is no significant difference in the attitude of B.Ed. and Special B.T.C. prospective teachers towards teaching profession on controlling their gender/ economic status or total. But on controlling academic background, B.Ed. prospective teacher of science stream had show better attitude towards teaching profession than their respective counterparts. No meaningful difference was found between the B.Ed. and Special B.T.C. prospective teacher of arts and commerce stream.','ATTITUDE TOWARDS TEACHING PROFESSION,B.ED.,SPECIAL B.T.C.,PROSPECTIVE TEACHERS','A STUDY OF ATTITUDE TOWARDS TEACHING PROFESSION OF B.odt','2014-03-21 15:17:13','579','submitted','0','27','42','','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(20,'IJEAS#20',7,'A STUDY OF ATTITUDE TOWARDS TEACHING PROFESSION OF B.ED. AND SPECIAL B.T.C. PROSPECTIVE TEACHERS','The present study was undertaken to assess and compare the attitude towards teaching profession of B.Ed. and Special B.T.C. prospective teachers. A sample of 400 B.Ed. prospective teachers and 200 Special B.T.C. prospective teachers was drawn by using stratified random-sampling technique from 3 district of Rohilkhand regions. When attitude towards teaching profession of prospective teachers was considered as the dependent variable, the variable like gender, academic background and economic status were considered as independent variable. Attitude towards teaching profession was assessed by Teacher Attitude Inventory developed and standardized by S. P. Ahluwalia (2006). Mean, SD, and t-test were used for the analysis of the data. Research findings revealed that there is no significant difference in the attitude of B.Ed. and Special B.T.C. prospective teachers towards teaching profession on controlling their gender/ economic status or total. But on controlling academic background, B.Ed. prospective teacher of science stream had show better attitude towards teaching profession than their respective counterparts. No meaningful difference was found between the B.Ed. and Special B.T.C. prospective teacher of arts and commerce stream.','ATTITUDE TOWARDS TEACHING PROFESSION,B.ED.,SPECIAL B.T.C.,PROSPECTIVE TEACHERS','A STUDY OF ATTITUDE TOWARDS TEACHING PROFESSION OF B.odt','2014-03-21 15:17:14','579','submitted','0','27','42','','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(21,'IJSFM#21',6,'RADIATION AND MASS TRANSFER EFFECTS ON NONLINEAR MHD BOUNDARY LAYER FLOW OF LIQUID METAL OVER A POROUS STRETCHING SURFACE EMBEDDED IN POROUS MEDIUM WITH HEAT GENERATION','The present paper analyzes the effects of mass transfer on steady nonlinear MHD boundary layer flow of a viscous incompressible fluid over a nonlinear porous stretching surface embedded in a porous medium in presence of nonlinear radiation and heat generation. The liquid metal is assumed to be gray, emitting, and absorbing but non-scattering medium. Governing nonlinear partial differential equations are transformed to nonlinear ordinary differential equations by utilizing suitable similarity transformation. The resulting nonlinear ordinary differential equations are solved numerically using Runge-Kutta fourth order method along with shooting technique. Comparison with previously published work is obtained and good agreement is found. The effects of various governing parameters on the liquid metal fluid dimensionless velocity, dimensionless temperature, dimensionless concentration, skin-friction coefficient, Nusselt number and Sherwood number are discussed with the aid of graphs.','MHD; boundary layer flow; porous medium; radiation; heat generation.','Ibrahim(AACS).docx','2014-04-07 17:30:58','606','submitted','0','36','55','','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(22,'ITAS#22',2,'cxbz','cbxzczxx','cxbzcxzf','aacs.sql','2020-07-23 10:54:42','1','submitted','0','59','112','','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(23,'ITMSC#3',1,'test title','title test','asd,bfg','try.txt','2025-01-18 18:30:00','nautiyalshivansh99@gmail.com','submitted','0','','','[197]','[]','[197]',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(24,'ITMSC#4',1,'Inventory models','This paper provide an comprehensive study in the  field of Inventory control','inventory demand','paper.docx','2025-01-18 18:30:00','singhdipti113@gmail.com','submitted','0','','','[201]','[]','[30]',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(25,'IJSE#5',10,'Warehouse inventory model for perishable items with hybrid demand and trade credit','The retailer frequently leases an additional warehouse to avoid the stockout situation. The mathematical framework for multiple warehouses handling decaying products is presented in this paper. The retailer offers discounts on less-effective products when product deterioration begins. As product promotion and offering price breaks can significantly boost demand, the analysis considers the relationship between advertising and product pricing. The study also discusses the idea of a trade credit policy, where the supplier grants the retailer a specified credit period for settling the account. The occurrence of global optimality under the ideal credit period, warehouse capacity, and replenishment time are demonstrated using a classical optimization approach. The study aims to minimize the total cost in terms of the above decision variables. Numerical examples and sensitivity analyses for key factors are provided to explore the impact on the systems optimal total cost, along with managerial insights.','Trade credit policy; Deterioration; Discount; Hybrid demand; Permissible delay','Process integration_PIOS.docx','2025-01-18 18:30:00','abhinavgoel4maths@gmail.com','submitted','0','','','[202]','[30]','[191]',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(26,'',10,'hedqdyuqhbvhvcyf','cbhgvcvhcvhjvhcgvsghvchvdshgcvhvchdsvjcvhjdsvchvdshgcvdshgvchdsvchvdshcvhgdvcghdsvhgcvdhsgvchgdvghcjvdshjcvhjsv','cbdhjscbkj, cgcwvcjh, wwjhcducb , bcddb cw','papers/user_206/user_206_paper_26_20260215_133521.pdf','2026-02-15 13:35:21','206','submitted','0','','','shivsaini75006@gmail.com','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(27,'',10,'hedqdyuqhbvhvcyf','cbhgvcvhcvhjvhcgvsghvchvdshgcvhvchdsvjcvhjdsvchvdshgcvdshgvchdsvchvdshcvhgdvcghdsvhgcvdhsgvchgdvghcjvdshjcvhjsv','cbdhjscbkj, cgcwvcjh, wwjhcducb , bcddb cw','papers/user_206/user_206_paper_27_20260215_133539.pdf','2026-02-15 13:35:39','206','submitted','0','','','shivsaini75006@gmail.com','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(28,'',10,'hedqdyuqhbvhvcyf','cbhgvcvhcvhjvhcgvsghvchvdshgcvhvchdsvjcvhjdsvchvdshgcvdshgvchdsvchvdshcvhgdvcghdsvhgcvdhsgvchgdvghcjvdshjcvhjsv','cbdhjscbkj, cgcwvcjh, wwjhcducb , bcddb cw','papers/user_206/user_206_paper_28_20260215_133649.pdf','2026-02-15 13:36:49','206','submitted','0','','','shivsaini75006@gmail.com','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(29,'',9,'bcdvchdvhcvdwywcvwvcjv','bcjdhvchjavjcbsbcnsb ncbsjvcjsbcjjcjcjsvjcvjhsvcjhdsvcjvdjcvjdkhcsavcjhacjasbckjbshjcbjhbcjhbcjhvcjbacvdhgcvh','cbshcbja','papers/user_206/user_206_paper_29_20260215_133738.docx','2026-02-15 13:37:38','206','submitted','0','','','shivsaini75006@gmail.com','','',1,0,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,0),(30,'',11,'bdqeguewbjfhcbewjhbcuyewfjcvbewhjc','fbewhvbewjfhcbewjhcbewciubewjhcbejwhbcjkhehbcuyewgwcbewkucvjhewchjewvcgjvwejcbcgewubcjewbcuevcuewcjbwecjhvwehc','behwcuegwbucbejw','papers/user_206/user_206_paper_30_20260215_133957.docx','2026-02-15 13:39:57','206','submitted','0','','','shivsaini75006@gmai