onstration of the Mon utility, we construct PARO (Pseudo Scalable Adaptive Randomized Overlay), a scalable and adaptive application-layer overlay tree, this overlay tree provides the deliverable macros for binding of processes to processors and a single process may receive cycles from other close relatives before eventually terminating . PARO uses Mon state information to locate appropriate peers for meeting application-specific delay and bandwidth targets and to dynamically adapt to changing network conditions, In case of application specific delays factors like minimum turn around time generally restrict the computing power of peers, due to the adaptive nature of PARO, this restriction trim down. A large-scale evaluation of N overlay nodes participating in an emulated 2N','','-','Monika , M. P. Singh and A. K. Pal','269-289','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','4','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(62,'Synthesis And Structural Studies Of Nickel(Ii) Complexes With 1, 5-Bis(4-Methyl,Benzimidazol-2-Yl)-3-Thiapentane (Bmbes) Ligand','Nickel (II) complexes with formula [Ni(BMBES)X2] have been synthesized, characterized and its geometry was found to be tetragonal on the basis of voltametric studies which shows following three transition ranges : 7000-13000 cm-1, 11000-20000 cm-1 and 17000-29000 cm-1, which are indicative of six coordinated tetragonal complexes in solution. The parameters varies as . 1HNMR contact shifted resonance lies in the range of  19.0 to + 55.0 ppm, typical of high spin Ni (II) complexes and do not show any significant dependence on . The sign of the contact shifts is indicative of a dominant sigma spin the delocalization mechanism. The same is confirmed by the shift of C13 NMR data lies in the range of +70  185 ppm with respect to TMS. No doubling of peaks is observed in NMR spectra implying a mirror plane of C2 axis of symmetry in the complexes. Ni complexes give a medium peaks in IR spectra at 1615 C=N stretching indicating the metal ligand bond.','','-','Meghraj Singh and K. B. Kumar','291-300','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','4','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(63,'Optimum Ordering Interval for Deteriorating Items with Price and Time Dependent Demand Rate','This study presents a deterministic inventory model for deteriorating products under the condition of instantaneous replenishment. The rate of deterioration is assumed to be a constant fraction of on hand inventory and demand is a function of selling price and decreases exponentially with time. It is shown that the developed model can be related to Cohen Model and Standard model without deterioration. A numerical example demonstrates the effectiveness of the developed model.','','-','Anil Kumar Sharma, Naresh Kumar, Neelam Kumari Goel and Suresh Lal Aggarwal','301-306','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(64,'A Mathematical Model for Dispersion of Air Pollutant Concentration Around a Hill and its Comparison with Gaussian Model','A mathematical model for dispersion of air pollutant concentration around a single three dimensional hill for stable stratified and potential flow is presented. The two-dimensional advection-diffusion equation with constant eddy diffusivity is solved analytically. The results obtained from this model are compared with the results obtained from available Gaussian model and found that Gaussian model cannot be used for prediction of pollutant concentration in the hill and complex regions.','','-','Jai Pal, Deepika Thapliyal and V.K. Katiyar','307-316','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(65,'Statistical Estimation of Cost and Return Analysis from Pond and Field Crop Enterprises','The field investigation was carried out from three villages in Ajmer district, (Rajasthan). Fifty farmers were selected at random who were engaged in both the pond and field crop enterprises. The data were collected through specially constructed schedule and a statistical analysis was done. The average land and pond size of the farmers were 1.5 hectare and 0.38 hectare respectively. The average cost and return per hectare from fish production were Rs. 75000 and Rs. 87500 respectively and from field crop production were Rs. 77375 and Rs. 89000 respectively. The return from pond and field enterprises was positively and significantly correlated with the size of pond and operated agricultural land. The result of two large sample mean test was found highly significant which indicates that the pond crop cultivation is more profitable than that of field crop cultivation.','','-','Sabiha Khan and Sanjay Jain','317-322','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(66,'Symmetric Duality for Multiobjective Programming Using Second Order  Convexity','This paper deals with a pair of second order Mond-Weir type symmetric dual. Various duality results are established under the assumptions of a new class of functions namely second order -convex functions. This new class of functions is a generalization of second order -convex functions.','','-','Soniya Gupta and Hari Kishan','323-332','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(67,'A Survey of Secure Routing Protocols for Mobile Ad Hoc Network','Mobile Ad hoc Network is the future of existing networks. It is a collection of wireless nodes that can exchange information dynamically among them without using a fixed base station or a wired backbone network. Routing protocols in MANET face many challenges like high degree of mobility, limited power, limited computation and limited memory resources. In addition to this security is the major concern and a great challenge to the secure routing protocols developers. This paper presents a review of existing secure routing protocols designed for mobile ad hoc network and also comparison for various parameters. This paper also reviews a short literature study on various types of security attacks and routing security schemes that have been proposed to prevent and detect these attacks.','','-','S. S. Tyagi and R. K. Chauhan','333-340','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(68,'Knowledge Management Approach for Managing IT Product Development - A Conceptual Framework','Knowledge Management is increasing day by day being used as a tool to accomplish strategic objectives like decreasing product development times to share best practices and even to manage the it product development. Systems that are networked across organizational boundaries can improve the knowledge flow to meet the organizational goals. Managing information technology product development is information processing procedure i.e. good Knowledge Management arrangement. Knowledge management approach has become essential as it assists to decrease the uncertainty during the course of product development. This paper focuses on the roll of knowledge management system to manage information technology projects. It also provides a concrete link between knowledge management and knowledge management systems to IT product development process. The use of managerial knowledge and past experiences of the existences enterprises (knowledge management) to build the new products will keep the enterprise young, growing and successful. In this research, and attempt has been made to access the importance of knowledge management strategy to enhance the competitiveness.','','-','Ashwani Kumar','341-347','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(69,'Iridoids from Aerial Parts of Ixora arborea','Ixora arborea is a small, much branched evergreen tree or shrub found throughout the greater part of India.The fruits and roots of Ixora arborea are used by Santals as an antidote for coloured urine. The flowers are pounded in milk and given for relieving whooping cough. A decoction of bark is used for anaemia and general debility. Chemical analysis of aerial parts of Ixora arborea afforded three Iridoids.The Iridoids were identified as sweroside, logonin and 8-Acetylharpagide.The structure of these compounds were determined by chemical method and extensive use of 1D and 2D-NMR spectroscopy','','-','R.K. Bachheti, D.P. Pandey and Archana Joshi','349-358','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(70,'A Note on an Inventory Model for Deteriorating Items with Time-Dependent Deterioration Rate, Quadratic Demand Rate, Unit Production Cost and Shortage','In this paper, an order level inventory unit production system for deteriorating items with a quadratic demand is developed. It is assumed that shortages in inventory are permitted and are completely backlogged. The finite production rate is proportional to the time dependent demand rate and deterioration rate is time proportional. The unit production cost is taken to be inversely related to the demand rate. Sensitivity of the decision variable to changes in the parameter values is examined and numerical example is presented to illustrate the model is developed.','','-','N.K. Sahoo, C.K. Sahoo and S.K. Sahoo','359-369','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(71,'Two Phase Sampling Difference Cum Ratio Type Estimators in the Presence of Non Response','The proposed two phase sampling difference cum ratio type estimators for population mean in the presence of non-response are found to be more efficient than corresponding two phase sampling ratio type estimators. The empirical study shows that in the case of fixed cost, the proposed estimators are more efficient with respect to the corresponding estimators and also has minimum cost in comparison to the other relevant estimators.','','-','Sanjay Kumar','371-378','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(72,'The Transport of Oxygen during Pranayama in the Respiratory Tree by the Alveolar Amplitude Response Technique using the Numerical Method','Theoretical data for the alveolar amplitude response technique for assessing lung function was simulated using single path model. A lumped parameter model of a human pulmonary acinus is derived using results from gas mixing simulations in an anatomically based asymmetric multi-branching model of the acinus coupled to a symmetric conducting airway model. The lumped parameter model applies a flux boundary condition at the end of a transitional bronchiole during inspiration to enable realistic concentration changes at this position, during expiration inspiratory parameters are used to predict concentrations at the end of the associated transitional bronchial. Previously published parameter techniques which are used to estimate dead-space volume alveolar volume and cardiac output. In the present study we solve the convection-diffusion equation for respiration (inspiration-expiration) numerically by finite difference scheme with initial and boundary condition and compared with the experimental results.','','-','Sarita, V. K. Katiyar and P Pradhan','379-390','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(73,'Optimal Ordering Policies with Pareto Life Time, Permissible Delay in Payments and Stochastic Backorder','An inventory problem with the assumption that the lifetime of the commodity is random and follows a generalized Pareto distribution. Shortages are allowed with partial backlogging and backlogging rate is a random variable. Holding cost is dependent of purchasing cost. We considered this model for a retailer, when the supplier offers a permissible delay in payments. The purpose of this study is to determine an optimal ordering policy for maximizing the expected total profit for the retailer.','','-','S.R. Singh, Surbhi Singhal and P.K. Gupta','391-400','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(74,'On the Cutoff Characteristics of a Metallic Sheath Helix Cladded Chirofiber','An analytical study of an optical fiber having a chiral core and surrounded by a dielectric medium with a metallic sheath helix at the core cladding boundary is presented. The characteristic equation for the system is derived and the cutoff conditions for the various modes have been solved analytically. Interestingly the pitch angle of the metallic sheath helix has no effect on the cutoff behaviour of various modes of the fiber.','','-','Sushil Kumar, U.N. Singh and Kh. S. Singh','401-409','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(75,'The Satellite Communication : A Survey on Routing & Performance Analysis Techniques','This Paper takes up the study of Routing & Performance Analysis (RPA) Techniques in Satellite Communications with special reference to Low Earth orbit System, here we will focus on the blocking Probability & New Blocking Probability of on going calls during handover, which Results in most preferable Techniques.','','-','V. K. Sharma and Ankur Gupta','411-423','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(76,'Application of Variational Method in a Theory of Decelerated Steady Motions of a Wide Class of Non-Newtonian Fluids','It is shown in the work that the special analytical form of relations describing the experimental diagram of stress-deformation rate should be chosen only for the sake of convenience of experimental data treatment, because the geometrically similar diagrams yield close values of the flow properties under study. The variational approach used has some advantage in studying viscoplastic media. The description of decelerated steady motions of a wide class of non-Newtonian fluids, considered as dissipative continua, is discussed in this paper.','','-','Prabir Kumar Shrivastava, Praveen Kumar, Deepika Sonal and Upendra Sah','425-431','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(77,'Effects of Suction in Mixed Convection Stagnation Point Flow Towards a Stretching Sheet in the Presence of Viscous Dissipation, Radiation and Chemical Reaction','The study presents the effect of suction, injection and chemical reaction on steady two dimensional stagnation point mixed convection boundary layer flow of an incompressible viscous fluid towards a vertical stretching sheet in the presence of viscous dissipation and radiation. The stretching velocity, surface temperature and surface concentration vary linearly with the distance from stagnation point. These equations of conservation of mass, momentum and energy, which govern the flow and heat transfer, are transformed into set of non- dimensional ordinary differential equations using similarity transformation. These equations have been solved by Runge-Kutta method with shooting technique. The effects of various physical parameters on the boundary layer velocity, temperature and concentration profiles have been discussed in detail for both the cases of assisting and opposing flows. The values of skin friction parameter, local Nusselt number and Sherwood number are given for different values of physical parameters. The results show the results show the effect of suction is significant and that is, that magnitude of velocity, temperature and concentration decreases with increasing values of suction parameter, for both assisting and opposing flow. The concentration decreases with increasing values of Schmidt number and chemical reaction parameter. There is no significant change in velocity and temperature profile due to chemical reaction parameter. It has also been noticed that, for assisting and opposing flows that the magnitude of skin friction coefficient and mass transfer coefficient decreases with increasing values of chemical reaction parameter, but no significant change in magnitude of heat transfer coefficient.','','-','Vandana Bisht, Manoj Kumar and Ziya Uddin','433-443','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','5','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(78,'Analysis of Two-Unit Redundant System with Imperfect Switching and Connection Time','This paper deals with the analysis of a two unit redundant cold-standby system with imperfect switching and connection time. Switching probably is the most overlooked and undervalued part of a system design. Great attention is spent selecting the measurement and stimulus instruments. But more often than not, the chosen switching does not complement the instruments. It doesn\'t matter how accurate the instruments are if the signals pass through a poor switch design to get to them. The distribution of repair times of units are taken to be negative exponential with different parameters. The system is analyzed to determine various reliability measures by using semi-Markov process and regenerative point technique.','','-','Sanjeev Kumar, Nitin Bhardwaj and Ashok Kumar','195-202','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(79,'Periodic Orbits of an Artificial Satellite','We have determined the periodic orbits of an artificial satellite moving under the gravitational forces of the sun including its solar radiation pressure, the moon and the oblate earth including its equatorial ellipticity. We have determined the periodic orbits when the reference plane, with the help of which the orbital plane is oriented, (i) coincides with the ecliptic plane, (ii) coincides with the equatorial plane and (iii) inclined to the ecliptic at a given angle. We have further studied the effects of the earths equatorial ellipticity and the solar radiation pressure on the periodic orbits.','','-','Abdullah, Iqbal Ahmad and K. B. Bhatnagar','203-222','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(80,'Some Similarity Solutions for Plane Symmetric Perfect Fluid Distributions in General Relativity','In the present paper, a new class of solutions of Einsteins field equations is investigated for plane symmetric space-time when the source of gravitation is a perfect fluid. We have discussed a set of six explicit solutions of Einsteins field equations for non-conformally flat accelerating perfect fluid plates using similarity transformations method by considering a five dimensional (5-D) flat metric. The solutions thus obtained are analyzed physically. All the solutions are new of their respective category as far as authors are aware.','','-','Sachin Kumar, Y. K. Gupta and Pratibha','223-240','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(81,'Exact and Numerical Solutions of Nonlinear Reaction Diffusion Equation by Using the ColeHopf Transformation','Many important applications are available for nonlinear reaction-            diffusion equation especially in the area of biology and engineering.               The present model, Consider a non-linear reaction diffusion equation  etc..','','-','Sanjeev Kumar and Ravendra Singh','241-252','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(82,'Note on Vorticity of Unsteady Flow of a Dusty Conducting Viscous Fluid Through Concentric Circular Cylinders','The unsteady laminar motion of dust viscous incompressible conducting fluid through concentric circular cylinders under time dependent pressure gradient has been discussed. The closed form solutions of the vorticity of fluid and dust particles are obtained and their natures for transient pressure gradient are shown graphically.','','-','P. K. Mittal,  Alok Darshan Kothiyal  and Giri Raj Gupta','253-259','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(83,'On the Time to Cross the Antigenic Diversity Threshold in HIV Infection - A Stochastic Approach','It has been recognized worldwide that the dreaded HIV infection takes place mostly under homo or hetero sexual contacts. There is still significant debate about the details of how HIV eventually overwhelms the immune system. One possibility is suggested by the antigenic diversity threshold hypothesis (Nowak and May 1990). This hypothesis suggests that HIV\'s rapid mutation rate allows the virus to churn out a constant stream of escape mutants. As more and more escape mutant strains appear, the immune system has to keep increasing the number of strain-specific antibody classes at the same time that its being systematically attacked by the virus. Eventually the virus builds up enough diversity. So that the immune system may find it harder and harder to mount responses against these newly emerging virus variants. Once the antigenic diversity of the virus population has increased above a threshold value, the immune system can no longer control of virus, which results in the development of AIDS. This paper aims at developing a mathematical model to find the time to get AIDS after the first infection, is made taking in to the consideration of antigenic diversity threshold.','','-','R. Elangovan,  R. Jaisankar and R. Sathiyamoorthy','261-268','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(84,'Centralized Controlled Hierarchical Routing Protocol for Wireless Sensor Network','Wireless sensor network consists of hundreds or thousands of micro sensor nodes, networking together, that allows user to accurately monitor a remote environment intelligently combining the data from the individual nodes. The main issue in WSN is energy limited characteristic of the sensor node. So the problem is to have the routing protocol in such a manner that it should be energy efficient in order to increase the life span of the whole WSN. Based on the network structure adopted, the routing architecture is classified as Data centric, hierarchical routing, and location based routing architecture. Hierarchical routing architecture divides the whole network in to a group of cluster and only cluster head is responsible to forwarding the data to base station directly or via other cluster heads. Broadly, Hierarchical Routing Protocol for WSN is classified as Centralized and Non-Centralized. In non-centralized, cluster formation is done by the sensor nodes itself. But in case of centralized hierarchical routing, cluster head formation is done by the base station. In this paper, new centralized routing protocol called Power Efficient Centralized Hierarchical routing (PECH) for WSN is proposed.','','-','Monika Sethi,  Mrityunjay Singh and Saroj Poonia','269-280','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(85,'Design of Double Sampling Rectifying OQ Plans','This paper is a generalization of earlier study by Hall (1979), who introduced outgoing quality and total inspection as well defined random variables under total rectification. In this paper OQ attribute rectification sampling plans for double sampling is developed based on Venkatesan (2005). An extensive simulation study is presented to illustrate the determination of the plan.','','-','D. Venkatesan and M. Gallo','281-289','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(86,'A Structure Based Computer Grammar to Understand Simple and Compound English Sentences','In this paper we are contributing to the Natural Language Understanding phase of the broader area Natural Language Processing. We present in this paper design of computer grammar that is capable of understanding simple and compound sentences of English language efficiently. To begin the design we have explored thoroughly all the possible syntactic structures of the simple and compound English sentences. We have considered all kinds of simple sentences along with the use of different tenses as well as voices. Then we prepared structural representation (SRs) of these sentences discussed in the analysis section. Finally we have converted all these SRs into computer grammar. We have also developed a test paper using some portion of the computer grammar discussed in this paper. This computer grammar can be used in many applications as elaborated in the conclusion.','','-','Himanshu Pandey, S.P. Upadhyay and U.N. Tripathi','291-299','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(87,'Nearly Weak thita - refinable Spaces and Covering Axioms','V. K. Sharma introduced the notion nearly weak  - refinable spaces. A space X is said to be nearly weak  - refinable if for regularly open covering u of X, there exists a sequence   of open families such that   is a refinement of u and for each  x ? X, there is an n(x) ? N such that un(x) is finite at x. In this paper we propose to study the relationships of nearly weak  - refinable spaces with covering axioms such as weak  - refinable subparacompact, metacompact and quasi-developable spaces respectively.','','-','V. K. Sharma','301-306','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(88,'Mathematical Formalism and Computer Program for Tense Conversion in English Grammar','The given paper is an attempt in the direction of defining grammar of the natural language with the help of mathematical concepts. Taking English as our language of study, we have developed effective rules for detecting grammatically correct patterns from non-grammatically patterns and then transform tenses from one to another form. The method incorporates the comparison of the text with a grammar database, calculation of the entered text score, its evaluation on the basis of its comparison with the English language grammar and then to authenticate the sentences on the basis of grammar. The computer programs developed by this process shall pave the way of grammatically perfect machine translation. The program is in human-readable source code form from which executable programs can be derived or compiled.','','-','Sumit Khulbe, Richanshu Sharma and H.S.Dhami','302-317','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(89,'Advanced Intrusion Detection System for Network Security','With the rapid increase in the uses of internet and its applications, the possibility of cyber attacks and cyber crimes has increased up to an alarming level. There is also a saying (wisdom) that Internet is very insecure, seems very correct. There are certain counter mechanisms available but still they are not enough. Due to increasing incidents of cyber attacks and security breaches; developing an effective system is essential for protecting information system security, and yet it remains an elusive goal and a great challenge. There are various counter mechanisms are also available like antivirus, firewall and IDS etc. For some certain problems antivirus are better solutions but for preventing our system from unauthorized access etc; firewalls and Intrusion Detection System (IDS) are of much usage. Among the available counter mechanisms for Internet threats Intrusion Detection System (IDS) sounds to be a much better option. In the current scenario the need of advance IDS is required. For making a complete secure system the combination of operating system, IDS and ACLs etc. is required. ACLs allow us to provide different levels of access to files and folders, websites, port numbers, and protocols. Basically it is a database list which keeps the names of permitted and non permitted IP addresses, protocols, websites, ports etc. Linux operating system seems to be a better option for providing the secure environment because of its architecture and tools. Linux being an open source software the possibilities of proposing an advanced ACL based IDS seems possible. The use of ACL in the IDS is of great importance. In this paper we will propose conceptual IDS on Linux platform which will be able to counter todays internet security threats / attacks in a better way.','','-','S. S. Tyagi and R. K. Chauhan','319-331','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(90,'Common Fixed Point Theorem for a Pair of Multivalued Mappings Satisfying the Ishikawa Type Iteration','In the present paper we extend and generalize the results of Kubiaczyk and Ali (1997), Rashwan (1995), Huang and Jeng (1997), Liu (2003) and others for a pair of multivalued mappings S, T in normed spaces, using the Ishikawa iteration scheme.','','-','Amit Singh and R. C Dimri','333-338','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(91,'On Einstein-Kaehlerian S-Recurrent Space','Mathai and Walker have studied Kaehlerian recurrent space. Matsumoto has considered Kaehlerian space with parallel or vanishing Bochner curvature tensor. Singh and Singh have studied and defined Kaehlerian conharmonic recurrent and Kaehlerian conharmonic symmetric spaces. Singh have studied Einstein-Kaehlerian conharmonic recurrent spaces. In the present paper we have studied Einstein-Kaehlerian conharmonic s-recurrent spaces and Einstein-Kaehlerian spaces with s-recurrent Bochner curvature tensor.','','-','Girish Dhobal and K. S. Rawat','339-343','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(92,'Steady Flow of a Viscoelastic Second-Grade Fluid Over a Shrouded Rotating Disc with Uniform Suction and Injection','The problem of steady laminar flow of a non-Newtonian viscoelastic second-grade fluid over a finite rotating disk enclosed within a coaxial cylindrical casing has been solved by finite difference method when there is suction and equal injection applied normal to the upper and lower disc respectively. The flow is subjected to a superposed small mass rate of symmetrical radial outflow (or inflow). The effects of the second order terms are observed to depend on the dimensionless viscoelastic parameter T. The presence of the shroud induces circulation about the axis of rotation. It is interesting to find that the maximum values  1 and  2 of the dimensionless radial distances at which there is no-recirculation, for the cases of net radial outflow and net radial inflow, decrease with an increase in the viscoelastic parameter T. The velocities at  1 and  2 as well as at some other fixed radii have been calculated for different values of T and suction parameter A. and the associated phenomena of recirculation#/no-recirculation has been discussed in detail and shown graphically. The change in the flow phenomena due to a reversal of the direction of net radial flow has been studied. Moreover, it is found that the moment on the rotating disk increases with T. Such flows are useful in mechanical and chemical industries.','','-','H.G.Sharma, Ritu and M. P. Singh','345-358','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(93,'Study of Congestion Control Mechanism of TCP over IEEE 802.11 Multihop Wireless Network','In this paper, we studies TCP performance over multihop wireless networks that use the IEEE 802.11 protocol as the access method. We focus on fairness and stability of the congestion control mechanisms adopted in several versions of TCP by investigating their timetransient behaviors through simulation based approach. In addition to TCP Tahoe and TCP Reno, we also consider TCP Vegas which has been proposed for higher throughput. Our simulation based analysis show that, TCP Vegas can achieve higher throughput than TCP Tahoe and TCP Reno in multihop static wireless network.','','-','Rakesh Sharma and Dinesh C. Dhobal','359-367','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(94,'Block Ciphering in KSA, A Major Breakthrough in Cryptography Analysis in Wireless Networks','Wireless communication is the transfer of information over a distance, without using cables or conductors. The distances involved may be short or long. Wireless communication has such features as freedom of access to the information transmitted via wireless networks that puts out different kinds of unauthorized actions of breakers. Solution of this problem is applying cryptography in wireless networks. We proposed 128-bit block cipher called Camellia. Camellia supports 128-bit block size and 128-, 192-, and 256-bit keys, i.e. the same interface specifications as the Advanced Encryption Standard (AES). Efficiency on both software and hardware platforms is a remarkable characteristic of Camellia in addition to its high level of security. It is confirmed that Camellia provides strong security against differential and linear cryptanalysis. Compared to the AES finalists, i.e. MARS, RC6, Rijndael, Serpent, and Twofish, Camellia offers at least comparable encryption speed in software and hardware. In this paper the author have proposed a block ciphering standard in providing confidentiality, security, integrity in wireless communication presently used in KSA.','','-','Yusuf  Perwej, Kashiful Haq, Uruj Jaleel and Firoj  Parwej','369-385','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(95,'Environmental Ethics...... Where Are We?','Life and environment are correlates and their relation is extremely intimate. Environment is present from the very beginning of life. Man being selfish forgot the basic truth that his whole existence was at the mercy of these elemental factors and in order to flourish he has to nourish, enrich and conserve them. Mans exploitation of nature has damaged the environment to such a great extent that it has resulted into environmental degradation. Environmental Degradation manifests in many ways. Rich countries are responsible for 72 percent of total green house gas emissions between 1950 and 2000. Rapid industrialization in India has made it now the worlds fourth largest emitter of green house gases. Many things can be done for protecting the environment from ourselves and others. It is our own lifestyle, greed, selfishness and lack of awareness that is the starting point of all the problems. As the cartoon character Pogo says we have seen the enemy and it is us. The society is in dire need of environmentally trained citizens as the environmental conditions are quite alarming. Finding the perfect balance between whats green and whats livable could lead us to paradise.','','-','Mrs. Pratiksha Juyal and Prof. R. C. Nautiyal','1-08','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(96,'Critical appraisal of the role of Information Technology in Teacher Education','This paper attempts to highlight the role of information technology in teacher education. The present teacher education program is said to be mechanical, sterotyped, traditional, dull, old fashioned and passive unable to prepare effective and competent teachers. Information technology improve present teacher education program. Information technology is the combination of computer and communication technologies. Presumbaly, when speaking of information technology ( I.T.) as a whole, it is noted that the use of computers and information are associated. To maintain standard or quality in education, teacher should make use of I.T. in teaching learning process. Teacher education is a continuous process and its pre-service and in-service components are inseparable ( The National Policy on Education  1986). The teacher can play the roles of director of learning, motivator, guide and organizer. For that he has to enrich his knowledge through the advancement of technologies, specially the information technology. According to Dr. Radha Krishnan,  A good teacher must know how to arouse the interest of pupil in the field of study for which he is responsible. He must himself be a master in the field  and be in touch with the latest development in the subject. He must himself be a fellow traveler in the exciting pursuit of knowledge.','','-','Mrs. Neeraja','09-14','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(97,'Higher Education in India: Problems and Prospects','India is rushing headlong toward economic success and modernization with significant advantages in the 21st century knowledge race. It has a large higher education sector, the third largest in the world in student numbers, after China and the United States. Now as India strives to compete in a globalised economy in areas that require highly trained professionals, the quality of higher education becomes increasingly important. So far, Indias large educated population base and its reservoir of at least moderately well-trained university graduates have permitted the country to move ahead. Indias colleges and universities, with just a few exceptions, have become large, under-funded, ungovernable intuitions. At many of them, politics has intruded into campus life, influencing academic appointments and decisions across levels. Under investment in libraries information technology, laboratories, and classrooms makes it very difficult to provide top quality instruction or engage in cutting edge research. India can build internationally recognized research-oriented universities overnight, but the country has the key elements in place to begin and sustain the process which require the active involvement of UGC and interest and favour of Finace as well as Human resources department of Government. A combination of specific conditions and resources are needed to create outstanding universities. Sustained financial support, with an appropriate mix of accountability and autonomy is the need of the hour.','','-','\"\"Dr. Candra Bhushan Pandey and ;\r\nDr. Diwakar Sharma\"','15-20','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(98,'Orienting Mass Media Towards People\'s Education for Peace','Mass Media have always been in existence in every society in some form or the other. People have created mass media as a tool for their recreation, knowledge and creativity. The welfare of the masses is the core function of mass- media. In the beginning of every society, oration, public speeches, fares, festivals and other social gatherings were the modes of mass media. Presently there are many components of mass media viz. print, non-print, broadcasting, tele-casting, satellites, etc. Now all persons of the world are connected through some sort of electronic devices like internet, e-mail, websites, cellphones, etc. Thus, it is evident that mass media are now the most potent instrument of education and communication.','','-','Mr.Kunwar Pushpendra Pratap Singh','21-24','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(99,'Common School System in Indian Democracy : Issues and Concerns','Commom school system refers to provide an equal quality of education to all children irrespective of their caste, creed, language, gender, economic or ethnic background , place of birth and where in all category of schools i.e. government, private and aided schools, should fulfill certain minimum infrastructural financial, curricular, pedagogical socio cultural norms, with free education to all children from the age group up to a stage as prescribed appropriately reflecting geo-cultural, linguistic diversity of the country with the board policies guidelines and the national curriculum framework for school education as approved by the central advisory board of education. In brief a common school system CSS is concerned to the application of common norms of quality education by all schools in the system. Equality is considered to be an essential and significant ingredient of both the sprit and form of democracy. The ideals of social justice and equality of opportunity is an integral part of the right to education in the constitution. Indian constitution aims at to build an egalitarian society in India. The role of teachers as transformer becomes the significant element in transforming the educational scenario. It is high time to restructure and reconstruct national educational system in India on the line of CSS to confirm equitable and equality education to all without any discrimination on the basis of sex, cast, creed birth, socio economic and cultural characteristics or type of school to order to enhance the values and ideals indicated in the constitution of Indian.','','-','Mr.Pardeep Kumar and Mrs Shaifali','25-32','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(100,'Teacher Empowerment in The Age of Globalization','Globalization refers to the accelerated international flow of goods, capital, labor, services and information which have occurred in response to improved transport, the seemingly limitless revolution in communication technologies and the deregulatory policies/restructuring adopted in many countries during the past two decades. The process of restructuring has made the nations to liberalize, and then privatize and globalize (LPG) during the last two decades. These structural reforms are mainly related to trade, industry, financial, fiscal and agriculture sectors. These reforms have shown tremendous impact on economic growth, education and training. Globlization has left also tremendous impact in the hole of teachers\r\nTeacher empowerment is an act of giving opportunity by authority of the teacher to make workplace decisions. Teacher deals with creating an organization which supports autonomy in decision making.\r\nTraditionally, empowerment has meant teacher participation in school decision making which has assisted administrators in coordinating and in building commitment among their faculty.','','-','Mr. Devendra Kumar Khokhar','33-40','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(101,'Challanges and Issues of Quality Improvement in Education','That to inculcate quality, everyone requires to do his best is not only the answer: For the purpose, one must know what to do, how to do? Knowing what to do involves teachers and students. Knowing how to do involves teaching and learning. Quality expects, the inspiring of every movement with respect to new developments in the field, its management and technology. To keep pace with internal quality standards ISO 9000 and ISO 9001 are widely recognized as quality measuring tools which are being adopted by quality conscious industrial as well as educational organizations in the world. Education is making shifts from individual to group education, to mass education, to network education and to widely distributed education.','','-','Mr. Pradeep Kumar','41-46','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(102,'Professional Ethics, Values and Competency in Teacher Education','Teacher is a profession needs special training intended to build up knowledge, competencies, develop skills and favourable attitude towards learners. The teacher must be an embodiment of eternal values-values that remain the same, however, much the circumstance may change. Truth, love and goodness are values that are admired across creeds, cultures and religions. The personal development of a teacher is the core of professionalization and forms the base for professional ethics.','','-','Dr. K.N. Gupta','47-50','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(103,'Globalization of Teacher Education Institutions and Quality Assurance:In reference to Privatization','The economy of a country depends upon the utility of educated manpower in the global context. The emergence of a new educational outline is going to change role of teachers. They would be expected to be more alert and sensitive to needs and aspirations of the students and the society. Any educational system is standing on a strong philosophy and value system which differs from culture to culture and nation to nation. When any private institution from other country will start a TEP in our country, are these teachers expected to have commitment to our nation, our society and our culture? Indian philosophical, sociological and cultural base is totally different from that of foreign countries. We want teachers who can develop sacrifice, equality, social awareness and social dignity among our young pupils then Self which is a characteristic of Western culture. People in developed country consider their education is of very high quality. This view is supported by us also due to uncritical attitude of our students and parents to accord higher value to degree of foreign universities. If these institutions will be permitted to run TEP in our country, what is the quality of research? These institutions are unlikely to promote research beneficial to our nation, but will promote research supportive to their professions. If we observe the unaided private TEP institutions, even in India, the situation of research is disappointing. Almost all these private TEP institutions link privatization only through economic perspective and not from socio-cultural perspective.','','-','Mrs. Sangeeta Bijalwan','51-56','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(104,'Teacher-Educators Perceived Ease and Usefulness of Using ICTs In Himachal Pradesh','The use of ICTs in Himachal Pradesh generally is increasing and dramatically growing. This study examined Himachal Pradesh Teacher-Educators uses of ICTs and its implications for further development of ICTs use in Himachali Teacher-Educators. The sample of the study consisted of 130 teacher-educators from 20 purposefully selected private B.Ed Colleges of Himachal Pradesh. This comprised 39 males and 91 females. Their age ranged from 2640 years with a mean age of 33 years. A modified instrument tagged Teachers ICT use survey adapted from ICT survey indicator for teachers and staff by UNESCO (2004) was used for the collection of data. The results showed that teacher-educators perceived ICT as being easier and very useful in teaching and learning. For continuous uses of lCTs by teachers, it was recommended among others that teacher training and professional development oriented policies should support ICT-related teaching models that encourage both students-teachers and teacher-educators to play an active role in teaching-learning activities.','','-','Dr. Ajay Kumar Attri','57-64','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(105,'Open and Distance Learning: Use of Communication Technology and its Impact','Present paper seeks to analyse the use of communication technology in Open and Distance Learning (ODL) system in general and Indira Gandhi National Open university in particular. Various issues pertaining to use of communication technology have been addressed in the paper by taking the perception of learners into consideration. Attempt has also been made to suggest the policy measures to improve the use of various means of communication technology including audio-video tapes/CDs, teleconferencing gyan darshan, gayanvani and EduSat.','','-','Dr.Anil Kumar Dimri , Dr. Anil Kumar Misra, Dr.Amit Chaturvedi','65-80','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(106,'Impact of Scholastic Achievement on Vocational Maturity and Level of Aspiration','The present study aimed to see the impact of scholastic achievement on level of aspiration and vocational maturity. A sample of 300 students of XI standard form arts and science discipline were taken. Result reveals that scholastic achievement has a great impact on vocational maturity and no impact on level of aspiration.','','-','Dr. Anjali Sharma','81-86','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(107,'Environmental Awareness & Environmental Education Attitude of Prospective Teachers','Environmental Education makes the people conscious about the environmental crises and method of averting it. Teacher and students both are equally important to deal with this problem. The prospective teachers, the root of future education must also have sufficiently positive attitude and awareness about the environmental issues to develop congenial atmosphere with in the school and out side. This study was an attempt to study the present status of Environmental Awareness and environmental Education Attitude of B.Ed. students. Both the variables were studied through survey method with the help of standardized tools. A comparative scenario was studied considering caste (General, OBC & SC), Academic achievement (High, Average & low) and Socioeconomic status as independent variables. The study reveals that Academic achievement, Caste and Socioeconomic status played a significant role to determine environmental awareness and attitude towards Environmental education among the B.Ed. Students','','-','Dr. Vivek Kaushik','87-110','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(108,'A Study of Teaching Competency as Related to Gender Differences and Background of Teachers','The investigator tried to know the competency level of the teachers who are getting more benefits i.e. prestige and security of job in comparison of those who get a few .Keeping in view the above, the investigator make an effort to design the study and to find out the competency level of teachers (male female) working in Tehri district amongst Govt. & Pvt. schools .The sample consists 240 teachers which were selected randomly from different belongingness viz. Male-Female, Rural-Urban background. The general findings show that the Govt. and Pvt. background as well as gender difference does not impact on their competency level even if they would be provided the same facilities. The location and the sex difference also do not impact on their competency level. However, there is adjudged some factors which impacts on their competency, but only these factors are not too dominant. The teachers who are in govt. job possess the same competency level in comparison of the teachers who are in pvt. job, if they would be provided the same facilities and the salaries as well.','','-','\"\"Dr. Pratap Singh Rana and  ;\r\nMr. Shakti Singh Rana\"','111-116','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(109,'A Study of Values Among Students in Relation to Their Cast at Primary Level','The present study aims at finding out whether these any difference in values between Backward and General students at primary level. the sample consist of 200 students (124 Backward and 76 General students ) 124IVQ scale by Prof Sherry and Varma has been used of the study for collecting the data in the study. The result indicate that the General students have more religious value against to Backward students at primary level.','','-','\"\"Dr.Rakesh Rai and  ;\r\nMrs Anita Rai\"','117-126','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(110,'Privatization of Secondary Teacher Education in India: A Discourse on Quality Concerns','Privatization as an agenda of development has been adopted by the policy makers for all the sectors including education for last one and half decades as a consequence of economic reform. This paper discusses about the development of teacher education in recent past as a shadow of larger policy; Liberalization, Privatization and Globalization. LPG movement has influenced entire higher education in general and simultaneously, secondary teacher education in particular. A phenomenal growth in teacher education institutions led to regional imbalance in availability of teacher education was also observed in last decade. It further stresses upon the increasing intrusion of for-profit educational organizations and its impact on the quality of most vital source of imparting education i.e. Teacher-Education in India.\r\nKey Words: Privatization, Quality, Teacher-Education, Self-Financing, India','','-','Mr. Bhanu Pratap Pritam','127-138','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(111,'Effect of Anxiety on the Academic Achievement of Graduate Females','The present problem intends to provide necessary information to understand the effect & level of anxiety. Women are taking part, responsibilities, duties in every area of (work) service. They are facing extreme competition and anxiety. Our system is totally performance related. One exam just qualifies for the next exam. There seems no end to the steps on the ladder. In this rat race, every one wants to be successful but some will succeed & some will fail. The present study was conducted on female graduates of degree colleges at Dehradun. The samples were selected on the basis of random sampling by using lottery system','','-','Mrs. Rashmi Negi and Mrs.Pratiksha Juyal','139-144','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(112,'Teacher Educators Attitude Towards Yoga Education: A Descriptive Study','Yoga is a divine science. Nowadays yoga is becoming more popular among people of the world. Yoga is a philosophy of life to support final goal of life. Realizing the importance of Yoga, there is a tremendous development in India and abroad. Here an attempt has been made to assess the attitude of teacher educators towards yoga education. To assess the attitude of teacher educators to words Yoga education, an attitude scale, YEAS was developed and the reaction was assessed, confidingly, It was found that variables like, sex, age and locale had tremendous impact on the attitude of teacher educators towards yoga education.','','-','Mr. Rajani Ranjan Singh and Dr. Pardeep Dehal','145-156','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(113,'A Study on the Impact of Age on Attitude of Teachers of Uttarakhand towards Female Foeticide','Census 2001 revealed shocking fact of adverse sex ratio. The sex ratio is 933 females per 1000 males. One obvious reason for this may be attributed to female foeticide. But for Kerala, almost in all the states of the country the number of women per 1,000 males is less than 1,000. Social scientists are of the view that if this trend is not checked immediately the society may collapse. Government has played a very positive role in prevention of female foeticide by making it a criminal offence. But unfortunately this alone has not proved to be effective. Concerned citizens are also coming forward to spread awareness regarding the issue and its fallout. \r\nTeachers should also be involved in the crusade against female foeticide as they are the role models of their students. The students of today or rather parents of tomorrow should be educated about the equality of the sexes. They have to be made aware that girls are not the children of lesser Gods and so should never carry out female foeticide in their lives. But before the teachers are assigned such a crucial responsibility it has to be ascertained if they have the right attitude about the whole issue related to female foeticide. \r\nHence, this research was carried out to find out the impact of age on attitude of teachers of Uttarakhand towards female foeticide','','-','Prof. R.C. Nautiyal Dr. Seema Dhawan and Mrs. Shruti Sharma','157-162','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','14','9','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(114,'An Enhanced Network Security Framework for Communication and Management in Cluster Based Ad-Hoc Networks','Wireless networking is an emerging technology with lower prices and higher data rates that allows users to access information and services electronically, regardless of their geographic position. The use of wireless communication between mobile users has become increasingly popular due to recent performance advancements in computer and wireless technologies. All nodes of Ad-hoc networks behave as routers and take part in discovery and maintenance of routes to other nodes in the network. Ad-hoc networks are limited in range, node mobility, security of data, proper communication and having limited bandwidth. However, advantages of ad-hoc networks over traditional cellular systems include on-demand setup, fault tolerance, and unconstrained connectivity. A key feature that sets ad-hoc wireless networks apart from the more traditional cellular radio systems is the ability to operate without a fixed wired communication infrastructure. This is useful in disaster recovery, military situations, and places with non-existing or damaged communication infrastructure where rapid deployment of a communication network is needed. A fundamental assumption in ad-hoc networks is that any node can be used to forward packets between arbitrary sources and destinations. Some sort of routing protocol is needed to make the routing decisions. A cluster based approach for ad-hoc network in a large region enables mobile node management, security, fault tolerance, network key management and routing. A standard framework design is needed for communication and management in cluster based ad-hoc networks. This paper studies existing security and communication strategies and proposes a new framework for data communication, management and security.','','-','\"\"Sharad Saxena, Sandeep Kumar Agarwal, Jagdish Chandra Patni  ;\r\nand Mohd. Uruj Jaleel\"','387-403','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(115,'Marginal Stability of Plane Couette Flow of Non-Newtonian Fluids with Superposed Temperature Gradient','The non-oscillatory stability of Benard Couette flow of visco-elastic fluids obeying the generalized second order differential constitutive equation is discussed. By a simple mathematical consideration, the stability equations have been treated for the marginal stability case. Limitations on the parameters GF and GRe are obtained under which a minimum Rayleigh number  ( )  is found out. It has been found that the limitations for GF and GRe provide the case of marginal stability under either   or  , where   and   are primary and secondary normal stresses respectively.','','-','Prabir Kumar Shrivastava','405-418','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(116,'On Comparison of Model-based and Design-based Estimators of Mean for Count Data with Excess Zeros','In many of the contingent valuation (CV) studies, the primary focus is on the average amount the respondents are willing to pay (WTP). In these studies, the amount is a quantitative variable and the common techniques that are used for the estimation are logit or probit regression models. However, when the respondents are not able to pay in cash, the valuation can be obtained in terms of the number of days they are willing to work. A commonly encountered problem here is the number of excess zeros than the ones predicted by the underlying distributions. In such cases, one has to use the inflated Poisson (Negative Binomial) distribution. In this paper we have investigated the performance of the estimators of mean for count data with excess zeros. We have also compared the performance of this model-based (maximum likelihood) estimator with design-based estimators namely, the sample mean, the ratio and the regression estimators. Even when the underlying distribution of the study variable is inflated Poisson, the regression and ratio estimators perform well compared to the model-based estimator.','','-','Jubin Antony and Aruna Rao','419-442','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(117,'Study on Multiplexer Based Array Multipliers','This paper deals with Multiplexer-based multiplication algorithm, circuit complexity, outperform them in terms of speed and power dissipation, Implementation of multiplexer-based multipliers with faster and lower power consumption full-adder circuits could further improve performance, it permits efficient VLSI implementation.','','-','\"\"Subhash Kumar Sharma, Kranti Kirnesh Dubey ;\r\nand Himanshu Pandey\"','443-452','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(118,'Forensic Investigation of Window Registry','This paper will introduce the Microsoft Windows Registry database and explain how critically important a registry examination is to computer forensics experts. In essence, the paper will discuss various types of Registry \'footprints\' and investigate an examples of what crucial information can be obtained by performing an efficient and effective forensic examination. Many of the Registry keys that are imperative and relevant to an examination will also be discussed.','','-','Mahesh Manchanda , Vandna Manchanda, Vishal Gupta and Manish Bisht','473-485','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(119,'Effects of Inflation on Inventory Systems for Decaying Items with Dependent Demand','The main purpose is to investigate the effect of inflation deterministic model for perishable inventory with stock-dependent demand and nonlinear holding cost. Here the demand rate is a function of the on-hand inventory. We developed an EOQ model under inflation. The traditional parameters of unit item cost and ordering cost are kept constant, but the holding cost is treated as a nonlinear function. The approximate optimal solution in both the cases are derived. The model are illustrated with some numerical examples.','','-','V. C. Goyal and  R. K. Yadav','487-496','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','2','8','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(120,'f\'k{k.k&izca/ku','fk{k.k ,d ,slh thoar izf;k gS] tks lh/ks&lh/ks vf/kxe ls tqM+h gSA nwljs \'kCnksa esa ge dg ldrs gSa] fd fk{k.k&vf/kxe ,d gh flDds ds nks igyw gSaA fk