 are solved numerically by finite difference method. The results are obtained for velocity, microrotation, temperature and concentration profiles. The numerical results are presented graphically for different values of the material parameters entering into the problem. Finally, the numerical values of skin friction are presented in pictorial form.','','-','Bhagwat Swarup , Kuldeep and Rajeev Jha','55-70','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','16','12','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(197,'Some New Non-Conformally Flat Fluid Spheres of Class One in General Relativity','A new class of solutions of Einstein field equations is investigated for spherical symmetric space-time when the source of gravitation is a perfect fluid. We have discussed a set of five explicit solutions of Einsteins field equations for non-conformally flat accelerating perfect fluid spheres by considering a five dimensional (5-D) flat metric. The solutions thus obtained are analyzed physically. All the solutions are new of their respective category as far as authors are aware.','','-','Sachin Kumar, Y. K. Gupta and J. R. Sharma','71-81','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','16','12','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(198,'Highly Accurate Series Solution of ODE with Singularity Occurring in Fluid Flow Problems using Symbolic Computation','A complex boundary value problem, consisting of a second order ordinary differential equation with singularities, arising in fluid mechanics is solved to high precision.  Because the differential equation has a singularity at the origin, a Frobenius series solution has been obtained. The series solution has been expanded along the axis using analytic continuity and it is matchede to an asymptotic solution. To obtain high accuracy, we used a large number of terms in each series solution, which is only possible by virtue of a symbolic computation system.  All the routines for this purpose were developed in a computer algebra system (CAS).','','-','Pratibha','83-90','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','16','12','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(199,'Stability of Stratified Compressible Shear Flows in Presence of Parallel Magnetic Field','In this paper, the stability of stratified compressible shear flows in presence of parallel magnetic field has been discussed. The fluid flow has been considered to be confined between two parallel rigid boundaries. The effect of magnetic field and compressibility on the stability of flows of compressible fluid has been discussed.','','-','Hari Kishan and Geeta Devi','91-101','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','16','12','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(200,'Mathematical Model for the Effect of Body Acceleration on Blood    Flow in Time Dependent Stenosed Artery','Pulsatile flow of blood under the influence of externally imposed periodic body acceleration through a time dependent stenosed artery is studied in this work. A mathematical model is developed by treating blood as a non-Newtonian fluid characterized by the casson fluid. The pulsatile flow is analyzed by considering a periodic pressure gradient, which is a function of time. In this analysis we try to find the computational results by using the  perturbation analysis, assuming that the Womersley frequency parameter is very small. The effect of body acceleration has been discussed with the help of graphs. The graphs show velocity profile, volumetric flow rate and the wall shear stress are decrease as the body acceleration parameter increase. It is noticed that the effect of yield stress and stenosis is to reduce flow rate and the presence of body acceleration is to increase the flow rate. The flow resistance is seemed to be increased substantially due to the presence of yield stress and stenosis. The body acceleration is found to reduce the flow resistance.','','-','Sanjeev Kumar and Archana Dixit','103-115','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','16','12','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(201,'Study of Molecular Properties of Polymer Materials and Continuum Theories of Fluids with Structure','In the present paper we wish to show by presentation of some examples, how the interpretive and practical value of continuum theories of anisotropic fluids can be augmented by joining the continuum formulism with certain theoretical and experimental results of a Molecular nature. The result can be an enhancement of the value of both molecular and continuum approaches to formulation of constitutive equations. Some ideas drawn from structured continuum theories are associated with results of various molecular descriptions of polymer solutions and melts.','','-','Prabir Kumar Shrivastava, Praveen Kumar, Deepika Sonal and Sunil Sinha','117-126','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','16','12','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(202,'Analysis of Incompressible Viscous Laminar Flow through a Channel Filled with Porous Media','The present analysis relates to the study of the incompressible viscous laminar flow through a channel filled with porous media. The second law of thermodynamics is applied to investigate the entropy generation rate. Based on some simplifying assumptions, analytical solutions for the velocity and temperature are constructed .The expressions for the entropy generation rate and irreversibility ratio are obtained. Our result shows that Viscous dissipation has no effect on the entropy generation rate at centerline of a channel filled with porous media .The result are presented graphically and discussed quantitatively for several values of group parameter (