ioms in topological spaces using weakly preopen sets. We use preinterior preopen sets to introduce the notions of weakly pre-T0, weakly pre- T1, Weakly pre- T2.','','-','Shalu','351-354','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','18','18','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(293,'Identity Based Public Verifiable Multi-Proxy Multi-Signcryption Scheme from Bilinear Pairings','This paper presents an identity based multi-proxy multi- signcryption scheme from pairings. In this scheme a proxy signcrypter   group could authorized as a proxy agent by the cooperation of all members in the original signcrypter group. Then the proxy signcryption can be generated by the cooperation of all the signcrypters in the authorized proxy signcrypter group on the behalf of the original signcrypter group. As compared to the scheme Liu and Xiao, the proposed scheme provides public verifiability of the signature along with simplified key management.','','-','Tej Singh and K.K. Kanodia','355-363','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','18','18','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(294,'Traffic Analysis for Wireless ATM Network Congestion','This paper focuses on the problem of congestion control in wireless ATM network based on analysis of Total  carried traffic versus load.The analytical result  are verified by a simulation study, which has shown that a non descriptive handoff with dynamic channel reservation does much lower  blocking probability under high traffic load and significantly reduce the average waiting time during handoff.','','-','Parag Jain, Sandip Vijay, S. C. Gupta','365-376','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','18','18','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(295,'Application of Data Mining Tools and Techniques in Textile Industry for Strategic Decision Making','Application of Information Technology (IT) is rapidly growing in textile sector like its Information technology is justifiably considered to offer far reaching solutions to a wide range of manufacturing and management problems encountered in almost every industry. However, in spite of the efforts being made in the field of technology management, it is evident that in several organizations information technology is not being used effectively, efficiently or even economically. This observation seems to be hold true for textile industry also. Introducing Data Mining Tools and Techniques into textile production processes can achieve a substantial increase in productivity with maintain the quality.  It is here that Data Mining plays a vital role.','','-','S.K. Tyagi & B.K. Sharma','377-389','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','18','18','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(296,'The Study on Arithmetic of Numbers','Mathematics is the foundation of all sciences (1). Everything is bound to some fix laws in this universe.  The four Vedas Rig, Yajur, Sama, and Atharva have four upvedas and six vedangs all of which form an indivisible part of divine knowledge. Upveda Sthapatyaveda comes under Atharvaveda includes engineering, architecture, etc. along with all branches of Mathematics.  Mahavir was a great Digambara Jaina mathematician who flourished in middle of ninth century A.D. in south India had contributed in number rules (3). Quite a large number of theories have been advanced to explain the origin of numerals in ancient India.','','-','Nidhi Handa and Padmavati Taneja','391-398','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','18','18','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(297,'Common Fixed Point Theorem For Eight Mappings in Fuzzy Metric Spaces','In this paper we prove common fixed point theorems for eight mappings in fuzzy metric space. Our main results extend, generalize and fuzzify, Sushil Sharma [1] and some known results in fuzzy metric spaces, Probabilistic metric spaces and uniform spaces.','','-','R.K. Saini, Pardeep Kr. Rana, Sunil Kumar','399-412','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','18','18','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(298,'Two Warehouse Multi Items Integrated Model with Inflation Induced Demand under the Credit Period and Shortages  ','<p>\r\n	The two-warehouse integrated problem for deteriorating items with inflation induced demand rate and credit period is considered. Production rate is also depends upon the demand rate. An alternative model in which each cycle begins with shortages and ends without shortages is proposed here and also considered in owned warehouse time varying linear deterioration and in the rented warehouse Weibull rate of decay with multi items. Finally, some numerical examples for illustration are provided.</p>\r\n','','Two-Warehouse; Shortages; Weibull','S.R. Singh, Diksha Bhatia  ','1-15    ','NO','-','International Journal of Inventory Control and Management','20','19','2023-01-03 08:27:23','e',5,'shivrajpundir@gmail.com',' D N (P.G.) College, Meerut',' 10.58517/IJICM.2011.1101 ','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(299,'Application of Chebyshev Inequality in Stochastic Inventory Model with Controllable Lead Time and Backorder Discount ','<p>\r\n	Many researchers have recognized the importance of lead time reduction in stochastic inventory model, as it helps the firm to improve service level, manufacturing schedule and low safety stock. A good amount of work has been published in this context. Most of the authors have assumed that demand during the lead time either follows a normal known distribution or an unknown distribution. For an unknown distribution, authors have obtained the results using Minimax approach usually. In this paper a continuous review inventory model is developed with controllable lead time and backorder discount where lead time demand distribution is unknown. The solution is obtained by using Chebyshev inequality. The comparative analysis of all the three approaches viz. Chebyshev inequality, Minimax and Normal is also presented.</p>\r\n','','- ',' Chandra K. Jaggi, Neetu Arneja ','17-21  ','NO','-','International Journal of Inventory Control and Management','20','19','2023-01-03 08:10:55','e',5,'',' ',' 10.58517/IJICM.2011.1102','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(300,'A single vendor and multiple buyers integrated inventory policy in demand declining market ','<p>\r\n	In this research paper, an integrated inventory policy for single vendor and multiple buyers is developed. The demand function is decrease with respect to time. A numerical example is given to support our proposed policy. It is established numerically that the integrated approach results in significant decrease in the total cost in compared with the independent decision approach by all the buyers. The sensitivity analysis is carried out for all the parameters.</p>\r\n','','- ',' Nita H. Shah, Nidhi Raykundaliya ','23-42  ','NO','-','International Journal of Inventory Control and Management','20','19','2023-01-03 08:11:07','e',5,'',' ',' 10.58517/IJICM.2011.1103','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(301,'Optimization Policy of Inventory Model under the Effects of Learning and Imprecise Demand Rate ','<p>\r\n	It is a natural phenomenon that the performance of a system engaged in a repetitive process improves with time. In literature, this phenomenon is referred to as the learning effect. In this paper we analyze the impact of this effect on optimal strategy of inventory problem. Here, we consider the learning effects on holding cost, ordering cost and number of defective items present in each lot. By incorporating these learning effects, the decision maker can establish a model to optimize the capacity of organization and increase the efficiency of inventory system. We seek to maximize the profit and obtain the optimum lot size in each shipment under the effect of learning and by assuming that the demand rate is imprecise in nature. We use the Extension Principle to obtain the membership function of profit and centroid method for defuzzification. We observe that learning effect produce direct impact on optimal solution. At the end, numerical example is illustrated and sensitive analysis is performed.</p>\r\n','','- ',' Dharmendra Yadav, Rachna Kumari, S.R. Singh ','43-56  ','NO','-','International Journal of Inventory Control and Management','20','19','2023-01-03 08:11:20','e',5,'',' ',' 10.58517/IJICM.2011.1104','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(302,'Application of Matrix in Deadlock Avoidance of the Computing System','Matrix, a two-dimensional representation of elements, can be used not only to represent numbers but also many important characteristics of the computing system. Deadlock avoidance, an activity of the operating system of the computing system, uses the matrices to represent the availability of the resource instances, allocation of the resource instances to the processes, resource instances request, etc. Here in this paper we have tried to uncover the application of matrix in the Bankers algorithm of deadlock avoidance within the computing system.','','-','C B Gupta, Shridhar B Dandin','413-424','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','18','18','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(303,'Indus Valley Script Dictionary','The ancient most known civilization of India is Indus Valley civilization .The civilization came into existence in 1921-22 A.D .Wherever we found its remainings, they are in developed condition . But still we do not know the exact causes of its origin and decline. Also we are not able to decipher the Indus script .This research paper is trying to decipher the Indus Script and constructed Indus Script Dictionary which will certainly help to find out the hidden facts of Indus Valley Civilization .In the Paper we have tried to construct the Indus Script Dictionary','','-','Dr. Ranbeer Singh Chouhan, Dr.M.S.Gusain','1-11','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','22','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(304,'A Study of Declining Child Sex-Ratio in Punjab','Now-a-days, gender issue is an important aspect of human being in various social-economic and cultural classifications of people in India. Since the ancient time in our society, female killing has been a regular feature and happens in different forms. It is a disgrace for the Indian society, which considers the birth of a girl child as a terrible investment in future. She is considered to be consumer rather than a producer and this narrow thinking of the Indian patriarchal society has lead to unpleasant practices like female infanticide and female foeticide which create sex imbalance in the society. For the past several years, Punjab has been at the receiving end on the issue of declining sex ratio. In this study an attempt has been made to investigate an important issue i.e. child sex ratio. The study analyses the data from NFHS-1, NFHS-2 and NFHS-3 for Punjab and enlightens some pertinent features of declining child sex ratio. For this purpose sex ratio at birth has been compared for all the three rounds of NFHS data for rural and urban part of Punjab and found a declining trend in sex ratio at birth. Results show that sex ratio at birth for lower parity of females is in favour of male child however for higher parity of females it is in favour of male child however for higher parity of females it is in favour of female child. Total sex ratio at birth is in favour of male child for both urban and rural part of Punjab. Sex wise parity progression ratios are also obtained in support of the results.','','-','\"\"Brijesh P. Singh				, 		 Niraj K. Singh\"\"','12-19','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','22','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(305,'An exploratory study of nonverbal communication	\r\n and business success','It has been observed that Non verbal elements of communication are often overlooked and considered relatively insignificant in the overall communication process. Many studies have been performed in this area. Earlier it was considered that words are more important and the person understands only through words. After undergoing a thorough research process now it has been agreed by all the scholars that the gestures and expressions are more important than words. It has been proved that body language and tone of voice account for 93 percent of what is communicated between two people, while words account for only 7 percent.. \r\nThe main aim of this paper is to study how can the knowledge of these nonverbal processes of communication enhance business success?  Considering that communication is important in human life, that nonverbal communication can continuously transmit information; and that knowledge and human power are synonymous, a thorough knowledge of the processes and uses of nonverbal communication can help managers to enhance their power, as measured by monetary success in the business world.  Environments are invisible because their ground rules, pervasive structure, and overall patterns elude easy perception. However, nonverbal communication makes visible this invisible environment.\r\nThis study presents a review to explore the vital link between nonverbal communication and business success which is becoming more profound in today\'s world.  In professional environment a person might use what he or she has learned about nonverbal communication in order to read what is called \'nonverbal leakage\'. This \'leakage\' represents the true feelings which underlie the social mask. Although most of us can control our words and our faces better than the rest of our bodies, and consequently the movements of feet and hands, arms and legs often convey information of which we are unaware. This fact may be exploited in competitive interview situations, by placing the interviewee\'','','-','\"\"Jyoti Sardana, 						 Alok Goel\"\"','20-29','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','22','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(306,'ROLE OF MEDIA AS POLICY INSTRUMENT:\r\nUS ADVENTURE IN IRAQ ;AFGHANISTAN','During the last 25 years the media technology has shown tremendous growth and now it has become an organized industry. Its influence is wide-spread in every walk of life. It is regarded as fourth pillar of state and its importance is recognized all over the world in all societies. Since long it has been used as policy instrument by the policy-makers to achieve their desired objectives. Recently its significance has enhanced due to its effective role in warfare. The war planners of the United States used media as an important instrument of their war policies during Gulf war 1991, Afghan war, 2001 and Iraq war, 2003.In this paper the author will study how the United States did use media to obtain its war objectives, how it influenced the masses as well as the adversaries, what were its positive and negative effects. The author will also examine whether the media, which is expected to play a neutral role in order to deliver fair piece of information to the people in order to apprise them of the facts, has discharge its obligation or it has worked as a policy instrument and indulged in unfair and biased reporting  and concealing  the facts to mislead the people.','','-','\"\"Dr.Ghulam Shabir				 Dr.Muhammad Zaffar Iqbal\"\"','30-40','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','22','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(307,'MUSLIM WOMEN IN UTTARAKHAND  AN OVERVIEW ON RELIGIOUS PRACTICES','In this paper the main objective is to provide an overview about religion and religious practices among Muslim Women in Uttarakhand. Social status of women is byproduct of the existing internal structure in the community. The effect of globalization and liberalization polices on Muslim women has not yielded positive results. As the data in the present study show that the Muslim women are still in the grip of traditional religious practices and rituals, yet a wave of slight change can be seen in certain spheres','','-','Dr. Geetali Padiyar','41-52','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','22','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(308,'LEGAL  EDUCATION  AND SOCIAL  JUSTICE','Social Justice ultimately means social equality i.e. equality in all respects. No individual should be discriminated on the basic of caste, colour, sex and creed. The constitution of India the framers of the constitution have solemnly promised to do justice to its all citizens. Justice-social, economic and political, these provisions of the constitution, particularly Part III deals with the Fundamental Rights and Part IV deals with the Directive Principles of State Policy.2\r\nThe Supreme Court has also firmly ruled in many cases that the concept of social justice is not a blind concept because it ensures the human life to live in a meaningful and liberal manner. So we can say that legal education has also played an important role in social justice.','','-','Dr. Sanjeev Kumar Chadha','53-59','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','22','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(309,'Stress Management at Work Place','There is a growing awareness of how stress adversely affects organizational efficiency. The implementation of stress management programs to counteract the problem of stress with in the organization. The workplace has become a high stressful environment in many organizations cutting across industries. Employees are experiencing high level of stress due to various factors such as high workload, tight deadlines, high targets, type of work, lack of job satisfaction, long working hours, pressure to perform, etc. Interpersonal conflicts at the workplace, such as boss-subordinate relationships and relationships with peers, were also a source of stress','','-','Vidushi Bhatnagar','60-70','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','22','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(310,'Self and Society: A Study of Vijay Tendulkar\'s Silence! The Court is in Session','Vijay Tendulkar (1928-2008) is known for his concerns for burning social problems and anomalies of Indian society. Vijay Tendulkar is a leading Indian playwright along with three other great India dramatists of the 20th century i.e. Mohan Rakesh in Hindi, Badal Sircar in Bengali and Girish Karnad in Kannada. He has authored thirty full length plays and twenty three one act plays, several of which have become classics of modern Indian theatre. He has made a yeoman\'s contribution in reshaping, rejuvenating and energizing Indian theatre in post-colonial times. Vijay Tendulkar is particularly provoked by deformity in Indian society. All his plays display his concern for the middle class individual set against the back drop of a hostile society','','-','Mamta Upadhyay','71-75','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','22','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(311,'Determinants of Saving Behaviour of the Rural Households in India - a Micro Econometric Perspective','Household saving is usually the largest component of domestic savings in developing economies, especially the lower income, predominantly agricultural LDCs. The ability, willingness, and opportunity of households to save overtime can therefore significantly influence the rate and sustainability of capital accumulation and economic growth in developing countries. A few studies (Muraleedharan, D., 2008, Loayza, R. 2000, Shetty S.L., 1990, Joshi V.H, 1970) have been concentrated on the saving behaviour of the households both rural and urban areas in India. But in reality, the saving behaviour of the rural households is quite different from the saving behaviour of developed urban areas in India, as this is based on rural economy. Hence this study itself addressed to study the saving behaviour of rural households in general and agricultural households in particular in the districts of Visakhapatnam and Vizianagaram in the state of Andhra Pradesh.For convenience this study is organized into three sections viz., Section-I which is introductory to the study, the Objective, Methodology and Profile of the study area have also been presented in the same section. Section-II, which analyses the Model specification, problems with Ordinary linear regression, importance of Odds ratio, etc., and Section-III deals with the empirical results of logistic regression for the saving behaviour of the rural households and Conclusions','','-','Dr.Surya Prakasa Rao Gedela, Mr.Raju Paila','76-89','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','22','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(312,'POST TREATMENT OPTIONS FOR UASB REACTOR TREATING MUNICIPAL WASTEWATER','In current study an analytical and comparative study of post treatment options for UASB reactor treating municipal wastewater is presented. The two important post treatment alternatives viz. facultative waste stabilization pond and aerated lagoon are considered, lagoon and pond refer broadly to basins constructed in, or on the ground surface, using earthen dikes to retain the wastewater within which natural stabilization process occur with the necessary oxygen coming from atmospheric diffusion, photosynthetic and / or mechanical sources','','-','Pratibha Singh','90-98','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','22','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(313,'lsok xq.koRrk esa lgdkjh cSadksa dk Lfkku','mRrjk[k.M jkT; ds _fkds\'k uxj esa dk;Zjr lHkh cSadksa dks U;kn\'kZ ds :i esa pquk x;k A bu cSadksa esa LVsV cSad lewg] jkVh;d`r cSad] {ks=h; xzkeh.k cSad] lgdkjh cSad ,oa futh cSad lfEefyr gSaA v/;;u dh n`fV ls LVsV cSad ,oa lg;ksxh cSadksa dks lkoZtfud {ks= esa lfEefyr fd;k x;k gSA {ks= dh O;kolkf;d lajpuk vkSj tula[;k lforj.k dks /;ku esa j[kdj \'kks/k dks fjVsy cSafdax vkSj miHkksDrk cSafdax ij dsfUnzr j[kk x;k A loZs{k.k esa lfEefyr 1000 xzkgdksa esa izR;sd cSad lewg ds 250&250 lnL;ksa dk izfrfuf/kRo gSA kks/k fudkZ ladsr djrs gSa & o [kkrk [kqyokus dh izf;k esa xzkgd lgdkjh cSad dh lsok ls larq\"V gS] D;ksafd budk QkWeZ laf{kIr gS ,oa fcYdqy lhfer lwpuk;sa ekaxh tkrh gSaA ysfdu ;g xzkgd izksQkby j[kus dh n`f\"V ls vuqi;qDr gSA o tek@fudklh lEcU/kh O;ogkjksa ds lUnHkZ esa] lgdkjh cSad dk futh cSad ds ckn nwljk LFkku gS D;skafd ;gka HkhM+ dh leL;k ns[kus dks ugha feyrh gS ysfdu mRikn J`a[kyk dk lhfer gksuk] lhch,l cSafdax u gksuk] \'kk[kk dk vR;Ur lk/kkj.k okrkoj.k] ,Vh,e u gksuk vkfn ds fy;s budh \'kk[kkvksa dh izk;% vkykspuk gksrh gSA o iklcqd v|ru djus ds fo\"k; esa] losZ{k.k esa ladfyr xzkgdksa ds vfHker ds vuqlkj lgdkjh cSad ds [kkrk /kkjd lokZf/kd larq\"V gSaA lgdkjh cSad dh dk;Ziz.kkyh ,slh gS fd ogak izR;sd ysu&nsu ds ckn vfuok;Z :Ik ls iklcqd iwjh dj nh tkrh gSA o psd cqd lqfo/kk ds ekeyksa esa lgdkjh cSad dh fLFkfr larks\"ktud gS D;ksafd bu cSadksa esa dk;Ziz.kkyh ljyre gS vkSj izR;sd xzkgd dks O;fDrxr /;ku fn;k tkuk laHko gks tkrk gSA o lgdkjh cSad ds xzkgdksa ls lq>ko feyk gS fd bu cSadksa dks Hkh ,Vh,e dkMZ tkjh djus pkfg,] rkfd xzkgdksa dks 