ionship of various dimensions of organizational climate and job satisfaction of teachers in open  and closed climate school and also to  find the difference between teachers in open and closed climate schools on the variable of job satisfactions. Study is descriptive and comparative in nature.  200 teachers of senior secondary schools of Haridwar district of Uttarakhand were  chosen. The sample was chosen by the method of multistage randomization of clusters. The Organizational Climate Descriptive Questionnaire (OCDQ) developed by Halpin and Croft (1963) to know the type of organizational climate and Job Satisfaction Scale (JSS) developed by Meera Dixit (1993) to measure job satisfaction, were used for data collection. Mean, S.D., SEM, Skewness, Kurtosis, coefficient of correlation and t- test were applied to analyze the data. It is found that  some dimensions of organizational climate showed significant relationship with job satisfaction in open  and closed climate schools but some dimensions showed insignificant relationship with job satisfaction. There exists no significant difference between teachers in open and closed climate schools on the variable of job satisfaction in the present study','','-','Sushil Chandra Badoni','1-18','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(316,'Career Motivation among Tribal Women Students in relation to     Level of Education and Achievement Orientation','The present study was undertaken to study the career motivation among college and university level tribal women students of Himachal Pradesh in relation to their level of education and achievement orientation. The sample of 400 tribal women students pursuing different courses (namely arts, science and professional) was drawn from different colleges and H.P. University. The results reveal that level of education has a significant effect on the career motivation whereas achievement orientation does not have statistically any significant effect on the career motivation. As the level of education increases the career motivation also increases. This means that level of education and career motivation are significantly and positively correlated with each other. There is no significant interaction effect of level of education and achievement orientation on the career motivation of tribal women students.','','-','Romesh Chand,   Nisha Sharma','19-24','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(317,'HRD Climate Survey of Government Aided Senior Secondary Schools in Uttar Pradesh','We are able to determine the climate of a place through parameters developed by modern sciences we can similarly determine the climate of an organization through parameters developed by behavioral scientists. To-day the modern management can not ignore the Human Resource Development and Organizational Climate. It is now accepted fact that congenial HRD Climate is extremely important for the ultimate achievement of organizational objectives.  It can be said that organizational climate is manifestation of the attitudes of organizational members towards the organization itself. Organization climate or HRD climate is the human environment within which employees of the organization perform their tasks. It may refer to the environment of a department, unit or branch of an enterprise or the entire organization','','-','Naresh K Goyal','25-38','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(318,'Importance of Soft skills development in 21st century Curriculum','In the 21st centurys global economy, the new challenges  are there and the engineering profession have to face it, confirming  the need to restructure engineering curricula, teaching and learning practices, and processes, including assessment. Engineering graduates possessing merely technical knowledge, is no longer a guarantee for a successful career. As a professional, the aim of the student is to succeed in the career path they have chosen for themselves. They want to be the best at what they do and move forward. However, sometimes students might wonder why they are not getting the \"breaks\" they need. Basically they have the hard skills; the technical knowledge and skills that will ensure that they do their job to the highest level of quality. And while all countries are facing this dilemma, India is also struggling the most. It has been argued that most Indian engineering educational institutions are struggling with the systemic problem of centralization coupled with an archaic examination system that is detrimental to student learning.','','-','Garima Sharma, Preeti Sharma','39-44','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(319,'Developing Emotional Intelligence in Children - Role of Parents','How children develop? is one of the most mysterious questions facing all human beings. Parents seek to inculcate the best habits in their children and make efforts to make them significant contributors to the society. Intelligence is one of the many important factors in deciding the overall effectiveness of a child. A child of high intelligence separates himself out from the masses through his unique ability to perceive and interpret things. But in recent years, a person\'s interpretation of effectiveness is shifted towards the degree of emotional intelligence he possesses. The ability to be aware of emotions, how and why they affect behavior, good interpersonal relationships, stress free living and managing own feelings and the feelings of others attain equal importance. These skills are prerequisites to effective living. All parents should be aware of how these things contribute to high emotional intelligence. The present paper is an attempt to guide the parents about the ways and means through which they can nurture emotional intelligence in their children to make their life effective and constructive.','','-','Manoj Kumar Saxena , Suresh Aggarwal','45-52','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(320,'A Study of the Problems of Personality Adjustment in Relation to their Gender Differences and Societal Status','The present study deals with the facts of teachers on their personality traits. It is well known fact that personality perform a key role in their adjustment either physical, mental, social, emotional etc. The study shows that the female teachers feel a sense of hesitation in comparison of male teachers while sharing their views with unknown people. It also came out in the study that although the female teachers feel fatigue soonly, but their strength and liability boost them in struggling with future challenges. It was also brought out that the female teachers shares most of the talks with their friends, relatives, while the male teachers do not show such domestic problems with their friends or relatives. It also came out that the female teachers are more emotional and nervous in comparison of male teachers. By overall observation of the study, it may be stated that the female teacher perform a main role in the adjustment of societal, domestic duty etc.','','-','Pratap Singh Rana, Shakti Singh Rana','53-58','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(321,'Guidance Needs of Adolescents Studying in Jawahar Navodaya Vidyalayas in Himachal Pradesh','In the present scientific age, increasing complexities of life are becoming responsible for the need of guidance and guidance has been a vital aspect of education. The country\'s success in various fields depends on the proper guidance of adolescents. The students need guidance at each step of their life and mainly when they are in the growing and changing period of their life. The adolescents of today are the potent hope of the future and hence cannot be ignored in their guidance needs. Jawahar Navodaya Vidyalayas are the residential schools and the students studying in these schools are away from their family members. The focus of present research paper was to study the guidance needs of adolescents studying in Jawahar Navodaya Vidyalayas in Himachal Pradesh. A sample of 350 students of class 10+2 was selected from four Jawahar Navodaya Vidyalayas in Himachal Pradesh. The results of the present study revealed that the male and female adolescents studying in Jawahar Navodaya Vidyalayas have maximum need for vocational guidance and male adolescents have more need for guidance in psychological area than their female counterparts.','','-','Anup Kumar, Rajesh Kumar','59-64','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(322,'M -learning:  A New Approach to Learn Better','In the 21st century M-Learning is one of the important aspect of learning process which has enormous implications in the present education system. But in a country like India, which is not free from technical as well as social and educational challenges, M-Learning is one of the important and new methodologies adopted by the educators as an effective aspect of providing learning. M-learning aims at making the learning process more flexible, accessible and personalized. M-learning is the acquisition of any knowledge and skills using mobile technology. It is defined as the ability to complete access and manipulate data and communicate by using a mobile. It is also referred to as wireless learning. It enhances in mobility of the learner, interacting with portable technology, learning in a mobile society, improves access to information so that people can update their knowledge continuously to satisfy the demands, to improve cultural experiences of life. Over the past ten years, mobile learning has grown from a minor research interest to a set of significant projects in schools, higher education, workplaces etc. around the world.','','-','Mandeep Singh','65-72','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(323,'A Study on Moral Judgement Ability of Pre-adolescent Children (9-11 Year) of Public Schools.','The present study was carried out to study the moral judgment ability of pre-adolescent (9-11 years) of public school of yamunanager.\r\n	Moral judgment involves a cognitive capacity to define situation in terms of right and duties. Pre-adolescent can see themselves better from other people\'s view and thus develop awareness for moral issues. The sample consisted of 200 children, 100 of which were in the age group of 8 -9 years and 100 in the age group of 10-11 years. Sex ratio was also maintained. Moral judgment was measured by Moral judgment Test developed by Meera Verma and Durga Nand Sinha. Results revealed a significant difference in the moral judgment ability between two groups with older children (10-11 years) scoring higher than younger ones (8-9 years) , suggested that maturity is a necessary (through not sufficient) condition for development of moral judgment ability. Various antecedently conditions to morality were also studies among which mothers\' and fathers\' education was found to have a paramount effect on Childs\' moral judgment. But gender shows a negligible impact on moral judgment ability of the child.','','-','Pushkrit Gupta, Puja','73-86','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(324,'Socio-psychological and Educational Factors as Determinants of Differential Learning Rate in Modern Mathe','The study was aimed to find out socio-psychological and educational factors as determinants of differential learning rate in modern mathematics. Mathematical task was given to all the students in order to see their learning ability, total time of learning total trial taken and categorizing them into rapid, average and slow learners. Classroom behaviour scale was given to 14 teachers to take their opinion about these students. Descriptive statistics such as mean, SD and t-ratio were employed. Significant differences were obtained in the socio-economic status of average and slow learners and also between rapid and slow learners due to significant t-value.','','-','S.C. Gakhar, Seema Setia','87-92','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(325,'Environmental Ethics : Initiatives for The Removal of Environmental Problems','\"I am ,I plus my surroundings and if I do not preserve the later, \r\nI do not preserve myself \" \r\n           ( Jose Ortegay Garret, 1914 )\r\n	Environment etymologically means surroundings. It is the natural world of land, sea, air, plants and animals that exist around us. In layman\'s language environment encompasses everything that is around us. It includes interaction and relationship among the natural elements living, non-living and man made. It is the sum total of external factors, substances and conditions which influence organisms without their intrinsic part. The environment through invisible has it is common all living organism-man, animals and plants.','','-','Amar Jyoti','93-100','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(326,'Impact of manomaya kosh-sadhana on adolescents\' mental health and leadership capacity','The present study aims to present the effect of manomaya kosh-sadhana given by Pt. Shiram Sharma Acharya (founder of all World Gayatri Pariwar) on adolescents\' mental health and leadership capacity.  Quota Sampling has been used to collect the sample. The sample consisted of 30 adolescents (13-19) from Swami Satyamitrananda Giri higher secondary school, haripur kalan dist. Dehradun, Uttarakhand. Pre-post research design has been used in this study. The practice time was 30 minutes in the morning and the duration of the practice was 90 days (except Sunday and holidays). After 90 days again the post test has been taken for the experimental group. The result of t-test revealed that the manomaya kosh-sadhana has significant effect at .01 level on mental health and leadership capacity of the adolescents.','','-','Bharadwaj Ishwar, Indrani Nishad','101-108','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(327,'A Study of Elementary  Level School Education in Himachal Pradesh','This paper deals with status of elementary level school education in Himachal Pradesh. The results of this study indicated that there is tremendous growth in the enrollment of students at the elementary level. The HP Govt. is taking necessary steps regarding the infrastructure of schools and quality education. The teacher training programs under Sarva Shiksha Abhiyan are continuously organized by DIETs at block and state level. The study focuses on the various facilities provided by the Govt. on the schools like free text books, Mid Day Meal, scholarships, classrooms, drinking water and toilet facilities. It is found in the study that enrollment ratio of the students in the Private schools is continuously increasing and is the matter of concern for the Govt. the researcher tries to give some suggestions regarding the quality improvement in the teaching - learning process and other important concerns.','','-','Sanjeev Kumar','109-118','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(328,'A study  of teachers view /perceptions with regard to learning capacity and problems of students with special needs in inclusive education setting','This study intended to explore teachers view /perceptions with regard to learning capacity and problems of students with special needs in inclusive education setting at primary level in the state of Himachal Pradesh. The sample of the study, which was selected through purposive sampling. The sample comprised of 280 general teachers of primary schools and 20 resource teacher. As no standardized instruments suitable for this study could be found, one questionnaire was developed by the investigator. The results of the study revealed that view and perception of rural and urban teachers with regard to learning capacity and problem of children in inclusive setting are equal. And view and perception of rural and urban teachers with regard to learning capacity and problem of children in inclusive setting were found to be different.','','-','R.K. Parua, Kusum','119-124','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(329,'Child Labour: A Menace to Society','This paper highlights Child Labour as a social evil effecting not only child destiny but also the future of any nation. The first section of this article is an attempt to answer the following questions. What is Child Labour? How Child Labour is different from Child Work?  The second section focuses upon the prevalence of Child Labour in different sections of the society. Further it discusses in brief about the organizations which have already come forward to create greater awareness about eradicating Child Labour. It also discusses state-wise distribution of Child Labour in India. The third section points out various types of labour activities in India. The fourth section of this paper discusses some constraints like poverty, poor quality of education etc., due to which government and other agencies are unable to find any solution for the complete eradication of Child Labour. It further discusses how Education and child labour interact profoundly and how good quality education can keep children away from work. The Fifth section of this paper brings into light some of the classroom implications, that how these implications can develop awareness and understanding amongst students in order to prevent the damage that can be done to individuals, families and nation by Child Labour. In the final section of this paper some remedial measures are suggested to overcome the problem of Child Labour.','','-','Sudha Kumari, Sadaf Jafri','125-134','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(330,'Evaluation of Class Viii English Text-book Prescribed By Himachal Pradesh Board of  School Education','The owner of the house judges the quality of carpenters  work. The parents are constantly observing the effects of control in the behavior of his offspring, so it is with the teacher; he needs to ascertain the effectiveness of the text-books, methods and other curricular and co-curricular experiences. Evaluation of textbooks pinpoints the strengths and shortcomings and thus suggested ways of improvement. Therefore findings of the study on evaluation of English text-book for class 8th prescribed by Himachal Pradesh Board of School Education will give comprehensive future guidelines to text-book writers, policy planners and curriculum experts to make the best learning material available to the students. A sample of 200 English teachers was selected by using convenient sampling technique. On the basis of analysis and interpretation, general conclusions were drawn. The results of the present study revealed that vocabulary used for writing the contents in the text-book is difficult.','','-','Promila, Narbada Devi, Ranjana Kumari','135-138','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(331,'A Survey of Prescribed Activities in Ncert and Pseb Geometry Text Books Actually Being Practised In Schools of Punjab','In modern societies the world over, there is a strong emphasis on the provision of good quality Science, Technology and Mathematics (STM) education. Mathematics plays a pivotal role in STM education. Mathematics enhances creative and logical reasoning about problems in our inherently geometric world. Students\' mathematical competencies have been closely linked to their levels of geometric understanding. Various studies have documented that many students encounter difficulties and performed poorly in both middle and high schools geometry classrooms. Data from various studies indicate that the performance of Indian high school students in mathematics is mediocre. This suggests that students lack higher order thinking skills. The average Indian achievement in geometry is unsatisfactory.  Moreover, researches show a decline in students\' motivation toward mathematics. Among the variables that affect student learning, researchers have suggested that the teacher has the greatest impact on students\' motivation , mathematics learning and the primary source for justifying instructional decisions noted by the teachers was textbooks.','','-','Khushvinder Kumar, Vikas Kumar','139-142','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(332,'A Comparative Study of Environmental Awareness of Secondary School Teachers of Himachal Pradesh','In this paper, an attempt has been made to study the environmental awareness of secondary school teachers. For this purpose 100 secondary school teachers were randomly selected and Environmental Awareness Test developed by Dr.(Mrs.) Suman K. Katoch was administered to them. To find the significance of difference between the various groups \'t\'-test was applied. Results indicated that government and private secondary school teachers do not differ significantly in their environmental awareness. Further gender wise and locality wise secondary teachers differed significantly in their environmental awareness.','','-','Suman Kumari Katoch','143-150','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(333,'Job satisfaction of Government aided and Non government aided secondary school teachers: A comparative study','The present study was conducted for studying job satisfaction of the teachers of government aid and non government aid secondary schools of Kanpur city. : Job satisfaction scale (DJSS) is used for the present study. This scale was con The teachers working in government aided secondary school and non-government aided secondary schools did not differ in the level of their job satisfaction structed by Dr. (Mrs.) Meera Dixit of National Degree College, Lucknow. The results are- (a)The teachers working in government aided secondary school and non-government aided secondary schools did not differ in the level of their job satisfaction (b)female teachers of both the managements did not differ significantly in their job satisfaction.(c) Male teachers of the managements did not differ significantly in their job satisfaction.','','-','Kalpana Agnihotri, Anupma Yadav','151-156','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(334,'A Study of The Effect of Om Chanting On Neuroticism of Criminals','The present study emphasizes the effect of Om chanting on Neurotic problem of Criminal males. A sample of 20 subjects was selected through Incidental sampling form Northern India. The Neurotic Measurement Scale has been administered for the measurement of neurotic problem. The tool developed by M.P. Uniyal & Abha Rani Bisht. Pre-post Research design is used. Statistical analysis was done through t-test. The result of the study significantly reduced the neurotic problems of criminal through Om chanting.','','-','Vidhya Bhooshan verma, Noopur Jaiswal','157-160','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(335,'Effectiveness of Inquiry Training Model on Scientific Aptitude of Students at Secondary Level','Educational systems around the world are changing rapidly in response to technological and economic restructuring that is sweeping the societies. The question is how to integrate current and emerging technologies as an integral part instructional practices especially in teacher education area. Social, economic and technological changes of past decades are making teaching more crucial than ever. The information and knowledge society needs a continue change in the role and the working of teachers. Being a teacher in the knowledge society, one has to deal with new knowledge and new ways for imparting knowledge, It is generally agreed that the objectives to be achieved through the teaching learning process are multidimensional in nature. It is also felt that a particular method or technique may not be appropriate for achieving multidimensional objectives. This lead researcher to explore the use of various methods and techniques in an integrated fashion which resulted in development of new instructional strategies. During the last two decades many new methods and strategies of teaching have been developed, tested, modified, and adopted to different kinds of learning situation. Models of teaching are one of such innovation in teaching strategies.','','-','Raksha Pal Singh Raghav, Akhilesh Kumar Upadhyaya','161-168','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(336,'Justice  Delayed  is  Justice  Denied','People approach courts with the conviction   that they would get reprieve within a reasonable time. It has created an alarming situation. Major amendments in Civil Procedure Code were made in 1976, 1999, and 2002 for the speedy justice. The Criminal Procedure Code was reenacted in 1973, and again as per Malimath Committee report for speedy justice but the efforts has not bore any fruit. Establishment of fast track courts on the recommendation of XIth Finance Commission by central government has also not fulfilled the dreams.','','-','Sanjeev Kumar Chadha','169-172','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(337,'Cerebral Hemisphericity Preferences of Deprived Adolescents with Reference to Their Sex and Locality','In this paper the focus is on the interaction effect of deprivation with sex and locality on cerebral hemisphericity preferences of adolescents for their styles of learning and thinking. The sample (406) consisted 206 deprived and 200 non-deprived  subjects selected from 1200 students of class VIII, IX and X of Rohilkhand region  in Uttar Pradesh. To ascertain the objectives - Mean, Standard Deviation, t-test, ANOVA, and Scheffe test were used for the data treatment. On summarizing the findings it can be said that deprived boys have poor dominance of right/left hemisphere for learning and thinking style, where as they prefer integrated hemispheres dominantly as compared to non-deprived boys. Non deprived urban  adolescents seem to prefer more right/left hemispheric functions while deprived urban adolescents prefer more integrated functions of both hemispheres for few tasks.','','-','Rashmi Agarwal, Mohd. Yunus Hussain','173-182','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(338,'kFkfed Lrj ds v/;kidksa ds ewY;ksa dk rqyukRed v/;;u','vkt ge oSKkfud ;qx esa viuk thou O;rhr dj jgs gSaA euq\"; ds thou esa izR;sd {ks= dh f;kvksa esa oSKkfud n`f\"Vdks.k viuk;k tk jgk gSA oSKkfud vkfo\"dkjksa rFkk vkS|ksfxd fodkl us ekuoh; ewY;ksa ds Lo:i dks ifjofrZr dj fn;k gSA ubZ f\'k{kk uhfr 1986 esa ;g Lohdkj fd;k x;k gS fd vko\';d ewY;ksa ds u\"V gksus ds dkj.k lekt esa cgqr lh cqjkbZ;ka ,d laked chekjh ds :i esa Qsyrh tk jgh gSA vr% ;fn gesa viuk Hkfo\"; dgh lqfuf\'pr djuk gS rks gesa vius fxjrs gq, ewY;ksa ds Lrj  dks lq/kkjuk gksxk ftlds fy, f\'k{kk gh lcls lqn`<+ ek/;e gSA','','NA','vkbZ0vkj0,l0flU/kq, MkypUn','183-188','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','h',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(339,'lar dfo dchjnkl ds lkfgR; esa fufgr ewY;ksa dk orZeku esa \'kSf{kd fufgrkFkZ&,d v/;;u','izLrqr kks/k v/;;u lar dfo dchj ds lkfgR; dh iquZleh{kk ls lEcfUkr gSA ftlesa dchj nkl th ds lkfgR; esa vUrZfufgr ewY;ksa dk v/;;u dj orZeku kSf{kd lUnHkZ esa mudh mikns;rk dh O;k[;k djus dk iz;kl fd;k x;k gSA  v/;;udkkZ us v/;;u gsrq ,sfrgkfld&nkkZfud iz.kkyh dk iz;ksx fd;k gSA v/;;u esa dsoy vk/;kfRed] lkekftd] uSfrd] vkfFkZd ,oa jktuSfrd ewY;ksa ij /;ku dsfUnzr fd;k x;k gSA kksk v/;;u ds fudkZ ds :i esa v/;;udkkZ us LiV fd;k gS fd lar dfo dchj nkl }kjk izfrikfnr ewY;ksa dks orZeku kSf{kd O;oLFkk rFkk ikB~;e esa LFkku fn;k tk; rks u dsoy lkekftd lksp esa ifjorZu gksxk oju~ ckyd ds ln~fodkl esa Hkh ;s ewY; vkt Hkh izklafxd gSaA','','NA','jpuk ikBd, iznhi dqekj xqIrk','189-194','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30',