 of learned beliefs, attitudes and opinions that each person holds to be true about his or her personal existence. Self concept has important implication for positive existence, a significant variable for achievement and positive development in the society in every sphere. With this theoretical assumption the study aims at ascertaining the nature of the selected self-concept domains taken for the study (namely behaviour, Intellectual and school status, physical appearance and attributes, anxiety, happiness and satisfaction) of the normal adolescent students in terms of gender and finally suggests significant measures from a guidance and counselors perspective for a positive development of self concept among the adolescent. The sample (N=160) have been drawn by simple random sampling from male & female adolescent student from the selected schools of the Southern part of Kolkata. Descriptive statistics andt test has been done for statistical treatment. Findings reveal marked specificity the selected domains of self-concept with respect to gender (male and females adolescents)','','-','\"\"Santoshi Halder,  ;\r\nPoulumi Dutta\"','1-12','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(342,'Evaluating Scientific Comprehension of a story: An Innovative Approach','The students have already learnt certain scientific principles over a period of seven years of their elementary education which may have helped them in constructing certain concepts. Students are able to visualize and directly experience the immediate applicability, in their day to day life and surroundings, of many of the concepts that they have learnt in science. This allows them for better scope of constructing their own knowledge and understanding about many of the events / phenomenon which they observe in the environment. Science helps in alerting teachers to the function of prior learning and existing concepts in the process of learning new material, by stressing the importance of understanding as a goal of science instruction, by fostering pupils engagement in lessons and other such progressive matters. However, the traditional approach of evaluating students knowledge has less scope for students to express their constructed knowledge. In this regard, an attempt was made by the authors of this paper to make use of an unconventional approach of evaluating the students and thus giving a scope to the students for revelation of the constructed knowledge.','','-','Jyotsna Amin, R. C. Patel','13-24','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(343,'Cognitive and Metacognitive Aspects of Learning Styles of Prospective Secondary Teachers in Relation to Teaching Aptitude and Self-Esteem','In the literature, learning styles are very often considered as a kind of general strategy of learning, for example characterized as surface-level or deep-level processing (Marton & Saljo, 1976), a holistic, vs a serialistic style (Pask, 1976, 1988), deep processing, elaborative processing, fact retention and methodical study (Schmeck, 1983). But learning styles are also described as types of learning like, for example, (a) concrete experience, (b) reflective observation, (c) abstract conceptualization and (d) active experimentation, resulting in four learning styles: divergers, accommodators, convergers and assimilators  (Kolb, 1976), as orientations like achieving, meaning, reproducing and non-academic (Entwistle, 1988), or as approaches to learning like surface, deep and achieving (Biggs, 1993).','','-','Surender Sharma, Reena Sharma','25-36','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(344,'ICT in Teacher Education : A Retrospection for Improvising Presentation Practices','ICT, day-by-day, is widening its wings in almost every field of human life with a lot of utilitarian scope. ICT has a lot of scope in the field of education especially in teacher education. It can improve the practices and procedures (Cohen, Manion, Morrison, 2005 Harris, 2001).\r\n In various universities, presentation on a certain topic is a vital and important part of the teaching-learning process in teacher-education courses. Students are allotted or they select an appropriate topic for their presentations. They prepare and present it in front of peer-group. After the presentation, feedback can be given and practice can be improved by the teacher. While giving feedback some major and important aspects can be left neglected due to lack of attention and overlapping of conversational aspects. Moreover individualization of observations can result in severe lacunae in feedback and improvement. So the question arises, how to improve presentation practices?\r\nIn the present study, to overcome problems in this regard and improve the practices, ICT was adopted as a means for maximizing the efficiency in observation, recall, confirmation, procedure and practices. A sample of students undergoing teacher-education course was taken for the study. In this study, a camcorder (video camera) followed by the computer with Windows Media Player was used to record the presentations and later the ranking was done by all the participants for presentations. Depending upon the ranking, various aspects were discussed to place a presentation at a suitable place. Detailed discussion was held for the presentations which were given extreme ranks viz highest and lowest one. It was possible, due to ICT, to retrospect the extremities and discuss the lacunae for improvement. As a result of the study certain issues and points came up as measures (Green list and Red list) for betterment of the practice. Moreover it depicted a hierarchical emphasis to be given to the various aspects of a presentation.','','-','Vinod Kumar Kanvaria','37-46','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(345,'A Comparative Study of the Adjustment of Hostler and Non-Hostler Female Students.','The purpose of the study was to determine if there is any difference between hostler and non- hostler female students in different dimensions of adjustment. The data were collected from random cum purposive sample of 200 female students (100 hostler and 100 non- hostler) of Kanpur city by using adjustment inventory of A.K.P Sinha and R.P.Singh. Data was analyzed by using mean and S.D and t test which revealed that there is no significant difference between social and educational adjustment of hostler and non hostler female students but found significant difference between emotional adjustment of hostler and non hostler girls students.','','-','Sangeeta Chauhan, Saroj Yadav','47-52','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(346,'Effect of Ron Davis Approach and Eclectic Approach on Word Fluency of Dyslexic Children','Dyslexia is one of the most common occurring reading disabilities. It is evident when accurate and fluent word reading and spelling develops incompletely despite conventional instructions adequate intelligence and educational opportunities. A research was conducted to study the effect of Ron Davis approach and Eclectic approach on word fluency among primary school dyslexic children. Sample for the study consisted of thirty students of third and fourth grades, which were identified from the ten English medium schools of Nawanshahr. Pre-test Post-test control group design was used to compare the effectiveness of Ron Davis approach and Eclectic approach as remedial strategies. Ron Davis approach was based on Davis Dyslexia Correction Programme of Ron Davis that originated in 1984 in California and is being applied worldwide by facilitators in six different languages. What separates this approach from the others is the fact that students are guided verbally and visually to obtain an orientation point. In the Eclectic approach the researcher used Alphabetic Phonic Method, Behavior Modification Method as well as Multisensory Structured Linguistic Method as broad range approaches to provide remedial instructions. Both these approaches were employed to the two experimental groups of ten students each, for the sixty sessions of thirty minutes duration. Analysis of co-variance (ANCOVA) was used as a statistical technique for analyzing the data. It was found that both Ron Davis approach and Eclectic approach were significantly superior to traditional approach for improving the word fluency of dyslexic children. At the same time it was also found that Ron Davis approach and Eclectic approach were not significantly different for improving the word fluency of dyslexic children.','','-','Khushvinder Kumar, Rekha','53-60','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(347,'A Study of Self-Confidence, Inferiority and Insecurity Feeling as related to Academic Achievement','The present research paper deals with the academic achievement, self-confidence, inferioirty and insecurity feeling of school going students. For obtaining the self-confidence, inferiority & insecurity feeling scores, a sample of hundred students was taken and devided into two parts i.e., 50 high & 50 low academic achiever. The self-confidence scores was determined with the help of ASCI (Agnihotris Self-Confidence Inventory) and their inferiorly & insecurity feeling was measured with the help of Inferiority & Insecurity Questionnaires. The results revealed that students with high academic achievement showed higher level of self-confidence than low academic achiever students. There was significant relationship between academic achievement and inferiority feeling, i.e. students belonging to upper academic achievement in school showed lower level of inferiority than students in lower academic achiever. Whereas, students who are high academic achiever in their school showed the lower level of insecurity feeling than low academic achiever students.','','-','Vikas Kumar Sharma','61-68','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(348,'Pre-service trainees attitude towards Inclusive Education','The inclusion of learners with special educational needs in general education is becoming more prevalent. As a result, various special education researchers have begun to examine the success of inclusion, as well as the attitudes and beliefs of general educators towards the inclusion of learners with disabilities in the general education classroom. In the present study, pre service trainees attitudes towards inclusive education were investigated. The participants were full time students of the Central Institute Of Education, Delhi University, New Delhi Jamia Millia Islamia, New Delhi and M.D.University, Rohtak. These students are registered for the Bachelor of Education and Master of Education programmes. The students were being taught in Bilingual. The sample comprised of 122 students, fifty seven males and sixty five females. Convenient sampling design employed. A questionnaire developed and standardized by the investigator (2005) was adapted and was used as a measuring instrument to record the responses of the research respondents. The adapted questionnaire comprised of the following sections: Biographical details, Attitudes towards inclusive education, Requirements for competency, Requirements for successful inclusion and Attitudes towards learners with Special Needs. Data were analyzed using descriptive statistics. The research participants were generally found to have positive attitudes toward inclusive education. The results of this investigation are significant in the sense that the understanding of pre-service trainees attitudes is critical for the successful implementation of inclusive education, (Mowes, 2005; Elloker, 2009; Gadium, 2007; Dover, 2005; & Mckeskey & Waldrom, 2007).','','-','Susanta Kumar Pathy','69-82','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(349,'Studying the Level of Emotional and Spiritual Intelligence of Student Teachers in A.M.U','It is generally assumed that people with high I.Q will naturally accomplish more in life. But new researches indicate that persons emotional intelligence and spiritual intelligence might be a greater predictor of success than his/her intellectual intelligence. The aim of the education is all round holistic development of the students. In pursuit of this goal, teacher plays a significant role. Emotionally and spiritually intelligent teachers help students with improved motivation, enhanced innovation, increased performance, effective use of time and resources, improved leadership qualities and improved team work. Hence, it is essential to develop both emotional and spiritual intelligence of student teachers during preservice in department of education. The present study aims at studying the level of emotional and spiritual intelligence of randomly selected 60 student teachers holding the post graduate degree in teaching subjects in the Department of Education in Aligarh Muslim University.','','-','Anjum Ahmed','83-90','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(350,'Job Satisfaction and Value Pattern Among Rural and Urban Secondary School teachers','This paper is an attempt to compare the rural and the urban secondary school teachers on job satisfaction and their value pattern. Sample comprised of 150 secondary school teachers of the Mandi district of Himachal Pradesh. To find out the job satisfaction job satisfaction scale developed by Brayfield and Rathore and preferred value pattern of secondary school teachers using Teacher Values Inventory developed by Dr. (Mrs.) Harbhajan L. Singh and Dr. S.P. Ahluwalia were used. It were concluded from the study that there exist significant differences in job satisfaction and value pattern among rural and urban secondary school teachers. Rural secondary school teachers were more satisfied with their job as compare to their counterpart. Further, Rural secondary school teachers were more Economical, Aesthetic and Social whereas urban secondary school teachers were more Theoretical, Political and Religious.','','-','Ajay Kumar Attri','91-96','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(351,'Socio-economic status as correlate of self-concept of secondary school students','Self-concept, as the persons total view about himself or herself (Hamacheck, 1987) defined as those perceptions, beliefs, attitudes, and feelings which the individual views as part of characteristics of him/herself. It is his/her own conception of his/her health and physique, intellectual abilities, academic status, temperamental qualities, mental health, emotional tendencies and socio-economic status. The present study is an attempt to explore the relationship between students self-concept and socio-economic status in a sample of 166 adolescents. The results of the study revealed self-concept to be positively correlated with socio-economic status on physical, educational & intellectual dimension. However, the correlation of social, moral & temperamental dimension of self-concept of adolescents is found significantly negative with socio-economic status indicating that for positive self-concept development among adolescents, basic thinking of students  belonging to below average socio-economic status about themselves and their ability to perform independently should be changed .The study has implications for educationists and parents as well.','','-','Anju Gupta','97-106','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(352,'A Comparative Study of Vocational Preferences of Students Studying at Intermediate Level','In the present study, an attempt has been made to investigate the comparison of vocational preferences of boys and girls of Intermediate level. Vocational preferences are the process of assisting the individual to choose an occupation, prepare for it, enter upon and progress in it. It concerns with individuals decisions and choices which is involved in future planning. In this study, the researcher wants to know the vocational preferences and the reason for the choice of vocations of boys and girls of intermediate level. The self made tool of vocational interest questionnaire was administered on the 90 male and 90 female students at Intermediate level of Meerut. The vocational preferences of boys and girls students were note down and mean value and percentage were calculated. It was found that there is a significant difference between the vocational preferences of boys and girls studying at Intermediate level.','','-','Prachi Pachauri, Leena Sharma','107-114','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(353,'Learning Achievement of Elementary School Children of West Garo Hills District of Meghalaya','Education is indeed a fundamental right of every Indian child and each child should take admission in schools to get a good and value based quality education. In view of such critical issues and their importance, an effective and qualitative education system is required to be implemented. Though, there are a number of factors which determine the quality of education, the most vital one that attracts the attention of one and all is the level of achievement which needs to be known periodically to keep a label on the general health of the education system. Thats why such a requirement warranted conducting of this learners achievement survey at class IV and VII stages of school education in West Garo Hills District of Meghalaya. Here in this study, students performance has been assessed by developed achievement tests on Mathematics and language and teachers head teachers view through questionnaire and schedule.  Normative survey method for data collection and, multistage random sampling design was used for the selection of 25 govt. LPS and 25 Govt./Govt Aided UPS from five Blocks, 30 head teachers, 45 LPS and 57UPS teachers and 195 children from class IV and 281 children from class VII as the total sample of this study. Mean, S.D., t test and percentage were used for data analysis where findings were asserted that there was significant differences on achievement of primary school children from class IV & VII i. e. gender and location wise. Many habitations were far away from the need of basic education, lack of good learning environment, lack of teaching learning materials, lack of trained teachers, less community involvement, and high ignorance about different schemes implemented by governments, faulty curriculum transaction in one hand and on the other hand the failure of different programmes, improper use and non use of different grants, unscientific use of methods and medias, unsystematic and stereotyped arrangement of training programmes, teachers faulty cla','','-','Siba Charan Subudhi','115-126','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(354,'Criteria for Evaluating Quality of Research In Education : International Perspectives','Universities and centers of higher education throughout the world today are expected to be both efficient and accountable and have reasonable standards in educational research. For last two decades, there has been growing concern at national and international levels  about the increasing cost of funding university-based research .and the need to obtain value for money for public expenditure on higher education.  In response, many governments have implemented mechanisms that attempt to relate funding to performance. Evaluation has thus emerged as key issue to ensure reasonable and measurable standards. \r\nEvaluations of educational research provide data on the research activities within a country. Transparent and objective way of examining research activity determines the quality of research.  Many countries have introduced various models of evaluation of educational research reflecting global demands for quality and accountability.  This paper compares various models used across the countries. Analysis of these models would provide insights and cues which would make it possible for the research communities to identify more valid, reliable methods and a comprehensive set of norms to judge the quality in educational research.','','-','Arun K. Gupta, D.R.Kapoor','127-138','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(355,'A Comparative Study of Favourable And Unfavourable Family Climate of the Hearing Impaired Students Adjustment.','The present investigation was undertaken to study the adjustment (social, emotional, educational and total adjustment) of hearing impaired students in relation to their family climate. The sample of the study consisted of 135 hearing impaired students from VI, VII and VIII class of Rajkiya Mook Badhir Vidyaya of Bareilly city. Researcher used family climate scale by Prof. Beena Shah for measuring the family climate of the hearing impaired children. (2) Adjustment Inventory for school students by Prof, A.K.P Sinha and Prof. R.P. Singh for measuring the adjustment of hearing impaired children. t-test revealed that 1) The emotional adjustment of the students of unfavourable family climate was better than student of favourable family climate. 2) Hearing impaired girls were found more social in comparison to boys. 3) There is a significant difference between boys and girls of unfavourable family climate.\r\nKey words:  Hearing Impairment, Adjustment, Favourable Family Climate, Unfavourable Family Climate.','','-','Ranjana Ruhela','139-140','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(356,'Changing Pattern of Cultivation and Sustainable Rural Development: A Case of Organic Farming','Indian agrarian system was based on the traditional knowledge and practices handed down from generation to generation. This could not produce enough to feed the increasing population. Introduction of high-yielding varieties of seeds after mid 1960s and the increasing use of fertilizers and irrigation are known collectively as the Green Revolution, which enabled the country to increasing in production and made India self-sufficient in food grains. Use of modern agricultural technologies led to evection of share cropping tenants and increasing use of daily wage workers, pauperization of rural population, increased disparity between rich and poor and proportionate increase in the marketable surpluses. As a result of Green Revolution production of food grains has increased four-fold, from 50.82 million tones in 1950-51 to 211.2 million tones in 2001-2002. Fertilizer consumption has increased 250 times, from 69,000 tones during 1950-51 to 17.4 million tones. On the other hand, consumption of pesticides has increased from 160 tones in 194849 to 64,000 tones in 2002-2003. Agriculture with the help of modern technology has helped India not only to produce enough food for own consumption but also to generate surpluses for exports. Although a large section of population is leaving below poverty line even today. Organic farming is recognized as the best known alternative to the farming system for 2nd green revolution in India. It is found that organic agriculture is gaining momentum as an alternative method to the agriculture with modern technologies introduced during green revolution. Both consumer and farmers are now gradually shifting back to organic farming in India. It is believed by many that organic farming is healthier. Though the health benefits of organic food are yet to be proved, consumers are willing to pay higher premium for the same. Many farmers in India are shifting to organic farming due to the domestic and international demand for organic food. Further st','','-','Anil Kumar Saini','149-156','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(357,'A Comparative Study of the Influence of School Climate and Culture on the Academic Achievement of Secondary Students in the Schools with High and Low Academic Achievement','There are various types of schools in which school climate and culture are not in proper way. In schools physical, social, affective & academic environment should be good. Physical attributes are such as building, furniture, playground, light, water etc. Psychological attributes are such as satisfaction, moral, trust; openness and cooperation are not available in proper way. In every school, school culture includes values, symbols, beliefs and shared meanings of parents, students and teachers and others conceived as a group or community. School culture also includes a social customs, traditions, historical accounts, norms, expectations, common meanings and shared assumptions. Academic achievement of students depends on a large number of activities both within and beyond the classroom. Therefore school climate and culture influences the academic achievement of the students. In this study the impact of school climate and  culture are investigated for the academic achievement of students.','','-','K.N. Gupta','157-164','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(358,'E-Learning in Higher Education : Its Challenges and Benefits','Advances in computers and Multimedia technology have changed traditional methods for learning and skills training. Online learning continues to play a major role in the success of any academic program. Such learning can personalize learning needs for students; it can provide an environment where virtual reality techniques are used to create interactive interfaces and real time software can monitor every response made by the user. E-learning is the learning experience that is delivered or enabled by electronic technology. The delivery of learning or content can be through the intranets, extranets or over the Internet, via CD-ROM Interactive TV, or satellite broadcast.  For the educational innovator, who seriously wishes to improve the quality of education and the learning experience, it is imperative that we create an education system that is clear about its values and sets its aims and ambitions high, and that is capable of rapid adaptation to its technological, as well as its social, cultural and political environment. The argument developed over this article suggests that we can do this if we exert some influence over the way in which e-learning is used in universities, and direct its power overtly towards the needs of learners.','','-','Alka Saxena,Poonam Padaliya','165-172','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(359,'The Challenges of Combating HIV And AIDS in African Universities: A Moral Perspective','HIV and AIDS have challenged the world in an alarming manner and has become a daunting threat to humanity and more so here in Africa.  It is an epidemic that has infected and affected millions of people to the extent of destroying any form of national development. As a challenge, HIV and AIDS has eaten into human and material resources and has put a lot of pressure on households as well as organizations that deal with humanity, making them to loose skilled and energetic manpower hence, human productivity has been drastically reduced to almost zero. The pandemic has impacted adversely on the education sector and affected quality, access, equity, supply and demand of educational services. To reverse the devastating situation, there is of dire need for collective responsibility in combating the spread of this pandemic. This paper deals with the delicate issues of HIV and AIDS and the role of the university community in Africa. It is contextualized within the Kenyan universities, but it can equally apply elsewhere in other African universities and the world at large where universities are challenged to develop policies that would effectively respond to HIV and AIDS issues. It is imperative to educate the people of Kenya, Africa and the whole world in general on all issues pertaining to HIV and AIDS since education is an essential element in prevention of HIV infection and its impact. Hence, properly and broadly carried out, preventive education works play a key role in combating HIV and AIDS and also in mitigating its effects on individuals, families and society. There is therefore, the need to scale up the campaign on behaviour change among the university community who are the think tank and cream of society. Such campaigns would demystify the myths surrounding the disease and in turn empower the people to make informed and responsible moral and social choices. This would enable the continent to attain the Millennium Development Goals (MDGs) of halting and reversing th','','-','Matthew Theuri M, Joseph M. Wamutitu','173-180','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(360,'Good Governance in New Era of Globalization','Good governance has been receiving considerable attention in political discourse in India. In fact, the term good governance is used so widely now that it is coming to replace in popularity that other buzz word of the eighties and nineties. A set of strategies to achieve good governance is being put forward by international lending agencies such as World Bank as also by our own government. But, still miles to go in all these aspects in order to implement the ideal of corporate governance which implies three basic conditions: (a) governance from below, (b) transparency and through it accountability; (c) corruption free governance. Reforms in these fields in an era of globalization are hoped to be affected whether the political masters want it or not but the pace on the political level will that is emerging in near future.','','-','Manoj Kumar','181-188','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','23','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(361,'fo\"k; % osnksa esa fufgr i;kZoj.k laj{k.k','osn izfr ds mUeqDr izkax.k esa jfpr os xzaFk gSa] tks lnSo gj {ks= esa ekuo tkfr dk ekxZnkZu djrs jgs gSaA vkt tcfd /kjrh dh izlo/kfeZrk gh nkWo ij yx pqdh gS] vkdkk] ty] ok;q lHkh dh LoPNrk ij ladV ds ckny eaMjk jgs gSa] gekjk /;ku lgt gh osnkas dh vksj vkV gks tkrk gSA ekuoh; lH;rk dh fodkl ;k=k esa Ik;kZoj.k&laj{k.k dh n`fV ls osnksa dk egRo v{kq..k jgk gSA osnksa us rks izkphu dky ls gh Ik;kZoj.k dk laj{k.k fd;k gS rFkk osnksa esa igys ls gh ;g fl) fd;k tk pqdk gSA i;kZoj.k ds fuekZ.k esa Hkh pkj osnk