ed Media','The objective is to optimize recombinant E. coli containing anticannine virus on undefined media instead of L.B. media.Study was carried on recombinant E. coli grown on undefined media and adding different components for better growth. Molasses is used a undefined media. There was better growth of recombinant E. Coli in molasses by adding some components like yeast extract. DNA concentration is much better in Molasses than L.B. media. Additional 5% yeast extract in molasses catalyzes better growth. Plasmid copy number is also high in this media. Yeast extract more than 5% is increasing the toxicity and cells starts dying.','','-','Sheetal Swaroop, Nirant Sharma, Krishan Pal','243-248','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','15','20','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(367,'Impact of Communication in International Business-to-Business Marketing Channels with Special Reference to Culture','Communication plays an important role in international business. As business-to-business marketing channels become more international in scope, communication in channels occurs among a more diverse set of channel participants from different national cultures. What is the impact of cultural variations on channel communications and how? This study examines the impact of communication in international business-to-business marketing channels comprised of channel members representing different cultural contexts. The findings show that there is a relationship between culture and channel communication in international channels. This influence stemming from cultural distance may have significant implications as business moves into the Ecommerce era of Internet-based B2B international channels of distribution.','','-','Manu Pathak, Sonia Gupta','249-255','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','15','20','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(368,'Conflict, Constitutional and Developmental News in Print: How Does the Press in Gilgit-Baltistan Treat Them?','Media and journalism in the Gilgit-Baltistan are operating under some of the worst conditions in the world. Government control of media, illiteracy, and lack of access to information as well as financial and social constraints are some of the issues limiting the populations\' access to truth and complete information. The main objective of this study is to investigate the local newspapers coverage on constitutional status of Gilgit-Baltistan, Development news coverage and conflicts coverage especially sectarian conflicts coverage in local newspapers of Gilgit-Baltistan. The method of content analysis has been adopted to study the questions.','','-','Zafar Iqbal, Ghulam Shabir, Rashid Hussain Saami','257-271','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','15','20','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(369,'Stress Management at Work Place','There is a growing awareness of how stress adversely affects organizational efficiency. The implementation of stress management programs to counteract the problem of stress with in the organization. The workplace has become a high stressful environment in many organizations cutting across industries. Employees are experiencing high level of stress due to various factors such as high workload, tight deadlines, high targets, type of work, lack of job satisfaction, long working hours, pressure to perform, etc. Interpersonal conflicts at the workplace, such as boss-subordinate relationships and relationships with peers, were also a source of stress.\r\nThe dysfunctional aspects of stress could directly impact an organization\'s performance and also affect the well-being of its employees. Stress at the workplace is linked to absenteeism, higher attrition, and decreased productivity. Stress lead to fatigue, irritability, poor communication, and quality problems/errors. High stress levels also affected the morale and motivation of the employees. Stress without effective coping mechanisms could lead to a host of physical and mental problems.','','-','Vidushi Bhatnagar','273-279','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','15','20','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(370,'Application of Lexicographic Goal Programming in Downstream Oil Industries','This paper presents a lexicographic goal programming (LGP) model for management decision-making in petroleum refinery industry for distribution of oil to the various depots. The model presented in the paper is designed to illustrate how LGP can be used as an aid for solving transportation problems with multiple objectives. The data for the study has been used from a petroleum refinery industry in India.','','-','A.K.Bhargava, Divya Bansal, A.B.Chandramouli and Arun Kumar','281-289','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','15','20','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(371,'An integrated inventory model under inflationary environment with capacity constraints and lead-time','In the present study, we have explored a three echelon supply chain, comprising of a supplier, a retailer and end customers. The whole environment of business dealings has been assumed to be inflationary, which conforms to the practical market situation. The supplier experiences the problem of lead time at his end. So even though the retailer has placed the order, he has to wait for the supplier to deliver. The lead time of the supplier is a probability density function of his managing cost. The more the supplier is ready to spend as managing expenses, smaller will be the lead time and vice versa. However, there is a constraint upon the amount the supplier can afford to spend; hence there is capital constraint also involved. Due to the life time in the rented warehouse, the product has no deterioration in the rented warehouse but in the own warehouse, the product has deterioration. There is even an expiration date beyond which the product cannot be used. Hence, the retailer plans out his cycle to finish off his inventory before the product reaches its expiration date. As a matter of fact, the retailer takes the length of the lifetime of the product to be his planning horizon and does not wish to retain inventory after that date. The setup has been explored numerically as well, an optimal solution has been reached at, and the sensitivity of that solution has also been checked with respect to various system parameters.','','-','Neeraj Kumar, S. R. Singh, & Rachna Kumari','291-306','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','15','20','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(372,'An Integrated Inventory Model with Stock Dependent Demand, Weibull rate of deterioration and Partial shortages','An optimal ordering decision for the producer - supplier  retailer chain is developed when the suppliers lead-time is considered. Here we develop a deterministic inventory model with variable deterioration and stock dependent demand. In this model the unsatisfied demand is partially backlogged, which depends on waiting time.','','-','Vikramjit Singh, Anubhav Partap Singh and Anand Chauhan','307-321','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','15','20','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(373,'Volume Flexibile Inventory Model For Unsystematic Rate of Deterioration With Lost Sales','We developed a deterministic and Probabilistic inventory model for unsystematic deteriorating items with exponential demand under volume flexibility, unsystematic deterioration of an item (food items or pharmaceuticals) depends upon the fluctuation of humidity, temperature etc. This is more sensible and logical. In our model we have assumed the deterioration functions depend upon a parameter with time. So consider an unsystematic rate of deterioration and shortages are allowed with partial backlogging, Because the occurrence of shortage is a natural phenomenon. And we also considered the backlogging rate is to be exponential decreasing function of time. \r\nSimilarly, the same assumption to develop a probabilistic inventory model, the probability density function of demand is negative exponential rate, which is a function of exponential distribution. And Holding cost is a non linear function of time. This model further can be extended with inflation and stochastic backorder rate.','','-','Anand Chauhan, Pankaj Kaushal  and Anubhav Partap Singh','323-336','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','15','20','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(374,'Optimal Ordering Policy for Deteriorating Items for credit linked Payment Time','In this article, the retailers optimal ordering policy and payment time permitted by the supplier is computed when trade credit is linked to payment time. The units in inventory are subject to constant deterioration. The retailer can opt for longer delay period offered by the supplier. The offer of credit period to delay the settlement of the account against the due purchases by the supplier to the retailer boosts his demand and attracts more retailers. Mathematical models have been developed to obtain the optimal cycle time and optimal payment policy for deteriorating items. Numerical example is given to validate the proposed model and managerial insights are also suggested.','','-','Sujata Rani and Sarla Pareek','337-350','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','15','20','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(375,'Effect of Life Time on An Inventory Model For Decaying Items with and Without Shortages','In this paper, we considered an EOQ inventory system for non-instantaneous deteriorating items with stock and time dependent demand rate, where suppliers offer an all unit quantity discount. In real life situations, there are certain condition that demand depends upon both stock and time. We also considered two cases: In the first case, shortages are not allowed and in the second case, shortages are allowed with partially backlogged. Special cases and cost minimization technique are also used in this study.','','-','Ravinder Kumar Arya, S. K. Shakya','351-365','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','15','20','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(376,'A Production Inventory Model for Time Dependent Decaying Item with Ramp Type Demand Rate and Inflation','NA','','-','S.K.Shakya and Ravinder kumar Arya','393-402','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','17','16','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(377,'An Inventory Model of Decaying Products with Life Time and Variational Demand','In this paper, an order level inventory for deteriorating items with life time has been discussed. Shortages are considered and fully backlogged. The demand rate has been considered of the form that first it increases linearly, then it remains constant and finally it decreases to zero in the shortage period. Such type of demand rate is more realistic. This model is interesting as it deals with wide variety of consumer demand behaviors. Cost minimization technique has been used to solve the inventory problem under consideration.','','-','Hari Kishan, Megha Rani, Sarvendar Saroha','1-12','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','25','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(378,'Integrated Inventory Policy with Linear Demand and Time Dependent Deterioration','This paper develops a joint optimal vendor buyer policy for deteriorating items with salvage value. The model is subjected to linear time dependent demand rate and time dependent Weibull deterioration rate. A numerical example is given to show that the joint approach result gives a significant cost reduction when compared with an individual decision by the buyer.','','-','Amit Sharma, Ruchi Goel, Shivraj Singh','13-26','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','25','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(379,'A New Cutting Plane Method for Finding the Integer Solution to the Problem of Allocating Sample Sizes in Stratified Sampling','Many cuts have been developed to solve integer programming problems. In this paper, we have proposed new cuts to solve the problem of allocating sample sizes in stratified sampling formulated as an integer non linear programming problem (INLPP). Integer solution is obtained using enumerative technique. An example is given to illustrate the procedure.','','-','Yashpal Singh Raghav, Irfan Ali and Abdul Bari','27-31','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','25','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(380,'Employee Drives, Motivation and Expectations from the Management','It is important to research and study the needs, drives, motivation and expectations of people we hire or employ, and aim at responding to and satisfying those, as it is with regard to customers. The study examined the ranked importance of drives and motivational factors of employees in organization. This addressed drives and motivation factors in the context of employee motivation theory. Finding suggest that inner drives like job security, interesting work and motivational factors like good pay/wages etc. are key to higher motivation. Carefully designed reward system i.e. job enlargement, job enrichment, promotions, internal and external stipends, monetary and non-monetary compensation, specific needs, drives, aspirations, capabilities, securities, self development, plan for future, expectations etc. should be considered.','','-','Prahlad Prasad','33-40','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','25','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(381,'Homotopy Perturbation Method for Solving ReactionDiffusion Equations','This work presents a homotopy perturbation method (HPM) to develop solution of the linear and nonlinear reactiondiffusion equations (KolmogorovPetrovslyPiskunov Equations). Reactiondiffusion equations have special importance in engineering and sciences, and constitute a good model for many systems in various fields. One of the newest analytical methods to solve linear and nonlinear equations is the application of homotopy perturbation techniques. The HPM deforms a difficult problem into a simple problem which can be easily solved. The results are compared with MATLAB solutions.','','-','Sanjeev Kumar and Ravendra Singh','41-52','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','25','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(382,'Analysis of Steady-State Solution of M/M (a, b)/1 with Queuing System','Analyzing bulk arrival, bulk service queues in steady state, where customers arrive in groups at a point and wait for next available group of customers. Under this policy the bulk queue with no control, the customer on arriving, will accept customers up to the capacity of the system and then leave independent of the number of customer waiting. The available capacity of the customers is assumed to be random but independent of length of the queue or the capacity of all previous customers. In this research paper we have discussed the Steady State Probability Distribution and Waiting Time Distribution with bulk service system with the finite waiting space by the method of state transition rate. The system under consideration is a queuing system with Poisson arrivals, general service time, and single server and where service is preformed on batches of random size and also obtains some of the particular cases with bulk service.','','-','Jitendra Kumar, Vikas Shinde  and B. B. Singh','53-62','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','25','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(383,'Second Order Convex Duality for Multi-Objective Fractional Programming Problem with Support Functions','A second order dual is formulated for a multi-objective fractional programming with support functions.','','-','G. VaralakshmiP, G. Sarada','63-70','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','25','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(384,'Determinants of Saving Behaviour of the Rural Households in India-a Micro Econometric Perspective','Household saving is usually the largest component of domestic savings in developing economies, especially the lower income, predominantly agricultural LDCs. The ability, willingness, and opportunity of households to save overtime can therefore significantly influence the rate and sustainability of capital accumulation and economic growth in developing countries. A few studies (Muraleedharan, D., 2008, Loayza, R. 2000, Shetty S.L., 1990, Joshi V.H, 1970) have been concentrated on the saving behaviour of the households both rural and urban areas in India. But in reality, the saving behaviour of the rural households is quite different from the saving behaviour of developed urban areas in India, as this is based on rural economy. Hence this study itself addressed to study the saving behaviour of rural households in general and agricultural households in particular in the districts of Visakhapatnam and Vizianagaram in the state of Andhra Pradesh.For convenience this study is organized into three sections viz., Section-I which is introductory to the study, the Objective, Methodology and Profile of the study area have also been presented in the same section. Section-II, which analyses the Model specification, problems with Ordinary linear regression, importance of Odds ratio, etc., and Section-III deals with the empirical results of logistic regression for the saving behaviour of the rural households and Conclusions.','','-','Surya Prakasa Rao Gedela, Raju Paila','71-82','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','25','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(385,'An Ordering Policy for Deteriorating Items Under Life Time, Trade Credit And Time Discounting','In this paper, an inventory model of deteriorating items has been developed under the assumptions of life time, trade credit and time discounting. The demand rate has been considered as linear function of time and deterioration rate as constant. Shortage of items is not allowed.','','-','Parihar, J.S., Megha Rani and  Shweta Dixit','83-90','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','25','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(386,'New Numerical Methods for Solving Non-linear Equations and Calculate Estimate Error','In this paper, false position method is verified on a number of test examples and numerical results confirm that the proposed method is very effective with respect to the Adomian decomposition method. We present a few efficient numerical algorithms for solving nonlinear equations based on Adomian decomposition methods and divided difference technique. false position method is a root-finding algorithm that combines features from the bisection method and the secant method The oldest surviving document demonstrating knowledge and proficiency in the false position method is the Indian mathematical. The method of false position uses the idea that it often makes sense to assume that the function is linear locally. The property of convergence is proved and some numerical illustrations are also given to show the efficiency of these algorithms.','','-','MukeshGrover, Aurn KumarTomer','91-98','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','25','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(387,'A Study of Declining Child Sex-Ratio in Punjab','Now-a-days, gender issue is an important aspect of human being in various social-economic and cultural classifications of people in India. Since the ancient time in our society, female killing has been a regular feature and happens in different forms. It is a disgrace for the Indian society, which considers the birth of a girl child as a terrible investment in future. She is considered to be consumer rather than a producer and this narrow thinking of the Indian patriarchal society has lead to unpleasant practices like female infanticide and female foeticide which create sex imbalance in the society. For the past several years, Punjab has been at the receiving end on the issue of declining sex ratio. In this study an attempt has been made to investigate an important issue i.e. child sex ratio. The study analyses the data from NFHS-1, NFHS-2 and NFHS-3 for Punjab and enlightens some pertinent features of declining child sex ratio. For this purpose sex ratio at birth has been compared for all the three rounds of NFHS data for rural and urban part of Punjab and found a declining trend in sex ratio at birth. Results show that sex ratio at birth for lower parity of females is in favour of male child however for higher parity of females it is in favour of male child however for higher parity of females it is in favour of female child. Total sex ratio at birth is in favour of male child for both urban and rural part of Punjab. Sex wise parity progression ratios are also obtained in support of the results.','','-','Brijesh P. Singh, Niraj K. Singh','99-105','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','25','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(388,'An Exploratory Study of Nonverbal Communication and Business Success','It has been observed that Non verbal elements of communication are often overlooked and considered relatively insignificant in the overall communication process. Many studies have been performed in this area. Earlier it was considered that words are more important and the person understands only through words. After undergoing a thorough research process now it has been agreed by all the scholars that the gestures and expressions are more important than words. It has been proved that body language and tone of voice account for 93 percent of what is communicated between two people, while words account for only 7 percent.. \r\nThe main aim of this paper is to study how can the knowledge of these nonverbal processes of communication enhance business success?  Considering that communication is important in human life, that nonverbal communication can continuously transmit information; and that knowledge and human power are synonymous, a thorough knowledge of the processes and uses of nonverbal communication can help managers to enhance their power, as measured by monetary success in the business world.  Environments are invisible because their ground rules, pervasive structure, and overall patterns elude easy perception. However, nonverbal communication makes visible this invisible environment.\r\nThis study presents a review to explore the vital link between nonverbal communication and business success which is becoming more profound in today\'s world.  In professional environment a person might use what he or she has learned about nonverbal communication in order to read what is called \'nonverbal leakage\'. This \'leakage\' represents the true feelings which underlie the social mask. Although most of us can control our words and our faces better than the rest of our bodies, and consequently the movements of feet and hands, arms and legs often convey information of which we are unaware. This fact may be exploited in competitive interview situations, by placing the interviewee\'','','-','Jyoti Sardana, Alok Goel','107-117','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','25','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(389,'Profit Maximization production inventory models with time dependent demand and partial backlogging','A production inventory model is developed for time dependent deteriorating items with linear trend in demand. In this model deterioration rate at any item is assumed to follow three parameter Weibull distribution function of time. This deterioration rate is suitable for items with and without life-period. Shortages are allowed with partial backlogging. Production rate is taken as decision variable and unit production cost is a function of the production rate. Profit maximization technique is used to get the expression of the profit function.','','-','Vipin Kumar, S.R. Singh, Sanjay Sharma','367-375','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','15','20','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(390,'Role of Communication in Employee Development','People\'s participation is becoming the central issue of our time, and participation requires communication.\r\nDevelopment programmes can only realize the full potential of the employees, if knowledge and technology are shared effectively, and if employees are motivated and committed to achieve success.\r\nCommunication is central to this task in many ways. Helping people at all levels to communicate empowers them to recognize important issues and find common grounds for action, and builds a sense of identity and participation in order to implement their decisions.\r\nWe live in a communication age, and the full impact of communication on development is just starting to be seen. Communication for development has reached the stage where it can have a noticeable and rewarding effect on many development programmes.','','-','Ritu Saxena','115-121','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(391,'Cultural Change The Perception of the Media and The Mediation of Its Images','In this article, the author analyzes cultural changes introduced by modernization in Colombia and their link to the development of media as a constitutive element in the countrys transformation.\r\nHe does so by studying the results of a research project that involved interviews\r\nwith mediators of societysocial science researchers, artists, writers, people working in communications, designers, high school teachersregarding the presence of the cultural in newspapers, radio, and television. He investigates the transformations that the very notions of culture and the cultural are currently undergoing in the agenda and discursive formats of mass media and their relation to innovations in both policy making and technology.','','-','Ghulam Shabir , Taimur-ul-Hasan','122-140','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(392,'Women and Higher Education-Periodical Preview','The issue of female education in the large, as emancipator and rational is broached seriously in the Enlightenment. The role of women outside the home has become an important feature of the social and economic life of the country and in the years to come this will become still more significant. From this point of view, greater attention will have to be paid to the problems of training and employment of women. Opportunities for part-time employment which would enable women to look after their homes and to have career outside will have to be largely expanded. Teaching, nursing and social service are well recognized areas where women can have a useful role to play. In addition, several new avenues will have to be opened out to them. Schooling for girls was rare; the assumption was still that education would be brought to the home environment. Comenius was an advocate of formal education for women. In fact his emphasis was on a type of universal education making no distinction between humans; with an important component allowed to parental input.','','-','Malvika. S. Kandpal','141-145','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(393,'Dependence Proneness Among Weaker and Stronger Section People','The Present Study focuses at the understanding of dependence proneness among weaker and stronger section people. \r\nThe study was planned as following the strength of poverty level 2 (W.S. vs. S.S.) x 2 (youth vs. adult) factorial design. In each treatment condition 20 Ss were placed. The poverty scale (P.S.) was developed by Sharma Krishna (2008). This was the reliable and valid measure of derivational experiences showing the strength of poverty. The dependence proneness scale (D.P.S.) was developed by J.B.P Sinha (1968) & was used to assess the dependence proneness. The obtained results clearly display the differential influence of weaker section vs. stronger section and youth vs. adult Ss on dependence proneness.','','-','P.S.N.  Tiwari , Krishna Sharma','146-151','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(394,'A Study to Examine Fluency Component of Scientific Creative Talent of Elementary Stage Students of Himachal Pradesh With Respect to Area, Type of School and Gender','The present paper focused on the fluency component of scientific creative talent of elementary stage students of Himachal Pradesh with respect to area, type of school and gender. The researcher has taken the sample of 1120 elementary stage students of classes VII and VIII studying in Govt. and Private schools of Himachal affiliated to HP board of School Education, Dharamshala from five selected districts. To collect the requisite data for the present study, the investigator used Verbal Test of Scientific Creativity constructed by V. P. Sharma, retired professor and head Department of Psychology, R. S. University, Raipur (C. G.) and J. P. Shukla, Department of Psychology, R. S. University, Raipur, (C. G.). The researcher has employed the technique of three way ANOVA (222) to analyse the data. The results revealed that elementary stage students of urban area are more fluent in scientific creative talent as compared to the elementary stage students of rural area. Also there exists a significance difference between the two. The elementary stage boys exhibited slightly more Fluency than the elementary stage girls with a significant difference at highest level of significance. It is found in the study that Area and School, School and Gender interact significantly. The paper discusses certain suggestions for productive thinking and studies in respective areas in the field of science.','','-','T.C. Rawat','152-161','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(395,'Problems of The Aged Person','It is universal truth that who have taken birth will have to be old and finally to die. But we saw that nobody is accepting it and hence the problems of the Aged person arise. There are several consequences which creates the problem for Aged person. In this paper we have tried to find out those problems.','','-','Anuradha Verma','162-165','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(396,'Agro- Based Industries and Rural Development a Geographical Review','national pace of development, rural development perhaps stands out fairly prominently (Urs. D.V. and Mishra, R.P., 1979, 54) The term \'Rural\' essentially means an area which is characteersied by non-urban style of life, occupational structure, social organisation and settlement pattern. \'Development means quantitative as qualitative change Rural development means development of the rural areas in such a way that each component of rural life change in a desired direction and in sympathy with the other components (Mishra, R.P. and Sundaram, K.V.G.)	\r\nTraditionally Indian villages enjoyed almost complete economic autonomy and self sufficiency. But the gradually increasing inflow of machine-made cheap consumer\'s goods made a dent restricting manual industries and creating unemployment.\r\nAgriculture having little capacity to absorb surplus labour, the rural people began to migrate to urban area creating numerous social, economic and sanitation problems. Outmigration of population, especially the young and able people is the cleares indication of difficulties of life in the rural settlements (Obot. J.U. 1984, 19)\r\nSo, rural industrialization is essential because agriculture, as compared to the magnitude of our population and its rapid growth and considering the inadequacy of arable land, could be expanded and intensified within narrow limits, too short of what was required for a prosperous and viable (Bhattacharya S.N. 1980, 14)','','-','A.K. Singh , Santosh Verma','166-170','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(397,'Impact of Cyber Crime In Society, New Challenges','The world isnt run by weapons anymore, or energy, or money. Its run by ones and zeros little bits of data its run on electrons. Theres a war out there, a world war. Its not about who has the most bullets. Its about who controls the information. What we see and hear, how we work, what we think, its all about information.  \r\nThe world of Internet today has become a parallel form of life and living because with the availability of artificial intelligence and new technologies, we are now capable of doing things, which were not even imaginable few years ago. The Internet is fast becoming a way of life for millions of people and also a way of living because of growing dependence and reliance of the mankind on these machines. The advent of the computer has been a boon to students, lawyers, businessmen, teachers, doctors, researchers and also, of course, to the criminals. Science as it is rightly said is double-edged weapon. So is the case with the invention of computers. The modern thief can steal more with a computer than with a gun.  Tomorrows terrorists may be able to do more damage with a keyboard than a bomb.\r\nUnauthorized access, damage to property, theft, fraud, mischief and the publication of obscene and indecent material are all familiar crimes. The expression crime is defined as an act, which subjects the doer to legal punishment or any offence against morality, social order or any unjust or shameful act. The offence is defined in the Code of Criminal Procedure to mean as an act or omission made punishable by any law for the time being in force.  With the emergence of Internet, the Traditional crimes have assured new dimensions.','','-','Sanjeev Kumar Chadha','171-174','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(398,'The Impact Of Socio-Economic Status On Life Stress And Adjustmental Problems of HIV Positive Patients','Background : The individual is devised the basic necessities. They cannot cope effectively with the demands of the social environment. Because of socio-economic inequality, social interaction, negatives, lack of motivation will definitely have high impact on the positive people live the healthy life. And it is more evident and visible in the Indian context, where sizeable part of the population is suffering from lot of SES and cultural handicaps and the HIV people in India are not exception   to this phenomenon, therefore, an attempt is made to study the impact of SES status on the life stress and adjustmental problems on HIV positive patients. \r\nObjectives : To examine the contribution of life stress and adjustment to adverse SES events. \r\nMethods : To meet the objective of the present study the data was collected at Gulbarga, Bidar, Raichur and Belgum (Karnataka) District ICTC and NGOs centres, by personally interviewed the each clients by help of inventory SES scale,  life stress and adjustment inventory. \r\nStage  1: SES scale was administered to the total 600 respondents to categorize them into the low SES groups (200) and high SES groups (200) taking the first and third quartile as cut off points respectively. \r\nStage -2 : Life stress scale and adjustment inventory were administered an the groups of high SES and Low SES. The response were scored and terminated. \r\nResults: The results reflects the SES of life stress of HSES and LSES of t-value is 3.95, (significant at 0.01 level) Male & Female of t-value of life stress M/F is 3.00 (significant at 0.01 level). Another scale adjustment of M/F t-value is 11.53 (significant at 0.01 level).','','-','Chandrakant Jamadar , S.P. Melkeri','175- 185','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(399,'Economic History of District Garhwal','During the British Period the shape of Garhwal was around 5471 square mile and its only 411 square mile was inhabited in the year 1911 AD is total population was 480167. Geographically it had unequal peaks and slops hence the trade routs were not developed. So the people had very hard life here. The land was not able to produce enough food grains. But in absence of industries the economy of the people completely depended on agriculture, animals and forest and forest products. Here we tried to get a historic background of British Garhwal economy.','','-','M.S.Gusain  , Ranjeet Singh','186-194','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(400,'Mental Health of Senior Secondary School Students In Relation to Certain Socio-Demographic Variables','Health is rightly said wealth. It involves ones physical as well as mental health. Mental health has much wider scope than physical health as it aims for the development of wholesome balanced and integrated personality. The acquisition of such personality is indeed a great asset and privilege for a normal individual. He can be able to actualize his self, live his life to his satisfaction and happiness. He strives to attain the goals of his life in the perfect tune of taking and giving something to the society. It is possible when one enjoys good mental health, and knows its value and importance along with the knowledge of means and ways of achieving and maintaining it. In the present scenario the students are facing a number of problems in home and school. They are facing unemployment, adjustment and family related problems. Due to these problems students are becoming victims of fear, anxiety, despair and frustration. These all are affecting mental health of the students. So, the focus of present research paper was to study the mental health status of senior secondary school students in relation to certain socio-demographic variables. A sample of 300 senior secondary school students was selected randomly from district Mandi of Himachal Pradesh. On the basis of analysis and interpretation, general conclusions were drawn.','','-','Promila  , Narbada Devi  , Ranjana Kumari','195-198','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(401,'Dispelling of A Chimera: In The Country of Deceit','Shashi Deshpande is one of the brightest stars in the literary sky of the contemporary Indian English fiction.  It is her profound understanding of a womans life which makes her a great writer. Her work is distinctive in the sense that never before the dilemmas in the life of an educated middle class woman dealt with so much of depth. In the Country of Deceit the author picks up the theme of adult love, hitherto unexplored even in her own novels. She believes that love is a basic human emotion and there is nothing banal about it. However, one cannot walk away from the consequences of the choices we make in life. In this way while taking up the theme of love in the backdrop of the feminine sensibility, the author goes on to describe the protagonists quest in search of answers to some of the existential questions of life.','','-','Rekha Narula','199-204','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(402,'An Assessment of  Customer Relationship Management Practices Opted by Banks for   Retaining Customers in Uttrakhand State','In recent times, there has been a rapid increase in the number of private sector commercial banks in India. But despite general economic growth and increased amount of saving, there was no concomitant growth in the number of depositors. Banks have taken steps to attract customers and satisfy them by adopting a service orientation with a focus on developing customer-employee relationship. Customer Relationship Management has emerged as a popular business strategy in todays competitive environment. It is a discipline which enables the companies to identify and target their most profitable customers. CRM involves new and advance marketing strategies which not only retain the existing customers but also acquire new customers. It has been invented as a unique technique capable of remarkable changes in total output of companies. While the concept of relationship marketing was formally introduced in early 90s when financial services, airlines and other service institutions stated to reward to retain the existing customers by introducing loyalty programs, CRM is only a product of the late nineties. The purpose of this paper is to find the differences in an organizations services employing CRM vis a vis others, as perceived by the customer. It also tries to find out the relationship between perception and satisfaction, commitment and loyalty which underlines the significance of CRM in Indian banking sector. Analysis also reveals that customers in the CRM bank rate its services far more favorably than those in the non-CRM which is an indicator of the superior level of services in the former.','','-','DS Chaubey  , Shivani Joshi , S.M.Tariq Zafar','205-217','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(403,'Celies Emancipation in the novel The Color Purple','Alice Walker is one of the best-known contemporary African-American women writers.Her novel The Color Purple portrays the struggle of black women for their own identity, self-esteem and independence. The Color Purple is Alice Walkers most famous work, which was published in 1982 and was awarded both the American Book Award for Fiction and the Pulitzer Prize. Steven Spielberg later made a movie from this novel with the same title. It is an epistolary novel told through the letters of the central character --- Celie. In the novel, Walker continues to explore the interrelationship of racism and sexism and their destructive effects on the black community, especially on black women. The Color Purple chronicles thirty years of Celies life from 1910s to 1940s in South America. The stories are revealed through 91 letters written by two sisters, Celie and Nettie. In The Color Purple, sisterhood plays an important role in Celies awakening: she gains spiritual encouragement fromhersisterNettie,herstepdaughter-in-law Sofia and her husbands love Shug.','','-','Sonal Singh  , Sushma Gupta','218-221','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(404,'A Geographical & Enviornmental Analysis of Forest Fire Hazards in Bhilangana Valley(Tehri Garhwal)','NA','','-','B.P. Naithani,Sunil Singh','222-228','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(405,'Migration Problem in South Asia','After the end of colonization many people suffered exodus from their native habitat. They were exploited on account of cast, race and religion and also for various political reasons. In the new age in 21st century the nature of original causes behind this large-scale migration has undergone a change. Economic compulsion an urge for a better life citizen from India, Pakistan, Srilanka, Nepal, Bangladesh & Bhutan keep crossing their national boundaries to make a home in a new socio-political milieu.\r\nAll the countries of South Asia deal with their problem of migration. No country is enthusiastic to follow the protocol & conventions set by U.N.O. or UNHCR. Consequently no country is able to successfully tackle this problem of their demographic change due to migration. The idea of repatriation is far fetched. Drastic measures have to be taken for establishing peace & the protection of human rights in this direction. In my research paper I will attempt to highlight the causes and possible solutions for this large-scale migration problem of this region.In this paper, I have concentrated on the problem of migration in South Asia. In South Asian countries, the problem of migration is very acute. The Indian peninsula is, geo-politically, the most vulnerable area for migration. Tamils, Nepaleese, Bangladeshis, Bhutanese, Pakistanis being aggrieved for various reasons in their respective native countries, have sought refuge in the immediately neighbouring state of India where they are accepted on humanitarian grounds. This exodus in an overwhelning number is a big burden on the exchequer of the sheltering country. Partition of India (1947), Partition of Pakistan (1971), Singhalization in Sri Lanka, military dictatorships and totalitarian regimes in Bangladesh, Myanmar amd Pakistan, conflicts of ethnic identity in Nepal and Bhutan, jihads in Pakistan and Afganistan have led to the mass exodus of refugees. This is a very unfortunate phenomenon of human existence.\r\nThough, the UN','','-','Bajrang Lal Saini','229-237','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(406,'Georgian Poetry','The poetry of the 20th century was characterized by traditional as well as experimental poetry. Traditional poetry roughly includes the Edwardian, Georgian, War poetry and so on. It was based on pastoral or homespun themes and followed a combined trend of the romantics and neo-classicists. Experimental poetry includes Imagist poetry; Neo-Metaphysical Poetry, Surrealist Movement and Neo-Romanticism.\r\nGeorgian poetry is poetry published during the reign of King George V (1910-1936) written mostly of the pastoral mode as well as in the escapist nature. These were poems written in the conventional manner without being experimental. The five anthologies entitled Georgian Poetry (1912-22) edited by Edward Marsh include poets such as Walter de la Mare, Rupert Brooke, John Drinkwater, J.E. Flecker, John Masefield, J.C. Squire, W.H. Davies, D.H. Lawrence, Abercrombie, Bottomley, R.Hodgson, Blunden, Sassoon, Robert Graves and Rosenberg.1 \r\nThe idea for an anthology began as a joke, when Marsh, Duncan Grant and George Mallory decided, one evening in 1912 to publish a parody of the many small poetry books that were appearing at the time. After some discussion it was decided to pursue the idea in all seriousness. Marsh and Brooke approached the poet and bookseller Harold Monro who had recently opened The Poetry Bookshop at Devonshire Street, London. He agreed to publish the book in return for a half share of the profits.2','','-','S. K. Singh','238-241','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(407,'The Effect of It Based Learning on Human Values of Students Undergoing Higher Education','This study investigated effect of  Internet-enriched teaching and learning environment on human values and attitudes among students toward using the Information Technology. Students re having computers facilities and required to complete compulsory generic courses in information technology, and the lecturers actively encouraged the use of information technology, in particular, the Internet in the teaching and learning processes. Results from the study indicated that students had positive attitudes toward using the Internet as a learning tool, adequate basic knowledge of the Internet, and viewed the learning environment as supportive of using the internet for learning. Effective and positive learning on the grounds of human values','','-','Vasudha Sharma','242-246','NO','-','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','21','27','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(408,'usg: o mudk f\'k{kk n\'kZu','n\'kZu\'kkL= vusd izdkj dh ,slh leL;kvksa ls lE