increasing function of time. It is assumed that the holding cost is linearly increasing function of time. We assume that supplier offers two progressive credit periods to the retailer to settle his account. An algorithm is presented to derive the retailers optimal solution. A classical optimization technique is applied to determine the optimal replenishment policy. Optimal solution for the proposed model is derived and the effects of different parameters are studied with the help of numerical example','','-','Shakti Singh Chauhan, Rachana Kumari,Nishant Kumar','615-636','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(587,'Design and development of fuel Pipe Bending Process','In automobile parts manufacturing, the fuel, exhaust pipes are specialized equipment that requires highly skilled, heavy machine and high problems arise when parts are not qualifying in the assembly line at long distance from manufacturers location or in overseas. This paper describes a project to develop the computer numerically controlled (CNC) pipe bending process that  for a pipe manufacturer that achieve final dimensions and have right fitting at assembly line .  The company has been using traditional methods of machine assisted manual pipe bending techniques. In a drive of continuous improvement, the company has acquired a pre-owned CNC bending machine capable of bending pipes automatically up to 15 bends. However, due to process mismatch, pipe does not qualify in the fixture or some time fixture is not make according to specification of pipes and take very long time due to either not referencing of pipe fixture or pipe bending process this take a very long time for developing new automobile pipe having large number of bends this paper help in developing new products sand reduce fitting problems and save cost and time.','','-','Barkat Ali, Shejad Ahemad','637-642','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(588,'Synthesis of Li0.3Zn0.3Mn0.1Fe2.3O4 ferrite by citrate precursor method and its characterization','Lithium ferrite with compositional formula Li0.3Zn0.3Mn0.1Fe2.3O4 was fabricated by citrate route. The synthesized sample was sintered at three different temperatures. X-ray diffraction (XRD) technique was used to study the structural properties of the ferrite samples. From the XRD analysis data, parameters such as lattice constant, theoretical density and crystallite size were calculated. Experimental density was also measured. Both theoretical and experimental densities were observed to increase with increasing sintering temperature. The variation of dielectric properties was investigated as a function of sintering temperature and frequency. Room temperature dielectric constant and dielectric loss show a decreasing trend with increase in sintering temperature. Dispersion in the dielectric constant and dielectric loss with frequency in the range 20Hz-1MHz is observed. There is a fall in the Curie temperature with increasing sintering temperature.  Possible mechanism contributing to all the above processes is being discussed','','-','Ibetombi Soibam, Sumitra Phanjoubam','643-650','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(589,'Some Transformation Formulas For a Srivastava-Karlsson Triple Hypergeometric Function','In the present paper I have deduced some transformation formulas for the triple hypergeometric function   given in Srivastava and Karlsson [4] in terms of the other triple hypergeometric functions given in Srivastava and Karlsson [4] in continuation of my previous study [5] of this function','','-','Lalit Mohan Upadhyaya','651-656','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(590,'Green Project Management Practices for Construction Industry','Applying the principles of sustainability to human activities ultimately must result in the scrutiny of all sectors of economic activity to assess the changes required to provide for a high quality of life for future generations. A high priority for evaluation, in the light of its impacts on environmental quality and resources, is industrial activity in general and the construction industry specifically. Construction has been accused of causing environmental problems ranging from excessive consumption of global resources both in terms of construction and building operation to the pollution of the surrounding environment, and research on green building design and using building materials to minimise environmental impact is already underway. Environmentally sustainable building construction has experienced significant growth during the past 10 years. The public is becoming more aware of the benefits of green construction as prominent politicians, celebrities, documentarians, and journalists highlight the built environments impact on greenhouse gas emissions and natural resource consumption. Other factors, including higher energy prices, increased costs of building materials, and regulatory incentives, are also pushing the green building market to grow and expand. However, barriers to green building continue to exist, including the ability to deliver a green project within acceptable cost constraints. In order for project managers to deliver sustainable construction according to clients cost expectations, modifications must be made to traditional project management processes and practices. The aim for sustainability assessment goes even further than at the design stage of a project to consider its importance at an early stage, before any detailed design or even before a commitment is made to go ahead with a development. However, little or no concern has 