is formed in terms of difference equation. The generating function technique has been adopted for the solution for the above set of model. Marginal Mean Queue Length, Mean Queue Length is also analyzed in this study. We can obtain other decision making parameters which can be used in the economical decision wherever this model can be applied','','-','L.M. Tiwari,Amit Mittal, Sangeeta Aggarwal','119-130','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(594,'Production model for Weibull Deteriorating Items with the effect of Learning and Exponential Demand','In most of the developed models researchers assumed that the shortages are either completely backlogged or completely lost. The first case, known as backordered or backlogging case, represent a situation where the unfulfilled demand is completely back ordered. In the second case, also known as lost sale case, we assume that the unfulfilled demand is completely lost. Shortages cause the businessman to bear the lost sales cost upon him, but later on he buys the lot required and sells it off immediately due to backlogged demand. This saves him from the depreciation cost which is reducing the profit margin considerably','','-','Dheerandra Kumar and S. R. Singh','131-144','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(595,'Effect of Inflation with Time and Stock Dependent Demand over a Finite Planing Horizon','In this paper, an inventory model for non-instantaneous deteriorating items with stock-dependent consumption rate has been developed. The competitive nature of the market has been accounted for by taking inflation into consideration. The model is developed for a finite planning horizon, keeping in mind the short lifespan of the customers preferences. An optimization frame work is presented to derive optimal replenishment policy when the present value of total cost is minimized. Numerical examples are provided to illustrate the optimization procedure. In addition, the sensitivity analysis of the optimal solution with respect to parameters of the system is carried out.','','-','Shalendra Singh, Vinay Kumar Tyagi  and S. R. Singh','145-160','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(596,'Retailers Optimal Replenishment Policy for Life Time Items Under Two-Level Trade Credit','So far, most work has been done under assumption that supplier offered to the retailer a fixed delay period, in settling accounts. The main purpose of this chapter is to investigate the retailer\'s optimal replenishment policy for life time items under two-level delay permitted to reflect the supply chain management situation. In which retailer also offered to his customer a fixed delay period, called the customer\'s credit period, in settling his account. Demand rate depend on the customer\'s credit period offered by the retailer. Shortages are allowed and partial backlogged and also depend on the customer\'s credit period offered by the retailer. Furthermore, numerical example is given to illustrate the results with sensitivity analyses develop in this study.','','-','Satish Kumar, N. K. Gaur  and S. R. Singh','161-178','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(597,'Applicability of Sharpes Single Index Model in Complex Indian Security Market and its Relative Impact','Three fundamental factors that determine the rate of growth of a nation are efforts, capital and knowledge. Among these, increasing capital formation has been considered as the most important factor in forecasting economic growth especially of the underdeveloped economies. To balance the requirement for over all developmental and to cater the apatite of expanding economies, financial institutions and capital markets in India and abroad emerged to mitigate the chronic problem of inadequacy of long term funds. The past decade in many ways has witnessed tremendous market sentiment in India. It has grown radically a battery of financial institutions stock exchanges and other intermediaries at the country and state level came into existence, amount raised from the market, the number of listed stocks, market capitalization, trading volumes and turnover on stock exchanges, and investor population. Despite the expansion of the securities market and reformatory measures taken by the GOI very small percentage of household savings are chanalized into the securities market. This indicates a lack of awareness and lingering confidence of the investors in the securities market. Primary objective of investing reserves in securities by the investors is to maximize earnings and to keep funds liquid and safe. The astute investment policy involves setting out investment objective, reviving investment needs of the investors, relevant policy guidelines with respect to size of the investment portfolio, approach of investment portfolio, effective portfolio diversification, maturity of the investment trading in securities, switching etc. Constructed portfolios should be revisited time and again in the light of external and internal developments and desired changes should be made in order to achieve optimum results. Thus, the present study tried to asses the applicability of Sharpes single Index Model in Indian security market and to analyze construction of optimal portfolios with minimum a','','-','S.M. Tariq Zafar , Prithvi Raj Sanyal  ,  Vikash Trivedi','179-198','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(598,'An Interval-Parameter Two-stage Stochastic Programming Problem involving Exponential Random Variables','Interval-parameter two-stage stochastic programming is an optimization problem by incorporating some of the input model parameters as random variables with known probability distributions and discrete intervals simultaneously within the two-stage stochastic optimization framework. In this paper, we proposed an interval-parameter two-stage stochastic programming problem considering only the right hand side parameters of the constraints as exponential random variables with known mean and variance and all other parameters are discrete intervals. Both the random variables and discrete intervals are simultaneously conceived under one roof for the model parameters. In order to solve the problem, first we remove the randomness from the problem and formulate an equivalent deterministic interval non-linear programming model. Then the deterministic interval non-linear programming model is solved and find the interval optimal solutions which provides several alternatives that reflect different decisions. A numerical example is presented to exemplify the usefulness of the proposed methodology.','','-','S.K. Barik, M.P. Biswal','199-214','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(599,'On Optimality Of Marine Oil Spill Pollution Control','Over the past three decades, intensive research on marine oil spill pollution control has been directed toward the development of mathematical models to predict and forecast the fate and transport of spilled oil and oil products in marine environments. Such research has been focused on selecting locations for the deployment of containment and collection systems to mitigate the effects of spilled oil on the environment. These models can be used for short-term tactical forecasting to help make decisions to contain, control and clean up accidental spill, however, they are not comprehensive for rapid response with regards to the clean up combating techniques strategy and also not accurate for spills detection. This paper proposes an operational research technique via optimal control theory and sequential decision processes as an alternative tool for optimal spill pollution control.','','-','Kufre J. Bassey','215-238','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(600,'Absolute-Value FunctionallinearPlus-Linear Fractional Programming','The programming problem considered in this work has a linearplus-linear fractional absolute value objective function with unrestricted variables. Mathematically this problem can be stated as:\r\nMaximize f(x)= ?_1^n??c_j |x_j | ? + (?_1^n??p_j |x_j | ?)/(?_1^n??q_j |x_j | ?)\r\nSubject to   A x=b, xis unrestricted.\r\nAdjacent extreme point (simplex-type) methods proposed by Teterev [13] cannot be used to solve this class of problems. However, this paper explores the conditions under which extreme point algorithms can be used to arrive at a desired solution for a linearplus-linear fractional programming absolute value objective function problem with unrestricted variables.','','-','S.S.Chadha, Veena Chadha','239-246','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(601,'Optimization Modelling For Coal Imports In A Power Plant','This paper details the application of linear programming and transportation model in a power generation company for optimizing the coal purchase plan. The company  a private sector utility company in India-purchases coal using base tonnage with certain tolerance on lower or higher side from different sources around the world and the coal needs to be shipped from the suppliers mines to the companys generating facilities. Company would like to have the optimum solution for coal allocations considering the various possible scenarios in the next five years. Based on LP Transportation model, a base coal allocation model is first developed to optimize the purchase of coal from different sources and allocation to different generating facilities. The technical constraints and cost elements are considered in each year with necessary modifications as required for the new plants coming on stream. The model is further extended to calculate the optimum coal allocation which minimizes the total purchase cost in case quantity discount is offered by different sources. Further, cost escalations due to various uncertainties - in clearance of shipments at ports, which may cause delays in transportation - are also considered and the model is extended to include the effect of the same on the allocation and total cost. This has been done with help of Risk Premium Solver.   The model can be further tweaked to include constraints on pollution control based on quality of coal (ash content, sulphur content etc.). The coal cost optimization model can also be extended to include simulation with appropriate simulation software like Witness, as done by Yabin Li [4]. \r\nKeywords : Transportation model, Coal purchase optimization, separable programming, integrated modeling.','','-','N. S. Nilakantan','247-260','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(602,'THE IMPACT OF INSTRUCTIONAL TELEVISION PROGRAMME ON ATTITUDE OF THE \r\nSECONDARY BIOLOGY STUDENTS','Television is the most powerful medium of mass communication which has ever existed and it has revolutionized our lives in many ways. Programmes designed specially for educational purpose can be used to create an interest on the ground which can not normally be dealt with success in the classroom and generally to improve the standard of teaching which the students receive then it should make a unique and important contribution to education. In the present study an attempt has been made to study the impact of instructional television programmes on attitude of the secondary biology students. The self-constructed attitude scale was administered on students of different schools of Meerut City. To find out the association between method of teaching and attitude towards ITV of secondary biology students, qualitative statistical technique (?2 test) is used to compare the observed frequencies and expected frequencies obtained on attitude scale towards ITV programmes. The result of investigation revealed that there is independence between method of teaching and attitude towards ITV.','','-','Surendra Kumar and Manju Gupta','59-62','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','34','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(603,'Attitude of Secondary School Teachers towards their Teaching Profession','The main aim of this study is to find out the attitude of secondary school teachers towards teaching profession. A sample of 112 secondary school teachers serving in government and private secondary school of district Mandi. Attitude scale towards teaching profession constructed and standardized by Dr. (Mrs.) Umme Kulsum was used to assess the attitude of secondary school teachers. The data was analysed by using t test. Analysis of results revealed that there exists no significant difference in the attitude of government and private, highly and less experienced secondary school teachers towards their teaching profession. Results further revealed that there exists significant difference in the attitude of male and female, graduate and post graduate, rural and urban secondary school teachers towards their teaching profession.','','-','Sangeeta  K.  Barwal','63-68','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','34','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(604,'Multi-Objective Stochastic Linear Programming with General form of Distributions','Probabilistic or Stochastic programming is a framework for modeling optimization problems that involve uncertainty. The basic idea used in solving stochastic optimization problems has so far been to convert a stochastic model into an equivalent deterministic model and is possible when the right hand side resource vector follows some specific distributions such as normal, lognormal and exponential distributions. In this paper, a multi-objective stochastic programming problem has been considered with right hand side resource vector following general form of distributions , which include many distributions such as Power Function distribution, Pareto distribution, Beta distribution of first kind, Weibull distribution, and Burr type XII distribution. In this approach, the multi-objective stochastic programming problem is converted into an equivalent deterministic model, which is then solved by a multi-objective programming genetic algorithm using Matlab. Few numerical examples are presented to illustrate the proposed approach.','','-','V. Charles,  S. I. Ansari and M. M. Khalid','261-278','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(605,'On Extended Fractional Programming Problem','In this paper, a generalized fractional programming problem with linear constraints and the objective function is the sum of the functions of the form \r\nMinimize  \r\nSubject to the linear constraints  \r\nand  \r\nwhere   are linear functions has been discussed. Solution of the above generalized fractional programming problem can be recovered by reducing it to a fractional programming problem.','','-','Adarsh Mangal, Pawan Kishor Tak and Praveen Deora','279-284','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(606,'Review of Literature of ABS algorithm to solve Linear Programming Problems','ABS methods have been studied a lot in last few years . This paper gives a review of work done by few researchers for applying ABS algorithm for different problems i.e; for solving determined or undetermined linear systems , linear least square optimization problem and integer equations and  linear programming problems.     \r\nAMS classification number :- 65F30','','-','Adarsh Mangal and Saroj Sharma','285-290','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(607,'Production Inventory Policy With Exponential Increasing Storage Cost Under A Discounted Cash Flow','In this paper a production inventory model is developed in which the production rate at any instant depends on the demand and the inventory level. The holding cost is an exponential increasing function of time. The effects of the time value of money are taken into the consideration. The demand rate is a linear function of time for the scheduling period. Through numerical example, sensitive analyses are carried out to examine the effect of the parameters. Results show that the discount rate parameter and the inventory holding cost have a significant impact on the proposed model.','','-','Ankit Prakash Tyagi, R.K. Pandey and S.R. Singh','291-302','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(608,'Security Metrics: Needs And Myths','In the growing area of interconnected computer, security is very essential task. Security in its most basic meaning is the protection from intruders. Therefore the issue of security metrics has seen considerable activity in recent times, and there are numerous approaches to monitoring and measuring \"security\" available. However, the majority of these efforts generally apply to subsections of technical, or IT, security with a few notable exceptions. While these technical metrics are in many cases very effective at the specific task for which they were designed, they say little about the overall security, or safety, of the organization and provide little guidance for effective management. Measuring the state of \"safety\" of an organization is vastly broader than knowing how many packets a firewall dropped and is typically well beyond the scope of IT, or for that matter, information security.','','-','Arun Bakshi, Khaleel Ahmad, and Nitesh Kumar','303-314','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(609,'Multiobjective Fractional Minimax Programming Involving Vector ?-convex Functions','In this paper, we derive necessary and sufficient conditions for differentiable multiobjective fractional Minimax Programming under vector ?-generalized convex functions and also weak and strong duality results have been proved.','','-','G. Varalakshmi, G. Sreelatha','315-326','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(610,'Statistical Inference For A Two Station Tandem Queue With Dependent Structure And At Most One Customer In Between The Stations','Consider a single channel two station tandem queue such that no queue is allowed in front of station 1 but at most one customer is allowed to wait in between station 1 and station 2 and with blocking. Assuming that the arrival process and the service process are dependent, we obtain the steady state solution for the system when the joint distribution of interarrival time, service time at station 1 and service time at station 2 is trivariate exponential. Also, the moment and CAN estimators and asymptotic confidence limits for the expected number of customers in the system are obtained.','','-','P. Chandrasekhar, E. Mini and  V.S.Vaidyanathan','327-332','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(611,'Application of Fuzzy Topsis Method for Solving Job-Shop Scheduling Problem','In this paper, we focused on the scheduling and sequencing which is a form of Decision Making (DM) that plays a crucial role in production manufacturing and service industries. Job- scheduling problem arise when there is a choice as to the order in which number of tasks can be performed. In such problems, we determine an appropriate order or schedule for a series of jobs to be done on a finite number of service facilities.\r\nThe paper presents the way of makingschedule of a finite number of jobs on a finite number ofmachines of unequal efficiencies by using the Technique for Order Preference by Similarity to Ideal Solution (TOPSIS) Method in fuzzy environment. The order of machinesis random. The time taken by the machines for conducting jobsis assumed as imprecise processing time or fuzzy numbers. The fuzzy evaluation values are given by Triangular FuzzyNumbers (TNFs). Weights are given to each machine according totheir efficiency. A new distance is defined using which thedistance of each job from the positive and negative idealsolutions are calculated. Also a closeness coefficient isdefined to determine the ranking order of the jobs so that thecomplete schedule or sequence may finish at minimum time-span. Finally, anumerical example is illustrated for proposed method.','','-','V.S. Jadhav and V.H. Bajaj','333-342','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(612,'Mathematical Model of Air Pollutant Emitted From A Time Dependent Area Source of Primary And Secondary Pollutants with Chemical Reaction','This model takes into account the realistic form of variable wind velocity and eddy-diffusivity profiles, which are functions of vertical height, frictional velocity, terrain categories, geostrophic wind and several stability dependent meteorological parameters. The model has been solved using Crank-Nicolson implicit finite difference technique. Upwind difference scheme, which follows transportive and conservative property, is used to discretise the advection term.','','-','Ramprakash Sharma','343-352','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(613,'An Integrated Inventory Model With Multi-Variate Demand For Perishable Items and Permissible Delay in Payments','In this paper an inventory system is developed for deteriorating items with multi-variate demand. Here, demand rate is a function of time, stock and selling price. In this study, we have taken production rate is demand dependent. We have also considered the situation, when the retailer has the reserve money but still wants to avail the facility of progressive credit period. Shortages are allowed in inventory which is completely backlogged. An optimization framework has been presented, which derives optimal ordering policies when the present values of total cost has been optimized.','','-','Ravinder Kumar Arya, S.K.Shakya and S.R.Singh','353-370','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(614,'Two Warehouse Inventory Model With Partial Backordering and Multi-Variate Demand Under Inflation','In this paper a two-warehouse inventory model for deteriorating items with partial backordering and time as well as stock dependent demand has been developed. The rate of deterioration of items in the two warehouses follows Weibull distribution. We consider inflation in problem analysis. Also, a single warehouse version for deteriorating items is discussed. We show that the total cost of the system is influenced by the deterioration rate, the inflation rate and the backordering ratio. Most researchers on inventory models do not consider simultaneously the phenomena with two-warehouse, varying rate of deteriorating, inflation and partial backordering. Since these phenomena are not uncommon in real life, we incorporate them in our problem development.','','-','S. R. Singh, A. K. Malik','371-384','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(615,'Optimal Replenishment Policy for Life Time Items under Trade Credit','So far, most work has been done under assumption that supplier offered to the retailer a fixed delay period, in settling accounts. The main purpose of this chapter is to investigate the retailers optimal replenishment policy for life time items under permitted delay to reflect the supply chain management situation. Demand rate depend on time. Shortages are allowed and partial backlogged. Furthermore, numerical example is given to illustrate the results with sensitivity analyses develop in this study.','','-','Jitendra Singh, B.B. Singh ,S.R.Singh','385-404','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(616,'Swastik-Shaped Patch Antennas for 5.8 GHz WLAN Communications','This paper presents the designing of two Swastik-shaped patch antennas operating at 5.8GHz which is designated for IEEE802.11b WLAN communications. The first proposed antenna is designed on a single layer of Rogers RO4350 resulting in a narrowband response of bandwidth 60MHz. The second proposed antenna is designed as two layered (air, Rogers RO4350) structure and has resulted in improved bandwidth. The obtained bandwidth is 210MHz which is 3.5 times of the bandwidth of the first antenna. The antennas are probe feeded. The Ansoft HFSS is employed for designing the antennas','','-','Uma Shankar Modani, Gopal Modani','405-412','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(617,'An Inventory Model for Decaying Items With Inflation and Backlogging Under Trade Credits','A look at the literature available on inventory reveals that several models have been formulated in a static environment. An inventory model for time dependent deterioration of units is formulated to determine the optimal ordering policy when the supplier offers a credit period linked to order quantity to settle the accounts. The environment of the whole study has been taken as inflationary.','','-','Shakti Singh Chauhan, Rachana Kumari,Nishant Kumar','413-428','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(618,'Modeling of an Inventory Model with Shortages Exponential Demand Under Capacity Constraint','Inventory may be considered as an accumulation of a product that would be used to satisfy future demands for that product. In this paper an inventory model with two warehouses for deteriorating items with shortages is developed. We took the exponential demand and linear deterioration rate of inventory items in OW and RW. A number of structural property of the inventory system studied analytically.','','-','Virpal Singh, Punam Sharma','429-454','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(619,'An Inventory model for decaying items with stock and time   dependent demand rate with time value of money','In the present paper an order level inventory model for deteriorating items with multi dependent consumption rate under the inflationary conditions has been developed. We have taken a more realistic demand rate that depends on two factors, one is time, and the other is the stock level. The stock level in itself obviously gets depleted due to the customers demand. In this model , shortages are allowed with complete backlogging. The results have been illustrated with the help of numerical example.','','-','Pankaj Kaushal, A.P.Singh & D. Singh','455-460','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(620,'Design of A Single Layer Swastik-Shaped Microstrip Patch Antenna','A single layer compact size Swastik-shaped microstrip patch antenna is designed and studied. The antenna is designed to cover the frequency band designated for IEEE802.11 b for WLAN applications. The proposed antenna has simulated return loss of -29.5dB at 5.8GHz frequency. The peak gain of this antenna at resonance frequency is 1.6dB. The antenna is probe feeded. The Ansoft HFSS is employed for the antenna design.','','-','Uma Shankar Modani, Gopal Modani','461-474','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(621,'An Integrated Inventory Model for Decaying Items with Exponential Demand and Backlogging Under Inflation','In this paper an integrated inventory model for decaying items with exponential demand has been developed. The inventory is allowed to deteriorate during the time it is stored and during this time it undergoes Weibull rate of deterioration. Partially backlogged shortages are permitted with constant backlogging rate. The effect of inflation is also taken in this study. Production rate is taken as demand dependent. Numerical results are presented and discussed to demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed model.','','-','Vikramjeet singh, A.P.Singh  &  D.Singh','461-474','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(622,'An Inventory Model for Decaying Items with Exponential Demand, Partial Backloggging Under Inflation','In todays business transactions, there are various reasons, namely, bulk purchase discounts, re-ordering costs, seasonality of products, inflation induced demand, etc., which force the buyer to order more than the warehouse capacity. Such situations call for additional storage space to store the excess units purchased. This additional storage space is typically a rented warehouse. Inflation plays a very interesting and significant role here: It increases the cost of goods. To safeguard from the rising prices, during the inflation regime, the organization prefers to keep a higher inventory, thereby increasing the aggregate demand. This additional inventory needs additional storage space, which is facilitated by a rented warehouse. Ignoring the effects of the time value of money and inflation might yield misleading results. In this study, a two-warehouse inventory model with exponential trend in demand under inflationary conditions having different rates of deterioration has been developed. Shortages at the owned warehouse are also allowed subject to partial backlogging. The solution methodology provided in the model helps to decide on the feasibility of renting a warehouse. Finally, findings have been illustrated with the help of numerical examples. Comprehensive sensitivity analysis has also been provided.','','-','Kapil Malhotra,, S. R. Singh','709-726','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(623,'An Inventory Model with Shortages, with Time Dependent Deterioration and the Demand Rate as Stock Dependent Over a Finite Planning Horizon','In this paper an inventory model with completely backordered shortages, in which units are, deteriorate with time dependent rates and the demand rate is stock and time dependent over a finite planning horizon. We discussed two cases of inventory system. First one is considered without shortages and second with shortages. The effect of inflation is also taken in this study.  Cost minimization technique is used. Numerical example is presented to demonstrate the developed model and the solution procedure. Sensitivity analysis of the optimal solution with respect to major parameters is carried out.','','-','Pankaj Kaushal, A. P. Singh ,D. Singh','727-742','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(624,'A Comparetive Study of Cadmium Uptake in Some Plant Species Grown in Sandy Loam Soil After Application of EDTA','Plants can be used to remove, transfer, stabilize and degrade contaminants. Current efforts now focus on expanding the phytoremediation strategy to reclaim contaminated soils as an attempt to remove the pollutants of soil is tried in the present work. In the present experiment EDTA was used to observe the translocation of the cadmium metal.','','-','Pushpendra','743-748','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(625,'Two Warehouses Inventory Model for Non-Instantaneous Deteriorating Items With Stock-Dependent Demand','This paper deals with two warehouse inventory model of determining the optimal replenishment policy for non-instantaneous deteriorating items partial backlogging and stock-dependent demand. In the model, shortages are allowed and the backlogging rate is variable and dependent on the waiting time for the next replenishment. The necessary and sufficient conditions of the existence and uniqueness of the optimal solution are shown. We discussed four special cases, the results for the models with instantaneous or non-instantaneous deterioration rate and with or without shortages are derived. Numerical example is presented to demonstrate the developed model.','','-','S. R. Singh, A. K. Malik, Satish Kumar','749-760','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(626,'An inventory model for deteriorating products with inflation, lost sales and stock and time dependent demand','In this paper, an inventory model for deteriorating items with linearly time dependent demand rate and lost sales under inflation is developed. The demand rate is a linear function of the time and stock We allow for shortages and time dependent backlogging rate is considered. We use numerical example to illustrate the model with sensitivity analysis.','','-','Sanjay Sharma, S. R. Singh','761-774','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(627,'An inventory model with time dependent demand rate, Trade credits and partial backlogging','In this paper we developed an inventory model for deteriorating items with time dependence of demand. Items deteriorate at a time dependent rate. Many inventory models in past were developed under the assumption that the holding cost is constant for the entire inventory cycle. But this is particularly false in the storage of deteriorating and perishable items such as food products. The holding cost is assumed to be varying over time in only few inventory models. Partially backlogged shortages are permitted and backlogging rate is waiting time for the next replenishment. Sensitivity analysis has also been done for some parameters.','','-','Vikramjeet Singh, D. Singh, A. P. Singh','775-790','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(628,'Optimal Inventory Replenishment Model for Deteriorating Items Taking Account of Time Discounting','In the present study, a two warehouse inventory model for deteriorating items with multi dependent consumption rate under the inflationary conditions has been developed. We have taken more realistic situations our model. We discussed here two cases of inventory system. First one is considered without shortages and second with shortages . Finally, the results have been illustrated with the help of four numerical examples. Also, the effects of changes of different parameters are studied graphically on the average profit. This whole setup is very close to the reality that is observed in the market.','','-','Jitendra Singh, B.B.Singh, S.R.Singh','791-812','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(629,'On an Inventory Model with Stock Dependent Demand, Shortage Under Inflation and Trade Credits','In this Paper, the researcher had addressed the issues relating to progressive credit period relating to the retailer to settle his account. A mathematical model has been developed for inventory system with stock dependent demand shortages which are fully backlogged in an inflationary environment. The assumption taken was that the supplier offers two progressive credit periods to the retailer to settle his account. An algorithm is presented to derive the retailers optimal solution. A classical optimization technique is applied to determine the optimal replenishment policy.','','-','Vinamra Sharma, Rachana Kumari','813-826','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(630,'A Mathematical Programming Approach for Wheat Cultivation in the States of North India','Agriculture occupies a prominent position in Indian economy not only because of its contribution to GDP but also because a large proportion of countrys population depends on this sector for its livelihood. At the same time, due to expanding population, diminishing arable land and rising service industry, there is growing need to increase the production by making optimum use of agriculture resources. Wheat is the main cash crop in Indian agriculture. Due to growing demand of wheat for consumption, it is imperative to come up with plans that help in increasing the production of wheat. The paper presents a linear goal-programming model to help the farmers to allocate different resources available like land, capital, labour, water etc.  for wheat production in optimum manner to obtain maximum production and profit at minimum cost.','','-','Kiran Vasishtha, Rajesh Dangwal, D. B. Ojha, Ashok Kumar Vasishtha','827-834','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(631,'Acoustoelectric Attenuation and Phase Transition Due to Carriers in Semiconductor','The response of the charge carriers of a semiconductor to a traveling acoustic wave leads to transfer of energy between the wave and the electrons, such a wave drags free carriers and as a result attenuation and phase transition appears across the sample, near a phase transition there are large fluctuation, in the case of a softening phonon mode, the fluctuations correspond simply to vibrational modes that are excited thermally when the energy of the phonons has been shifted down near to zero. The effects of interaction with thermal phonons, which produce temperature dependent attenuation and free carriers which may give attenuation or amplification, and electrons bound to shallow donors, giving rise to attenuation at low temperatures. There are obtained a complex form for the change in distribution function arising due to the passage of acoustic wave through a semiconductor. The imaginary part of this function has been used for ascertaining the phase transition between the self-consistent field and the acoustoelectric current and the real part has been utilized for computing the attenuation constant for n  Indium antimonide.','','-','Praveen Kumar, Amita Kri and Ujjwal Alok','835-840','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(632,'Analysis of Financial Instruments and Mutual Funds','The main aim of this paper is to compare and contrast the performances of the various schemes, tradable asset or negotiable item such as a security, commodity, derivative or index, or any item that underlies a derivative with mutual funds. An instrument is a means by which something of value is transferred, held or accomplished. An economic variable that can be controlled or altered by government policymakers in to cause a desired effect in other economic indicators.  Financial instruments can be thought of as easily tradable packages of capital, each having their own unique characteristics and structure. The wide array of financial instruments in today\'s marketplace allows for the efficient flow of capital amongst the world\'s investors.  Mutual funds can be win-win option available to the investors who are not willing to take any exposure directly to the security markets as well as it helps the investors to build their wealth over a period of time. The Indian Equity Market has grown significantly during the last three years; Mutual Funds are not left far behind. Both the avenues have created wealth for the investors. But for the creation of wealth through this avenue a proper understanding of the Mutual Funds is must. A Mutual Fund is a trust that pools the savings of a number of investors who share a common financial goal. The money thus collected is then invested in capital market instruments such as shares, debentures and other securities. The income earned through these investments and capital appreciation realized is shared by its unit holders in proportion to the number of units owned by them.','','-','Sarish, Ajay Jain','841-848','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(633,'An Inventory model for deteriorating items with time dependent demand under inflation','An order level inventory model for deteriorating items with time dependent demand rate and shortages has been developed. Items deteriorate at a time dependent rate. In totality the whole study has been done under the implications of inflation, gives it a viability that makes it more pragmatic and acceptable. Therefore, to make our study more suitable to present-day market, we have done our research in an inflationary environment. The problem has been formulated analytically and has been used to arrive at the optimal solution. Numerical example is to illustrate the model. Cost minimization technique is used in this study.','','-','Anil Kumar Sharma, Kavita Sinha,','849-858','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(634,'Modellling of an Inventory System is Dependent on Selling Price, Stock and Time Dependent Demand Rate With Partial Backlogging','Light plays an important role in physiological activites of leaf. Leaves of plants are concerned with photosynthesis, chloroplast are the organelles of the cell which are concerned with photosynthetic activity, disorganization of chloroplast is described as one of the first events to appear by the effect of various pollutants. \r\nIn a comprehensive survey of pollution impact on the photosynthetic efficiency of  certain plants in city junctions of Meerut i.e. Hapurstand, Begumpul, Collectorate crossing Mawana stand and in outskirts area i.e. Medical college, Delhi road, Pallavpuram, Shastri nagar L-block, a clear cut adverse impact has being recorded in the various process of photosynthetic efficiency.\r\nIn the control area photosynthetic efficiency parameters were quite higher. In the high polluted area of Meerut city like Hapurstand, Shastrinagar L-block, Begumpul has maximum impact and lowest hill reaction rate observed due to number of automobiles run on road throughout the year.\r\nHowever, in winter season a significant reduced efficiency has also been observed in other crossing of Meerut city in comparison to summer season and photosynthetic rate of final year showed a significant reduction in the age of roadside plants of city, where as, in control area of Gandhi bagh the photosynthetic rate either the same or there was a little increase in hill reaction rate during final season. Photosynthetic response of junctions is in following order : Hapurstand < Shastrinagar L-block < Begumpul < Medical college < Delhi road < Pallavpuram < Mawana stand < Collectorate. \r\nPlants response is in following order : Kaner < Bougainvillea < Shahtoot < Shishum < Eucalyptus','','-','Rakesh Agrawal, Debangna Rajput','859-970','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(635,'Dielectric Behaviors of Zinc Substituted Lithium Ferrites','Lithium zinc ferrites having the compositional formula Li 0.5-0.5x ZnxFe2.5-0.5xO4  where 0.2 ? x ? 0.6 in steps of 0.2 were synthesized by the citrate precursor method. The spinel phase structure of the samples was confirmed by the XRD analysis. Dielectric behavior was studied on the synthesized samples as a function of frequency, and temperature. Decrease in the value of dielectric constant with frequency is observed. The dielectric constant and dielectric loss increases with increase in temperature for all the composition. Possible mechanism contributing to all the process is being discussed.','','-','Ibetombi Soibam ,  Sumitra Phanjoubam','871-876','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(636,'Co-composting of Pressmud and Flyash with Distillery Effluent','India is producing 20 million tones of sugar annually. Most of the sugar industries are incorporated with the cane molasses-based distillery units. The distillery effluent from these industries is discharged directly into river or on land without treatment. An attempt has been made to compost the effluent with pressmud (by product of sugar industry) and flyash (waste from boilers) for the production of biomanure, so that discharging of effluent into open waterbodies can be reduced, and the byproducts can be used to improve the soil fertility. The concentrated effluent was sprayed to maintain moisture content (approximately 50-60%). The chemical and physicochemical parameters as well as biological tests to determine the quality of compost have been performed. The mixture of pressmud and flyash (3:1 weight basis) was assessed suitable filler material for utilization of distillery effluent. The C:N ratio of this compost  was also higher than other mixtures.','','-','Nishtha Yadav, Vikash Talyan and C.P.Kaushik','877-886','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(637,'Hydrogen Nano Polymer, A Clean Sources of Hydrogen Energy','Hydrogen Nanomaterials have attracted great interest in recent years because of the unusual mechanical, electrical, electronic, optical and magnetic properties endowed by confining the dimensions of such materials and because of the combination of bulk and surface properties to the overall behavior. The high surface to volume ratio of these materials has significant implications with respect to energy storage devices of electrochemical active sites (e.g. batteries, ultracapacitors, etc.). The diverse tunable properties of nanomaterials also offer potential promise for hydrogen storage. It is important to address and appreciate the advantages and disadvantages of nanomaterials for hydrogen storage, as well as how to control their synthesis and properties. This is a sizeable challenge facing those involved in materials research into energy storage. \r\nBoth the high surface area and the opportunity for nanomaterial consolidation are key attributes of this new class of materials for hydrogen storage devices. Nanostructured systems including carbon nanotubes, nano-magnesium-based hydrides, complex hydride/carbon nanocomposites, boron nitride nanotubes, TiS2/MoS2 nanotubes, alanates, Tetrathiophene-9,9-spirobi[9H-fluorene, polymer nanocomposites and metal organic frameworks are considered to be a potential for storing large quantities of hydrogen. Recent investigations have shown that nanoscale materials may offer advantages if certain physical and chemical effects related to the nanoscale can be used efficiently. Associated phenomena, such as surface interactions, materials transport, defects, vacancies, phase transitions, grain boundary phenomena and the formation of new and metastable phases may also play an important role in the development of reversibly working hydrogen storage materials with high cycling stability. Developing novel nanocatalysts and understanding the mechanistic behavior for the enhancement of hydrogen sorption kinetics is a great challenging task f','','-','Parshuram Singh, Rajeev Kumar Singh','887-894','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(638,'Flow of a Dusty Fluid Between Two Infinite Parallel Plates','In this paper, we study the Beltrami flow of a dusty fluid between two infinite parallel plates. By considering the fluid and dust particle are at rest initially, the analytical expressions are obtained for velocities of fluid and dust particles using Laplace transform technique in three different cases. The changes in the velocity profiles for different Reynolds number are shown graphically','','-','Sombir, P.K. Shukla','895-904','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(639,'FT-Raman and FT-IR spectra, vibrational assignments,ab initio HF and DFT analysis of 6-Amino-1,3-dimethyl-uracil','The Fourier transform Raman and Fourier transform infrared spectra of 6-amino-1,3-dimethyl-uracil were recorded in the solid phase. The equilibrium geometry, natural atomic charges, harmonic vibrational frequencies, infrared intensities and Raman intensities were obtained by means of ab initio Hartee Fock (HF) and density functional theory (DFT) gradient calculations with complete relaxation in the potential energy surface using  6-31+G(d,p) basis set. The scaled theoretical wavenumbers showed very good agreement with the experimental values. A detailed interpretations of the infrared and Raman spectra of 6-amino-1,3-dimethyl-uracil is reported on the basis of the calculated potential energy distribution (PED). The theoretical spectrograms for the Raman and IR spectra of the title molecule have been constructed','','-','Jyoti Chaudhary , Manju Singh, B. S.Yadav','905-916','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(640,'A Time Dependent Deteriorating Inventory Model with Ramp Type Demand and Inflation','In this paper, we developed a time dependent deteriorating inventory model with ramp type demand. Deterioration rate is taken as two parameters Weibull distribution. In this study, a more realistic scenario was assumed where part of the shortage was backordered and the rest was lost with time dependent backlogging rate. The environment of the whole study has been taken as inflationary. The whole combination of the setup is very unique and smore practical. Finally, numerical example is presented to demonstrate the developed model and the solution procedure.','','-','Pawan Kumar, N K Gaur','917-928','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(641,'Supply Chain Model with Exponential Demand Rate, Weibull Deterioration Under Inflation','In this paper an integrated inventory model is developed from the perspective of both the manufacturer and the retailer. The model assumes exponential demand rate. Production rate is taken as demand dependent under the effect of inflation.  Shortages are allowed and the unfulfilled demand is partially backlogged. A numerical example along with sensitivity analysis is given to illustrate the model.','','-','V K Sharma, Prachi Kansal','929-942','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(642,'A Fuzzy Approach to Query Based Image Retrieval','The current trend in the rapid growth of on-line image databases has brought forth several innovative approaches to current based image retrieval. Most current techniques retrive images based on an example or object shapes/features extracted from images. Retrieval based on linguistic queries has not received much attention. We present a fuzzy connective approach to handle queries consisting of multiple attributes, we represent each attribute in a complex query by a membership function. The degree of which an image satisfies the attributes is obtained by funding the membership value of the feature vector corresponding to the image in the membership function for the attributes. We propose the use of fuzzy connectives to combine the degree of satisfaction of multiple attributes in a complex query to arrive at an overall degree of satisfaction. This overall degree is used to rank image for retrieval.\r\nThe membership function for the attributes can be generated in various ways. In this paper we consider attribute such as \'Bark-like\' and \'Water Like\' which correspond to fuzzy categories in the images. In order to determine the membership function corresponding to fuzzy attributes we use a maximum-like hood-based robust mixture decomposition technique to organize the given database according to categories that are inherent in the database The robust mixture decomposition algorithm provides us with membership function to represent the categories and these membership function can be used to handle complex queries','','-','Rakesh Sharma, Saurabh Rawat, Anushree Sah','943-950','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(643,'Study of The Effect of Surface Tension on The Cnoidal And Solitary Waves','The present paper is devoted to the theoretical study of the effect of surface tension on the cnoidal and solitary waves. it has been found that it is possible to find the different approximations in the friedrichs systematic development of the shallow  water wave theory when the surface tension at the free surface is also taken into account. it has been noted that the wave length of the conidal wave is aregmented and the solitary waves are widened due to surface tension. the vertical velocity is also lessened due to the inclusion of surface tension : the limiting height and the maximum velocity have also been found out for any solotory wave.','','-','Prabir Kumar Shrivastava, Praveen Kumar and  Deepika Sonal','951-964','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(644,'Industrial Effluents and their potential hazard to Agricultural Land in Luni Tehsil of Jodhpur district','Industrialization not only raises the economy but also invites the pollution problem with it as in Jodhpur, Rajasthan. Industrial waste is a main source of pollution for all environments. Jodhpur has specifically textile and stainless steel units. These units discharges large amount of effluents in the Jojari River and causes serious environmental problem to the nearby villages of Luni Tehsil. The effluents of some industries are treated in Common effluent treatment plant (CETP) while many other discharge their effluents directly to main drain. Receiving end of wastewater discharged from these industries is seasonal river Jojari, a tributary of Luni River. Due to heavy rainfall in last year monsoon, industrial water along with rain water overflows the Jojari drainage system and contaminated water spreads over the agricultural lands of villages downstream. Which cause the devastating damage of standing crops, contamination of surface and ground water resources, soil productivity and serious harm to Doli-Melwa Wild Life Sanctuary. The present study is carried out to evaluate the extent of problem in the area and find out the factors responsible for the creation of the problem and its continuance. The study has also come across various pollution control strategies available to overcome the problem.','','-','Trapti Sharma, S. Palria','965-976','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(645,'Analysis of Pattern Recognition (text mining) with Web Crawler','To design a web crawler that can find out the similarity between the input text file and the text available on the various links visited by the web crawler.\r\nIt is organized and gives the evolution of the internet and discusses general architecture of search engine; as we have used a type of Web Crawler known as Focus Web crawler.\r\nIn this we have discussed about the pattern recognition, here pattern we mean only text and how we are using pattern recognition over the crawler. It also covers the algorithms that we are using for pattern recognition along with their pseudo code. It covers the steps to tell how our crawler will work and generates the comparisons after mining of text.','','-','Abhay Bhatia, Anil Kumar, Imran Khan, Vikas Kumar','435-450','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','33','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(646,'Performance comparison of EW and Genetic Algorithm for Dynamic CMST','In the real world, there are usually such cases that one has to consider weight of each edge and the capacity of the network design based on the demand of each node. Analysis and Comparison of EW and GA with two encodings Prufer and Netkey for the capacitated minimum spanning tree.','','-','Anil Kumar, Abhay Bhatia, Imran Khan, Vikas Kumar','451-466','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','33','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(647,'Economic Utilization of Pine Litter Waste for Generating White Coal Energy and Vermicompost Bio-Resources in Uttarakhand','In Uttarakhand state, attention towards the forest fires related losses and promoting organic farming is the major concept. In high altitudes (>1000m), Pine spp. are dominated which is the main reasons for the repeated forest fires in Uttarakhand state, as probably producing the burning raw material pine needles. Pine needles are more prone to forest fire where whole forest floor finally ends up in ashes. For controlling forest fire, the pine needles, Lantana shrub and waste litter of the other trees can be utilized for the production of biomass energy (white coal + vermicompost) into fruitful uses. If a community project is started to collect all this biomass (pine needles, other trees waste leaves, waste dry wood and Lantana shrub as raw material) from the forests, which can be subsequently converted into vermicompost and white coal briquettes (high density biomass) will help in transportation of the biomass for commercial purposes. This gives an alternative to the energy generation coupled with a lot of jobs to the hill local youth to collect the biomass from the forests and then converting the same into the briquettes and vermicompost. If this is achieved, Forest Department will also be able to stop forests fires. This type of local projects can be highly successful in hilly state of Uttarakhand. \r\n\r\nThe present issue is quite important considering the facts of controlling repeated forest fires and the subsequent loss of governmental, public and private property as well as the wild life and biodiversity, causing heavy loss to Forest Department and hilly natural resources. The forest biomass waste (Pine needles and Lantana shrub) can easily be used in vermicompost manufacturing and also be used as an efficient fuel (white coal) for kitchen cooking even in the most modern home. It has been demonstrated that totally smokeless combustion can be achieved from these biomass sources. Fuel is prime need of every industry & pollution free environment is the prime concern','','-','Deepak Kholiya, Rakesh Bachheti','467-484','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','33','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(648,'Service Quality Perceptions: A Case Study of Banking Services','In the past, banking was concerned only with borrowing and lending activities. But at present, banking is catering to the entire requirement of individual customers and is emerging as a potential sector for the consistent growth of business. Customers retention is one of the top priority of the banks. Many customers are not wanting but are expecting better services. Customers have started demanding variety in banking services and their preference for delivery channels are changing. It is true that technology has provided a unique competitive advantage to some banks in India, as these banks have taken a lead in the use of technology for introducing special products and services viz. Cash management, credit cards, ATMs, Electronic Fund Transfer(EFT), Real Time Gross Settlement(RTGS), debit cards etc. But as far as this study is concerned it is more focused on the services in the bank premises. When banks are providing so many and adopting new techniques to satisfy their customers, they should also try to find out whether the customers are really satisfied with their customers, they should also try to find out whether the customers are really satisfied with their services or not. Issues such as offering a proper reception at the counter, consideration for their time, updating of their passbooks, speedy collection of their cheques and drafts are considered to be of the prime importance to the most of the customers. Realizing this, the present study has undertaken to assess the quality of services being rendered to the customers by public and private sector banks. The main aim of this research paper is to assess and re-assess how customers perceive banking services, what are the emerging customers expectations and to study customers satisfaction level with banking services provided by the public and private sector banks.','','-','Somprabh Dubey','485-500','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','33','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(649,'Potential of Sacred Groves in Promoting Ecotourism in Uttarakhand Himalayas','In Uttarakhand state lots of villages have temple forests both in Garhwal and Kumaon regions, where deities or spirits are worshipped by local communities. These are patches of forests containing different indigenous wild life species and natural water springs (aquifers) present in these patches of forests are the main sources of water for the local people in many cases. e.g. Badrivan, ancient sacred forest of Badrinath, where two important trees Bhojpatra (Betula utilis) and Badri (Juniperus macropoda) and shrubs of Badriphal (Hippophae salicifolia) were the predominant vegetation. These sacred forests are at the verge of disappearance due to a variety of reasons, particularly anthropogenic. A restoration programme should be undertaken for environmental conservation / biodiversity conservation and preservation of the spiritual and cultural values of these important sacred places of Hindus. Hariyali, as a sacred forest of Garhwal Himalaya is yet another example where people have conserved the forest through socio-cultural and religious practices. There are so many more, which need to the enlisted and documented for conservation and other purposes, that becomes one of the main long term objective as a tourist product for promoting sustainable eco-tourism.\r\nUttarakhand has a age-old tradition of having protected temple forests near villages, where deity / deities are worshipped in a grove or groups of trees. The trees / vegetation growing in these groves are not allowed to cut / fell, as it is believed to belong to the deity. Only the dead / dried parts are sometimes used by them. Even sometimes sudden dying of trees / plants of these forest are said to be bio-indicator of mishappenings / misfortune for the villagers. This type of restriction in these forests have helped conservation of native / indigenous species of these areas. The future studies should be conducted because documentation / enlisting of medicinal plants present in these sacred forests / temple forest','','-','Deepak Kholiya, Laxmi Rawat and Preeti Joshi','501-524','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','33','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(650,'Electrical And Structurel Properties of CdTe/ZnTe Heterojunction Thin Films','Thin film of highly pure (99.999%) CdTe/ZnTe was  prepared by high vacuum technique                (HVT 5x10-6 torr), on glass substrates at different substrate temperatures. Thin Films have thickness 0.25 ?m. The X-ray diffraction study of the film represents amorphous nature at lower deposition temperature but poly-crystalline nature at higher deposition temperature.  The film deposited at lower temperatures was annealed for one hour in vacuum of 5x10-4 torr at as-deposited to 600K. The annealed film also represent poly-crystalline nature as film deposited at higher substrate temperature, because all films having different grain sizes, for lower  temperature the conductivity is essentially temperature dependent and at higher temperature the potential barriers localized at grain boundaries limit.','','-','P.K.Pandey, K.S.Upadhyay, S.N.Shukla,P.K.Singh,D.Sharma','525-528','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','33','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(651,'Molecular Polarizability of 2-hydroxy-4-methyl  Pyrimidine hydrochloride','The one dimensional Semi-empirical deltafunction model of chemical binding has been used to evaluate the average molecular polarizabilities  of some   heterocyclic molecules. A Simplified general approach has been adopted to evaluate the residual atomic polarizability degrees of freedom (ndf) assuming a planer structure for the molecules. The results obtained are in close agreement with those obtained by other methods, both  theoretical and experimental. The present calculations provide an excellent support to earlier study.','','-','Manoj Kumar Singh, Sudesh Kumar Sharma, Preeti Yadav, Vijay Kumar, Jayant Teotia, B. S. Yadav','529-536','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','33','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(652,'An Integrated Production-Inventory Model for Deteriorating Items under the effect of Inflation','During this paper, an integrated inventory model for deteriorating items from the perspectives of both the manufacturer and the retailer is developed. A mathematical model with integrating single supplier, single producer and single buyer is derived to obtain the optimal number of deliveries and order lot-size, when the joint total cost of the supplier, the producer and the buyer is minimized. The proposed paper divided into two sections with respect to demand rates, backlogging rates and deterioration rates. A numerical example is presented and with sensitivity analysis of the model is carried out.','','-','N. K. Gaur, Satish Kumar,S. R. Singh','537-542','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','33','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(653,'An Inventory Model with Stock Dependent Demand, Weibull Deterioration Rate and Shortages under Inflation and Time Discounting','This paper deals with an extended EOQ-type inventory model for a perishable product where the demand rate is a function of the on-hand inventory. Many supermarket managers have observed that, for some items, the demand rate is directly related to the amount of inventory displayed. It is a common believes that large files of goods displayed in a supermarket will lead the costumer to buy more. These observations have attracted many marketing researchers and practitioners to investigate the modeling aspects of this phenomenon.','','-','Kamal Kumar, Ashok Kumar','563-572','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','33','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(654,'Two Warehouse Model With Ramp Type Demand With Partially Backlogging','In this paper we developed a two-warehouse inventory model with ramp type demand rate. Demand rate is the combination of increasing-steady-decreasing demand patters. Every change in demand is directly correlated to the production rate of that particular commodity. Shortages are permitted and partially backlogged. Backlogging rate is waiting time for the next replenishment. The production planning and control system should be designed to complement the corporate strategy and to provide additional competitive advantage. Therefore, we have taken production rate proportional to the demand rate. Results are illustrated with numerical example.','','-','Mahendra Singh, Punam Sharma','573-590','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','33','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(655,'A Note on Vorticity of Hydromagnetic Flow on a Continuously Moving Vertical Surface','This paper deals with study of vorticity of hydromagnetic flow on a continuously moving vertical surface. A flow of this type represents a new class of boundary  layer flow at a surface of finite length. The vorticity of the flow has been found for different values of magnetic parameter M and Pradlt number . Some important conclusions have been drawn on the effect of magnetic parameter M and Prandtl number   over the vorticity of the flow.','','-','Anu Agarwal  and M.P. Singh','1-4','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','39','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(656,'A Note on the Vorticity in Effect of Thermal Diffusion on Steady Laminar Free Convective Flow Along a Moving Porous Hot Vertical Plate in the Presence of Heat Source with Mass Tansfer','The purpose of the present problem is to investigate the vorticity in effect of thermal diffusion on steady laminar free convective flow through porous medium along a moving porous hot vertical plate in the presence of heat source with mass transfer. The vorticity profiles Gr >0 (flow on a heated plate) are depicted graphically and discussed in detail. The skin friction coefficient is also obtained in this paper.','','-','S.K.Shakya and Shri Prakash','5-8','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','39','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(657,'Thermal  Instability of  Hetrogeneous   Rotating     Fluid Layers in Presence of Magnetic Field with Free Boundaries','In this paper, we consider the thermal instability of density stratified horizontal layer of an electrically conducting fluid in the presence of a constant magnetic field in the horizontal direction. Also we have studied the instability of a viscous, incompressible and non-homogeneous rotating fluid layer with free boundaries under a horizontal magnetic field. It is assumed that the fluid is rotating with an angular velocity ? about the vertical axis in the presence of a horizontal magnetic field. The density depends on Z, the vertical co-ordinate. Further, we take the system with respect to rotating co-ordinate system, rotating with the same angular velocity ? about Z-axis, so that with respect to this co-ordinate system the fluid can be taken to be at rest. In this paper we get the wave frequency and Rayleigh number at marginal state. Also we see that the marginal state does not exist for  ,  and non-oscillatory modes are unstable for  . We also discuss the variation of  , , ,  with one another numerically with the help of eight different tables.','','-','Paramjit Singh, Sapan and Arun Kumar Tomer','9-20','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','39','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(658,'Effect of Magnothydrodynamic on Time Varying Flow of a Power Law Fluid Through Porous Medium Between Parallel Porous Plates With Heat Source Under an Exponential Decaying Pressure Gradient','Aim of present study to the effect of magneto hydrodynamic on time varying flow through porous medium of a viscous incompressible non-Newtonian power law fluid between two parallel horizontal porous plates is studied with heat source under an exponential decaying pressure gradient. A uniform suction and injection through the surface of the plates is applied. The two plates are kept at different but constant temperatures, while the viscous dissipation is