velocity of rotation of particles and skin friction are obtained. The effects of couple stresses and, permeability parameter and other parameters entering into the problem on velocity distribution and skin friction are shown graphically and discussed numerically. It is found that the velocity of the fluid is increased when the couple stresses and increased.','','-','Vimal Kumar,  and S. S. Yadav','37-44','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','39','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(661,'Some Fluid Spheres of Embedding Class One with Non-Vanishing Weyl -Tensor in 5-Flat Form','Some non-conformally flat fluid spheres are obtained by considering a 5-flat space-time. All the solutions are invariant under the Lie group of transformations. The same problem was tackled by the other workers using the same technique but with lesser number of symmetries and hence could obtain only lesser number of solutions as compared to the number of solutions in this present article.','','-','Sachin Kumar, Y. K. Gupta and Pratibha','45-58','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','39','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(662,'A Mathematical Model for Pulsatile Blood Flow in an Artery','In this paper we obtain the effect of Cassons fluid on pulsatile flow of blood. In order to study the flow rate, wall shear stress and velocity profile, we have extended the Picarads type iteration procedure. The steady flow in rigid tubes is modified into pulsatile flow by introducing pressure gradient as a function of time.','','-','Isha Agarwal, P.K. Shukla','59-64','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','39','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(663,'Thermal Instability of Rivlin-Ericksen Visco-Elastic Fluid in an Anisotropic Porous Medium in Presence of Weak Magnetic Field','Thermal of instability Rivlin-Ericksen Visco-elastic fluid in anisotropic porous medium in the presence of weak magnetic field has been derived and solved analytically and numerically. Important results obtained in this paper include the sufficient condition for stability, marginal state of the system and solution of the problem for free boundaries.','','-','A. K. Agarwal, R. Goel , S. C. Agrawal','65-76','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','39','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(664,'A Mathematical Model to Study the Effect of Magnetic Field on Blood Flow','In this paper our aim is to find the effect of magnetic field in stenotic artery. We have modeled the artery as a circular cylinder consisting of stenosis. We have considered the realistic model of the basic function unit taking the steady viscous flow in artery with the help of equation of motion and one-dimensional diffusion equation. We have investigated the resistance to flow in artery for different values of magnetic field.','','-','Isha Agarwal, P.K. Shukla','77-82','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','39','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(665,'Flow of a Dusty Fluid Between two Infinite Parallel Plates','In this paper, we study the Beltrami flow of a dusty fluid between two infinite parallel plates. By considering the fluid and dust particle are at rest initially, the analytical expressions are obtained for velocities of fluid and dust particles using Laplace transform technique in three different cases. The changes in the velocity profiles for different Reynolds number are shown graphically.','','-','Sombir, P.K. Shukla','83-92','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','39','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(666,'Effect of Themal Diffusion on Vorticity of Mhd Visco-Elastic Boundary Layer Flow Through Porous Medium With Free Convection Past a Continuous  Moving Surface With Heat Source','In the present paper the behavior of Heat and Mass transfer free convective boundary layer flow of an electrically conduction visco-elastic, incompressible fluid through porous medium over a continuous moving flat surface in the presence of uniform magnetic field with perpendicular to the moving flat surface and heat source. The vorticity field is assumed to be applied Reynolds Number (R), Hartman Number (M), Prandtl Number (Pr), Schmidt number (Sc), Heat source parameter (S), Thermal diffusion parameter (A) and permeability parameter (K) on Vorticity field has also been discussed with the help of graph.','','-','Satyapal  Singh  , Dharm Pal Singh','93-100','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','39','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(667,'Effect of Thermal Diffusion on Unsteady Laminar Free Convective Flow of Dusty Viscous Fluid Through Porous Medium Along a Moving Porous Hot Vertical Plate With Hall Current ','The purpose of the present problem is to study the effect of thermal diffusion on unsteady laminar free convection flow of dusty viscous fluid through porous medium along a moving porous hot vertical plate in the presence of heat source and Hall current. The governing equations of motion are solved by finite difference technique. The numerical results are presented graphically for different values of the parameters entering into the problem on the velocity profiles of dusty fluid, dust particles, temperature, concentration profile and skin friction profile. ','','- ',' Smita Sharma,B.B.Singh ','135-142','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','40','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(668,'A Note on Vorticity of Hydromagnetic Free Convective Flow Past An Infinite Vertical Porous Plate ','The present paper deals with the study of the vorticity of hydromagnetic free convection flow of an incompressible viscous electrically conducting fluid past an infinite vertical porous plate. The vorticity of the flow has been found for different values of magnetic parameter M and Grashof number . Some important conclusions have been drawn on the effect of magnetic parameter M and Grashof number   over the vorticity of the flow\r\n\r\nNomenclature: = Free stream;  = Velocity components in  - and  direction respectively;  = Grashof number;  = Prandtl number; M = Magnetic Parameter;  = Magnetic induction; g = Acceleration due to gravity;  = Thermal diffusivity \r\nGreek symbols: = Density;  = coefficient of volume expansion;  = Kinematic viscosity:  = Electric conducting;  = Suction parameter;  = Non-conducting amplitude parameter;  = Vorticity ','','- ',' Anu Agarwal, M.P. Singh ','143-152','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','40','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(669,'Stability Analysis of Food Chain Model ','This paper is concerned with equilibrium and chaotic dynamics of the food chain of three species. The food chain includes of one prey X and two predators Y and W where Y depends on the prey X and the predator W depends upon the species Y only. The two predators Y and W have no competition. Conditions for the existence of all equilibria and stability properties are derived. The mathematical calculation we use Lipunave function and variational matrix to check non linear stability of the global equilibrium point and other equilibrium points respectively. Numerical simulation shows that the stability condition of the interior point is satisfied for the considered parameters. ','','- ',' Poonam Sinha, Geeta Gautam, Neeta Saxena ','153-166','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','40','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(670,'Application of Graph in Educational Sector','The great challenge for the Government and private technical Institutions in India is to impart quality education to generate industry competent professionals. In last ten years, a number of educational institutions came into existence. If we analyze the net outcome, we find  (i) Passing out students are semitrained (ii) Institutes are facing acute shortage of experienced faculty (iii) Employees turnover rate is alarmingly high in these institutions. (iv) The prevailing situation is chronic and it is very much possible that institutions which were born in geometric progression may vanish at much faster rate. Now, a time has come to examine the strategies and tactics with the intention of efficient allocation of scare resources to strengthen educational sector in India. In this competitive world of advanced technology where the changes and development run together, enough infrastructures has been developed in the sector and the private sector is ever willing to inject much more. The paper investigates an efficient and effective mechanism to identify resources and their allocation through graph for rigid quality assurance in Educational Sector.','','-','Sanjeev Kumar, B. K. Singh, Nisha Agarwal','1-10','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(671,'Experimental (FT-IR and FT-Raman) and theoretical (HF and DFT) investigation and frequency estimation analyses on 1-Chloro-3,5-dibromobenzene','The FT-IR and FT-Raman spectra of 1-Chloro-3,5-dibromobenzene (1-Cl-3,5-DBB) have been recorded in the region of 4000-100 cm?1. Ab-initio-HF (HF/6311+G (d, p)) and DFT (B3LYP/6311++G (d, p)) calculations have been performed giving energies, optimized structures, harmonic vibrational frequencies, depolarization ratios, IR intensities, Raman activities. The vibrational frequencies are calculated and scaled values have been compared with experimental FTIR . The observed and calculated frequencies are found to be in good agreement.','','-','Munish Kumar, Rajesh Kumar, M.K.Yadav','11-22','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(672,'UV Spectroscopic Investigation of Halogen Substituted Benzene Using DFT Calculations','UV-absorption spectra of 1-Chloro-3,5-dibromobenzene  has been recorded in two solvents of different polarity. The results indicate that the studied molecule pertains to the Benzene molecule structure. A common feature of the observed spectra is the overlap of the spectral bands. Absorption wavelengths and oscillator strengths were studied with density functional theory (DFT) and time-dependent density functional theory (TD-DFT). All calculations were carried out with Gaussian03 software package with the aid of density functional theory method at B3LYP/6-31 G (d, p) basis set in conjugation with a Polarizable Continuum Model (PCM). The calculated HOMO and LUMO energies show that charge transfer occurs within the molecule. An excellent agreement between the experimental and computed data for ?max determination was observed.','','-','Munish Kumar, Rajesh Kumar, M.K.Yadav','23-34','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(673,'Steady And Unsteady Boundary Layer Flow In 2-D Through','In the present chapter we have investigated, The stream function, Velocity component(u,v), Velocity potential, Complex potential of steady and unsteady boundary layer flow in two dimension through porous medium.','','-','Vishvas Chand, M.P.Singh, Rajendra Kumar','35-42','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(674,'Linear Stability Of Flow Under Porous Medium','In the present paper we have investigated linear stability of flow under porous medium, by normal mode technique, is more widely used. This is because it is applicable to a wider class of problems. In this method an linear theory, we assume the perturbations are arbitrary small in magnitude so that the non-linear terms on the perturbation variables and/or their derivatives, can be neglected as compared to the linear terms. More over we assume that the perturbations are regular function & of space variables & therefore the Fourier analysis of the perturbations is possible. Thus in this method the arbitrary perturbations & are split an some fundamental modes and the reaction of the system to all such mode is observed. If the system is stable with respect to each mode then the flow is stable (of course according to linear theory), & if there is even one mode for which it is unstable then the flow is unstable (in linear theory) because after some time this mode will dominate over the whole flow. If we take an Cartesian co-ordinates, any typical perturbation variable & if flow extends to infinity an x- and y- directions, then we take the Fourier analysis of this variable with respect to x and y. This is possible because at any instance, the perturbations are taken to be regular functions of space variables & bounded as x and y tends to infinity. We also take an exponential dependent variables w ? and t ?\r\n(W ?,T ?) =[W(Z ?),?(z ?)] exp(st ?+ilx ?+my ?)\r\nWhere t(lx ?,my ?,0) is called the wave number vector ?=l?l is called wave number.\r\nSince the normal mode technique is more widely used we shall mainly adopt this technique for discussing the stability of flows.','','-','Vishvas Chand, M.P.Singh, Rajendra Kumar','43-50','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(675,'Concept of Digital Systems for Square Root ','This paper deals with three algorithms implementations for square root computation. Newton-Raphson\'s, Iterative and Binary Search Algorithm implementations are completely designed, verified and compared. The algorithms, entire systems realization and their functioning are described. ','','- ','Shubhash Kumar Sharma,  Vishal Kumar Srivastava, S. N. Shukla ','51-60  ','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(676,'Molecular Polarizability and Thermodynamic parameters of 6-bromo-2-methylquinoline','The onedimensional Semi-empirical deltafunction model of chemical binding and rigid rotor harmonic oscillator model have been used for the calculation of molecular polarizabilities and statistical thermodynamic parameters of 6-bromo-2-methylquinoline. Same have been calculated by the computational density functional theory method with the standard higher basis sets 6-31+G(d,p) and 6-311++G(d,p). Statistical methods and spectroscopy have been combined to evaluate thermodynamic functions like enthalpy, entropy, free energy and heat capacity of substituted quinoline. Their temperature dependence has been studied in the temperature range 200-1500K.','','-','\"\"Sudesh Kumar Sharma, Ritu Saran, Manoj Kumar Singh, Vijay Kumar,  ;\r\nB S Yadav\"','61-72','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(677,'Statistical  Effect  of  Cadmium  Chloride  Toxicity on  Protein  Content  in  Lebistes  Reticulatus (Guppy','The toxic effect of cadmium chloride of two different sub lethal concentrations on Lebistes reticulatus have revealed drastic changes in the protein content in the tissue liver and kidney of fish. The statistical study fish exposed to sub lethal concentration for 15, 30 and 45 days showed decrease level of protein content.','','-','Sabiha Khan and Sanjay Jain','73-78','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(678,'Implementation of IEEE-754 to Decimal Conversion of  Library Components for Floating Point Arithmetic Unit','This paper deals with implementation of IEEE-754 to Decimal Conversion using VHDL. This work will minimize the work of the processor unit.  Here, we have utilized VHSIC Hardware Description Language and Xilinx to implement this conversion. A floating point processor unit is able to process all the operations on integers as well as on float values or all real values. It first converts the real values in normalized form then performs the different operations. The floating point unit is that part of computer that actually helps the ALU to perform arithmetic and logical operations on data. All of the other elements of the computer system-control unit registers, memory, I/Os are there mainly to bring data into the ALU for it to process and then to take the results back out.','','-','Subhash Kumar Sharma, Vishal Kumar Srivastava, Sachchida Nand Shukla','157-164','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(679,'Development of IEEE-754 to Decimal Conversion of Library Components for Floating Point Arithmetic Logic Unit','This paper deals with implementation of IEEE-754 to Decimal Conversion using VHDL. This work will minimize the work of the processor unit.  Here, we have utilized VHSIC Hardware Description Language and Xilinx to implement this conversion. A floating point processor unit is able to process all the operations on integers as well as on float values or all real values. It first converts the real values in normalized form then performs the different operations. The floating point unit is that part of computer that actually helps the ALU to perform arithmetic and logical operations on data.','','-','Udai Kumar Jha','165-170','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(680,'Optimal Replenishment Policy for Deteriorating Items with Time Dependent Demand under the Learning Effect','This paper considers the impact of the learning on set up cost on the classical Economic Order Quantity (EOQ) model for deteriorating items subject to trapezoidal type consumption rate and shortages. Deterioration models consider the gradual reduction in quality and quantity of products over time. In this study the deterioration rate is taken as three parameter Weibull distribution function of time. Deterministic inventory model with two levels of storage (i.e., a rented warehouse is used to store the excess units over the fixed capacitated own warehouse) has been studied by numerous authors. In contrast to the traditional deterministic two-warehouse inventory model with shortages at the end of each replenishment cycle, an alternative model in which each cycle begins with shortages and ends without shortages is proposed. The model is developed over an infinite time horizon to determine optimal replenishment policy by minimizing total system running cost of entire season. Finally, through numerical examples, sensitive analysis shows the influence of key model parameters.','','-','Shivraj Singh, Monika Vishnoi','171-186','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(681,'Some Transformation Formulas for a Srivastava-Karlsson Triple Hypergeometric Function','In the present paper I have deduced some transformation formulas for the triple hypergeometric function   given in Srivastava and Karlsson [4] in terms of the other triple hypergeometric functions given in Srivastava and Karlsson [4] in continuation of my previous study [5] of this function.','','-','Lalit Mohan Upadhyaya','187-192','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(682,'Alternative Second-Order Conditions in Multi-objective Optimization','In this paper, new formulations are given for the second order necessary conditions in parameter optimization with equality constraints. The new conditions are shown to be equivalent to previously known conditions by using the properties of projection matrices. The various conditions require various computational tools, as one of the obtained condition requires standard computational tools (i.e matrix inversion and eigen value computation), it might be useful in applications.(e.g real time optimization schemes) when these standard tools are already in use.','','-','Shifali Bhargava and Abhishek Agrawal','193-202','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(683,'An Inventory Model with Time Dependent Demand Rates under the Effect of Inflation','The main purpose of holding inventories is to meet the demands of the market. Generally, retailers face many types of demands for different kinds of goods. These demands are not within the control of the organization. This chapter presents an inventory model for decaying items with time dependent demand rate. The deterioration rate considered as linear function of time. Shortages are allowed and partial backlogged. Holding cost is taken as a linear increasing function of time. Results are illustrated with numerical example for models along with sensitivity analysis.','','-','Anand Chauhan, A.P.Singh and S.R.Singh','203-216','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(684,'Development and analysis of an inventory system with stock dependent demand and two types of holding facilities','In this paper we develop an inventory model for deteriorating items with two warehouses having limited capacities by removing the impractical assumption regarding the storage capacity of rented warehouse. Due to different preserving facilities and storage environment, separate inventory holding costs and deterioration rates are considered in the different warehouses. The demand rate is a linear function of the on-hand inventory and deterioration rate is taken as time dependent. Shortages are allowed with partial backlogging. Finally, the profit function maximization was illustrated by numerical example and sensitivity analysis','','-','Pankaj Kaushal ,A.P.Singh,D. Singh','217-230','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(685,'Energy Simulation of a Single Zone Building Determining\r\nIndoor Air Temperature','The quantitative estimation of indoor air temperature of a building has been made by giving attention to fluctuation of climate and variation in design in a computational method considering climatic data, thermo physical properties of materials used in the building and other appliances. The evaluation of indoor temperature involves solution of the system of equations where the time dependent heat flow characteristics are expressed in terms of transient operators, which relate the heat flow at inside surface of each element with the temperature variation at internal and external surface and the internal air. Indoor air temperature has been determined by taking all the input data such as outdoor air temperature, solar radiation and specification of the materials used in building components, diffusivity, film heat transfer coefficient, absorption coefficient of exposed surface etc. The results obtained by this method have been compared with those obtained by ISO/DIS: 13791 pertaining to thermal insulation materials. By this method and procedure taking all the inputs given in the standard, the result is approximately within the limit imposed by ISO/DIS: 13791 may not differ by more than 0.50C.','','-','B. M. Suman','231-242','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(686,'Modelling and Analysis of an Inventory System with Ramp  Type Demand Rate and Backlogging','In this paper an inventory model for deteriorating and ameliorating items with variable holding cost has been developed.  e considered the ameliorating items which follow time varying demand with ramp type pattern. Shortages are permitted and partially back-ordered. The back-ordering fraction is taken to be decreasing function of waiting time. Total cost of the system is formulated and optimal replenishment policy is derived, keeping in view the above factors of the system','','-','Vikramjeet Singh ,A.P.Singh, D. Singh','243-256','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(687,'Two warehouse inventory model for deteriorating items with time and on hand inventory level dependent demand,Partial backlogging Under inflation','An inventory problem for a deteriorating item having two separate warehouses, one is an own warehouse (OW) of finite dimension and the other rented warehouse (RW) of infinite dimension, is developed under inflation and time value of money. Deterioration rates of items in the two warehouses are different, which is time dependent. In addition, shortages are allowed and partially backlogged. Due to different facilities and storage environment, inventory holding cost is considered to be different in different warehouses. The demand rate of items is a unique combination of time and on-hand inventory level. The stocks of RW transported to OW in continuous release pattern. In this study, particular cases are also provided with different demand rates and with or without shortages. The model has also been exemplified with the several numerical examples in the later part of the chapter. The results have also been interpreted graphically','','-','Jitendra Singh, B.B.Singh,S.R.Singh','257-274','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(688,'An approach for Software Reliability Growth Model Selectiion and Deciding Software Release','Software reliability is one of the most important attribute of software quality. Developing reliable software is the difficult problem which software industry facing. It is also very hard problem to know whether or not the software being delivered is reliable .There exist a large no of software reliability growth models for reliability prediction. There does not exist a single model which can be universally recommended or can be used (fitted) in all cases. Therefore, recent works have been focused on selecting of software reliability model which is appropriate for the cumulative failure data. We proposed an algorithm for selection of most appropriate software reliability growth model according to the failure data. If the Software reliability Growth model pass the proposed criteria they may be used to make the release decision. We eliminate some weaknesses in previously published algorithm strigfellow, 2002 and add some useful part to the algorithm.. The algorithm is tested with publically available data set and we analysis the performance of the algorithm.','','-','Amit Bindal,D.S. Rao, Gurpreet Singh','275-284','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(689,'Integral Representations for the Srivastava Karlsson Triple Hypergeometric Function','In the present paper I have established some integral representations for the Srivastava Karlsson triple  hypergeometric function   (see Srivastava and Karlsson [12]).','','-','Lalit Mohan Upadhyaya','285-290','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(690,'On Legendre Matrix Polynomials and its Applications','The aim of this paper is to define and study the Legendre matrix polynomials. An explicit representation, a three-term matrix recurrence relation, Rodrigues\'s formula, hypergeometric matrix representations and Christoffel formula for the Legendre matrix polynomials are given, and the Legendre matrix differential equations of second order are established.','','-','Lalit Mohan Upadhyaya, A. Shehata','291-310','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(691,'An Inventory System With Life Time, Incremental Holding Cost and Partial Backlogging','This paper deals an inventory model for deteriorating items with power demand and life time. Deterioration rate is taken as time dependent. Shortages are permitted with partial backlogging and backlogging rate is waiting time for the next replenishment. Many inventory models in past were developed under the assumption that the holding cost is constant for the entire inventory cycle. But this is particularly false in the storage of deteriorating and perishable items such as food products. The longer these food products are kept in storage, the more sophisticated storage facilities and services needed and therefore, the higher holding cost. The holding cost is assumed to be varying over time in only few inventory models. Numerical analysis and sensitivity analysis has also been done for some parameters.','','-','Shakti Singh Chouhan, Rachana Kumari','311-320','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(692,'An Inventory Model with Exponential Demand with Weibull Distribution Deterioration with Partial Backloging & Trade Credit Under Inflection','This paper deals an inventory model for deteriorating items with power demand and life time. Deterioration rate is taken as time dependent. Shortages are permitted with partial backlogging and backlogging rate is waiting time for the next replenishment. Many inventory models in past were developed under the assumption that the holding cost is constant for the entire inventory cycle. But this is particularly false in the storage of deteriorating and perishable items such as food products. The longer these food products are kept in storage, the more sophisticated storage facilities and services needed and therefore, the higher holding cost. The holding cost is assumed to be varying over time in only few inventory models. Numerical analysis and sensitivity analysis has also been done for some parameters.','','-','Vinamra Sharma, Rachana Kumari','321-332','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(693,'Profit Optimization Model for an Enlarged Product Line Firm Dealing with Time Bound Delivery','In todays competitive environment, to meet the rising demands and expectations of the customers, the companies keep on expanding their horizon, they have to deal in a number of products but many times, due to unavoidable circumstances they fail to follow time bound schedule and it becomes difficult for them to meet the requirements of all the customers at one go. The proposed model deals with the problem of profit maximization of firms, which offer enlarged product line but at the same time have to deal with customers who insist for immediate delivery of the product.','','-','Kiran Vasishtha, Rajesh Dangwal, D. B. Ojha, Ashok Kumar Vasishtha','333-342','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(694,'Mathematical Study Of Blood Partial Pressure Of Human Respiratory System','The process of control of the respiratory system is one of the most important tasks in physiology of respiration. The role of blood partial pressure in our body system is very crucial because it depends on the heart rate and ventilation. The construction of a model and its analysis are actually linked with understanding the nature of the mechanisms, including physiological mechanisms that satisfy the need of living organism.\r\nIn the present paper we study the blood partial pressure of our body system mainly the arterial system and venous system. Two nonlinear coupled ordinary differential equations have used associated to arterial pressure and venous Pressure. The solution of the system of non linear coupled ordinary differential equations numerically is obtained using fourth order Runge kutta method.','','-','Devdatta, V.K.Katiyar, Pratibha, Anju Saini','343-346','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(695,'Performance Comparison Between AODV and Modified AODV Protocol in Ad-Hoc Network','Mobile ad-hoc network is the collection of node which dynamically forms a temporary network without the use of any existing network infrastructure or centralized administration. When the mobility in the network is high and the topology changes frequently the route maintenance overhead in AODV increases. Because nodes can move link breakages can occurs. Long path is more vulnerable to link breakages and requires high control overhead for its maintenance. In this paper we introduce a new modified AODV protocol. This new protocol uses HELLO packets of intermediate nodes to find the most sable neighbors and therefore most stable path. This new proposed protocol is SR-AODV (Stable Route-AODV) protocol. We simulate both AODV and SR-AODV with ns-2 in similar scenario. We find that SR-AODV will show better performance than AODV.','','-','Pratima Gupta, Rakesh Kumar','347-352','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(696,'Integrated  inventory Model with Inflation Induced Demand and Shortages under two Storage','In this paper an inventory model is developed in which shortages are considered with two-storage under inflation induced demand rate. Due to different preservation environment it is assumed that in one warehouse deterioration rate is time varying linear and in the other it is taken as Weibull distributed deterioration. The classical optimization technique is used to drive the optimal solution. Finally, some numerical examples for illustration are provided.','','-','V K Sharma, Prachi Kansal','475-484','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(697,'An Analysis of Innovative Classroom Practices from Childrens Perspective','The present study analyses how students perceive innovative classroom practices being used in their classes to make education stress free. The objective of the study is to know the different innovative methods introduced recently, to understand their practicability, usability and analyse whether these methods are helping to make education stressfree or simply adding to the woes of students by adding to their workload. For the present study, 50 students were chosen studying in 7th and 8th standard in top rung CBSE schools of Delhi. A semi-structured schedule was prepared to judge students responses, which were duly recorded for content analysis. Results revealed that classroom practices have undergone a distinct change, especially after schools have been compelled to adopt CBSE directive of Continuous and Comprehensive Evaluation. Now the schools are embracing methods that promote holistic development of the child. However there are many unresolved issues associated too. Students perceive these classroom practices as being beneficial for them but also seem skeptical about teacher biases (as there are no fixed standards of evaluation), future competition (studies get neglected) and expenses incurred. On one hand they seem happy with the increased activities of the classroom on the other hand they complain about the increased workload and HW. It is suggested that the implementation of these innovative practices should be undertaken with utmost care and within the classroom so that students do not carry the burden of projects and assignments back home.','','-','Ekta Sharma , Sweta Singh Rathore','01-04','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(698,'IQ AS A DETERMINANT OF MORAL JUDGEMENT','The present study was carried out to study the relationship between IQ and Moral Judgement among children of 8-11years age group.The sample consisted of 152children, 76 out of which were in age group 8-9 years and 76 were in the age group 10-11 years. Sex ratio was also maintained. Intelligence Quotient was measured by J.C Ravens Colored Progressive Matrices and moral judgement was measured by Moral Judgement Test (MJT) developed by Meera Verma and Durganand SinghResults revealed a significant association as well as positive and significant correlation between IQ and moral judgement, suggesting that IQ is necessary (though not sufficient) condition for development of mature moral judgement.','','-','PUJA GULATI','05-10','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(699,'Impact of Constructivist Approach on Science Achievement of 8th standard Students','he main aim   of science education at the primary, middle and high school level are assumed to help students to become healthy and creative members of the society with some necessary scientific literacy. To learn science from a constructivist approach implies direct experience with science as a process of knowledge generation in which prior knowledge is elaborated and changed on the basis of fresh meaning negotiated with peers and teachers. A constructivist approach is based on the idea that the learner constructs his or her own knowledge through negotiation of meaning. This study compares the use of constructivist environment to teach science to a traditional lecture method. The purpose of this research paper was to observe the impact of constructivism approach on science achievement of 8th standard students with the help of pre test, treatment program and post tests on experimental and control groups which were equated on the basis of intelligence and socio-economical status. The findings revealed that constructivist approach had a positive impact on the science achievement of 8th standard students and there is no significant difference in the performance of boys and girls of both the groups.','','-','Rita Chopra,  Ranjana Gupta','11-16','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(700,'RESTRUCTURING TEACHER EDUCATION IN 21st CENTURY','The present educational scenario of the 21st century has become prone to stressing more on QUALITY than on QUANTITY. Apart from this, education has been declared a fundamental right and as a result of this  equity, access and quality has to be ensured for all. In the light of global scenario teacher training process needs a complete transformation. A curriculum needs to be framed which is equipped with such provisions for development of teaching competencies. First a comprehensive system of providing experiential learning to the student teachers need to be incorporated in pre service teacher education programme which is skill based. In this context it will be fruitful if during training process some provision is made for providing real school exposure to students.  It should provide opportunities to the student teachers to get acquainted with real experiences. There is need of providing real classroom teaching experiences to the student teachers so that they develop competencies which help them to faces these challenges of 21st Century. The curriculum should be practical oriented and project based that help them understand the real role of a teacher. There should be more emphasis on classroom oriented training. In this context it is noteworthy to mention that MANGALAYATAN UNIVERSITY has initiated a B.Ed.- Innovative Program from the session 2009-10 which is an  innovative program of teacher preparation with strong accent on development of teaching competencies and capabilities for designing effective teaching learning systems blended with value education','','-','Jyoti Sankar Pradhan','17-20','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(701,'ARVA SHIKSHA ABHIYAN  : FULFILLING THE NEEDS OF RURAL & URBAN  CHILDREN','Sarva Shiksha Abhiyan (SSA) is an initiative of Government of Indian with a clear time frame for Elementary Education. It also provides an opportunity for promoting social justice through basic education all over the country where every child will have access to education irrespective of caste, creed or locality of the child. The researchers made efforts to investigate whether this programme is a success in fulfilling the needs of children or not. Total 364 students (182 rural and 182 urban) were selected randomly from 30 primary and upper primary schools (15 rural and 15 urban) of Dehradun district of Uttarakhand. The data was analysed by employing percentage method. It was found that overall approach of government under SSA for providing education to rural & urban children suits the need of these children.','','-','Anil Kumar Nautiyal,Himani Dangwal','21-26','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(702,'Effect of Weibull Distributed Deterioration on an Inventory Model with Exponential Demand and Inflation','This paper investigates an inventory situation where producing process would go out of control. This study also assumes Weibull rate of deterioration for the manufacturers raw material, finished goods inventory and retailers inventory. Shortages are allowed at the retailers part only and the unfulfilled demand is partial backlogged. Whole study has been studied in an inflationary environment.','','-','Meghna Tyagi and S. R. Singh','853-867','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','17','28','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(703,'OPINION OF TEACHERS TOWARDS USING MULTIMEDIA LEARNING PACKAGE','The present study aims to investigate the perception of teachers towards multimedia learning package. Sample included 10 educational technology teachers from different colleges of Education. For obtaining the opinion of teachers, self constructed opinionnaire was developed The opinion of the teachers suggest that MML Package has a vital role in the teaching in the present scenario. It is highly accepted and recommended by the teachers for making teaching-learning process successful. Teachers also have the opinion that it is very useful for distant learners as well as for the self- study of the students.','','-','Hemant Lata Sharma, Nidhi Kakkar','27-36','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(704,'A HISTORICAL STUDY OF EDUCATIONAL STATUS AND REHABILITATION FACILITIES OF CHILDREN UNDER CARE AND PROTECTION IN CORRECTIONAL INSTITUTIONS','Correctional Institutions are the institutions for correcting, reforming and rehabilitating the children under care and protection.  Institutions provides measures for bringing about a change in positive direction in thinking, perception, personality, traits, attitude and behaviour pattern of the children.  Correctional Institutions are established in all states according to provision under the Children Act 1960.  Such fourteen institutions are established in Karnataka state, In this research these institutions are taken for study.  This study is historical in nature, Tools used in this study for collecting data are questionnaire, interview, annexure,  and observations schedule.','','-','K.K.PRAKASHA, BASAPPA','37-42','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(705,'LACK OF PARENTAL involvement: STRESS PRONE CHILDREN','Parental involvement is necessary for childrens Cognitive, Behavioral and Emotional development in the early years of age. This involvement is must because at this age parents are closely connected to their children as far as emotional level is concerned. It is said that mother is the first teacher of a child. Those children who are closely attached with their parents they are good in studies, emotionally sound and have full faith on their caliber but if parents do not show their involvement with their children, there are chances of stress in those children. Several studies have been conducted by the Department for Education and Skills (U.S.A) and found that childrens progress in schools and their behavior can be hindered or affected by lack of parental involvement.\r\nThis paper is an attempt to know about parental involvement and also to know that due to lack of this involvement children become victim of stress. The story does not stop here only, this goes to their adulthood also so it is important to know the types, causes, symptoms of stress and also to suggest some coping strategies for such type of adults.','','-','Ismat Jahan Siddiqui','43-48','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(706,'ICT AND PROFESSIONAL DEVELOPMENT OF TEACHERS','The pace of technological revolution and emergence of a knowledge society can change the traditional role of the teacher and the students. Traditionally, the teacher used to be the source of knowledge for the students. There is some cooperation among students to explore new knowledge. In many cases, the teachers do not posses adequate knowledge to supplement the view of the student. And the main source of knowledge remains limited to text book. The development of ICT changes the epic centre of knowledge. Technological development always warrants transition to newer technologies by jeopardizing the cost effectiveness of the education programme. The increase in expenditure on elementary education alone over the last four Five Year Plan periods has been more than the increase in expenditure on education as a whole. development goes beyond the term training with its implications of learning skills, and encompasses a definition that includes formal and informal means of helping teachers not only learn new skills but also develop new insights into pedagogy and their own practice, and explore new or advanced understandings of content and resources. This paper presents the role of ICT in the professional development of teachers. ICT can contribute to teacher and student learning; and good models of effective computer integration as a learning tool; and high quality professional development that transforms this vision into classroom reality, policymakers can turn schools into partners in the creation of the knowledge society envisioned in national policy plans.','','-','Garima Choudhary, Shikha Bhardwaj','49-52','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(707,'EVALUATION OF GENDER INFLUENCES ON THE EFFECTIVENESS OF SECONDARY SCHOOL TEACHERS','There have been a fairly large number of researches in the recent past that have dealt with the status of women in academic settings. Studies have raised the issue whether female teachers acquire qualitatively and quantitatively different levels of effectiveness than males in view of the concerns regarding greater share of the females in the family responsibilities. Stereotypic representations of females and macho culture of society makes the gender gap in effectiveness all the more vital correlate to be examined. Following a brief introduction on the subject, the paper discusses demographic factors like marital status, training, location and medium of instruction of male and female teachers in relation to their teaching effectiveness. Overall, male and female teachers exhibited insignificantly different teaching effectiveness however variations were noticed with respect to different demographic factors. The paper concludes by arguing that since the quality of education being delivered, generally, has been considered as a function of teachers degree of effectiveness, there is need for both a substantive and methodological focus on gender specific responsibilities and requirements, in order to take out maximum from male and female teachers to produce high degree of effectiveness in their teaching.','','-','Fatima Islahi, Nasreen','53-60','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(708,'Consumer Protection Education- Its Awareness and utilization among the Senior Secondary School Students of Jagadhri','Everybody infant to an oldest one is a consumer in one form or another. Consumer is the beginning and end of marketing process. Even then the consumer in India have manifold problems such as ignorance about goods, absence of an association, trading malpractices and poor implementation of the provision of the various acts like Prevention of Food Adulteration and Prevention Act, Indian Standard Institution Act etc. Among them the problems of ignorance is universal in character. Professor Galbraith puts it, The notion that the consumer is the sovereign influence in the market economy will serve only those who wish to believe in fairy tales. In reality he is important but powerless; he is made to buy whatever is thrown before him, at whatever prices at whatever places and whatsoever manner. So, he is neither a king nor a powerful consumer but only a powerless consumer. Consumers even in the developed countries are not able to purchases intelligently because of ignorance. It is a pitiable affair that all of them are not conscious about their rights and privileges.','','-','Raghuvir Tageja, Ramana Sood','61-66','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(709,'attitude of Pupil  teachers towards grading system IN RELATION TO THEIR GENDER AND LOCALITY IN HIMACHAL PRADESH','his study intended to explore the attitudes of Pupil  teachers towards  grading system The sample of the study, which was selected through purposive sampling. The sample comprised of 100 Pupil  teachers of VSLM College of education Chandi. The independent variable for this study were gender, locality. The dependent variables constructed for this study were Grading system.  As no standardized instruments suitable for this study could be found, one attitude scale developed by the investigator. The results of the study revealed that Urban area  Pupil  teachers attitude have positive attitude  towards Grading System in comparison to rural area Pupil  teachers attitude towards Grading System,  And female Pupil  teachers have also found more positive in their attitude towards grading system as  compared with male Pupil  teachers.','','-','Kusum','67-72','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(710,'Effect of Parental Encouragement on achievement motivation of adolescents.','Achievement motivation is defined as a disposition to strive for success and/or the capacity to experience pleasure contingent upon success. It involves a concern for competition with some standard of excellence (Atkinson, 1957). There has been extensive research on the influences on students achievement motivation. Educational and psychological research has identified multiple factors that play a role in predicting adolescent achievement motivation. A review of the literature indicated that, examined individually, family background, individual, and school experience factors are related to adolescents achievement motivation (Eccles & Wigfield, 1985; Eccles & Harold, 1993; Hanson, 1994; Hossler & Stage, 1992). Among these are parental level of education, parental educational expectations and encouragement, school climate, and teachers educational expectations and support. Tpurpose of the present investigation was to study the influence of parental encouragement on achievement motivation of adolescents. A total of 80 students of class XI were administered Parental Encouragement Scale (PES) of R.R. Sharma and Achievement Motivation Test (AcMT) by Dr. V.P. Bhargava. results indicated that parental encouragement level influences the achievement motivation in academic area. Higher the level of parental encouragement, better the achievement motivation.','','-','Sonal Chabra, Lalita Kumari','73-78','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(711,'A Study of Relationship between Emotional Intelligence and Adjustment Among College Going Students','In the present investigation data were collected from a stratified random sample of 200 college students by using Emotional Intelligence test and Self-Esteem Inventory. The two-tailed test of significance for difference between means and Pearsons product moment correlations were the statistical techniques used in addition to computation of vital statistical indices. The result showed that no differential effect of gender on the basis of emotional intelligence and self-esteem. Whereas highly and significant correlation was found to between emotional intelligence and self-esteem.','','-','Sangeeta Chauhan','79-82','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(712,'Research in the Language Laboratory: Efficacy of Language Laboratory on Teaching Vocabulary Building in English','This paper attempts to highlight the efficacy of teaching of Vocabulary Building in the Language Laboratory to Secondary School students. New trends in language teaching must result in research in the language laboratory too, it being one of the latest innovations signifying the astonishing potential afforded by information technology.\r\n	Main objectives were to develop an understanding about language laboratory, to ascertain the difference between language laboratory method and the traditional method used in teaching of vocabulary building English and to compare the vocabulary of the students taught through language laboratory and the students who received traditional instructions.\r\n	To achieve these objectives, two leading research questions were formulated. First, what are the similarities and differences of language teaching and learning between a traditional classroom and a language laboratory under the communicative interaction framework? Second, are there any changes in the roles of teachers and students when they are in a different teaching environment from traditional classroom? Students studying in class VII constituted the population of the study. The sample was divided into two groups after equating them on the basis of scores on pre-test. Each group comprised of 30 students. One group was randomly taken as experimental group and the other one as control group. The treatment was given to the experimental group whereas the control group received traditional instruction. The experiment continued for two weeks. Post test was administered immediately after the treatment was over to the whole sample to obtain final data.','','-','Talwar Mini Satish','83-90','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(713,'Teacher as a Leader and an Agent of Change in a Community','The scope and quality of the educational system and teachers are certainly determining factors in a countrys level of empowerment and development.\r\nThe success of any educational system depends on the quality and capability of the teacher who is indispensable to the system and thus the teacher forms an important force in the development of a society.\r\n	The quality of the educational institutions and their organizational climate shape the destiny of our class rooms. Therefore to produce the desired outcome, importance is to be given to the quality management of educational institutions. No scheme of educational reconstruction will produce the desired result unless it is administered with vision and efficiency.\r\n	The Education Commission (1964-66) began its report with these words- The destiny of India is now being shaped in her classroomsTherefore there is a need to develop leadership strategies that will raise quality of education and quality of life so that educational leaders and Teachers are trained as per the demand to become visionaries and provide a new perspective to the educational system of our Country.','','-','Azkiya Waris','91-94','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(714,'HIV/AIDS AWARENESS AMONG TRIBAL SCHOOL GOING ADOLESCENTS IN HIMACHAL PRADESH','AIDS has become an epidemic around the globe. AIDS is the final stage of HIV infection. In India, 15% HIV/AIDS patients are children under 15 years of age. The adolescent age with its specific psychological and social attributes is more susceptible to sexual curiosity and behavior that make them particularly vulnerable to HIV infection. A number of knowledge, belief and attitude studies conducted in different parts if India reveals widespread ignorance and misconceptions among this vulnerable age group. No such assessment has ever been attempted in tribal regions of Himachal Pradesh and that is why the researcher undertook this study. In the present study the research tool developed and standardized by Dr. Anup Kumar (HIV/AIDS Knowledge and Awareness Test) has been used to collect the data. In this survey type of research 200 school going adolescents (100 Male and 100 Female) has been taken as sample by using Multistage Random Sampling Technique. Statistics like Mean, Standard deviation and t-value have been calculated to test the hypotheses. The study reveals that female tribal school going adolescents are more aware than male adolescents with respect to government provisions/facilities for bringing HIV/AIDS awareness. But there is no significant gender-wise difference in overall HIV/AIDS awareness among tribal school going adolescents. Both male and female adolescents have moderate HIV/AIDS awareness level and possess more or less the same knowledge and information regarding HIV and AIDS.','','-','Anup Kumar,Rajesh Kumar','95-100','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(715,'A STUDY OF SPORTS FACILITIES IN GOVERNMENT   SCHOOLS OF HIMACHAL PRADESH: AN EVLUATIVE STUDY','Sports is directly related to physical education because contribute to knowledge of exercise, health and disease. Physical education can contribute to this knowledge by instructing individuals about their bodies, movements, the importance of nutrition, physical activities, rest and sleep by informing them the danger that exist to guard against disease. In this way physical education helps to improve the health of a person through knowledge and participating in sports and physical activities. The present study intended to evaluate the sports facilities in Government schools of Himachal Pradesh. The results of the present study indicate that many schools do not have playing fields for those games, which require flat and large area.The environment of sports in most of the schools was good. The students were satisfied with it and indoor facility was not available in even a single school.','','-','VED PARKASH','101-104','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(716,'A Study on the Environmental Education Curriculum of  Punjab University','The goal of environmental education is to improve all ecological relationships including the relationship of mankind with nature and people with their surroundings. The objectives of environmental education are that individual and social groups should acquire awareness and knowledge, develop positive attitudes, skills and abilities and participate in solving real life environmental problems. Environmental education envisages the environmental approach to education and more so a way of learning rather than a subject. To make the students environmental oriented, their teachers themselves should be environmental facilitators. An effective curriculum at training stage and positive attitude play significant role in acquiring the related skills. The paper presents the study of environmental education curriculum of B. Ed. course of Punjab University. It highlights the need of an effective environmental education curriculum at teachers training and emphasizes to make it compulsory at this stage.','','-','Seema Dhawan, Rina Joshi','105-110','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(717,'Attitude towards information and communication technology of secondary school students in relation to their fathers occupational status.','Information technology has recently provided a number of new tools, such as multimedia and simulated software. These tools help the Teacher in recreating real life experiences in the class room which can only be described in words so far. This, in turn, can increase the quality and effectiveness of learning but the effective learning, resulting from the use of information technology in education, depends upon a number of social and personal factors like the attitude towards information technology. The development of favorable attitude towards information technology is considered for two main reasons. Firstly, the attitude which an individual has influences his learning to a considerable extent .secondly. The possession of favorable attitude   towards information technology is an important characteristic of a scientifically literate person.  In this particular study the investigator has tried to study the attitude towards information technology of secondary school students in relation to their fathers occupational status The sample of the study comprises of 250 secondary school students. Information Technology Attitude  scale developed by Dr. Tahira Khatoon (2001) Department Of Education A.M.U,  was used for data collection, t-test when applied on data revealed that the result is   .05 level of confidence.','','-','Shafeeqa Bano, Tabinda Iqbal','111-114','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(718,'CHALLENGES BEFORE TEACHER EDUCATION','No Doubt that the education plays a significant role in the development of nation, but the quality of education is greatly determinate by the quality of teachers. Therefore, great efforts were made and still are being made to improve the quality of teacher education. Restructuring of teacher preparation process is highly essential for professional development and empowerment of the teachers. Hence, there is a need to solve the problems of present teacher education system. \r\nTeachers are the national builder and educational institutions are the functional heads of all that goes to make the foundations of a nation strong. Teachers form an essential aspects of the India system of education. Teacher is accepted as a guide and philosopher the man of higher ideals in molding the society. He is the builder of students character, behavior and the whole personality. The teacher is now expected not only to inculcate knowledge but also to encourage thinking. As a guide he has to teach the students how to learn rather than stuff his mind with factual information.','','-','Pramod Kumar Singh','115-118','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(719,'Creativity and Level of Aspiration of Learning-Disabled and Non- Disabled Children','Learning disabled is a term used to describe children who show the symptoms of considerable difficulty in understanding or using spoken language, reading, writing, spelling and /or arithmetic during the developmental period (before16 years of age).\r\n	This paper discusses the specific characteristics of learning disabled children, and compares the learning-disabled and non- disabled children on the basis of creativity and level of aspiration as there is a close relation between learning disability and creativity\r\n	Knowledge of the Creativity and Level of Aspiration of Learning-Disabled and Non- Disabled Children can be used to take advantage in the design of appropriate and effective educational Programmes for Learning Disabled. The joint efforts of the teacher, parents, curriculum planner and teacher training institutions could emerge as most successful tool in managing this disorder.','','-','AMRITA MAHESHWARI,  SANGEETA','119-126','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(720,'A Study of Job Involvement of BTC and Special BTC Teachers','An attempt has been made to investigate the difference between job involvement of BTC and special BTC teachers. 250 BTC and 250 special BTC teachers were selected randomly from various primary schools of Bareilly, Pilibhit and Badaun districts, affiliated to Basic Shiksha Parishad, Uttar Pradesh. Job involvement scale developed by Kapoor & Singh (1978) was employed to collect the data. The data were analysed by employing percentage analysis, mean, standard deviation andt test. BTC teachers are more involved in their job in comparison to special BTC teachers. Male BTC teachers have higher job involvement than female BTC teachers and sex does not make any effect on job involvement of special BTC teachers. Further, differences do not exist between rural and urban teachers of BTC and special BTC in relation to job involvement.','','-','Santosh Arora , Mohd. Irshad Hussain','127-132','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','27','42','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(721,'izkFkfed fo|ky;ksa ds f\'k{kd vkSj f\'kf