(2008)  . This is reliable and valid measure of deprivational experiences showing the strength of poverty. The obtained results clearly display the differential influence of youth vs adult and urban vs rural Ss on poverty.','','-','Krishna Sharma, P.S.N. Tiwari','209-214','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(726,'Thermal Convection in a Viscoelastic Fluid with Hall Currents in Porous Medium','An incompressible Oldroydian viscoelastic fluid layer heated from below in the presence of a constant horizontal magnetic field to include the effect of Hall currents is considered. For the case of stationary convection, Oldroydian viscoelastic fluid behaves like an ordinary Newtonian fluid. The Hall currents are found to have a destabilizing effect on the thermal convection, whereas magnetic field is found to have a stabilizing effect on the thermal convection. Medium permeability has both stabilizing and destabilizing effect on the thermal convection under certain conditions. The results are presented through graphs in each case.','','-','Himanshu Malik, Vivek Kumar, Pawan Kumar Sharma','215-223','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(727,'A Production Inventory Model for Decaying Items With Time Dependent Demand in Inflationary Environment','In this paper we developed an inventory model with the effect of inflation, partial backlogging. We considered a linear demand and demand dependent production. Shortages are also taken in an account with partial backlogging. The inflationary implications have been considered in this chapter. The optimal number of cycles that minimizes the average system cost over a finite time horizon is determined. The results are illustrated with numerical examples.','','-','S K Shon, Megha','79-90','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(728,'Simple Technique For Computing The Radiation Pattern Of Reflector Antennas','Simple Technique For Computing The Radiation Pattern Of Reflector Antennas','','-','Surendra Kumar Roy , Prateek Raj','91-96','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(729,'A Note On Two Variables Z-Transform','The present paper introduced a two variables Z-transform and their properties. Also convolution, shifting, initial value and final value theorems for this transform has been investigated','','-','Mumtaz Ahmad Khan, Mohd. Khalid Rafat Khan','97-108','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(730,'Acoustoelectric Attenuation and Phase Transition Due to Carriers In Semiconductor','The response of the charge carriers of a semiconductor to a traveling acoustic wave leads to transfer of energy between the wave and the electrons, such a wave drags free carriers and as a result attenuation and phase transition appears across the sample, near a phase transition there are large fluctuation, in the case of a softening phonon mode, the fluctuations correspond simply to vibrational modes that are excited thermally when the energy of the phonons has been shifted down near to zero. The effects of interaction with thermal phonons, which produce temperature dependent attenuation and free carriers which may give attenuation or amplification, and electrons bound to shallow donors, giving rise to attenuation at low temperatures. There are obtained a complex form for the change in distribution function arising due to the passage of acoustic wave through a semiconductor. The imaginary part of this function has been used for ascertaining the phase transition between the self-consistent field and the acoustoelectric current and the real part has been utilized for computing the attenuation constant for n  Indium antimonide.\r\nKeywords : Attenuation constant, Indium antimonide, Free carriers, Phase transition, Self-consistent field.','','-','Praveen Kumar, Amita Kri , Ujjwal Alok','109-114','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(731,'Dielectric Properties of Ferroelectric Crystal PbHPO4  With External Biasing','By using double-time temperature dependent Green\'s function method, expressions for dielectric constant are derived. Model Hamiltonian used by earlier workers is modified and used in the derivation. Model values are fitted and compared with experimental data of others.','','-','Trilok Chandra Upadhyay And Mayank Joshi','115-120','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(732,'Review of N-Policy Queueing Systems','Here in this paper, we have reviewed the N-policy queueing models, since its inception to till now. In N-Policy queueing models, a server does not start service until there are N-Customers accumulated in the queue. This policy is very useful to control the expected total cost of a system, when the setup cost of server is very large. Various authors worked on N-policy queueing models, which are reviewed in this paper.','','-','Rekha Rani','121-124','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(733,'Availability Analysis of Sheet Formation System of the Utensils Industry Mathematical View','Availability Analysis of Sheet Formation System of the Utensils Industry Mathematical View','','-','Zeenat Zaidi, Yogesh Kumar Goya','125-140','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(734,'Potential of Sacred Groves in Promoting Ecotourism in Uttarakhand Himalayas','A computer programme to calculate availability of a sheet formation system of Utensils industry for constant failure and repair rates is developed which makes possible the implementation of the matrix method [9]. The reliability equation enables to calculate MTBF. Effect of failure and repair rates of different sub systems on long run availability is studied with the help of tables and graphs.','','-','Deepak Kholiya, Laxmi Rawat , Preeti Joshi','141-164','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(735,'Half-wave Dielectric Rod Resonator Filter','In Uttarakhand state lots of villages have temple forests both in Garhwal and Kumaon regions, where deities or spirits are worshipped by local communities. These are patches of forests containing different indigenous wild life species and natural water springs (aquifers) present in these patches of forests are the main sources of water for the local people in many cases. e.g. Badrivan, ancient sacred forest of Badrinath, where two important trees Bhojpatra (Betula utilis) and Badri (Juniperus macropoda) and shrubs of Badriphal (Hippophae salicifolia) were the predominant vegetation. These sacred forests are at the verge of disappearance due to a variety of reasons, particularly anthropogenic. A restoration programme should be undertaken for environmental conservation / biodiversity conservation and preservation of the spiritual and cultural values of these important sacred places of Hindus. Hariyali, as a sacred forest of Garhwal Himalaya is yet another example where people have conserved the forest through socio-cultural and religious practices. There are so many more, which need to the enlisted and documented for conservation and other purposes, that becomes one of the main long term objective as a tourist product for promoting sustainable eco-tourism.','','-','Rajiv Sinha','165-170','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(736,'Co-composting of pressmud and flyash with distillery effluent','India is producing 20 million tones of sugar annually. Most of the sugar industries are incorporated with the cane molasses-based distillery units. The distillery effluent from these industries is discharged directly into river or on land without treatment. An attempt has been made to compost the effluent with pressmud (by product of sugar industry) and flyash (waste from boilers) for the production of biomanure, so that discharging of effluent into open waterbodies can be reduced, and the byproducts can be used to improve the soil fertility. The concentrated effluent was sprayed to maintain moisture content (approximately 50-60%). The chemical and physicochemical parameters as well as biological tests to determine the quality of compost have been performed. The mixture of pressmud and flyash (3:1 weight basis) was assessed suitable filler material for utilization of distillery effluent. The C:N ratio of this compost  was also higher than other mixtures.','','-','Nishtha Yadav, Vikash Talyan , C.P.Kaushik','171-178','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(737,'High Availability Using Virtualization','I have described and proposed a new solution to achieve the failover capabilities in the field of virtualization where more than one virtual machines runs on a single physical host or server, as well as designed and tested cases to achieve the proper load balancing and failover in terms of applications as well as covered the alternate solution for the session replication on http web based applications.','','-','Mukesh Negi, D.K. Pandey Director','195-200','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(738,'A Survey Study of Participation of Scheduled Caste in Business Activities','The author of present research paper is a research scholar of C C S University, Meerut and who has submitted his research study in the university which belongs to the study of economic status of scheduled caste in district Meerut and district Saharanpur. In his research work he examined the economic progress made by the people of scheduled caste community with regard to their education, employment, opportunities in business sector etc.\r\nThe author of the present paper, who belongs to a scheduled caste family, made an effort to analyse the reasons of non-acceptance of scheduled caste people by the business community of India. For the purpose he interviewed the 1000 families of scheduled castes of district Meerut and district Saharanpur and found that 2369 people of these families were engaged in different economic activities. The results of the results study are presented in the present research paper','','-','Axey Kumar, Shwetabh Mittal','201-208','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(739,'An Almost Product and Almost Decomposable Bi-Recurrent and Bi-Symmetric Manifold','Tachibana (1959) studied on almost analytic vectors in almost-Kaehlerian manifolds. Sato (1966) studied and defined almost analytic tensor fields in almost Complex manifolds. Shirokov (1967) studied and defined structures on differentiable manifolds. Further, Hasegura structures on differentiable manifolds. Further, Hasegawa (1974) studied H-Projective recurrent Kaehlerian manifolds and Bochner recurrent Kahlerian manifold. Rawat(2003) studied and defined Kaehlerian bi-recurrent and bi-symmetric manifold. Rawat and Silswal(2008) studied and defined totally real submanifolds of a Kaehlerian manifold.\r\nIn the present paper, we have studied an almost product and almost decomposable bi-recurrent and bi-symmetric manifold and several theorems have been established and proved therein','','-','K.S.Rawat, Mukesh Kumar','209-218','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(740,'ERP Involves the Seamless Integration in Educational Sector','ERP systems include several configurable modules that integrate core business activities into a single environment based on an integrated, shared database.  Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) systems have been recognized as the most important development in the corporate use of information technology in the 1990s (Davenport, 1998), promising seamless integration of all the information flows throughout a firm. This applies to ERP system applications, which are seen as key in supporting business processes in many organizations.  ERP involves the seamless integration of processes across functional areas such as finance, human resources, manufacturing and logistics.  They support improved workflow, standardization of business practices, and improved capabilities.     Implementation of enterprise resource planning (ERP) systems improves corporate performance.  But implementing an ERP system is a costly and time-consuming task and these costs are due mainly to the short supply of professionals with ERP skills. This paper discusses about the demand of ERP professionals in the industry, ERP education Scenario in Indian context requiring integration of Business Schools with industries. \r\nThis paper reveals a clear view of education ERP, as education industry is one of the prime industries in India. Its importance in commercial value is less appreciated but its contribution to nation building is well known. With the surprising growth of the education sector, education institutes are becoming complex organizations. This paper discloses the impact of Education ERP over education participants, i.e. how; they will be beneficial after having this solution in their Colleges/Universities.','','-','Ashok Kumar, Vinit Kumar Sharma, Padmveer Malik','219-230','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(741,'Determinents of Income and Employment of Women in Urban Informal Sector  A Study in Visakhapatnam City','In recent years the informal sector has acquired great significance over the years as a source of employment and livelihood for an increasing number of people, especially women, in both urban and rural areas of the developing world. The reason for this may be that the informal sector activities are characterised by easy entry, reliance on indigenous resources, negligible capital investment, labour intensiveness and highly competitive unregulated markets. So far, considerable numbers of studies have been undertaken for analyzing the socio-economic characteristics, income and employment in the informal sector of rural areas but not much light thrown on the urban informal sector. This study made an attempt to fill this gap and concluded that the poverty levels and the employment levels are low among petty trading households. Since the migration is the main cause for the overcrowding of urban labour market, the government has to formulate and adopt the policies which are useful to reduce the migration from rural areas to urban areas and implement the Programmes to improve the technical skills among women who have already settled in the urban informal sector, because the lack of skill is the main cause for low levels of income and employment in urban informal sector.','','-','D. Narayana Rao','231-238','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(742,'Generalization of Common Fixed Point Theorems of H.L.Guang and Z.Xian in Complete Cone Metric Spaces','Some common fixed point theorems are proved in this research paper satisfying Banach fixed point condition.','','-','S. C. Ghosh','239-244','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(743,'Structural characterization of zinc substituted lithium ferrites','Zn substituted lithium ferrite with compositional formula Li 0.5-0.5x ZnxFe2.5-0.5xO4 where 0.2 ? x ? 0.8 in steps of 0.2 were synthesized by the citrate precursor method. The sample was given sintering at 1100oC. Structural investigation was carried out using the X-ray diffraction (XRD) and the scanning electron microscopy (SEM) measurements. From the analysis of the XRD data, the average lattice constant and crystallite, size was calculated. Study of grain size was carried out using the SEM measurement. It is observe that the crystallite size increases with the increase in Zn concentration. The mechanism involved in the above observation is being discussed.','','-','Ibetombi Soibama, Sumitra Phanjoubamb','245-250','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(744,'A Critical Analysis on Employees Satisfaction on Grievance Handling Mechanism, (AT APOLLO TYRES LIMITED, PERAMBRA, KERALA)','Grievance is nothing but discontent or dissatisfaction arising out of anything connected with any aspect of the organization. In every company there is a grievance handling mechanism by which all the issues are solved effectively. This grievance handling system helps the employees to ventilate their dissatisfaction and get their concerns solved immediately. A grievance is a sign of employees discontent or dissatisfaction with his job or his relationship with his colleagues. Grievances generally arise out of the day to day working relations in an organization. The employee has got certain aspirations and expectations which he thinks must be fulfilled by the organization where he is working. When the organization fails to satisfy the employee needs, he develops a feeling of discontent of dissatisfaction. So this discontent or dissatisfaction whether expressed or not, valid or not, arising out of anything connected with the company which an employee thinks, believes or even feels to be unfair, unjust or inequitable. Since there are such situations in every organization they must follow a proper grievance handling system by which the company can effectively minimize and eliminate the source of an employees grievance at the earliest. The researcher selected Apollo Tyres Limited for the research work and have chosen the topic Employee Satisfaction on Grievance handling Mechanism, at Apollo Tyres, because of its reputation and good working environment. In the context of the political background of Kerala, the survival of such a reputed company is something miraculous and I was curious to know that what makes the employees happy and content at Apollo. Whichever industries or companies we take, there are issues and problems and many times that are not handled properly which leads to the shutdown of them permanently. So the researcher believe that there must be a proper grievance handling system of which the employees are happy and content to a certain extent. \r\nA= agree,','','-','Shri Nath Gupta, Kamal Kishor Shukla','251-266','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(745,'Teach Biology Science Using a Computer Simulation Process','The computer simulation (Arneson and Ticknor, 1990) has been implemented in the general biology laboratory and the science methods course for elementary teachers to reinforce the processes of science and to allow the students to engage, explore, explain, elaborate and evaluate the methods of building concepts in science. The students develop testable hypotheses and then use the program to run experiments and collect data. In addition, they research relevant background information and subsequently present their results in a poster during class.','','-','Milan Kr. Singh, Soni Singh,Amita Kumari3& Praveen Kumar','267-270','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(746,'Critical Success Factors in ERP Implementation in India','ERP is one the latest technologies that many organizations have undertaken. Enterprise Resource Planning (ERP) systems are software packages composed of several modules, such as human resources, sales, finance and production, providing cross-organizational integration of transaction-based data management throughout imbedded business processes support. These software packages can be customized up to a certain limit to the specific needs of each organization. ERP was characterized as the most important development in the corporate use of technology in the 1990s. Unfortunately, many ERP projects have not been effective enough and hence have been unable to achieve all the results envisaged. As the cost of an ERP implementation project is very high, it is critical for an organization to make the project a success and start obtaining benefits out of it as fast as possible. Enterprise resource planning (ERP) systems are highly complex information systems. The implementation of these systems is a difficult and high cost proposition that places tremendous demands on corporate time and resources. Many ERP implementations have been classified as failures because they did not achieve predetermined corporate goals.','','-','Ashok Kumar, Padmveer Malik','271-280','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(747,'A Parallel Shared Memory Computation Model','This paper present  a new model of parallel computing, an experimental test bed of the model, and a set of experimental data on the use of the model. Specifically, we model memory computation in computers with technology similar to current parallel computers. The processors compute independently using their local memories. The   processors communicate via a limited asynchronous access to an amount of shared memory. The modeling concentrates on a set of parameters that describe the shared memory access limitations of the processors. The experimental part of the work was done using a configurable emulator to study various combinations of the different parameters.','','-','Pawan Singh, Azeem Aftab, Ankur Rastogi','281-294','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(748,'Effect of inflation on a multi echelon inventory system with ramp type demand and partial backlogging','In this chapter we proposed a collaborative system with ramp type demand rate and shortages that are partially backlogged. Demand rate is the combination of increasing-steady-decreasing demand patters. Every change in demand is directly correlated to the production rate of that particular commodity. The production planning and control system should be designed to complement the corporate strategy and to provide additional competitive advantage. Therefore, we have taken production rate proportional to the demand rate. Demand rate under two specific assumptions are discussed in two sections. In the first one, six possible cases related to the demand transfer points and cycle times are discussed. In second section, the model considered is both amelioration and deterioration under inflationary environment. Results are illustrated with numerical examples for both sections','','-','Sarvpreet Kaur, D. Singh, A. P. Singh','295-314','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(749,'Two Warehouse Model with Ramp Type Demand and Ameliorating Items','-','','-','Pratap Singh, D. Singh, A. P. Singh','315-328','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(750,'Some New Results on Laguerre Polynomials of Three Variables','New generating functions of Laguerre polynomials of three variables have been obtained. Series expansion formulae, summation formulae and recurrence relations for this polynomial in terms partial derivative are defined. Relationship with two variable Laguerre polynomials and four variables Laguerre Polynomials of this polynomial is also given.','','-','Mumtaz Ahmad Khan, Mohd. Khalid Rafat Khan','353-366','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(751,'A Two Unit Warm Standby System with Main Operating System','This paper presents the analysis a two unit repairable redundant system with main operating system and converter. Converter is used to switch the standby unit into operation at the time of failure of an operative unit. Failure time distributions of the both operative and standby units are negative exponential, while repair time distribution of failed unit, converter and MOS (Main Operating System) are arbitrary. The various reliability characteristics useful to system designers are obtained.','','-','Vinay K. Tyagi, Shiv Kumar, Anil Kumar','367-374','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(752,'Availability Analysis of Utensils Formation System of Utensil Industry, Thematical View','A Utensils formation system of utensils industry is analyzed for its availability. Birth and death equations governing the system are formed, taking constant failure and repair rates, using Markov method. These equations are solved using Matrix method. These equations are solved using Matrix method with the help of computer programme. The approaches are identified through availability analysis of utensils formation system of utensils industry which could help in improving its availability. Long run availability is studied with the help of tables and graphs. The results so obtained are useful for reliability engineers and the managers.','','-','Zeenat Zaidi, Yogesh Kumar Goyal','375-386','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(753,'Integral Representation of K series','In this research paper we define a new Special Function, known as K-Series. The M- series [7], ?(_p^)F?_q^  - Generalized Hypergeometric Function[6] and the Generalized Mittag-Leffler function [1], [2], [3], [4], [5], [8] and [9] are particular cases of K-Series. \r\nAlso we calculate four different Integral Representation of K  Series given by equations (11), (16), (18), (22) and (23).\r\nFor particular values of parameters, we can evaluate Integral Representation of ?(_p^)F?_q^  - Generalized Hypergeometric Function, given by equations (13),(19) and (24) and  the Integral Representation of Generalized Mittag- Leffler function given by equations (14), (15), (20), (21), (25) and (26).','','-','Kuldeep Singh Gehlot, Chena Ram','387-396','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(754,'An Almost Product and Almost Decomposable Bi-Recurrent and Bi-Symmetric Manifold','Tachibana (1959) studied on almost analytic vectors in almost-Kaehlerian manifolds. Sato (1966) studied and defined almost analytic tensor fields in almost Complex manifolds. Shirokov (1967) studied and defined structures on differentiable manifolds. Further, Hasegura structures on differentiable manifolds. Further, Hasegawa (1974) studied H-Projective recurrent Kaehlerian manifolds and Bochner recurrent Kahlerian manifold. Rawat(2003) studied and defined Kaehlerian bi-recurrent and bi-symmetric manifold. Rawat and Silswal(2008) studied and defined totally real submanifolds of a Kaehlerian manifold. In the present paper, we have studied an almost product and almost decomposable bi-recurrent and bi-symmetric manifold and several theorems have been established and proved therein.','','-','K.S.Rawat, Mukesh Kumar','397-404','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(755,'Common fixed Point Theorem in Complete Cone Metric Spaces','Our object in this present paper is to develop fixed-point theorem in complete cone metric space. In this paper we have established fixed-point theorems on comparison function and self-mapping in complete cone metric spaces.','','-','S.C. Gosh','405-409','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(756,'A Survey of Security Issues in Cloud Computing','cloud computing is emerging as one of the most significant shifts in information technology where on demand services are required. Cloud computing use are reaching the point where computing functions as a utility has great potential and flexibility which we cant imagine right now. However with these advantages in future we are facing some serious threats to data and code residing on the service provider premises. In this paper we are going to analysis the security issues so far occurred and at last we add some conclusion and purpose some new threats to the cloud computing. General Terms: security, risk, vulnerability.','','-','Tejbir Singh, Kapil Sharma','411-424','NO','-','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','24','38','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(757,'MHD Free Convection Laminar Flow of an Incompressible Visco-Elastic Fluid Past a Porous Vertical Wall with Constant Suction and Heat Source','Aim of this paper to illustrates the flow of visco-elastic (Rivlin-Ericksen) fluid past a porous vertical wall with the constant suction and heat source under the influence of uniform transverse magnetic field. The velocity distribution, temperature distribution, rate of heat transfer, and the coefficient of skin friction are analyzed under the given initial and boundary conditions. The effects of Porosity of porous medium, magnetic field, visco-elastic parameter, Prandtl number, heat souurce and suction parameter have been investigated on the flow of Rivlin-Ericksen (Second order) Fluid and the results are presented graphically for different values of the parameters entering the problem.','','-','Rakesh Kumar Shakya ,B.B.Singh','101-114','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','39','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(758,'Mathematical Model of Blood Flow Through Porous Artery in Presence of Magnetic Field','A mathematical model for blood flow in the small porous artery in the presence of magnetic field is presented in this paper. The reliability of influence of magnetic and porosity effect has been tested by t- test and we found the influence of magnetic and porosity parameters on blood flow. Further, we carried forward the work to obtain velocity field, volume flow rate and the HDRF. On the basis of computation and graphs, we have shown the dependence of HDRF on magnetic parameter (M) and porosity (K) and we observed its influence for the shear rate. All the result has been obtained and discussed through graphs.','','-','Gaurav Gupta, J. S. Chaudhary , Rajeev Jha','115-120','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','39','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(759,'Hydromagnetic Thermal Instability of Suspended Particles in a Stratified Fluid Layer','In this paper, we discuss the hydromagnetic instability of suspended particles in a stratified fluid layer which is heated from below and we observed that the Principle of the exchange of the stability (PES) is not valid for this configuration and we shall establish a variational principle in terms of Rayleigh number and further, we also drive some analytical results.','','-','Shivdeep Singh Patial, Gurpreet Kaur ,A.K.Tomer','121-134','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','39','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(760,'A Mathematical Model To Study The Effect Of Magnetic Field On Blood Flow ','In this paper our aim is to find the effect of magnetic field in stenotic artery. We have modeled the artery as a circular cylinder consisting of stenosis. We have considered the realistic model of the basic function unit taking the steady viscous flow in artery with the help of equation of motion and one-dimensional diffusion equation. We have investigated the resistance to flow in artery for different values of magnetic field ','','- ',' Sangeeta Gupta, P.K. Shukla ','167-172','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','40','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(761,'Effect of Chemical Reaction on Mhd Free Convective Flow of Heat And Mass Transfer Past a Vertical Porous Plate with Heat Source ','We have analysis the influence of a first-order homogeneous chemical reaction on MHD free convective flow of heat and mass transfer past a vertical porous plate with heat source taking viscous and Darcy resistance terms into account and the constant permeability of the medium. The velocity, temperature, concentration, the rate of heat transfer and rate of mass transfer are analyzed for the variations of different parameter. We know from the physical point of view that the Grashoff number Gr > 0 corresponding to cooling of the surface by free convection currents and Gr < 0 corresponding to heating of the surface by free convection which agrees our results ','','- ',' Anurag Dubey, U. R. Singh and Prof. Rajeev Jha ','173-185','NO','-','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','40','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(762,'Energy Efficient Approach in Wireless Sensor Networks','India is producing 20 million tones of sugar annually. Most of the sugar industries are incorporated with the cane molasses-based distillery units. The distillery effluent from these industries is discharged directly into river or on land without treatment. An attempt has been made to compost the effluent with pressmud (by product of sugar industry) and flyash (waste from boilers) for the production of biomanure, so that discharging of effluent into open waterbodies can be reduced, and the byproducts can be used to improve the soil fertility. The concentrated effluent was sprayed to maintain moisture content (approximately 50-60%). The chemical and physicochemical parameters as well as biological tests to determine the quality of compost have been performed. The mixture of pressmud and flyash (3:1 weight basis) was assessed suitable filler material for utilization of distillery effluent. The C:N ratio of this compost  was also higher than other mixtures.','','-','Anand Mishra ,Rakesh Kumar','179-188','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(763,'Performance Comparison Between AODV and Modified AODV Protocol in Ad-Hoc Network','Mobile ad-hoc network is the collection of node which dynamically forms a temporary network without the use of any existing network infrastructure or centralized administration. When the mobility in the network is high and the topology changes frequently the route maintenance overhead in AODV increases. Because nodes can move link breakages can occurs. Long path is more vulnerable to link breakages and requires high control overhead for its maintenance. In this paper we introduce a new modified AODV protocol. This new protocol uses HELLO packets of intermediate nodes to find the most sable neighbors and therefore most stable path. This new proposed protocol is SR-AODV (Stable Route-AODV) protocol. We simulate both AODV and SR-AODV with ns-2 in similar scenario. We find that SR-AODV will show better performance than AODV.','','-','Pratima Gupta, Rakesh Kumar','189-194','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','41','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(764,'An Approach to Resolve Father-Child Problem Under Artificial Life','Father-child problem is very critical problem in artificial life. The approach used is that Child produced by father is depend upon the consumption of food by father and whether father alive or not depends upon his age so in this paper we simulate father-child problem by comparing the age of father with his energy level and production of child depends upon consumption of food by father.','','-','Ashok Kumar Rai, Rakesh Kumar','977-983','NO','-','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','25','37','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(765,'A Study of the Problems of School Dropouts at Primary Level in Slum Areas of Delhi','Our constitution has guaranteed free and compulsory education to every child up to the age of fourteen & for that several educational programmes and committees were held for developing the primary education. During the past fifty years a lot of schools have increased and quality of education has improved but India could not achieve the objective of compulsory education.\r\nField visits and micro level studies indicate that most of the illiterate reside in the slum areas. Studies report that the dropout rates are higher among the slum children. The dropout problem has reached such magnitude that it has created an imbalance between the school and society.\r\nThe problem of school dropout in slum areas is now a days becoming more alarming keeping in view the rate of growth of slums.\r\nTo study the dropout problem interview schedule and information Performa for dropout were developed by investigator.  the main reason of  irregularity were ill health  and lack of  transport facilities, money, proper food ,dress, etc..,  To  overcome the problem of dropout  it is suggested that  there should be a strong relationship between educational  system and needs of community.','','-','Anuradha Agarwal','165-172','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(766,'W. H. Audens last Poetic Phase','The last phase of W. H. Audens poetry   encompasses the period from 1947 to 1973. In fact, for a poet of Audens sensibility the problems of man and his society become the problems of his own heart. Auden deals with the larger life outside the individual a life which is never without a close connection with as well as a direct and profound impact upon the individuals life. The poet and his personal feelings become inseparable parts of universal theme because he states from his heart and intellect as well. In Auden there is a direct relationship between the personal feelings and poetic expression. Learning from the past experiences, Auden now seems to celebrate the life even with stresses and strains without a sense of despair.','','-','S. K. Singh','173-176','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(767,'Marketing and Software Development Problems Faced by Software Companies','Information technology is one of the fastest spreading technologies in the world in terms of its usage and production. The Information technology is a very broad term, which is used for a host of technologies such as hardware and software technologies. The paper is based on study of problems faced by software companies in Northern region. It is worthwhile to examine the key issues for IT sector such as operational, software development and marketing so as to make comprehensive recommendations that can further accelerate the growth of this industry. The study also attempts to present a comprehensive view of the strategies being currently adopted by different application software companies. For the sake of present study, it has been assumed that the application software has not been developed and marketed in Northern India as it has been developed and marketed in other parts of India.','','-','Anil Kumar Mittra, Dharm Bir Singh','177-188','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(768,'Constructivist Class Room: Inquiry Based Instructional Model','When education is faced with new challenges emerging out of call for Education for All at one hand and Quality Education on the other, is there any scope for our teachers to adopt the constructivist approach? The present paper is a humble attempt to answer this question. The National Curriculum Framework, (2005) brought out by N.C.E.R.T. has highlighted this philosophy in India. It believes that learning is the process of construction of knowledge. In constructivist classroom, role of the teacher has changed from transmitter of knowledge to facilitator in the exploration of knowledge and role of the students has changed from passive receiver to one of knowledge creator. Constructivists have developed number of pedagogies like problem based learning, discovery learning, web quest learning, collaborative learning. Inquiry based learning is one of these pedagogical approaches which is being promoted largely by educationist today. Research studies suggest that 5E Instructional Model ensures positive enhancement of learning outcomes of the students at different cognitive levels. This model follows five steps namely Engagement, Exploration, Explanation, Elaboration and Evaluation enabling students to construct new ideas or concepts depending upon their knowledge and experiences. This model has a capability to transform the present scenario of traditional classroom.','','-','Pooja Walia','189-198','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(769,'Effect of Integrated Syntax of Advance Organizer Model and Inductive Thinking Model on Achievement and Retention of class IX students in Mathematics','The present study aims to investigate the effect of Integrated Syntax of Advance Organizer Model and Inductive Thinking Model on achievement and retention of class IX students in mathematics. For this purpose a sample of 60 students is drawn from IX class students from a school at Kurukshetra (Haryana) affiliated to CBSE. Two groups of students each comprising 30 students were formed and were labelled as Experimental Group (A1), and control group (A2). Both the groups were equated on intelligence using Ravens Progressive Matrices Test. Lesson plans on Integrated Syntax (AOM and ITM) were prepared and  implemented after pre-testing on Achievement Test. After completion of the instructional treatment achievement test was administered twice as post test-I and post test-II (Retention Test) to students of Experimental group and Control group both. Three-Way ANOVA was used to arrive at the following conclusions: (i) Experimental Group was found to attain significantly higher achievement scores as compared to Control Group;(ii) Experimental Group also was found to attain significantly higher retention  scores as compared to Control Group.','','-','Puneet Walia','199-211','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(770,'A Comparative Study of B.T.C. and Special B.T.C. Teachers Regarding Their Self Concept','The teacher should be a person and/or with such qualities and enables to deliver the citizens desired by the nation so the teacher much is very effective. The teachers\' quality and their positive self concept play an important role in implementation of positive changes in our school teaching and learning activities.','','-','Dhirendra Singh Chikara, Rachna Tyagi','213-216','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(771,'Thermo-Optical Behavior of Liquid Crystals Mixtures','In this paper liquid crystal displays (LCDs) have established a firm foothold on the market as flat panel displays for computer\'s, transportation communication (especially in its mobile version) instrumentation and in the future with increasing importance for television [1-5]. The opitcal properties can be described in terms of refractive indices. The most important feature of a liquid crystal  which determines the anisotropy in its physical properties, is its orientational order, and this is generally characterized by  microscopic order parameter S that results from angular correlation between the molecules.','','-','Praveen Kr. Sharma, M.K. Bansal','217-224','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(772,'A study of Correlation Between Intelligence and Emotional Intelligence at Higher Secondary Level','The present study has conducted to see the correlation between emotional intelligence and intelligence. A Correlation design is used. The sample of 120 adolescent from different senior secondary school of Jaipur city was selected randomly. The emotional intelligence scale by Hide, Pethe and Dhar and General intelligence scale by S.M Mohsin were employed. The objectives of the study were to study the correlation between emotional quotient and intelligence quotient of adolescents and in gender perspectives also.  Null hypothesis were formulated against the objectives.  The study revels that emotional intelligence is not significantly correlated with intelligence either comprehensively or in gender perspectives.','','-','Anjali Sharma','225-232','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(773,'Globalization and Higher Education','Higher education is a global business. It should be noted that Indian spend nearly $ 4 billion annually to send their children abroad for higher studies and technical training while there is no reasons for India not emerging as a global hub for higher education and technical training. The real challenge therefore, is to expand capacities in higher education to keep ahead of the curve of rising domestic and global demand. This paper explains effects of globalization on higher education sector. The students migration to get higher education, entry of foreign universities, privatization of higher education in India, contractual appointment in higher education, economic help for students to get higher education, emphasis on innovative skilled and high-tech education, grading system in higher education, dress code for convocation ceremony, proliferation of colleges and deemed universities, boom of knowledge economy, single window to regulate higher education, emphasis on private investment to improve educational infrastructure are some changes which we can observe due to globalization. The new environment holds both threats and opportunities to higher education in the country. Cut throat competition for employment, high fee structure, challenges for local institutions are some examples of difficulties which are in practice. On the other hand, there are some positive features also; student will get a qualitative education easily. They would get a wide range of employment and opportunities. India need to have a proactive demand based policy towards private higher education including foreign institutions/universities desirous of setting up campuses in India or entering into joint ventures. This has to be combined with the establishment of a regulatory mechanism that ensures that students welfare is not compromised and quality standards are maintained.','','-','Sarika Sharma','233-238','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(774,'Secondary Education: A Challenge for the 12th FYP','We recognize that Secondary Education is mainly the concern of the states but in view of its impact on the life of the country as a whole, both in the field of culture and technical efficiency, the Central Government can not divest itself of the responsibility to improve its standards and to relate it intelligently to the larger problems of national life.\r\nSecondary Education Commission, 1952-53\r\nSecondary Education is a crucial and terminal stage of the school system. It is a gateway for higher education and also a vital link to the world of work. While the developed world has reached a stage where secondary education has become universal, it is undergoing a transformation in the developing countries including India. The greatest pressure in the coming years will be to redefine the role of secondary education consistent with the longterm social and economic development strategy of the country. Traditionally, secondary school is viewed as a place where the students pick up skills and competencies demanded in the labour market. However, this role of secondary education has also been questioned on many grounds. We have moved from a stage of supply-driven, as was prevalent up to the eighties, to that of demand- oriented courses in the early nineties. The recent trends indicate that even this is changing and the emphasis is shifting to general education, lifelong learning, alternating between education and work for which the present system is ill-equipped.','','-','Subhash Singh','239-246','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(775,'Communication in Social and Psychological Perspective- An Overview','The aim of the paper is to understand the communication in social and psychological perspective. The content has been discussed under some points as: meaning of communication, process of communication with the help of model, differentiation between effective and in effective communication types of communication, fact related with communication and importance. The meaning of communication is explained with working definition and within process three complexities are coded and elements of communication sender and receiver are discussed with encoding, decoding and channels. In which noise (external and internal) plays an important role. There are various types of communication as formal & informal communication, informal communication exist like grapevine and more effective and supports the formal ways of communication. Some facts as impression also involved merely with expression and it is also vary important for an educational institution or school system because school communicates with society and vice versa.\r\n	The conclusion of the paper is drawn that the communication is social-psychological process as in communication an individual and a group of individual i.e. People is involved, individual itself is psychological factor and group of people is social factors. The communication exists between these two factors, most of the times these two interact with each other and many problems arise due to mishandling with social and psychological factors. To create effective communication, not only we should understand that but should carefully deal also.','','-','Anjali Sharma','247-259','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(776,'Role of NAAC in Indian Context','There are over 250 university level institutions and over 12000 colleges in India, which offer various types and levels of program. These institutions widely differ in terms of the mandate to offer program and courses, student\'s enrolment, infrastructure, delivery systems, sources of funds and governance. The quality of a teachers performance in the classroom and school context is determined largely by the initial academic and professional training he/she receives before being inducted to schools as well as recurrent in-service training and professional development support and the job experience gained on an ongoing basis. It is satisfying to note that significant, path-breaking efforts are taking place in the field of teacher education for quality improvement. The National Assessment and Accreditation Council (NAAC) in India and the Commonwealth of Learning (COL) started to work together responding to the concerns for quality assurance in teacher education','','-','Mahima Gupta','261-266','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(777,'Women Education in India','The constitution of India, adopted in 1950, with its many measures for social reforms, contained several provisions by which there was guarantee of equality before the law as well as clauses for equality of opportunity to all in many spheres such as the matters relating to employment. Above all there is an affirmative action clause in the constitution, which states that nothing shall prevent the state from making any special provision for women and children. Many laws have been passed to improved womens position in pursuance of the constitution ideals. While the de jure position is enviable the de facto position of women is at variance with it in the educational, social, economic and political field where they are under- represented or invisible .the constitution also included the achievement of free and compulsory universal primary  education as  directive  principal within ten years.\r\n             There is no chance of the welfare of the world unless the condition of women is improved. It is not possible for a bird to fly on one wing.                                   - Swami Vivekananda\r\n                The evolution of Indian womens education has been spread over centuries. Its history is as old as the history of India.','','-','Archna Maheshwari, Nisha Shukla','267-272','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(778,'Privatization of Higher Education','The National Knowledge Commission as well as the Millennium Development Goals has given new directions to view education in a different context placing responsibility on the authorities and the incumbents. Privatization represents the current trends in education. Adequate measures have to be taken to ensure that these factors do not leave anyone without education and good quality of life.','','-','Reena Gupta','273-277','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(779,'Leverage and its Impact on Earning Capacity in Essar Steel Limited','Steel Industry in India is on an upswing because of the strong global and domestic demand. India\'s rapid economic growth and soaring demand by sectors like infrastructure, real estate and automobiles, at home and abroad, has put Indian steel industry on the global map. According to the latest report by International Iron and Steel Institute (IISI), India is the seventh largest steel producer in the world. This paper attempts to make an analytical study of application of financial leverage, earnings per share and dividend per share of steel industry with data for the period of 2006 to 2010. It is an effort to understand and measure the variations in financial performance of steel industry.  For the purpose of analysis, ratio techniques and to test hypothesis other statistical tools i.e. correlation has been used for the research purpose. The result of the study indicates that there is a correlation between DFL and EPS and the difference is insignificant where as result of correlation coefficient at 5% level of significance showed that the diffidence is significant between DFL and DPS and EPS and DPS.','','-','Asha Sharma','279-288','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(780,'Rising Indian Automobile Industry: Looks do Matter!','This paper reports a part of an ongoing investigation in Indian Automobile Industry. Indian Automobile Industry is under continuous reforms so, an attempt has been made to examine the 5 features of a car namely uniqueness, luxury, looks, technical superiority and car accessories which attract customers the most while purchasing a car. A systematic random sampling from five residential areas of urban Jaipur was done to select 50 car consumers. An investigator-constructed questionnaire was used to collect data on these factors. The data analysis using chi-square test was done to describe the nature of the sample and to test the null hypothesis that the choices for purchase of car is equally distributed on five features. Data Analysis has been done by using non parametric chi-square test. It was analyzed that features of car effect car purchasing decision.','','-','Sakshi Modi, Tapsya Jhulka','289-296','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(781,'Philosophy of Existentialism','Existentialism represents a protest against the rationalism of traditional philosophy, against misleading notions of the bourgeois culture, and the dehumanizing values of industrial civilization. Since alienation, loneliness and self-estrangement constitute threats to human personality in the modern world, existential thought has viewed as its cardinal concerns a quest for subjective truth, a reaction against the negation of Being and a perennial search for freedom From the ancient Greek philosopher, Socrates to the Twentieth Century. French philosopher, Jean Paul, Sartre, thinkers have dealt with this tragic sense of ontological reality - the human situation within a comic context.','','-','Deepika Agarwal, Kavita Bansal','297-302','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(782,'cqyUn\"kgj ,oa uSuhrky esa vuqlwfpr tkfr dh Nk=kvksa dh izkFkfed Lrj ij kSf{kd miyfC/k dk foys','vuqlwfpr oxZ dh vfk{kk] csjkstxkjh cjdjkj gS ftlesa buds lkekftd Lrj esa Hkh fuEurk LFkkbZ gSA fk{kk ekuoh; fodkl] lkekftd fodkl dh loksZRre fuf/k gSA fk{kk dh miyC/krk dh vuq:irk gh O;fDr dh vkfFkZd] lkekftd] jktuSfrd] vk/;kfRed lksp mldh thou kSyh ds izfr vfHko`fRr esa ifjorZu mldh O;kidrk ,oa fodkl dks laof/kZr djrh gSA O;fDr dh ftruh ,oa tSlh fk{kk esa miyfC/k gksxh mlds thou kSyh ds izfr vfHko`fRr Hkh mlh ds vuq:i