 one in which we may have some\r\nhope of improving our lot.','','-','Arun Kumar','309-316','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(805,'An Overview of Indian Agriculture\r\nin Present Scenario','India is one of the fastest growing economies of the world and is\r\ncurrently the focus of a great deal of international attention. It is the\r\nseventh largest country in the world in terms of its geographical size.\r\nToday it has a population of nearly 1.1 billion which makes it the second\r\nmost populous nation in the world. With current population growth by\r\n2025 India may even have caught up with China according to the UN.\r\nAgriculture is the main occupation of the Indian peoples. Performance of\r\nIndian economy is dependent upon the growth of Agriculture sector. It\r\ncontributes nearly 16% of Indias Gross Domestic Product (GDP) & 13%\r\nof total exports. It provides employment to 52% of the countrys work\r\nforce and livelihood security to more than 620 million people.\r\nAgriculture plays an important role in economic development, such as\r\nprovision of food to the nation, enlarging exports, transfer of manpower\r\nto non-agricultural sectors, contribution to capital formation, and\r\nsecuring markets for industrialization. Agriculture forms the backbone of\r\nIndian economy and even though large industrialization in last 60 years,\r\nagriculture still occupies a place of pleasure.','','-','Arun Kumar','317-323','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(806,'Contribution of Sarojinis Naidu in\r\nEnglish Poetry','In bringing out her selected poetry, this concluding chapter of this\r\nthesis making any special claims for the value of significance of\r\nher writings except that Sarojini Naidu was an important figure in\r\nIndias recent history of Indian English literature. Her works\r\ntherefore deserves to be available to present and future readers.\r\nShe presented various kinds of role in her life as a Politician,\r\nNationalist Leader, Poetess, and Activist for Womens Rights,\r\nOrator and a Celebrity.','','-','Sunita Singh','325-330','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(807,'Impacts of Nitrogen Use in Agriculture','Nitrogen is the most abundant element in our atmosphere and is a major constituent of all living organisms. Compounds of\r\nnitrogen useful for the nutrition of living things are made available\r\nby several different processes varying greatly in magnitude and\r\nimportance During thunderstorms small amounts of atmospheric\r\nnitrogen gas are converted to nitric acid by electrical discharges\r\nand same ammonium nitrogen is reported to be derived from a\r\nfew types of rocks during the weathering process. In many\r\nagricultural situations the availability of a suitable source of\r\nnitrogen is the major factor limiting crop productivity. Inputs of\r\nnitrogen into agricultural systems are primarily from chemical\r\nfertilizers and nitrogen derived from atmospheric di-nitrogen by\r\nthe process of biological nitrogen fixation, which is the microbial\r\nconversion of atmospheric di-nitrogen gas into plant usable\r\nammonia. Indeed, the provision of biologically fixed nitrogen plays\r\na key role in crop production in world agriculture.','','-','Dhirendra Kumar','331-339','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(808,'Relevance of Green Manure and\r\nNitrogenous Fertilizers in Agricultural Environment','The attention on nitrogen stems from the problems intrinsic in\r\ncontrolling it. Too much or too little nitrogen can have a profound\r\neffect. New plants won\'t grow without nitrogen and established\r\nturf will not thrive if it is starved for nitrogen. Yet, too much\r\nnitrogen can cause burning.','','-','Dhirendra Kumar','341-346','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(809,'A Comparative Study of\r\nEnvironmental Awareness Among\r\nthe Secondary School Students in\r\nPunjab and Himachal Pradesh','The study compares the environmental awareness among\r\nthe secondary school students of Punjab and Himachal Pradesh.\r\nThe need of the environmental awareness has risen, as man over\r\nlooked the importance of environment as an integral part of\r\nhiswell being. The various dimensions of environmental\r\nawareness studied were causes of pollution, conservation of soil,\r\nforest, air etc., energy conservation, conservation of human\r\nhealth and conservation of wild life and animal husbandry. The\r\nsample of 200 secondary school students was selected by\r\nstratified random sampling. The tool used in the present\r\ninvestigation was Environmental Awareness Ability Measure\r\n(EAAM) developed by Praveen Kumar Jha. The data collected was\r\ngiven suitable statistical treatment like mean, standard deviation\r\nand ANOVA. It was found that the secondary school students of\r\nHimachal Pradesh are more aware about their environment than the secondary school students of Punjab.','','-','\"\"Kamaljit Kaur, Sarita ;\r\njaswal\"','347-352','NO','-','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(810,'A Supply Chain Production Inventory Model for Deteriorating Products','In this Paper, a coordinated system for supplier, producer and retailer has been discussed for optimal collection, material control, production control and ordering policies of a deteriorating product deteriorating linearly with time. The demand rate and the production rate are considered as linear functions of time. The deterioration rate is considered of Weibull distribution form given by  where   and   are constant. Both cases of shortages and without shortages are considered. The shortage is considered as fully backlogged.','','-','Sarvpreet Kaur, A. P. Singh,D Singh','1-20','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','47','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(811,'Effect of Permissible delay in payments and inflation induced demand on a two warehouse model','In this paper a two-warehouse supply chain inventory model with inflation induced demand is developed. we have assumed the inventory costs including holding cost and deterioration cost in RW are higher than those in OW. The effect of permissible delay in payments has been taken in to account. Shortages are allowed with complete backlogged. Production rate is considered as demand dependent in vendor model. Holding cost is taken as variable. We believe that our study will provide a solid foundation for the further study of this sort of important inventory models. A numerical example is given to illustrate the system.','','-','Pratap Singh, Dinesh Singh, A. P. Singh','21-32','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','47','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(812,'Effect of Inflation on Two-Warehouse Inventory Model With Stock-Dependent Demand','An important problem arises in inventory control is to decide where to stock the goods. Furthermore, in some practical situations, when suppliers provide price discounts for bulk purchases or when the item under consideration is a seasonal product such as the output of harvest or the replenishment cost is higher than the other related cost, etc., the inventory manager may purchase more goods than can be stored in its own warehouse (OW). From economical point of views, they usually choose to rent other warehouses than rebuild a new warehouse. Thus, the excess quantities are stored in a rented warehouse (RW).','','-','Pawan Kumar, N.K. Gaur','33-46','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','47','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(813,'A deteriorating inventory model with time varying linear demand and partial backlogging','A deteriorating inventory model taking into account the linear deteriorating rate of items, is developed for a deteriorating inventory system with linear time dependent demand. In this model, shortages are allowed with partial backlogging. Demand is a linear function of time and deterioration rate is also linear function of time. As a result in this paper, we establish a model to find the optimal order quantity by minimizing the total inventory cost. Sensitivity analysis of the optimal solution with respect to the parameters of the system is carried out.','','-','Balvinder Singh Sandhu, Arun Kumar Tomer','47-54','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','47','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(814,'Some Optimality and Duality Results for an Efficient Solution of Multiobjective Nonlinear Fractional Programming Problem','Kaul and Kaur [7] obtained necessary optimality conditions for a non-linear programming problem by taking the objective and constraint functions to be semilocally convex and their right differentials at a point to be lower semi-continuous. Suneja and Gupta [12] established the necessary optimality conditions without assuming the semilocal convexity of the objective and constraint functions but their right differentials at the optimal point to be convex.\r\nSuneja and Gupta [13] established necessary optimality conditions for an efficient solution of a multiobjective non-linear programming problem by taking the right differentials of the objective functions and constraint functions at the efficient point to be convex. In this paper we obtain some results for a properly efficient solution of a multiobjective non-linear fractional programming problem involving semilocally convex and related functions by assuming generalized Slater type constraint qualification.','','-','Paras Bhatnagar, Sanjeev Rajan','55-66','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','47','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(815,'Multistage Bicriteria Scheduling Problems: Minimizing Rental Cost with Minimum Makespan','This paper is an attempt to study a bicriteria in n jobs m machines flow shop scheduling problems under a specified rental policy in which processing times are associated with probabilities. We consider bi-criteria scheduling problems involving minimization of rental cost of the machines with minimum makespan. A heuristic approach to find the best possible sequence by optimizing both the criterias simultaneously is discussed. The effectiveness of the heuristic approach is justified by mathematical proofs and bi-criteria In-Out flow table of the jobs. A computer programme followed by a numerical illustration is given to substantiate the algorithm.','','-','Deepak Gupta, Sameer Sharma, Seema Sharma','67-86','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','47','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(816,'Swap Analysis in Supply Chain of Sugar Industry Applying Linear Programming','This paper proposes and examines several swap strategies for the sugar industry to create win-win situations for industries supplying sugar to their customers. A realistic data from three sugar mills of Uttar Pradesh, Maharashtra and Bihar is used to build a number of linear programming models of the strategies under investigation. The optimal solutions of these models are analysed to identify the strategies advantages or disadvantages.\r\nThe success of swap strategies relies on alliances and partnerships between the sugar industries. They, however, seem to advocate very attractive alternative policies, create potentials for substantial cost savings and assure more reliable lead- time to delivery','','-','Sonam Sharma, Megha Rani, S.M.Gupta','87-98','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','47','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(817,'On Generalizations of Shannons Inequality and Coding Theorems','In the present paper we study two generalizations of Shannons Inequality and their applications in source coding. We define two new generalized mean code word lengths and study their bounds in terms of the generalized measures of entropies obtained by applying these generalizations. Particular cases are also obtained.','','-','D.S Hooda ,Sonali Saxena','99-110','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','47','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(818,'Application of Fuzzy Topsis Method for Solving Job-Shop Scheduling Problem','In this paper, we focused on the scheduling and sequencing which is a form of Decision Making (DM) that plays a crucial role in production manufacturing and service industries. Job- scheduling problem arise when there is a choice as to the order in which number of tasks can be performed. In such problems, we determine an appropriate order or schedule for a series of jobs to be done on a finite number of service facilities.\r\nThe paper presents the way of making schedule of a finite number of jobs on a finite number of machines of unequal efficiencies by using the Technique for Order Preference by Similarity to Ideal Solution (TOPSIS) Method in fuzzy environment. The order of machines is random. The time taken by the machines for conducting jobs is assumed as imprecise processing time or fuzzy numbers. The fuzzy evaluation values are given by Triangular Fuzzy Numbers (TNFs). Weights are given to each machine according to their efficiency. A new distance is defined using which the distance of each job from the positive and negative ideal solutions are calculated. Also a closeness coefficient is defined to determine the ranking order of the jobs so that the complete schedule or sequence may finish at minimum time-span. Finally, a numerical example is illustrated for proposed method.','','-','V.S. Jadhav and V. H. Bajaj','111-118','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','47','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(819,'Analysis of trade credit financing in an EPQ environment with credit sensitive demand','Trade credit financing has become a powerful tool to improve demand and profit in industry. In general, a supplier/retailer frequently offers trade credit to its credit risk downstream member in order to stimulate their respective demand. The main purpose of the present paper is to explore the impact of credit period on the retailers demand, which may be instant or delayed. An EPQ model under the condition of two echelon trade credit with credit sensitive demand has been analyzed. This type of demand pattern can be observed in many consumer durables. The optimal credit period offered by the retailer and the optimal replenishment time has been jointly evaluated in order to maximize retailers profit. Results have been validated with the help of examples. Comprehensive sensitivity analysis has been performed on different parameters.','','-','Chandra K. Jaggi, Mona Verma','119-134','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','48','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(820,'An EPQ Model with Imperfect Production Systems with Rework of Regular Production and Sales Return','The Economic Production Quantity (EPQ) model is commonly used by practitioners in the fields of production and inventory management to assist them in making decision on production lot size.  The common assumptions in this model are that all units produced are perfect and shortages are not allowed.  But, in real situation the defective items will be produced in each cycle of production and shortages and scrap are possible.  These assumptions will underestimate the actual required quantity.  Hence, the defective items can not be ignored in the production process. Rework process is necessary to convert those defective into finished goods.  This study proposes EPQ model that incorporates both imperfect production quality and falsely not screening out a proportion of defects, thereby passing them on to customers, resulting in defect sales returns. Two models of rework processes are considered; the EPQ model without shortages is studied first and with shortages is investigated next. To active this objective a suitable mathematical model is developed and the optimal production lot size which minimizes the total cost is derived.  The relevant model is built, solved and necessary and sufficient conditions for a unique and global optimal solution are derived.  An illustrative example is provided and numerically verified.  The validation of result in this model was coded in Microsoft Visual Basic 6.0','','-','C. Krishnamoorth','135-158','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','48','2013-07-23 17:36:30','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(821,'A note on: A Replenishment Policy for items with Price-dependent Demand, time proportional Deterioration and No Storages ','Begum et al. (DOI: 10.1080/00207721.2010.543481) developed replenishment policy when demand rate is price-sensitive, deterioration rate follows three parameters, Weibull distribution and shortages are not allowed. In the paper it is observed that that the retailers inventory stock is zero before the deterioration of units start. This article rectifies the model formulation. The remodel is validated with a numerical example and the sensitivity analysis of parameters is carried out. ','','- ',' Nita H. Shah, Hardik Soni and Jyoti Gupta ','159-164  ','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','48','2013-09-17 12:41:22','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(822,'A Mathematical Model for Bicriteria in Constrained Three Stage Flow Shop Scheduling  ','This paper presents bicriteria in n-jobs, three machines flow shop scheduling problem to minimize the total elapsed time and rental cost of the machines under a specified rental policy in which the processing time, independent setup time each associated with probabilities including transportation time and job block concept. Further the concept of the break down interval for which the machines are not available for the processing is included. A heuristic approach method to find optimal or near optimal sequence has been discussed. A computer programme followed by a numerical illustration is given to substantiate the algorithm  ','','-  ','  Deepak Gupta, Sameer Sharma, Seema Sharma  ','165-174','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','48','2013-09-17 12:41:57','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(823,'Applications of Response Surface Methodology on Mullite Formation From Red Sediment Placer Sillimanite Using Microwave Energy ','This paper deals with the applications of Response Surface Methodology (RSM) on the effect of microwave heat treatment for mullite formation from placer sillimanite. The results of these investigations reveal that RSM data obtained from microwave heat treatment studies show that there is 92.55% of mullite formation under optimized conditions with composite charge material having 40% Al2O3, 60% sillimanite, with additive 60% SiC and 10% binder. The confirmatory experimental data of RSM optimised conditions also suggest that there is 97% of mullite formation using microwave heat treatment. A mullite is formed within 25 minutes from the sillimanite, under the above experimental conditions. FESEM image analysis shows the mullite formations in cluster form, SiC in massive structure and alumina needle form in microwave treated sample. Thus microwave heat source is much effective to form mullite from sillimanite. ','','- ',' Satya Sai Srikant, P.S. Mukherjee , R. Bhima Rao ','175-188  ','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','48','2013-09-17 12:42:26','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(824,'Integrated  inventory Model with Inflation Induced Demand and Shortages under two Storage ','In this paper an inventory model is developed in which shortages are considered with two-storage under inflation induced demand rate. Due to different preservation environment it is assumed that in one warehouse deterioration rate is time varying linear and in the other it is taken as Weibull distributed deterioration. The classical optimization technique is used to drive the optimal solution. Finally, some numerical examples for illustration are provided. ','','- ',' V K Sharma, Prachi Kansal ','189-198','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','48','2013-09-17 12:42:58','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(825,'Two-Warehouse Inventory Model for Deteriorating Items under the Effect of Inflation and Partial Backlogging ','Considerable amount of analytic work has been done for the case where the enterprise has got one warehouse, but little work has been done for the case where an enterprise has got more than one warehouse. In the present paper, we consider a situation where the enterprises have got two warehouses. In the proposed model, the demand rate is taken as a time and stock dependent. Shortages are allowed and partial backlogged and the backlogging rate is variable and is dependent on the length of the waiting time for the next replenishment. The longer the waiting time is the smaller the backlogging rate would be. Effect of inflation on the model also considered. A numerical example with sensitivity analysis is given to validate the results of the proposed model. ','','- ',' Satish Kumar, S.R.Singh, N.K.Gaur ','199-214','NO','-','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','48','2013-09-17 12:43:32','e',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(829,'A Note on Almost Kaehlerian Bochner Recurrent and Symmetric Spaces','Patterson (1956) has studied some theorems on Ricci-recurrent spaces; Prasad (1973) has defined and studied certain properties of recurrent and Ricci-recurrent almost Hermite spaces and almost Tachibana spaces. Singh and Samyal (2004) have studied on a Tachibana space with parallel Bochner curvature tensor. Further, Negi and Rawat (2009) have studied some theorems on almost Kaehlerian spaces with recurrent and symmetric projective curvature tensors.  In this paper, we have defined and studied almost Kaehlerian Bochner recurrent and symmetric spaces and several theorems have been established.','','Kaehlerian, Bochner, Recurrent, Symmetric, Space.','U.S. Negi and Kailash Gairola','01-07','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','34','50','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(830,' The Disturbance Caused In Heat Flow Due To The Presence Of Two Griffith-Cracks Opened By An Interior Wedge In An Isotropic Rectangle','The Closed form expression of disturbance in temperature distribution in a rectangular isotropic plate in the presence of two Griffith cracks opened by an interior wedge under steady state heat conduction is being obtained by using the principle of cross-linear-superposition along with Fourier transform. It is found 