tool that can evaluate the software quantitatively and monitors the changes in reliability performance is software reliability growth modeling A number of such models that relate the number of failures (faults identified/removed) and execution time, have been discussed in the literature. These models are used to predict fault content and reliability of the software. Generally two patterns have been observed for the fault removal; exponential or S-Shaped .In this study we have tried to focus on yet another important class of SRGMs which can depict, depending upon parameter values, both exponential and S-Shaped growth curve. They are known as flexible SRGMs. Here, we have started the description for three existing flexible SRGMs due to1) Obha,2)  Bittanti et. al. and 3) Kapur and Garg. We have progressively described the discrete version of the Kapur and Garg model and later shown their equivalence to the existing models as well. The model due to Kapur and Garg proves to be mathematically and computationally simpler than the others. Furthermore, we have also incorporated the concept of  Power Logistic learning function which proves to be very flexible in the sense that it represents various curve types  Exponential, Rayleigh, Weibull or simple Logistic','','Software Reliability Growth Models (SRGMs), Non-Homogeneous Poisson Process, Flexible SRGMs',' Ompal Singh1, V.K.Sharma, Jagvinder Singh, Indarpal Singh',' 25-36','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','34','50','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(833,' Integral Transform of Generalized K- Mittag-Leffler Function &#12310;GE&#12311;_(k,&#945;,&#946;)^(&#947;,q) (z)','This paper deal with the new Generalized K- Mittag-Leffler function, GE_(k,&#945;,&#946;)^(&#947;,q) (z) ,[5] and study its particular cases. For the Generalized K- Mittag-Leffler function, GE_(k,&#945;,&#946;)^(&#947;,q) (z) ,we evaluate its Mellin-Barnes integral represen