 with linear demand and shortages. A rented warehouse (RW) is used when the ordering quantity exceeds the limited facility of the owned warehouse (OW). We assume that the production rate is finite and dependent on the demand rate. It is assumed that deterioration rates of items in the two warehouses may be different. Shortages are allowed and partially backlogged. Salvage value is related to the deteriorated items. The model is analytically solved by numerical example. Sensitivity analysis is also shown in this model.','','Two warehouse production model, shortages, salvage value.','Mamta Sharma,B.B.Singh, R.K.Srivastav,Jitendra Singh','357-366','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(857,'Estimation of Iridium(III) using Amino Acid-Hexacyanoferrate(III) Redox Reaction','A new kinetic spectrophotometric method is developed for the determination of Ir(III) in aqueous alkaline medium. The method is based on the iridium(III) catalyzed oxidation of some amino acids by hexacyanoferrate (abbreviated as HCF) (III)) ions in aqueous alkaline medium. The kinetic studies on eight essential amino acids are carried out in aqueous alkaline medium. Out of eight amino acids four are glycine, alanine, valine and leucine (abbreviated as AA) while the other four are sulphur containing as cystine, cysteine, isoleucine and methionine (abbreviated as SAA). The comparison of the results shows that Beers limit is low for SAA than AA. For SAA value of Beer limit is 0.258 to 8.37 gcm-3 and for AA it is 0.99 - 39.98 g-\r\ncm-3. Again higher molar absorptivity & low sandells sensitivity value show that the use of SAA oxidation reaction is better than the use of AA for Ir(III) determination.The molar absorptivity & sandells sensitivity are found to be 0.367 x 103 to 1.425 X 103 l mol-1 cm-1 and 0.524 to 0.135 gcm-2 forAA and 2.31 x 103 to 5.57 X 103 l mol-1 cm-1 and 0.0834 to 0.0345 gcm-2 for SAA respectively. The coefficient of determination lies between 0.9588 to 0.9989 for AA & 0.9734 to 0.9997 for SAA. The effect of few interfering ions have been worked out for developing the calibration curves in terms of absorbance or initial rates or pseudo first order rate constant vs. Ir(III) plot, absorbance was noted at &#955;maxof 420 nm. Thus the present method is more simple and sensitive then the reported methods and especially useful in absence of the expected interfering ions.\r\n','','Determination, Oxidation, Hexacyanoferrate, Glycine, Alanine, Valine, Leucine, Cysteine, Methionine, cystine, Isoleucine, Ir(III)','Shakunj, Savita Devi and Anjali Goel','367-373','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(858,' Future of fullerenes (NPMs), as vehicle fuels','Hydrogen-fueled vehicles offer the promise of significantly reducing the amount of pollutants expelled into the environment. However, the technology that is needed to store the hydrogen fuel onboard and deliver it to the propulsion system is different from what consumers and even engineers currently know and understand. As an early step in identifying critical safety requirements for these vehicles and, if needed, develop appropriate Federal Motor Vehicle Safety Standards, the National Highway Traffic Safety Administration requested that Battelle undertake a high-level failure modes and effects analysis to characterize potential hazards from compressed-hydrogen fuel cell vehicles and identify potential safety issues.  \r\nEnergy use for transportation purposes and the number of passenger vehicles is increasing rapidly around the world. Fuelling infrastructure based on hydrogen provides an attractive alternative to predominating fossil fuels. This paper includes research on hydrogen fuel cell vehicle and its local refueling station based on hydrogen production from physisorption-based, NPMs.  \r\nOn-board hydrogen storage technology is critical to H2-powered fuel cell vehicles in future transportation applications. To be practical, the storage system must have a gravimetric capacity of at least 0.06 kg H2/kg and a volumetric capacity of 0.045 kg H2/L at ambient temperature. Furthermore, the adsorbent should be able to be produced at commercial scale to bring the cost down. All these pose significant technical challenges to the hydrogen storage materials. \r\nWe plan to address these challenges by developing a new class of physisorption-based hydrogen adsorbent, NPMs. Polymers usually have excellent thermal stability within typical adsorbent operating temperature and tolerance to moisture and other contaminants. Furthermore, they can be produced at commercial scale with the current industrial infrastructure. The uses of porous polymers as hydrogen adsorbent have been report','','-','Parshuram Singh,  Rajeev Kumar Singh','375-390','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(859,'The Fullerenes: A Novel Nanostructured Polymeric Material for Hydrogen Storage','Recently, nanostructured materials adsorbing hydrogen on their surface have received much attention as a hydrogen storage medium because of the potential of good reversibility, fast kinetics, and high capacity. However, it has been found that the storage capacity in these nanomaterials decreases significantly near room temperature and ambient pressure. The reason is that the binding energy of H2 molecules on these materials is mediated by the van der Waals interaction (~0.04 eV) which is much short of the required energy of ~0.3&#8722;0.4 eV.\r\nIn recent years, transition metal (TM)-dihydrogen complexes have been of intense interest for hydrogen storage purposes because of the potential of the application of these complexes to hydrogen storage materials that operate at room temperature and ambient pressure. Density functional theory (DFT) studies have shown that, using TM-dihydrogen complexes, TM (Sc, Ti, V, and Ni)-decorated nanomaterials adsorb H2 molecules with a binding energy of ~0.2&#8722;0.8 eV via the hybridization of TM d orbits and H2 &#963; or &#963;* orbits. The hydrogen storage capacity reaches the gravimetric goal of 9 wt% of the Department of Energy (DOE) by the year 2015. However, it has turned out that the aggregation of TM atoms is energetically preferred and changes significantly the adsorption nature of the H2 molecules, resulting in the dissociation of H2 molecules and the reduction of dihydrogen complexes. Instead of TM atoms, searching for different elements for decoration is necessary to overcome the issues of the aggregation in metal-decorated hydrogen storage systems. Recently, alkali or alkali earth metal atoms have been considered as elements for decorating nanomaterials for hydrogen storage. It has been found that alkali (or earth) metal-decorated nanomaterials can absorb H2 molecules with a binding energy of ~0.1&#8722;0.2 eV.19-23. In this paper, we show that coating of C60 fullerenes with suitable metal atoms may lead to the synthesis ','','Polymers, nanocomposites, coatings, nanoparticles, nimrods, evaporation, sputtering, magnetic, high frequency, antibacterial','Parshuram Singh, Rajeev Kumar Singh','391-400','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(860,' Evaluation of Reliability and Mean Time to System Failure of A Complex System Models by Using Boolean Function Techniques','The present paper deals with the reliability analysis of  a complex system ,which consists of a number of components of varying nature.The analysis of the model is performed with the help of Boolean Function Technique by taking general and non-identical life time distributions of the components of the system.In particular Weibull distribution with different scale parameter  (i = 1,2,16)is taken as lifetime distribution of the components.Some important measures of system effectiveness have been obtained.A graphical study has also been carried out to highlight the importance of the results.','','Boolean Function Technique, Weibull distribution, MTSF and hazard rate.',' C.K.Goel , Dhanpal Singh and Baljeet Kour','401-410','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(861,'A Common Coincidence Points Theorem For Eight RWeakly Commuting Maps','The aim of this paper is to obtain a common coincidence point theorem for eight mappings using the concept of R  weakly commuting mappings on a complete metric space. Which generalizes several previously known results due to, Tayyab kawran [11], Daffer and Kandko [10]. ','','Rweakly commuting mappings, Coincidence points fixed points, complete metric space','Pardeep Kr. Rana, Khilendra Singh, Sachin Kr. Agrawal',' 411-416','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(862,' A production inventory model for deteriorating items with shortages and time dependent exponentially decreasing demand','In this paper, a production-inventory model for deteriorating items is developed over a finite planning horizon where the demand decreasing exponentially with time. The production rate is assumed to be finite and constant. Shortages in inventory are allowed and are completely backlogged. Deterioration rate is constant. As a result, we establish a model to find the optimum values of time and inventory level by minimizing the average cost.','','In this paper, a production-inventory model for deteriorating items is developed over a finite planning horizon where the demand decreasing exponentially with time. The production rate is assumed to be finite and constant. Shortages in inventory are allowed and are completely backlogged. Deteriorati','Balvinder Singh Sandhu, Arun Kumar Tomer','417-426','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','43','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(863,'FTIR, Raman And Themodynamic Functions Of 5-Carboethoxy-4-Hydroxy-2-Mercapto Pyrimidine','The infrared, Far-infrared and laser Raman spectra of solid 5-carbethoxy-4-hydroxy-2- mercaptopyrimidine. Thermodynamic functions have been computed and discussed.','','-','A.K. Mishra, S.K. Sharma, Nitin Singh, Narendra Pathak4, Ranjeet Singh','427-436','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','52','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(864,'Finding Various Tandem Repeat patterns in DNA : A study and Techniques','Tandem repeats occur in DNA when a pattern of two or more nucleotides is repeated and the repetitions are directly adjacent to each other. The importance of Tandem Repeats in some genomes is now well established. We have reported elsewhere some interesting new results obtained by means of a preliminary program for finding Tandem Repeats in DNA sequences, together with a brief description of the basic ideas of the algorithm. Many algorithmic techniques exist to detect the tandem repeats from a DNA sequence, which can be broadly classified to be either exact or heuristic. Exact methods use mathematical techniques like Fourier transform, K-tuples based method, etc. Heuristic methods use tools like combinational methods, suffix trees, statistical models, Hamming distance, and such others to identify approximate tandem repeats. Most of the available software tools for identification are designed to be data intensive due to the huge size of genomic data and variable number of tandem repeats in genome sequence. In this paper we describe about why tandem repeats , their importance and different techniques of finding them.','','-','D. K. Pandey, Preety Khatri','437-448','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','52','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(865,'Two warehouse inventory model with time varying demand and partial backlogging ','In this paper, we developed a two warehouse production model with linear demand and shortages. A rented warehouse (RW) is used when the ordering quantity exceeds the limited facility of the owned warehouse (OW). We assume that the production rate is finite and dependent on the demand rate. It is assumed that deterioration rates of items in the two warehouses may be different. Shortages are allowed and partially backlogged. Salvage value is related to the deteriorated items. The model is analytically solved by numerical example. Sensitivity analysis is also shown in this model.  ','','Two warehouse production model, shortages, salvage value. ',' Mamta Sharma,B.B.Singh, R.K.Srivastav,Jitendra Singh ','449-458  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','52','2013-09-19 02:14:17','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(866,'Mining Biological Data for mining frequent sequential patterns ','Biologists are stepping up their efforts in understanding the biological processes that underlie disease pathways in the clinical contexts. This has resulted in a flood of biological and clinical data from genomic sequences, DNA microarrays, and protein interactions, to biomedical images, disease pathways, and electronic health records. We are in a scenario where our capability to generate biomedical data has greatly surpassed our abilities to mine and analyze the data. We can expect data mining to play an increasingly crucial role in furthering biological research, since data mining is designed to handle challenging data analysis problems. In fact, it is our hope that data mining will be the next technical innovation employed by biologists to enable them to make insightful observations and groundbreaking discoveries from their wide array of heterogeneous data from molecular biology to pharmaceutical and clinical domains. In this paper we discuss about different data mining tasks for finding biological patterns and for finding frequent sequential patterns for finding disease ','','- ',' D. K. Pandey, Preety Khatri ','459-474  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','52','2013-09-19 02:15:08','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(867,'The disturbanc caused in heat flow due to the presence of two griffith-cracks in an isotropic rectangle. ','The closed form expression of temperature distribution in a rectangular isotropic under steady heat conduction is being obtained by using the principle of cross-linear-superposition along with Fourier series. It is found that temperature distribution at crack tip is smooth. Flux possesses Cauchy type singularity at crack tips. ','','[1] Flux intensity factor (FIF) [2] Fourier Series [3] Cross-linear- ',' Ranjeet Singh, Harendra Singh, P.S. Kushwaha ','475-488  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','52','2013-09-19 02:16:10','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(869,'Reliability /Survivability Analysis for Newly Developed (Weibull) Model with its Characteristics  ','The present paper deals with the reliability and hazard rate estimation of new type Weibull model. Its use as a life testing model has also been illustrated. The proposed model has been found better then exponential and general Weibull for two sets of life time data. Some characteristics of the model have also been given.\r\nKey Words : Reliability Function, Hazard Rate Function, Life Testing Model, Maximum likelihood estimator, Moment generating Function\r\n  ','','-  ','  D. K. Pandeyand Anusheel Mishra  ','489-494   ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','52','2013-09-19 02:16:33','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(870,'Estimation of Parameter for a new Type of Weibull life testing model ','The present paper deals with the reliability and hazard rate estimation of new generalized Weibull type model. Here maximum likelihood estimates of the parameters are obtained for sample uncensored and censored. Its order Statistics and UMVUE also obtained. ','','Maximum likelihood estimates, Reliability Function, Hazard Rate Function, Distribution of order Statistic, UMVUE, Pitman Estimation for scale ',' D. K. Pandey and Anusheel Mishra ','495-502  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','52','2013-09-19 02:09:18','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(871,'Effect of Trade Credits With Exponential Demand on Integrated Inventory Model ','- ','','- ',' Pawan Kumar, N.K. Gaur ','503-516  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','52','2013-09-19 02:09:46','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(872,'Use of Middleware Technology in Banking System ','Current generation is very dynamic and majorly focused in the area of Information and communication technology as a result of technological innovation, increased awareness and demands from customers. Today when we go through the news paper, refer to term \"new economy\" or the \"Information society\". ICT are also introduced in Banking, Railway, Aviation, Health, Transportation, Food Industry, Manufacturing or any business bodies. Earlier it was very difficult to wait for branch opening hours or stand in a queue, now a days hole banking process are going through the e-way and providing the customer to e-facilities including 24*7 customer supports. This paper describes about the middleware technology used in banking sector and what is the main feature and advantage with this technology. Middle tier technology designed in such a way, developers provides the graphical user interface (GUI) through any programming language and user\'s computer contain that GUI and application-specific entry forms or interactive windows. ','','Scalability, High-Availability, Load Balancing, Security and Security Architecture ',' Ganesh Pandey, D.K. Pandey ',' 517-522  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','52','2013-09-19 02:10:07','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(873,'Network security : Challenges and Issues in organizations ','Network security is a major issue in the computer world. This security begins with the top-down policy. Policy begins with understanding what it is you need to protect and what it is you need to protect against. Best practices in network security are more about the what and why of securing the organization\'s information assets than about the how. This paper discusses the three step framework to establish the network security program: Prepare, Organize and Execute. Network security in organization conducts a risk analysis for security posture which includes running a password cracking utility on the network in privileged mode to uncover not so obvious privileges. Organizations also have the security team responsible for policy awareness and enforcement as well as being informed on the technical aspects of the security architecture.\r\nThe goal of execution is to create security awareness, minimize risk and maximize the use of technology. Testing techniques for network security are predominantly manual, requiring an individual to initiate and conduct the test. Other tests are highly automated and require less human involvement. Regardless of the type of testing, staff that setup and conduct security testing should have significant security and networking knowledge, including significant expertise in the following areas: network security, firewalls, and intrusion detection systems, operating systems, programming and networking protocols.\r\nAfter running any tests, certain procedures should be followed, including documenting the test results, informing system owners of the results, and ensuring that vulnerabilities are patched or mitigated. This paper discusses about the different tests and their technical aspect on the security architecture.\r\n ','','Prepare,  Organize, Execute, Operating System,  Network Protocol ',' D.K. Pandey, Sanjay Pachauri ',' 523-536  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','52','2013-09-19 02:10:33','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(874,'Security Feature With Middleware Technology in Banking System ','Nowadays we are doing everything though the internet, like shopping, booking of e ticket for railways, airline etc, means if we are doing anything that involved an electronic transaction then almost certainly middleware will have played  a part in it.  Suppose we are checking the balance in our bank account, looked the availability of railway ticket, booked a movie ticket or bought a burger in a supermarket in the background messages would have moved between computer systems through the middleware. Some of the most important uses of middleware occur within the financial sector where it handles everything from money transfers to share transactions. Middleware provides services such as communication, identification, authentication, authorization, administration, and security. This paper about the efficiency and security because all business that is belongs to financial sector need information to be transferred between different systems and applications. ','','SSL (Secure Socket Layer), One way SSL, Two way SSL and SSL cycle ',' Ganesh Pandey, D.K. Pandey ',' 537-544  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','52','2013-09-19 02:11:14','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(875,'Computer-Based Application Prototype for Effective Teacher Evaluation in Higher Education ','Evaluation of teachers performance is a very important part of educational policies which ensure that teachers have adequate teaching skills and provide a high-quality education to the students. Teachers evaluation by student rating is considered as one of the important criteria to evaluate teachers quality attributes in order to improve teaching quality at higher education. Unfortunately, the manual process of teaching performance evaluation makes it impossible for academic institutions to make better decisions. Information technology has provided new opportunities for educational institutions to be more responsive to the information needs of administrators, employees, students and other stakeholders. This paper proposes a computerized teacher evaluation system for Sharda University (SU). The paper also described the problems encountered using a manual teacher evaluation system and benefits using computerized teacher evaluation system. ','','Computer-Based Application, Teacher Evaluation, Feedback System, Decision-Making. ',' Himanshu Sharma, Ashok Kumar Vasishtha ',' 545-552','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','52','2013-09-19 02:11:35','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(876,'Ecological change and happiness among villagers of eastern Uttar Pradesh ','The present research has examined ecological change and happiness among villagers in a sample of 240 subjects from a set of villages of eastern U.P. having different levels of ecological change (high & low). All the subjects were required to respond in their own way on two questions related to happy life. The responses were content analyzed. The results of content analysis of happy life projections revealed a quite similar pattern among villagers. Villagers were more concerned with personal and agriculture needs. Social, psychological and community needs were not frequently emphasized. The implication of the present findings has been discussed. ','','happiness, needs, villagers, ecological change. ',' A.B. Singh and P.S.N. Tiwari ',' 553-558  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','52','2013-09-19 02:11:50','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(877,'Microbiological Evaluation of Carbon and Nitrogen sources on the growth and  production of Antibiotics produced by Actinomycetes','The present study indicates that C and N sources  are significant for antibiotic production. Streptomyces isolate DC- 25 and DC-30 are specific to utilize C&N sources for their growth onto Various Carbon Source like Xylose, maltose, Lactose etc. utilized by Actinomycetes but cellulose was poorly utilized. The compounds which have generally amino group is easily utilized by streptomyces and to accelerate its growth for production of antibiotics by adding various amino acids and like glycine, Alanine, phenyl alanine, leucine, thyroxin.','','Streptomyces isolate DC-25 and DC-30, Carbon and     Nitrogen  Source.','Aishwarya Tandon, Laxmi Chand',' 559-562','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(878,'Studies on management of leaf blight disease of wheat incited by Alternaria alternata (Fries,keissler) by the actinomycetes  producing antifungal antibiotics','Out of various kind of Microorganism some are present in soil sample which infect the Wheat crop & cause the infection Alternaria alternata for which various antifungal antibiotics are used which form zone of  inhibition of 14.2 mm. due to effect of streptomyces albus (DC- 25 ) when it  introduced into infected soil','','-','Aishwarya Tandon','563-566','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(879,'An EOQ Model for Deteriorating Items with Stock Dependent Demand and Effect of Learning ','In present paper, authors developed an EOQ model for deteriorating items with stock dependent demand, in which the effects of learning and inflation factor is applied, so that model becomes more realistic and can be compared with several real life scenarios. In last, numerical example is generated.','','- ',' Ankit Kumar Goyal, Shyamli Gupta S. R. Singh ','567-574  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(880,'Optimal Policy for Detoraiting Inventory with Permisable Delay in Payment Under Inflation',' Most of the inventory models have developed that the demand rates taken as either constant or depended upon a single factor only, like, stock, time etc. But changing market conditions have rendered such a consideration quite unfruitful, since in real life situations, a demand cannot depend exclusively on a single parameter. A combination of two or more factors grants more authenticity to the formulation of the model.','','-','Sudhakar Singh, S. R. Singh','575-582','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(881,'Changes in the Dehydrogenase Levels of Fish Lebistes Reticulatus Under Cadmium Stress','The fish Lebistes reticulatus was exposed to sub-lethal concentration of 6x10-3 &#956;g/ l cadmium for 30th days (probit method). Autopsy of liver and kidney was done after 30th days and SDH, GDH, MDH and LDH levels were estimated by using the method of Nachlas et al. (1960), Srikanthan and Krishnamoorthy (1955), Lee and Lardy(1965) and Burns and Bergmeyer (1965) respectively. A decrease in SDH activity levels is due to accumulation of the succinate. . Decreased GDH activity in both tissues is an indication of decreased oxidation of glutamate. Reduction in GDH activity may also be due to low utilization of amino acids and low oxidation of amino acids. Marked drop in MDH levels in both tissues might be due to restricted supply of substrate, since it was observed that SDH activity decreased. Decrease in MDH may be due to diversion of aerobic metabolism at the level of malic acid, leading to the production of pyruvic acid. The elevation in the activity levels of LDH in both tissues indicates an increased production of pyruvate (or) greater breakdown of lactate. Increase in LDH activity might be due to high energy demand for survival in anaerobic conditions and to overcome cadmium stress.','','Cadmium, SDH, MDH, LDH and GDH.','Sabiha Khan','583-586','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(882,'A Financial Analysis of Top Pharmaceutical Companies in India','The pharmaceutical industry is an exciting industry worldwide with growth rate of 8% and a turnover of around US$ 650 billion. In terms of value, the major constituents are the United States (US) (48% share), European Union (EU) (28%share) and Japan with a share of 12%, and the rest of the world, including India, contributes around 20%. However, in terms of volume, the share of the rest of the world is approximately three times larger. An example in this regard, is India, which ranks 4th in terms of volume with a share of 8% in the world pharmaceutical market and only 13th in terms of value. The annual turnover of the Indian pharmaceutical industry is approximately, US$ 19 billion. The period of the 1995-2008 (i.e. the Post-TRIPS period) saw the strongest performance of the Indian pharmaceutical industry on several fronts. Not only did the industry improve its production performance seen in the previous decades, and that too by a significant margin, Currently the Indian Pharmaceutical industry is valued at approximately 90,000 Crores or US $ 20 billion, constituting 1.8% of the GDP and expected to grow more than 11% going forward. The country now ranks 3rd worldwide by volume of production and 14th by value thereby accounting for around 10% of world\'s production by volume and 1.5% by value. Globally, it ranks 4th in terms of generics production and 17thin terms of export value of bulk actives and dosage forms. Through to 2015 and 2020, India\'s pharmaceutical market will post local currency CAGRs of 14.6% and 13.5% respectively','','-','C. Lal, Rajiv Ranjan','587-596','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(883,'An Analysis of Dividend Policy in Top Pharmaceutical Companies in India','Dividend decision of the firms is considered as one of the important decisions that the firm would make. It must be depends upon what portion of earnings is to be retained by the firm and what portion is to be paid off. There is always an inverse relationship between these two larger intentions such as investment decision and financial decision making of the firm. Pharmaceutical industries shows an impressive growth figures over the recent years, the major objectives of this study is to determine the performance of dividends declaration policies of select pharmaceutical companies in India for the purpose of analysis five companies under took with past six years of their financial statements, datas are mostly belongs to the secondary data collected from selected companies official websites and official website of NSE India. The datas are analyzed using statistical tools such as Trend analysis, Mean, Standard deviation and hypothesis was tested using by ANOVA and its conclude that companies belong to the same industry adopted a different dividend policies among themselves','','-','C. Lal, Rajiv Ranjan','597-610','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(884,'Psychological Stress and Managing Strategies of the Parents of Mentally Retarded Children','Lot has been written about the stressors in the lives of parents of children with disabilities. Studies have been done to understand the types, causes and the effects of these stresses. Most often, only the negative aspects of this situation are highlighted. The work is primarily addressed towards understanding and measuring the negative attitude and adverse consequences of having a child with disabilities. This article examines the existing research done on this aspect. However, the article takes a step forward and focuses\r\non the cognitive processes as a result of experiencing a traumatic event. The authors move away from the negative outcomes and highlight the process of developing positive perceptions in these parents. The focus is on the process of coping that generates positive perceptions and the ways that these positive\r\nperceptions are used as an effective managing strategy.\r\n','','-','O. P. Chaudhary, Khusbhu Singh','611-618','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(885,'A Pshychological Case Study of Parents Caring for Children with Physical Disabilities in Bareilly District','This study aimed at identifying the needs of families of children with physical disabilities in Bareilly District. The sample of the study consisted of 100 parents of children with physical disabilities whose ages ranged from 6 to 16 years old. A survey of Needs of Caring Parents was developed to achieve the purposes of this study. Results revealed that the most important needs identified by participants related to the dimensions of information and the involvement in the caring process, while the least important family needs related to the dimensions of counseling support and family support. Results also revealed that there were significant differences in the perceived needs of caring parents according to mother\'s vocational status (i.e., working or not working) in most of the survey dimensions. Yet, there were no significant differences in the perceived needs of caring parents that can be attributed to child\'s gender and age; family income range; and parents relations with their extended family. Based on the study results, different recommendations were offered to service providers and to pre- and in-service special education teacher training. This research must be considered as a starting step in inviting institutions which provide care for the children with disabilities to focus on meeting the needs of caring parents.','','-','O. P. Chaudhary, Khusbhu Singh','619-628','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(886,'An Empirical Analysis of General Insurance Industry in India','In this paper attempt has been made to analyze the overall performance of General Insurance Industry of India between pre- and post economic reform era. To measure the current status, volume of competitions and challenges faced by the General Insurance Corporation of India and to measure the effectiveness of investment strategy of GIC over the period 1980 to 2009. Data were analyzed by using t- test and ANOVA. The study reveals that there is a tremendous growth in the performance of Indian General Insurance industry and NIC due to the policy of LPG. Insurance industry also improved a lot due to the emergence of Private sector and opening up for foreign players. Further there is also a huge change in the investment pattern of NIC. There is a increasing trend toward the investment in Stock market by NIC from 60% to 93% from 1980 to 2009 due to the effective regulation of SEBI and increasing transparency of stock market.','','Performance, Insurance, Investment Strategy etc','D. K. Pandey, Vivek Pathak','629-638','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(887,'A Study of Agricultural Insurance Schemes in India','Agriculture is an inherently risky business. It is subject to a number of random price, climatic, biological, and geological shocks that require coping strategies and financial management instruments to deal with the implications. Traditional risk management strategies and ex post government provided emergency relief has often not proven to be sufficiently effective and robust in preventing serious economic loss or permitting a speedy recovery. This paper focuses on production risk management, explaining key concepts, understanding why crop insurance markets have been slow to develop, and making recommendations about how to build sustainable markets in developing country contexts. Nonetheless, agricultural insurance is reemerging as a topic of interest, especially in light of the need to improve agricultural competitiveness in increasingly integrated commodity markets. The challenge is how to overcome obstacles and deliver efficient and sustainable agricultural insurance products.','','Performance, Insurance, Investment Strategy etc.','D. K. Pandey, Vivek Pathak','639-646','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(888,'Estimation of Iridium(III) using Amino Acid-Hexacyanoferrate(III) Redox Reaction','A new kinetic spectrophotometric method is developed for the determination of Ir(III) in aqueous alkaline medium. The method is based on the iridium(III) catalyzed oxidation of some amino acids by hexacyanoferrate (abbreviated as HCF) (III)) ions in aqueous alkaline medium. The kinetic studies on eight essential amino acids are carried out in aqueous alkaline medium. Out of eight amino acids four are glycine, alanine, valine and leucine (abbreviated as AA) while the other four are sulphur containing as cystine, cysteine, isoleucine and methionine (abbreviated as SAA). The comparison of the results shows that Beers limit is low for SAA than AA. For SAA value of Beer limit is 0.258 to 8.37 gcm-3 and for AA it is 0.99 - 39.98 g-\r\ncm-3. Again higher molar absorptivity & low sandells sensitivity value show that the use of SAA oxidation reaction is better than the use of AA for Ir(III) determination.The molar absorptivity & sandells sensitivity are found to be 0.367 x 103 to 1.425 X 103 l mol-1 cm-1 and 0.524 to 0.135 gcm-2 forAA and 2.31 x 103 to 5.57 X 103 l mol-1 cm-1 and 0.0834 to 0.0345 gcm-2 for SAA respectively. The coefficient of determination lies between 0.9588 to 0.9989 for AA & 0.9734 to 0.9997 for SAA. The effect of few interfering ions have been worked out for developing the calibration curves in terms of absorbance or initial rates or pseudo first order rate constant vs. Ir(III) plot, absorbance was noted at &#955;maxof 420 nm. Thus the present method is more simple and sensitive then the reported methods and especially useful in absence of the expected interfering ions.\r\nKeywords Determination, Oxidation, Hexacyanoferrate, Glycine, Alanine, Valine, Leucine, Cysteine, Methionine, cystine, Isoleucine, Ir(III)\r\n','','-','Shakunj, Savita Devi and Anjali Goel','647-652','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(889,'Prospects of Religious Tourism in Rajasthan','The State of Rajasthan is one of the most desired tourists destinations in India for both Domestic & International traffic. The colourful and exotic state of Rajasthan, the spell-bounding \'Land of the Kings\', epitomizes the core essence of India The culture of Rajasthan is very distinct and unique and the unique amalgamation of diverse topography, history and intriguing lifestyle makes Rajasthan the state of rich culture and heritage. The religious places of Rajasthan are known for exquisite architecture and rich carvings. The skills and craftsmanship of the workers are reflected profoundly when one explores these destinations. As tourists explore the religious places in Rajasthan, they reawaken their lost spirits and feel spiritually contented. Some of the places are on tourists map like Brahma temple in Pushkar, Dargah of Khwaja Moinuddin Chisti in Ajmer, Srinathji temple in Nathdwara, Dilwara temples in Sirohi, Eklingji in Rajsamand, Sri Mahavir ji, Ranakpur, Nakodaji, Khatu Shyamji and Govind Dev ji in Jaipur but there are places of high potential tourist destinations still unharnessed. It is, therefore, necessary to think out of the box and to develop unexplored religious destinations. Many untapped places offer unprecedented work of genius, have unmatched natural greenery with soundless calm beauty which mesmerised and adds to the immortal memories of the tourists. This paper focuses on the Prospects of Religious Tourism in Rajasthan concentrating on the three divisions of Rajasthan state-Ajmer, Bharatpur, and Jaipur','','-',' Deepika Sharma','653-662','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(890,'Cobalt(II), Nickel(II) and Copper(II) Complexes Of Bidentate Bipyrazoles','Complexes of Cobalt(II), Nickel(II) and Copper(II) with bidentate bipyrazoles, [M(L&#61485;L)Cl2], where L&#61485;L are methylene bis (1,1|&#61485;pyrazole); methylene bis (3,3|&#61485;pyrazole) and dimethylene bis (3,3|&#61485;pyrazole) are prepared and characterized by different physico&#61485;chemical methods. The four coordinate complexes have distorted tetrahedral or square co&#61485;planar structures. The bridging entity between the two donor groups apparently influences the ligand field strength and the ligands occupy a higher position than that of pyrazole in the spectrochemical series.\r\nIntroduction: The coordination properties of benzimidazole derivatives have been extensively investigated(1&#61485;4) because of their wide ranging pharmacological and biochemical relevance. The pharmacological activity is enhanced if benzimidazole is substituted at the 1&#61485; or 2&#61485;positions(5). Studies on binuclear ligands are however restricted chiefly to dihydro&#61485;2,2|&#61485;bi&#61485;2&#61485;imidazole and closely related derivatives(6&#61485;9) coordination of Cu(I) and Cu(II) by bis&#61485;benzimidazole ligand has been the subject of extensive investigation during the last decade. Copper coordination chemistry of bis&#61485;benzimidazole complexes has been extensively studied because of their potential as low molecular weight mimics for the active sites in many metalloproteins.(10,11)\r\n','','-','Meenal Saxena, Asha Chauhan, Muzaffrudin, Sumita Dawas','663-668','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(891,'Complexes of Guanidino-Benzimidazole 2-Carboxaldehyde','Some complexes of Guanidino benzimidazole&#61485;2&#61485;carboxaldehyde with copper(II) have been prepared and characterize by elemental analysis, magnetic moment measurement, ir spectral and electronic reflectance spectral studies.','','-','Meenal Saxena, Asha Chauhan, Shilpi Gupta, Sumita Dawas','669-673','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(892,' Mixed Ligand Complexes of Copper(II) With 1&#61485;Thiocarbamyl&#61485; 5&#61485;Methyl Pyrazole&#61485;3&#61485;Benzimidazole and Heterocyclic Amines','The coordination behaviour of a new pyrazole&#61485;derived NNS&#61485;tridentate, 1&#61485;thiocarbamyl&#61485;5&#61485;methyl&#61485;pyrazole&#61485;3&#61485;benzimidazole (abbreviated as (NNSH) has been studied by complexation with copper(II) mixed ligand complexes of general composition Cu(NNS)B.nH2O [B=Py/(&#945;&#61485;, &#61538;&#61485; and &#61550;&#61485;) pico/bipy/o&#61485;phen; n=1,2,3,4] have been isolated and characterized by various physico&#61485;chemical techniques; the complexes have usual distorted octahedral configuration as revealed from magnetic and electronic spectral data. The species [Cu(NNS)Cl]2H2O is given a bridged dimeric structure occurring through thiocarbamyl group of the ligand. The IR data suggest a monoprotic (NNSH&#61485; tridentate behaviour of the primary ligand molecule in its thiol form) in all the complex species.','','675-682','Meenal Saxena, Asha Chauhan,Chandrawati and Shilpi Gupta',' 675-682','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(893,' Production Inventory Model with Inflation Induced Demand  and Shortages Over a Finite Planning Horizon ','In this paper we have developed a production inventory model for decaying item with inflation induced demand and finite production rate. We have considered the rate of production to depend upon the demand in the market. Holding cost is taken as variable. The effect of inflation has been taken into account. We have discussed two cases: first is when shortages are not allowed and second is shortages are allowed with complete backlogging. To demonstrate the fact time value of money, we have also considered time value assumption in calculating the costs of proposed model. Finally, to illustrate the model, we have given a numerical example and observations of it also provided in the end of this study. This way, the whole research caters to put forward some aspects of a model with some real world considerations and market deliberations.','','- ',' V K Sharma, Sadhana Singh ','683-692  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(894,'Optimal Replenishment Cycle for Two-Warehouse Inventory Problem Under Time Value of Money, Varying Rate of Deterioration and Partial Backordering ','In this paper a two-warehouse inventory system for deteriorating items has been developed with shortages.  The rate of deterioration in both warehouses is different and follows a two-parameter Weibull distribution. Further, this study takes into account of inflation and applies the discounted cash flow approach for problem analysis. In this study, we developed two types of models which are; Model-1, in which the demand rate is linearly increasing with time and shortages are partially backlogged with constant backlogging rate. Model-2, in which the demand rate is exponentially increasing with time and shortages are partially backlogged with exponential backlogging rate.','','- ',' V K Sharma, Sadhana Singh ','693-708  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(895,' Structure Properties of PBSE Thin Films From Chemical Bath Technique','Polycrystalline semiconductor nano particles are emerging as an important materials for electric and optoelectronics devices. PbSe is an interesting narrow band gap IV-VI compound semiconductors which is used in photo detectors and photo resistors. Polycrystalline semiconductor thin film of lead selenide (PbSe) deposited on glass substrate by chemical bath deposition technique by  Eltek made Fluxstirrer MS 203. The structural properties of the film characterized by  X-ray diffraction. The improvement of crystallinity of PbSe films, which is deposited at different temperature was studied using X-ray diffraction (XRD) methods. The morphology and composition of the films were characterized by scanning electron microscopy (SEM) and energy disperse analysis by X-ray, respectively','','Structural properties, X-ray diffraction, Scanning electron microscopy,  Chemical bath deposition','Pramod Kumar, Anita Rani and R. K. Sharma',' 709-714','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(896,' Selection of Best Electrode for Minimum Surface Roughness of Tungsten Carbide Machining with EDM by Two Different Electrodes and Developing Mathematical Power Models','Material Removal Rate, Electrode Wear and Surface Roughness are the three main Characteristic of machining hard material by Electrical Discharge Machining. The processing parameters have the influence on quality characteristics and to achieve the minimum surface roughness of Tungsten carbide.  In the present paper, the orthogonal array technique is used to formulate Design of experiment and Numbers of experiments are conducted and results were analyzed for minimum surface roughness. The effect of processing parameters examine for obtaining minimum surface roughness of Tungsten carbide while machining with Copper (Cu) and Copper-Tungsten (Cuw) electrodes. Process parameters selected are Voltage, Current, Pulse on time and Pulse off time. To quick estimate the surface roughness, power regression models are developed for both the electrodes. From the results it is concluded that the copper-tungsten electrode gives the minimum surface roughness as compare to copper electrode with same process parameters. The copper-tungsten electrode shows that it have lesser impact on surface roughness even at the higher current hence copper- Tungsten electrode is best and more suitable.','','Electrical Discharge Machining, Surface Roughness, Electrode','T. C. Bhagat and H. S. Payal','715-724','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(897,' Effect of Lost Sales on an Integrated Inventory Model for Decaying Items with Stock Dependent Demand Under Inflation  ','In this paper an inventory model for deteriorating items with stock dependent demand has been developed. Deterioration rate is taken as time dependent. Shortages at retailers part have been discussed. The environment of whole study has been taken as inflationary. A numerical example along with sensitivity analysis is given to explore the model numerically. Some observations are presented on the basis of sensitivity analysis. ','','-  ','  V K Sharma, Sadhana Singh  ',' 01-14','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','54','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(898,' Analysis of Different Rates of Reserve Bank of India, With Stock Market Indices (A COMPARISION WITH STOCK MARKET MOVEMENT FROM 2001 to 2012)',' The role of RBI in the fiancial market is very important to monitor different polocies.The RBI Controls the money market operetion in India,First the primary intrest of the RBI in fianacial market  as Because of its critically in the transmission of monetary policy. Second finacial balancing has emerged as one of the important concern for the RBI, resulting in increased attention to financial market development.RBI  decides different rates like CRR, SLR, Bank rate, Repo rate, Reverse repo rate, to control Indian financial market,and to develop indian economy.these rates are very important for the investors for the purpose of investment.these rates are also important to control inflation','','CRR, SLR, Bank Rate, Repo Rate, Reverse Repo Rate, Sensex',' Rupesh Roshan Singh ,Ummed Singh','15-20','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','54','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(899,'An Economic Production Quantity Model with Stock and Time Dependent Demand with Price and Quantity Incentives','In the present paper a production inventory model for non-instantaneous deteriorating items has been formulated. Deterioration has been taken to be  constant. Production rate is variable and depends on demand which is time dependent linearly increasing and stock dependent. Discount on selling price is given when demand becomes only time dependent. During deterioration quantity discount is given to boost up the demand and to reduce the loss due to deterioration. The model determines optimal discount to be given on unit selling price when demand becomes only time dependent so as to maximize the total profit. Numerical example with sensitivity analysis is presented to illustrate the model.','','Variable production rate and demand rate, non-instantaneous deterioration, price and quantity incentives.','Bindu Vaish, Deepshikha Agarwal','21-34','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','54','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(900,'Application of Fuzzy c- means clustering for Facility location and   Transportation problems','This paper aims to built up a location selection model on basis of generalized transportation cost by considering of effect of the quantity and  position  of depots on transportation cost with economical scale theory and to solve the problem by using fuzzy C-means clustering .This algorithm is feasible and effective , it emphasizes to decrease the cost and  time of gaining optimized solution and consumption of calculating resources on the premise the solution is feasible and being moderately optimized.','','Location selection model, Transportation cost, Fuzzy C-means clustering','Rakesh Kumar and Sandipan Gupta','35-42  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','54','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(901,'Prominences Eruptions and their relation to the other solar activity','Prominence Eruptions are one of the earliest known forms of mass ejections from the sun.  In this article we have described the basic facts for understanding type (1) active (2) Eruptive (3) Sunspot (4) tornado (5) quiescent Prominences and their relation to other solar activity. We have shown the association of CMEs with the type of active and eruptive Prominences. The prominence can provide useful information about solar sources. It is now known that Prominence eruptions is the near surface activity most frequently associated with CMEs. In our study almost all the events are associated with CMEs and some related with core and other activity','','-','Pooja Gupta, Udit Narain , Ruby Yadav','43-52','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','54','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(902,'Production lot-sizing for a Volume flexible system with Stock Dependent Demand and Limited Storage Capacity ','In this paper, we studied a production model for a volume flexible system where demand is taken as stock dependent for a single item. Time horizon taken as infinite and storage capacity taken as limited. In this model at the start of each production cycle, the production process is always in an in-control state and perfect items are produced then production process shifts from the in-control state to an out-control state. During out-control state imperfect quality items are produced and these are reworked at a cost immediately. Finally numerical experiment and sensitivity analysis are provided to illustrate the system ','','- ',' Abhinav Goel, R K Pandey ','215-227  ','NO','','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','48','2013-09-17 12:43:56','E',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(903,'Effect of Trade Credits on an Inventory Model with Stock Dependent Demand and Deterioration ','- ','','- ',' Pankaj Kaushal, D. Singh ',' 228-237','NO','','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','48','2013-09-17 12:44:52','E',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(904,'Heat Characterstic of Mhd Natural Convective Flow Past Through Vertical Flat Plate in Porous Media Under Radtition Effect','The present paper deals with the study of the vorticity of hydromagnetic free convection flow of an incompressible viscous electrically conducting fluid past an infinite vertical porous plate. The vorticity of the flow has been found for different values of magnetic parameter M and Grashof number . Some important conclusions have been drawn on the effect of magnetic parameter M and Grashof number   over the vorticity of the flow.\r\nNomenclature:  = Free stream;  = Velocity components in  - and  direction respectively;  = Grashof number;  = Prandtl number; M = Magnetic Parameter;  = Magnetic induction; g = Acceleration due to gravity;  = Thermal diffusivity \r\nGreek symbols:  = Density;  = coefficient of volume expansion;  = Kinematic viscosity:  = Electric conducting;  = Suction parameter;  = Non-conducting amplitude parameter;  = Vorticity \r\n','','-','S.K.Shakya, S.Kapoor and Shriprakash','185-194','NO','','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','40','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(905,'Study of Blood Flow Through Modelled Vascular Stenosis','The effect of an axially symmetric mild stenosis on the steady flow of blood, when blood is represented by Newtonian model have been studied. Theoretical results for the velocity profile, pressure gradient, wall shearing stress and separation phenomena are obtained by solving the momentum integral equation. The results obtained are discussed graphically for mild stenosis for Reynolds number (Re) of Re = 10-100 and the significance of the analysis are pointed out by comparing the results with similar studies. Our results are in good agreement with published experimental and theoretical results','','-','S.R. Verma','195-206','NO','','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','40','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(906,'Effect of Magnetic Field on Unsteady Blood Flow Through a Narrow Tube ','In this paper a mathematical model has been developed for studying blood flow through a narrow tube in the presence of magnetic field. The laminar, incompressible, fully developed two layered Newtonian flow of blood in narrow tube is studied under the action of transverse magnetic field. The analytical results obtained in the proposed model for flow rate and apparent viscosity have been evaluated numerically for various values of the parameter available from published works. The results are discussed graphically for different Hartman number and Womersely frequency parameter. Effect of peripheral layer thickness on flow rate and apparent viscosity is also discussed. ','','Unsteady flow, magnetic field, peripheral layer, apparent viscosity, Hartmann number. ',' S.R. Verma and Anuj Srivastava ','207-218','NO','','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','40','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(907,'Effect  of Thermal Diffusion on MHD Free Convective Flow of Oldroyd Fluid Through a Porous Medium Bounded by an Oscillating Porous Plate in Slip Flow Regime With Heat Source/Sink and Radiation','An analysis of velocity, temperature, concentration and skin friction of a Oldroyd fluid of small electrical conductivity in a porous medium near an oscillating infinite porous flat plate in slip flow regime under influence of a transverse magnetic field of uniform strength with radiation and thermal diffusion is carried out. In this study velocity of fluid increases with the increase in Gm (Modified Grashof number), K (Porosity parameter) and A (Thermal diffusion parameter), but it decreases with the increase in M (Hartmann number).','','Porous medium, Oldroyd fluid, Hydromagnetic Flow, Radiation, Oscillating Porous Plates, Thermal Diffusion, Heat Source/Sink.','Pavan Sharma, C. B. Gupta and N. K. Varshney','219-228','NO','','International Journal of Stability and Fluid Mechanics','29','40','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',6,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(908,' An Inventory Model for Decaying Items Considering Time Quadratic Demand Rate under Trade Credits with Partially Backlogging','In this paper we develop an inventory model for decaying items considering time quadratic demand rate under the condition of permissible delay in payment with partially backlogging. Effect of inflation is also taken in consideration. The primary objective is to minimize the cost and to determine the optimal inventory policy. We use some numerical examples and sensitivity analysis is also carried.','','-','V K Sharma, Sadhna Singh','485-497','NO','','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','23','35','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(909,' Production Lot Size Model with Variable Demand Rate and Rework of Imperfect Production','In this paper, inventory models for a single-stage production process are developed where defective items are produced in regular production process with a proportion of defectives as scrap. Defective items are reworked after the regular production.. Reworked items are good items and serviceable. Production rate is constant and demand is time dependent. This paper includes two models (a) Model without shortages (b) Model with shortages and complete backlogging. Cost minimization technique is used to solve the models. Numerical examples are presented to illustrate the models. special cases of the models are also discussed.','','Time dependent demand, Perfect inventory, Imperfect inventory Rework Process',' Bindu Vaish, Deepshikha Agarwal','53-73','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','54','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(910,' Optimized Layout for machines by applying Genetic Algorithm ','Developing a machine layout is an important step in designing manufacturing facilities due to the impact of the layout to material handling cost and time, and consequently, affects the overall productivity of the shop floor. Poor layout would result in having more parts spending longer time moving from one machine to another, and thus results in increasing material handling costs.  In contrast to the block layout, the objective of the machine layout problem is to find the appropriate placement of machines in a cell. This paper provides descriptions to solve the layout problem and describes a novel method based on genetic algorithms (GA) to solve the machine layout problem. The GA-based method developed to solve this uses the objective of minimizing the movements of parts being processed in the cell.  ','','machine layout, genetic algorithms, cellular manufacturing. ',' Anuj Kumar Jhankal, Vikas Sangwan and Subhash Chand Gupta ',' 238-242','NO','','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','32','48','2013-09-17 12:45:20','E',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(911,'Analysis of Energy Consumption in Mobile Ad-Hoc Routing Protocols through  Route Recovery and Maintenance Mechanisms','Mobile Ad-hoc network transfers the information from one hope to another one. Route selection and route recovery mechanism plays an important roll with conservation of energy. Due to the mobility reasons the establish path breaks frequently. It is requires to recover the path and transmits the remaining data. This paper analyses the comparison of already exist ad-hoc routing protocols like AODV, DSR and DSDV which are used a particular mechanism of route recovery and maintenance. Moreover, mobile nodes are often power constrained so energy conservation is also an important issue on evaluating protocols. Simulation studies have been done for energy conservation based on different route recovery and maintenance models. These protocols are compared under four different data insertion rate (CBR) on the network. In this paper Random Waypoint mobility model is used to generate various scenarios by using NS-2.','','Energy consumption, Route Discovery and Maintenance, Mobile ad hoc networks, Constant Bit Rate','Madan Mohan Agarwal and Anuj Kumar Jhankal','121-130','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','34','50','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(912,'  Flexible Manufacturing Inventory Model with Permissible Delay in Payments and Cash Discounts under the Effects of Time Value of Money and Inflation','In this paper an attempt is made to formulate the mathematical model for a production inventory system for deteriorating items with stock-dependent demand under the effect of inflation and time value of money. The supplier offers not only an acceptable delay but also a cash discount to the retailer. A deterministic model is developed to optimize the per unit time profit for the retailer. Genetic algorithm (GA) is used to maximize the profit function for an optimal order cycle and order receipt period. The theoretical results are illustrated using a numerical example and sensitivity analyses on some parameters.','','Inflation, Cash Discount, Time Value of Money, Stock Dependent Demand','Abhinav Goel, R. K. Pandey','131-144','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','34','50','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(913,'Determination of Expected Time to Recruitment- A Stochastic Approach','In any organization it usually happens that whenever the policy decisions regarding pay perquisites, promotion and targets of work or sales to be achieved are received then there will be exit of personnel, which in other words called the attrition. Attrition is one of the serious problem faced by industrial, marketing and others types of organizations. The concepts of attrition are very much pronounced in the area of Human resource management. With a view of curtail expenditure or recruitments of organizations start recruitment only on reaching a particular level of manpower loss which is the threshold. If the depletion of manpower on successive occasions is below threshold then the normal work routine can be carried out. The attrition on employees takes place at decision making epochs. Persons leave the organizations due to unsatisfactory packages or unsatisfactory work targets or both. This leads of the depletion of manpower. The magnitude of manpower depletion at each decision, manpower exceeds the so called threshold level, the recruitment of persons becomes imperative. In this paper the expected time to recruitment due to the depletion of manpower is derived using Shock model approach. Numerical examples are also provided','','Attrition, Human Resource Management, Decision Making Epochs, Threshold Level and Shock Model Approach','R. Arulpavai, R. Elangovan','247-254  ','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','34','51','2013-09-19 03:08:04','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(914,'A Study of Data Mining as Knowledge Discovery in Databases','The data mining as \"the process of discovering meaningful new correlation, patterns & trends by shifting through large amount of data stored in repositories, using pattern recognition technologies as well as statistical & mathematical techniques\". In this we focus our attention on data mining. We explain concept & History of data mining, architecture of data mining, function of data mining & types of data mining.','','Data, Database, knowledge discovery, data ware house, data mining.','Shailendra Sahni, UpendraNath Tripathi, Vinodini Katiyar, Subhash Kumar Sharma',' 255-258','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','34','51','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(915,' FDI in Indian Retail Market: The Proxy Way of Using Game Theory by Multinational Companies in India Market','From ancient time to present 21st century, India is always an attraction for other world countries for trade and business. These trades and business have made India many times rich and prosperous country in world. But in eighteen century a company came to India for trade but slowly takes full advantage of that time political condition and become the master of this nation. The declined of trade and the drainage of wealth to Europe made this prosperous country to stand in line of world poorer country in world. After independence the mixed economy of country and hard working Indian people along with industrialists again made India economy to stand in world trade.\r\nToday, India provides a large market for trade and business for the multinational companies (MNCs). Every country of world is egger to make the trade relation with India. The developed countries found a good market within India for their finished products and services. India had large resources for exploitation and purchasing power of India people made India in better position to compete the MNCs. In this paper, we study how these MNCs are using the game theory in strategy to capture the Indian market from Indian companies with analyzing its impact on India companies, market and business. The prime focus of this research paper on FDI for retail sector as one of strategy of game theory used by MNCs against in direct competition and making collaboration with Indian industries. And tried to find optional strategy should the Indian nation evolve to safe guard its companies and people healthy interest against those MNCs coming through FDI in Indian market.\r\n','','MNC, game theory, market, information,','Himanshu Pandey, Upendra Nath Tripathi, Avinash Singh, Ashutosh Pandey',' 75-82','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','54','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(916,' In Vitro Screening of Barnyard Millet for Lead Tolerance','Barnyard millet (Echinochloa crus-galli) is also known as Panicum crus-galli (L.). Its habitat include ditches,roadsides and waste places in S. Europe  and wet places and rich soils in India (Orrisa, Karnataka, Tamil Nadu, Uttarakhand) and also in the desert region (Rajasthan). Lead is among those heavy metals which have no known biological function; yet it is absorbed and accumulated in different plant tissues with the highest amount in the root tissues. In the present study characterize In vitro screening of barnyard millet for lead tolerance and studies of different physiological parameters in barnyard millet grown in different lead concentrations were done for 30 days. The results depicted growth upto 1mM Pb concentration and a gradual decline in germination, root length, shoot length,plant height, number of leaves, total dry matter, leaf area index, chlorophyll content and increase in membrane injury index with the increasing concentration of lead for Barnyard millet.','','Phytoremediation, Echinochloa crus-galli, lead','Deepti Malhotra, Ashutosh Dubey, Preeti Juyal, Hem Pant, Shahana Jabi','83-90','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','54','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(917,'A Study of Distributed Data Mining With Refers to Architecture, Classification, Association & Cluster','Distributed data mining (DDM) techniques have becomes necessary for large & multi scenario datasets requiring resources. Which are heterogeneous & distributed in nature. In this paper we focus our attention on distributed data mining. We explain distributed data mining (DDM), distributed data methods & distributed data mining algorithm & that deals with the above issue in order to discover knowledge from distributed data in an effective & efficient way.','',' Data, Database, Data mining, distributed databases.','Shailendra Sahni, UpendraNath Tripathi, Vinodini Katiyar, Subhash KumarSharma','91-96','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','54','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(918,' Instigating Expected Transmission Count Metric (ETX) for Locating High-Throughput Paths on Multi-Hop Wireless Networks','Multi-hop wireless mesh networks are in current trend forhassle free and efficient internet access. Many current wireless networking standards have the multi-rate capability. These include the 802.11b , 802.11a , 802.11g draft, and Hiper- LAN2 standards. A noblemethod of finding high-throughput paths on multi-hop wireless networks using expected transmission count metric (ETX) is presented. ETX will minimize the expected total number of packet transmissions (including retransmissions) required to successfully deliver a packet to the ultimate destination. The ETX metric is useful in many ways. It reducesthe effects of link loss ratios and presents asymmetry in the loss ratios between the two directions of each link. It is also capable to create interference among the successive links of a path. Route selection using ETX accounts for link loss ratios, the asymmetry of the loss ratios in the two directions of each link, and the reduction of throughput due to interference among the successive hops of a route. This paper describes the design and implementation of ETX. The work shows that  ETX improve the performance up to a considerable standard. The study also suggests that ETX will become more useful as networks grow larger and paths become longer.','','-','Mamta Sachdeva, Sohan Garg',' 259-270','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','34','51','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(919,'An Inventory Model with Inflation Induced Demand Rate under Volume Flexibility Environment','The paper deals with an economic manufacturing quantity (EMQ) model for Inflation induced demand pattern. We discussed the effect of two storage facility model under volume flexibility manufacturing system. Unit production cost is taken to be dependent on several factors. Capacity of own warehouse is fixed. Procedures are developed for determining the optimal cycle time for all cost structures. A numerical assessment is provided to illustrate the model with sensitivity of some parameters.','','Inflationary environment, Volume elasticity, Planning horizon, Two warehouse','S.R. Singh , Urvashi','271-282','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','34','51','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(920,' A two- warehouse model with imperfect production process under FIFO dispatching policy','This article puts emphasis on two warehouse production model for deteriorating items with time dependent demand. All the manufacturing units plan to produce perfect quality items. Owing to elongated process, different problems pertaining to the mechanism, labor prospective or service from other resources may occur. As a result, the method shifts from in-control state to out-of-control state that affects the production of imperfect quality items. The manufactured batch can be monitored at a cost and then segregated defective items can be sold at a reduced selling price. In this paper, we determine the maximum total profit and the corresponding optimum decision variables. Using FIFO (first in first out) dispatching policy, the formulated problem is a constrained nonlinear programming and Genetic Algorithm (GA) is implemented to solve it efficiently. The model is illustrated by means of a numerical example and outcome is analyzed about the impact of various parameters.','','Two-warehouse; Imperfect production process; Variable production rate','Himani Dem, S.R. Singh',' 283-296','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','34','51','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(921,' Effect of Probabilistic Backorder on an Inventory System with Selling Price Demand Under Volume Flexible Strategy ','In this paper, an inventory system for decaying items with selling price demand in flexible environment has been discussed. Holding cost is linear increasing function of time. Shortages are allowed with partial backorder and backorder rate is taken as random variable with beta distribution of first kind. Finally, numerical example is presented to demonstrate the developed model. Sensitivity analysis of the optimal solution with respect to major parameters is carried out. ','','Volume flexible manufacturing system, variable holding cost, probabilistic backorder ',' Surbhi Singhal, S.R. Singh ','297-304  ','YES','16 ITMSC.52.pdf','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','34','51','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(922,' An approach of building detection using spectral and spatial enhancement techniques from high resolution satellite images','The availability of high-resolution remote sensing commercial satellites (e. g. IKONOS and QuickBird) images, the information extraction becomes much easier and accurate than ever before. These information have applications in various fields, like communication, agricultural, disaster management, flood monitoring, city planning etc. Due to this reason, the extraction of buildings from high resolution satellite images is a major concern for the modern researchers.\r\nIn this paper, we propose an approach for the extraction of building edges by using different spectral mathematical expression and enhancement techniques with the help of ENVI 4.5 and ERDAS IMAGINE software .The algorithm is examined on 1meter IKONOS satellite data of Moradabad city of Uttar Pradesh, India. In present days both spatial and spectral domain properties are used to extract the building features but due to heterogeneity present in the high resolution images, it is not possible to extract the features accurately using only one of them. So in present paper, we try to use the combination of both the techniques which shows better results.\r\n','','Spectral and spatial enhancement technique, high resolution images, fused image, building edge.','Deepak Anand Vishnoi, Sanjay Padaliya and P. K. Garg','725-732','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(924,' Determination of Protein  Polyelectrolyte Interaction','Proteins mainly function when they are folded in their native conformation. The therapeutic effect of protein is affected by a change in the structure in the protein which could have an adverse immune response to drugs. Certain additives/excipients are added to protein solution in order to control protein aggregation, caused because of incorrect folding of proteins. Here we study the electrostatic interactions formed between BSA and PSS. Investigation of these protein-polyelectrolyte complexes is important not only for protein formulation and purification to prevent aggregation, but also in the design of many other applications such as drug delivery, and enzyme immobilization. Turbidimetry measurements were used to monitor the pH values at which the soluble protein polyelectrolyte complexes start to form. The static light scattering experiments were used to determine the weight average molecular weight of the BSA-PSS complexes. As the salt concentration increases the complexation pH decreases because the salt weakens the attractive electrostatic interactions.','','-',' ','97-102','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','54','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(925,' Compensation of Harmonic Distortion at the point of common coupling (PCC) for Single-Phase Voltage Controlled Grid Connected Solar PV System','Future ancillary services provided by photovoltaic (PV) systems could facilitate their penetration in power systems. Also low power PV systems can be designed to improve the power quality. This paper presents a single-phase photovoltaic system that provides grid voltage support and compensation of harmonic distortion at the point of common coupling (PCC) thanks to a repetitive controller. The power provided by the PV panels is controlled by a Maximum Power Point Tracking (MPPT) algorithm based on the incremental conductance method specifically modified to control the phase of the PV inverter voltage. Simulation and experimental results validate the presented solution.','','single-phase PV inverter, shunt controller, MPPT algorithm.',' Krishan Kumar Pahuja, D. K. P. Singh','103-112','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','54','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(926,' Separation and Sensing of Chlorpyrifos in Water Through Molecularly Imprinted Polymers Membranes','Stability of antibodies, peptides, and enzymes as molecular recognition elements in chemical and biological sensors has been facing threat due to their lack of stability and signal transduction mechanisms limits. Molecularly imprinted polymers (MIPs) with recent advancements have created synthetic materials that can mimic the function of chemical and biological receptors but with less stability constraints. These polymers can provide high sensitivity and selectivity while maintaining excellent thermal and mechanical stability. In the present study molecularly imprinted membrane has been fabricated for the specific recognition of pesticide Chlorpyrifos which is being used widely to control insects in crop management system. The composite membranes have been prepared by using methacrylic acid (MAA) as functional monomer, selected by electrostatic interactions based computational simulation and ethylene glycol dimethacrylate (EGDMA) as cross linker. The garbing of chloripyrifos MIP on membrane matrix was confirmed by the SPE, UV-VIS spectrophotometer, FTIR and Scanning Electron Microscopy (SEM). The sensing of chloripyrifos was done using a specially designed electrochemical sensing device which could detect the herbicides up to a very sensible limit.','','sensor, molecularly imprinted polymer (MIP), SPE, electrochemical sensing device','H.V. Pant, Prashant Singh, K.P. Singh and S.Kumar','113-124','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','54','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(927,' Use of mathematical morphological filtering and band operators to highlight building features from IKONOS satellite image','In this paper, we have proposed an approach to highlight buildings features from very high resolution (VHR) multispectral images using band based segmentation and mathematical operators. Building inventories and their attributes, such as structure type, shape  size (building footprint), year built, and number of stories are considered to be essential to make disaster management plans from natural and man-made hazards, municipality for house tax calculations, urban planning and risk modeling.  In first stage of present work, different band combinations to segment the images are used and then different spatial enhancement techniques are used to highlight the buildings. In next stage, the mathematical operators are used to improve the quality of overall appearance of features in the images. The proposed approach is tested on 1m resolution IKONOS satellite image of Moradabad city in Uttar Pradesh, India.','','Image segmentation, buildings, high resolution images, mathematical morphology, band operators.','Deepak Anand Vishnoi, Sanjay Padaliya  and P. K. Garg','125-130','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','54','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(928,' Determination of Pesticide Residues in Tomato (Lycopersicon esculentum Mill.) Fruit at Supervised Trial','A study was conducted to obtain a systematic monitoring data on the contamination levels of selected organochlorine and organophosphorous pesticide residues in different varieties of Tomato plant. The analysis was carried out with GC-MS/MS multiresidue analytical technique. The concentration of organochlorine pesticides (OCPs) was ranged between 0.0079-0.042 mg/kg with an average of 0.0236  0.0156 mg/kg (wet weight). The selected vegetable had residue levels, much below the recommended maximum 