ent. By the end of March 2002, there were 3.4 million small industry units, accounting for more than 40% of the gross value of output inthe manufacturing sector, about 35% of the total exports and provided employment to over 19.2 million persons, which is second only to agriculture (Planning Commission, 2002). This much contribution has emerged despite the sector being exposed to intensifying competition during the decade since 1991. Small scale industry in India has been confronted with growing competitive environment since 1991 due to (1) liberalisation of investment regimes in the 1990s, favouring foreign direct investment (FDI) at the international level, particularly in socialistic and developing countries.','','Small Scale Industry, FDI, Investment',' Sudhir Kumar Sharma',' 363-369','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','31','57','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(973,' Exploration of entrepreneurship potential in rural youth','              Entrepreneurship is a concept used to describe the phenomenon of an individual who wishes to develop an idea, establish it, mobilise it and establish a new business venture (Volery, 2004). The present paper is an attempt to give a birds eye view about the entrepreneurship as an alternative occupation options for the rural youth.Young people with such perspective and with the help of rightly channelized efforts would be userin an era of rural entrepreneurship. Rural entrepreneurship is, in essence, that entrepreneurship which ensures value adding to rural resources in rural area engaging largely rural human resource.The paper deals with the brief description of entrepreneurship, significance, principles and types, dynamic perspective and future as well as obstacles in rural entrepreneurship. The implication of the rural entrepreneurship in demand as a career, with training and sustaining supporthas also been discussed.','','Entrepreneurship, Entrepreneurship potential, rural youth',' Kamana Tripathi ',' 47-54','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','31','45','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(974,' Information and Communication Technology in Teacher Education','      Teaching is becoming one of the most challenging professions in our society where knowledge is expanding rapidly and much of it is available to students as well as teachers at the same time. As new concepts of learning have evolved, teachers are expected to facilitate learning and make it meaningful to individual learners rather than just to provide knowledge and skills. Recent developments of innovative technologies have provided new possibilities to teaching profession but at the same time have placed more demands on teachers to learn how to use these technologies in their teaching. Information and Communication Technology is an important instrument, which can transfer the present isolated, teacher-centered, book- centered learning environment into a rich student- centered environment. This new learning environment developed by the ICT is called Interactive Learning Environment. ICT is a new paradigm of the teaching- learning process; we must accept the new technology and use ICT as a tool of teaching- learning process. ICT aims at transferring the old traditional paradigm of learning to the new paradigm of learning.  ','','Information and Communication Technology, Interactive Learning Environment, teaching- learning process',' Surinder Singh Thakur ',' 55-62','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','31','45','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(975,' Cast Factor in Arundhati Roys the God of Small Things','        Arundhati Roy has portrayed the socio-political realism of democratic India, where still one community is becoming the victim of the brutality of the majority and the flatterers of 