e a useful promotional technique for a new product introduced with a new brand name. Although consumers evaluations and perceptions of risk were most favorable in the condition in which the brand extension was introduced without bundling, there may be situations in which the manufacturer chooses not to use a brand extension. ','','Limitations, Pramotional Offers, Indian FMCG ',' Puneet Vishnu',' 143-152','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','31','45','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(989,' Bal Gangadhar Tilak: Born Indian Freedom Movement','Bal Gangadhar Tilak was a social reformer and freedom fighter. He was one of the prime architects of modern India and strongest advocates of Swaraj (Self Rule). He was universally recognized as the \"Father of Indian Movement\". Tilak was a brilliant politician as well as a profound scholar who believed that independence is the foremost necessity for the well being of a nation.','','PIL, Self rule, Extremism',' Naveen Kumar Verma',' 153-160','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','31','45','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(990,' CRM-An Effective Way Tool Emerging Consumers in Global Era','This paper will address issues of customer retention through managerial excellence. In todays tough competitive environment, advanced technology is an essential requirement for success. It is only the power of technology that can propel a company ahead of its competitors. Companies are therefore placing greater emphasis upon the acquisition and utilization of technology.\r\nTo provide the much needed technology to support an organization and also in the globalize era UDCs are importing technology and skills from Developed countries. But it is essential to retain our customer strongly because of many competitors are playing major role in searching of new customers so we should retain our customer first and search the new customer after that. In this context CRM is an important technology. This paper highlights the meaning of CRM, implications of CRM and about the useful ingredients of CRM, which required for organizational effectiveness and make a rich customer stake to be successful in the modern world, especially if organizations in India wish to be at par with organizations in the other parts of the developed world.\r\n','','CRM Technology, Customer Retention,  UDC',' Sudhir Kumar Sharma',' 161-168','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','31','45','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(991,' A Re-Appraisal of Kamala Das\'s Poetry ','Kamala Dass Poetry shows that though she claims to be a liberated woman yet she has not freed herself fully from the clutches a society that manoeuvres to silence a woman. Her lines well express this ambivalence. At times a strange cowardice stalks me, makes me want to deny my past, deny my nature and to tell my relatives and friends that I wrote lies and that I need the money the brave books provided me with. I feel tempted to tell them that I have been conventional like them and that I projected a false image to make my books sell. But this is aging without grace. It is like dying the hair and wearing padded brassieres. ','','Tradition Bound Society; Spiritual Development; Confessional Art ; Feminine Modesty ','Lakhvinder Kaur , Ashok Kumar Kundu ','353-358  ','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(992,' Theme of Protest in Mistero Buffo','  Mistero Buffo is a Re-Creation of the Christian, Biblical and medieval history from an alternative, unofficial and unorthodox point of view -that of the medieval peasants in general and the common man in particular, in its medium being that of a pagan and secular depiction of the religious Gospel and its sacred figures. It can also be seen as an attempt to expose the corruption and exploitive nature of the church and the political implications of its power. By stressing on the popular, humorist and impertinent aspects of the medieval mystery plays and religious cycles, Fo voices the angst-ridden needs of the marginalized classes using the language of the Italian peasant, whom he sees as a symbolic representative of peasants in every epoch, all over the world.','','Religious Cycles; Christianity; social  historical roots; Revival Marxism',' Monalisa Pradhan , Ashok Kumar Kundu',' 359-368','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL);
INSERT INTO `paper_published` VALUES (993,' Post-Colonialism in the Novels of Shashi Deshpande','  For Deshpande, women must speak as Silence in her fiction becomes cumulatively metaphorical in meaning freedom on the individual in her fiction. 	Through The Binding Vine, the novelist opens a new world, and erects bridges between the modern and ancient India.  She does not just open up a rich world of Indian traditions and mythology but also shows the anguish felt by an unwilling wife who knows what the coming of the night inevitably brings for her.  The world, the novelist depicts here, is mainly womens world.  It is the kind of a world in which women suffer numerous losses and they have to learn to cope up with all such depravation. It is the hallmark of many characters that whatever happens in their lives, her protagonists do not lose hope and quickly learns to survive against all odds and suffering.','','Post-colonialism, Silence,  Feminine Consciousness, traditions, Suffering, Courage',' Rebecca B. S. Chauhan',' 369-376','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(994,' Personality and Well-being among Weaker and Stronger Section People','The Present Study focuses at the understanding of personality and well-being among weaker and stronger section people. \r\n	The study was planned as following the strength of poverty level 2 (W.S. vs. S.S.) x 2area (urban vs rural) x2age (youth vs. adult) factorial design. In each treatment condition 20 Ss were placed. Three measures had been taken. First poverty scale (P.S.) was developed by Sharma Krishna & Tiwari P.S.N. (2008). This was the reliable and valid measure of poverty. Second measure NEO-PI-R (Mc crae 1992) was used and third well-being measure (Nag pal 1995) was taken in the study. The obtained results clearly display the differential influence of weaker section vs. stronger section and urban vs. rural and youth vs. adult Ss on different three measures.\r\n','','Personality, well-being, poverty',' Krishna Sharma   P. S. N. Tiwari',' 379-394','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(995,' A Study of Role Conflict in Relation to Frustration Tolerance of Secondary School Teachers','In this study looked in to the relationship between role conflict and frustration tolerance of school teachers of Meerut region. A cluster sampling method was used with 400 (200 male & 200 female) school teachers. Date was measured by the role conflict scale (Gupta, S.P.) and frustration tolerance (S.N. Rai). Statistical finding of study, total role conflict of male & female teachers is significantly related with their frustration tolerance and total role conflict rural and urban teachers is not significant related with their frustration tolerance or total role conflict.','','Role Conflict, fruistration',' Ruchi Agarwal',' 395-398','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(996,' Different Perspectives in Social Mobility ','Social mobility is understood any transition of an individual or social object or value anything that has been created or modified by human activity from one social position to another. We should discuss below some of the major processes of social and cultural mobility in the Indian caste system. Some major processes of upward mobility are Sanskritization, Kshatriyaisation, Elite emulation model and Westernization. Downward caste mobility is also possible in the caste system, although it is infrequent and a very slow process. Many authors have tried to examine \"social mobility consequences\" of caste system in India. To recapitulate, the theoretical formulation, and to facilitate further studies, it would be useful to present some substantive propositions. An egalitarian and secular constitution and laws have been greatly instrumental in converting education, occupation, various other class characteristics, political power, leadership positions, civic and political privileges from being inscriptive aspects of status to the achievable, and we can see low castes have begun to acquire education, higher level occupations, political influence and leadership positions. ','','Mobility Models  ','Pradeep Kumar,  R. K. Saini,  Hemlata Saini ',' 1-16  ','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','37','58','2013-07-23 17:36:30','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1000,' vk/kqfud Hkkjr esa \'kSf{kd iqu:RFkku ds egku iSxEcj johUnz ukFk VSxksj dk fpUru   ','johUnz ukFk VSxksj cgqeq[kh izfrHkk ds /kuh O;fDrRo okys O;fDr FksA mUgkasus vius ys[kksa] dforkvksa] ukVdksasa] miU;klksa rFkk fucU/kksa ds }kjk jktuhfrd] vkfFkZd] lkekftd rFkk /kkfeZd fok;ksa ij fopkj izfrikfnr fd;s A mUgksaus lekt dh Toyau leL;kvksa ij Hkh vius fopkj vfHkO;Dr fd;sA mUgkasus ,d u;s ;qx rFkk u;h lkekftd O;oLFkk dk lw=ikr fd;kA os ewyr% ,d dfo Fks rFkk mUkdh dfoRo dh Hkkouk us mUgsa thou ds O;ogkjkRed vuqHko ls oafpr j[kkA mudh d:.kke; Hkkouk us mUgsa HkkSfrd txr ls izFkd j[kkA blls muds fopkjkas dh izd`fr vlkekU; gh jghA   ','','lkekftd O;oLFkk, Hkkjrh; lekt esa v/;kid   ','    latho \'kqDyk   ',' 153-163      ','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','32','2013-07-23 17:36:30','H',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1001,' ;ksx nkZu esa bZoj dk fopkj ,oa mi;ksfxrk   ','iratfy ds vuqlkj bZoj&fopkj ;ksx&lk/kuk esa lgk;d gSA bZoj egku gSA mldk viuk ,d vk/;kfRed vfLrRo gSA bZoj ds fopkj esa ,d fofp= vkd\"kZ.k gSA /;ku vkSj lekf/k ds fo\"k; ds :i esa bZoj dk gksuk vR;Ur gh vko;d gSA bZoj ds ij /;ku dks dsfUnzr djus esa vkUrfjd \'kfDRk feyrh gSA lekf/k dh voLFkk esa bZoj fopkj gh Kku dh l`f\"V djrk gSA   ','','fopkj ,oa mi;ksfxrk,\r\n