ntact in order to concludethe presence of flaw detection.\r\nSteel samples AISI/SAE 1038H with roughness of 0.34m, 4.67m, 11.34m and 23.92 m were used. The back surface roughness of all specimens was kept constant at 1.5 m Ra by grinding operation. 1.5, 2, 3, 4 mm. holes were drilled at constant depth and to same side of each specimen to represent reference reflectors at frequencies of 2.0 and 4.5 MHzs. Best signals of reflectors wereattained at the frequency of 4.5 MHz in steel samples.\r\nFrom the test results, it can be seen that the attenuation of the signal depends on the surface roughness. The analysis of the spectrum of the signalsdisplays that attenuation increases with the surface roughness.Though there was no uncertainty observed about not being able to detect discontinuity because of roughness but the correct couplant and frequency choice has a positive effect on correctly sizing the discontinuity and at attenuation measurements\r\n','','Surface Roughness, Ultrasonic Testing, Pulse Echo Method, Frequency, %Reduction',' Jatinder Chhabra and Brajesh Tripathi','239-251','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','56','2013-09-19 02:37:21','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1038,' An Inventory Model with deteriorating items and Selling Price Demand rate in Fuzzy Environment','In the present paper, we discuss the production model for a deteriorating item over a finite planning horizon with a price dependent demand and shortages under fuzzy environment. The machine production rate is assumed to be flexible in nature. The production-inventory system in each cycle consists of four stages.','','-',' Priti Agarwal, B S Kalra',' 252-267','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','','','2013-09-19 02:38:07','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1039,' An Inventory Model with deteriorating items and Selling Price Demand rate in Fuzzy Environment','In the present paper, we discuss the produc