fer the trade credit period to his/her customer. Based on this argument a two-warehouse inventory model for deteriorating items under two-level trade credit financing is derived with stock-dependent demand. Sensitivity analysis of the optimal solution with respect to the parameters of system is carried out with the help of a numerical example.</p>\r\n','','-  ','  Niketa D. Trivedi and Nita H. Shah  ','239-256    ','NO','05_IJICM(SI).pdf','International Journal of Inventory Control and Management','41','68','2023-01-09 15:36:45','E',5,'','  ',' https://doi.org/10.58517/IJICM.2012.2205 ','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1088,'An EOQ Model for Deteriorating Items Quadratic Demand and Shortages   ','<p>\r\n	The scope of this model includes the application of inventory management. It has been empirically observed that the life expectancy of many items can be expressed in terms of Weibull distribution. This empirical observation has prompted researchers to represent the time to deterioration of a product by a Weibull distribution. It is also observed that demand of a consumer product usually varies with time and hence, the demand rate should be taken as time-dependent. Our purpose is to focus on a mathematical model on inventory production system considering all these factors. Therefore, we develop an economic inventory model for deteriorating items with quadratic demand and shortages in inventory.</p>\r\n','<div>\r\n	[1]. Bahari-Kashani, H. (1989), &lsquo;Replenishment schedule for deteriorating items with time-proportional demand&rsquo;, Journal of the Operational Research Society, 40, 75-81.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[2]. Begum, R, Sahoo, R. R., Sahu, S. K. and Mishra, M. (2010), &lsquo;An EOQ model for varying items with Weibull distribution deterioration and price-dependent demand&rsquo;, Journal of Scientific Research, 2:1, 24-36.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[3]. Chakrabarty, T., Giri, B.C. and Chaudhuri, K.S. (1998), &lsquo;An EOQ model for items with Weibull distributio