ational Journal of Education and Information Sciences','37','59','2014-03-08 08:51:55','H',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1199,' Mobile Technology: Changing the Life ','In this running life, everyone wants to keep the updated/current information about the activities run across the world, world/national politics, world/national economy which is changing at every second, wants to know the various sports ,keens to know the history related to people ,places. People who roam across the nations/cities wants to inform their closers about their present location which is not possible at every time to update its status by sitting in front of computer system and net surfing, but with the emerging of mobile technology, it is possible, People are too busy in their professional life so that they are not able to extract enough time from their hectic schedule, to sit at the front of computer and spend time in net surfing. \r\nWith the emergence of mobile computing the internet is  coming closer to people which not saves their valuable time and effort but also make them always  connected to net with the electronic gadget they are carrying with their self, On the basis of an international survey , it is found that  all over world about 5.6 billion are mobile users which is  79.86% of total population. India alone covers 78.71% of mobile users from its 1.21 billion populations. \r\n\r\nMy paper is based on some observation in mobile industry to reveal out latest mobile technology that will affect modus-operandi, position of company in the market and opportunities to achieve high performance in mobile computing industry\r\n ','','Mobile Computing, trends, issues and challenges, future ','Ashish Joshi, Arpita Joshi ','199-203','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','40','70','2014-05-16 17:17:35','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1200,' Performance Evaluation of NOIDA Special Economic Zone','A Special Economic Zone (SEZ) is a geographical region that has economic laws that are more liberal than a countrys typical economic laws. The objective of the present study is planned to analyse the export, employment and investment performance of NOIDA SEZ. For evaluation of performance the secondary data available from various sources has been used. This paper gives a birds eye view about the NOIDA Special Economic Zone, objectives, role of U.P. Govt., features of UPSEZ Policy and finally the paper ended up with the performance of NSEZ. It can be concluded that Noida project is an interesting concept for the rapid development of the region and increasing exports from the country. It will benefit for the State and the Country immensely.','','Special Economic Zone (SEZ), Foreign Direct Investment (FDI)',' Kamana Tripathi',' 707-716','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','3','10','2014-04-29 14:09:16','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1201,' A Supply Chain Model with Ramp Type Demand and Deterioration    ','This paper investigates a supply chain system in which a single manufacturer procures raw materials from a single supplier, process them to produce finished products and then deliver the products to a single-retailer. The customer demand rate is assumed to time-sensitive in nature (ramp type) that allows two-phase variation in demand and production rate is demand dependent. Shortages are allowed with partial backlogging of demand for retailer, i.e. rest goes as lost sales. A simple solution algorithm is presented to determine the optimal order quantity and optimal cycle time of the total cost function. The results are discussed with a numerical examples and particular cases of the model discussed in brief. A sensitivity analysis of the optimal solution with respect to the parameters of the system is carried out.    ','','Two echelon supply chain, ramp type demand, deterioration, backlogging, inflation    ','    Jaivindra Tomar, Soshal, S.R. Singh, Sanjay Singh    ','133-150        ','NO','','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','39','72','2014-04-29 15:39:21','E',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1202,' Two Storage Inventory Model for Decaying Items with Time Dependent Time with Trade Credit and Lost Sales','In this paper, we develop an economic order quantity (EOQ) model, in which demand is taken exponentially increasing with time. Not only the demand function is fluctuating with time but also the backlogging rate of unsatisfied demand is a decreasing function of the waiting time. As a result, our proposed model is in a general framework. We then prove that the optimal replenishment schedule uniquely exists and the total profit associated with the inventory system is a concave function of the number of replenishments. Hence, the search for the optimal number of replenishments is simplified to finding a local maximum. In addition, we provide numerical examples for illustration. A sensitivity analysis with respect to parameters of the system is also made.','','Economic Order Quantity, Replenishments, Trade Credit and Lost Sales','Rekha Choudhary and Anchal Goel  ',' 115-132','NO','','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','39','61','2014-04-29 15:27:10','E',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1203,' Optimum Policies for an Integrated Inventory System with Time Dependent Demand and Shortages','In this paper, we developed an integrated inventory system of a deteriorating item, taking into account the views of both the vendor and multi buyers. This model contains the linear deterioration rate and demand rate is taken as exponential function of time. Production rate is taken as demand dependent. Partially backlogged shortages are permitted. This paper seeks the optimal number of order and size of order and the appropriate inventory level. Numerical experiment of the model is also developed.','','Integrated inventory system,   deterioration, partially backlogged shortage','Sarvpreet Kaur, A. P. Singh, D. Singh',' 151-164','NO','','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','39','72','2014-04-29 17:25:20','E',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1204,'Differential Evolution with Information Preserving Selection for Solving Sciences and Engineering Problems','This paper seeks the optimal number of order and size of order and the appropriate inventory level. Numerical experiment of the model is also developed. This paper presents a novel selection strategy, named as, information preserving selection, for Differential evolution algorithm (DE) to generate the population for the next generation. To investigate the performance of Differential evolution (DE) and its new version with information preserving selection strategy (IpDERL), 4 real life problems of science and engineering have been taken from the literature. Experimental results show that the proposed IpDERL is quiet competent for solving the considered real life problems and proved the efficiency in term of convergence rate, robustness and solution accuracy.','','Differential evolution, Information preserving selection, Real life problems, Global optimization',' Megha Gupta, Ashwini Kumar,Pravesh Kumar',' 165-181','NO','','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','39','72','2014-04-29 17:32:28','E',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1205,' Kinetics and Mechanism of Oxidation of Dimethyl Sulfoxide by Sodium bromated-Sodium bisulphite Reagent in aqueous Medium','The kinetics of oxidation of DMSO by HOBr produced in situ from sodium bromatesodium bisulfite reagent has been studied in aqueous medium iodometrically over the temperature range 308K to 323K.	Under the conditions [DMSO] >> [HOBr], the plot of log [HOBr] versus time is linear indicating a first order dependence in [HOBr] . From the slopes of such plots, the pseudofirst order rate constants (kobs) have been evaluated at different initial [DMSO]. The order in [DMSO] is fractional (0.30) when [DMSO] is between 0.01 and 0.5 mol dm3. A fractional order in [DMSO] points to the formation of an intermediate adduct between DMSO and HOBr (step 2). This fact further stands support by the linearity of 1/kobs versus 1/[DMSO] plot with finite intercept. This adduct decomposes in a rate determining step to yield the product DMSO2.','','Dimethyl sulfoxide , Hypobromous acid, Sodium bromate, Sodium bisulfite, Dimethyl sulfone,','  Munesh Kumar,Deepali Rani,Dinesh Chandra Agarwal','617-628','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','35','69','2014-04-29 17:45:18','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1207,' Kinetic Study of Ag(1) Catalysed Oxidation  of Some Ethers by S2 O8 2    ion','The oxidation of Di-isopropyl ether, Di-n-butyl ether was kinetically studied by K2S2O8 catalysed by AgNO3 in acidic medium. Each reaction was found to be the first order in  and zero order in each substrate. The first order rate constant decreases with the increase in . This decrease was found due to constant ionic strength or due to [k+]. Various energy parameters have been calculated. The reaction was found to be suppressed by allyl acetate. A free radical mechanism has been proposed and the corresponding rate expression was derived. ','','Radical Mechanism ethers',' Monika Sharma,P. K. Sharma',' 1-8','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','73','2014-04-30 16:56:20','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1208,' An Inventory System for Decaying Item with Demand Dependent on Selling Price and Displayed Stock and Partial Backlogging','In this paper, a two-warehouse inventory model is developed for deteriorating items with finite warehouse capacity, permitting shortage and time-proportional backlogging rate. In this study, the demand is the combination of stock and price. Holding costs are different in OW and RW due to different preservation environments. To reduce the inventory costs, it will be economical for firms to store goods in OW before RW, but clear the stocks in RW before OW. In particular, the backlogging rate considered to be a decreasing function of the waiting time for the next replenishment is more realistic. In practice, we can observe periodically the proportion of demand which would accept backlogging and the corresponding waiting time for the next replenishment. Here, the main objectives are to maximize the profit and minimize the total shortage cost. ','','two-warehouse, deteriorating items, permitting shortage','Rekha Chaudhary, Anchal Goyal',' 09-26','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','73','2014-04-30 17:10:32','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1209,' A Study of the effects of Solar Cycle 23, on the critical frequencies of F2 layer over Grahamstown ','This paper aims to study the effect of the long term solar activity on the critical frequencies of ionspheric F2 layer over Grahamstown (South Africa) during the solar cycle 23, (1996-2008). In this study, we have discussed the effect of sunspot numbers and solar events on the critical frequency of F2 layer, which is the most important ionspheric parameter.\r\nIt is found that the critical frequency of this layer is closely related to the sunspot numbers during the years of the solar cycle 23.\r\n','','Ionosphere, HF radio wave propagation, Critical frequency, solar cycle, sunspot number and solar activity.','Rachna Sharma and  Udit-Narain',' 27-40','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','73','2014-04-30 17:12:44','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1210,' An inventory model for deteriorating products with lost sales and Time dependent demand under inflation ','In this paper, an inventory model for deteriorating items with linearly time dependent demand rate and partial backlogging under inflation having two separate warehouses, one is an own warehouse and other a rented warehouse is developed. We allow shortages in the owned warehouse and time dependent backlogging rate is considered. Due to different preservation facilities and storage environment deterioration rates in the two warehouses is taken as different and inventory holding cost is considered to be different in different warehouses. We use a numerical example to illustrate the model and sensitivity analysis. ','','Time-dependent demand, Partial backlogging, Time dependent deterioration, Inflation    ','  Ashwani Kumar, Megha Gupta, P K Vashistha ',' 41-54  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','73','2014-04-30 17:19:49','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1211,' Multiplicative Quadruple Fibonacci Sequences','In this paper multiplicative quadruple Fibonacci sequences have been discussed which is the extension of multiplicative triple Fibonacci sequences. ','','Fibonacci sequences, Multiplicative Quadruple Fibonacci sequences','Satish Kumar and Hari Kishan',' 205-212','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','40','70','2014-05-16 17:21:20','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1212,'Soft Computing Based Procurement Planning of dynamic  Demand in a production System','Soft computing is likely to play a very important role in science and engineering, but eventually its influence may extend much farther. In the present study We have discuss a method based on genetic algorithm to optimize logistics  in supply chain management we also focus on to specifically determine the excess  level and shortage level required for optimization such that the total cost is minimized. ','','Soft computing, genetic algorithm.','AMIT KUMAR',' 191-200','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','40','70','2014-05-16 17:23:04','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1213,'Effect of Inflation and Lost Sales on Inventory System with Linear Demand Rate and Deterioration','In this paper a two-warehouse inventory problem with a linear trend in demand for deteriorating items is considered. Shortages are allowed and are partially backlogged. The results have been validated with the help of some numerical examples and comprehensive sensitivity analysis has also been performed.','','Two-warehouse, Deteriorating items, Shortages ','Rekha Choudhary and Anchal Goel',' 223-234','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','40','70','2014-05-16 17:25:05','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1214,' Inventory Model for Deteriorating Items with Stock Dependent demand and Inflation','In this paper we consider the problem of deteriorating item, in which demand depends on stock level. It is assumed that a constant fraction of on-hand inventory deteriorates per unit of time. Effect of inflation is taken into account. This paper has the scope of direct application in very practical situations. Shortages, if any, are allowed and partially backlogged with a variable rate which depends on the duration of waiting time upto the arrival of next lot. To illustrate the results and its significant features, a numerical example is given','','inflation, stock-dependent demand and deterioration','Ashwani Kumar, Megha Gupta, P K Vashistha',' 235-245','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','40','70','2014-05-16 17:27:14','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1215,'Inventory Model for Deteriorating Items with Stock Dependent demand and Inflation','In this paper we consider the problem of deteriorating item, in which demand depends on stock level. It is assumed that a constant fraction of on-hand inventory deteriorates per unit of time. Effect of inflation is taken into account. This paper has the scope of direct application in very practical situations. Shortages, if any, are allowed and partially backlogged with a variable rate which depends on the duration of waiting time upto the arrival of next lot. To illustrate the results and its significant features, a numerical example is given.','','inflation, stock-dependent demand and deterioration',' Ashwani Kumar, Megha Gupta, P K Vashistha',' 235-245','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','40','70','2014-05-16 17:30:15','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1216,' Review of Genetic Algorithm and Fuzzy Logic based Models on logistics','This paper presents a review of the advances of Genetic Algorithm and Fuzzy Logic based Models on logistics. The models available in the literature have been collected and classified to bring out information regarding development of the subject','','Genetic Algorithm and Fuzzy Logic','Amit Kumar',' 246-254','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','40','70','2014-05-16 17:31:38','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1217,'PREVENTING COVERT CHANNEL ATTACKS BY USING SOFTWARE AGENTS  ','Information sharing and their protection is a major problem for organisations having sensitive data. Shared resources are utilized by the covert channel for indirectly transmit sensitive information to unauthorized parties. For security purpose some mechanism such as seLINUX rely on the tagging the file system with access control properties. Such mechanism does not provide strong protection so colored LINUX, an extension to seLINUX is used to color the content of the file according to security classification to enhance resistance information laundering. In this paper we discuss about the mobile agent based approach to provide the environment to automate the process of detecting and coloring the respective file system(host) and monitoring the colored file system for instance of potential information leakage.','','covert channel, information laundering, information leakage, notify, overwhelming                                                                                                                                                                                                       ','Deepika Sonal, D.Kiranmayi',' 255-264','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','40','70','2014-05-16 17:33:13','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1218,'EVALUATION OF RELIABILITY - COMPARISON OF DIFFERENT SOLUTION TECHNIQUES OF THE LOAD SHARING SYSTEM','In the present work, Reliability of the Load sharing system is estimated. Here, Mathematical model has been developed on the basis of Markov birth-death process using probabilistic approach. The first order governing equations thus formulated using the Mnemonic rule is solved to estimate the reliability of the load sharing system. The solution of these equations is carried out using three different solution techniques namely; Laplace Transform method, Simple integration and Matlab 7.8.0 (R2009a). The Mean time to failure (MTTF) is also computed. The research result shows the comparison of different solution techniques for computing the reliability of the Load sharing system.','','Reliability, Markov birthdeath process, Mnemonic rule, MTTF and Laplace Transform method.','Zeenat Zaidi','265-273','YES','15 ITMSC 62.pdf','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','40','70','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1219,'(Q, r) Inventory Model with Embedded Quality Inspection ','<p>\r\n	The classical (Q, r) Inventory model is revisited and the effect of quality changes on lot sizing are discussed. The lots received from the supplier suffer from a known proportion of defectives and each lot is accepted after passing through a single sampling plan of the attribute type with rectification. The lot size Q is a part of this exercise and the parameters (n, c) of the plan are determined. An iterative procedure is developed to simultaneously determine n, c, Q and r of the model. The working of the model and the sensitivity are numerically illustrated.</p>\r\n','<div>\r\n	1. B.M.C. Sekhar Naidu, K.V.S. Sarma, and S.K.Goyal, (1995), Optimum two stage production-Inventory policy with whole lot and split lots, Production Planning and control, Vol 6, No.2, 134- 139.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	2. Johnson and Montgomery,(1974) &ldquo;Operations research in production planning, scheduling, and Inventory control&rdquo; ,John Wiley &amp;Sons , New York.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	3. Jaggi, Chandra K. and Mandeep Mittal (2011), &quot;Economic Order quantity model for deteriorating items with imperfect quality&quot;, Revista Investigaci&oacute;n Operacional, Vol. 32, No. 2, pp. 107-113.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	4. Kalro, A.H and Gohil, M.M (1982), &ldquo;A Lot Size Model with Backlogging when the Amount Received is Uncertain&rdquo;, International Journal of Production Research. Vol.20, No.6, p. 775-786.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	5. Konda Reddy N and K.V.S.Sarma (2003), Economic Lot Size Model with sample inspection of the received lot, International Journal of Management and Systems, 19(1),</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	6. Montgomery, D.C (1977), &ldquo;An Introduction to Statistical Quality Control&rdquo;. John &amp; Wiley, Inc.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	7. Mohan Naidu G and Sarma, K.V.S (1995), An EOQ model with two levels of storage when the quality received is uncertain, OPSEARCH.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	8. Naidu, G.M. and Sarma, K.V.S (1997), &ldquo;A Stochastic Inventory Model with Quality-Dependent Demand&rdquo;, Calcutta Statistical Association Bulletin. Vol.47, p. 215-222.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	9. Silver, E.A (1974), &ldquo;Establishing the Order Quantity when the Amount Received is Uncertain&rdquo;, INFOR. p. 32-39.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	10. Sarma, K.V.S and G. Mohan Naidu (1997), Optimal order level systems for products with imperfect quality, Industrial engineering Journal, Vol.XXVI, 5-11.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	11. Sarma, K.V.S and G. Mohan Naidu (1997), A stochastic inventory model with quality dependent demand, Calcutta Statistical Association Bulletin, Vol. 47, 187-188.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	12. Sunitha.M , and K.V.S. Sarma , &ldquo;An Inventory Model With Embedded Acceptance Sampling Plan&rdquo;, International Journal of Statistics and Analysis. Volume 2, Number 4(2012), pp. 369-378.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	13. Wei Shih (1980), &ldquo;Optimal Inventory Policies when Stock Result from Defective Products&rdquo;, International Journal of Production Research. Vol. 18, p. 677-686.</div>\r\n','(Q, r) Inventory model, Fraction defective, Consumers risk, Rectifying inspection, Average Total Inspection.    ',' K.V.S.Sarma, M.Sunitha     ','269-283        ','YES','IJICM_2013_V3N1_1.pdf','International Journal of Inventory Control and Management','45','74','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',5,'sarma_kvs@rediffmail.com','Senior Professor of Statistics Sri Venkateswara University, Tirupati, India ',' https://doi.org/10.58517/IJICM.2013.3101','pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1220,'Optimal Inventory Policies for Single-Supplier Single-Buyer Deteriorating Items with Price-Sensitive Stock-dependent Demand and Order Linked Trade Credit  ','<p>\r\n	The integrated inventory policies of single-supplier single-buyer are studied under order-dependent trade credit terms. The units in inventory are subject to constant rate of deterioration. The demand rate is assumed to be price-sensitive stock-dependent. Under order-dependent trade credit scenario, the buyer is eligible for settlement of account at allowable delay period if the order quantity is larger than that of pre-specified order by the supplier. The objective is to maximize joint profit of the supply chain with respect to retail price of the unit and cycle time and number of shipments from the supplier to the buyer. The numerical example is given to illustrate the mathematical analysis. Sensitivity analysis is carried out to deduce managerial ins