on, International Journal of system Science 32, 259-268.</div>\r\n','Inventory, Periodic review, Crashing cost, Lead-Time, Backorder discount, Service level    ','Chandra K Jaggi, Haider Ali and  Neetu Arneja    ','303-327      ','YES','IJICM_2013_V3N1_3.pdf','International Journal of Inventory Control and Management','45','74','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',5,'ckjaggi@yahoo.ac.in','Department of Operational Research Faculty of Mathematical Sciences University of Delhi Delhi-110007',' https://doi.org/10.58517/IJICM.2013.3103','pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1222,'EOQ MODEL WITH NATURAL IDLE TIME AND WRONGLY MEASURED DEMAND RATE  ','<p>\r\n	The traditional concept of economic order quantity (EOQ) inventory model is that, the demand rate is continuous throughout the cycle time. But through clinical inquiry anybody can notice something different from that assumption. In reality, for any inventory we usually observe that each day has an unavoidable natural leisure/closing time and at that time no demand rate is viewed. Considering this phenomenon in an EOQ model we may split a day into two parts, one is the opening time period and the other one is closing time period. However, the demand rate which is out-flowed from the system has a measuring error. In the basis of low, zero and excessive measuring error, the model itself is divided into three parts, for a finite cycle time (counted in days only). Due to the flexible nature of the opening and closing time period of the model, a general Fuzzy set and Intuitionistic Fuzzy Optimization (IFO) technique have been analyzed to illustrate the model. Numerical examples and sensitivity analysis have been made with the help of LINGO software and got a wonderful optimum solution near 12-hour opening time duration in a day. Finally a conclusion is made keeping some scope of future work.</p>\r\n','<div>\r\n	[1] A. Kaufmann, M. Gupta, Fuzzy Mathematical Models in Engineering and Management Science, North Holland, 1988.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[2] Alireza Kabiran, Sigurdur Olafsson, Continuous Optimization via Simulation using Golden Region Search , European Journal of Operational Research. 208(2011) 19-27.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[3] A. Banerjee, Production lot sizing with work in process considerations in response to periodic demand, Int. J. Prod. Econ. 26 ( 2 ) (1992) 145-151.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[4] Chiang Kao, Wen-Kai Hsu, A Single period Inventory model with fuzzy demand, Computers and Mathematics with Applications. 43(2002) 841-848.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[5] H. J. Zimmermann, Fuzzy linear programming with several objective functions, Fuzzy sets and Systems. (1978) 146-55.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[6] K. Atanassov, G.Gargov, Interval valued intuitionistic fuzzy sets, Fuzzy sets and Systems. 31(3) (1989) 343-349.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[7] K. Atanassov, Intuitionistic fuzzy sets and system. Fuzzy sets and Systems. 20(1986) 87-96.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[8] Liang- Yuh Ouyang , Hung- Chi Chang, A Minimax distribution free procedure for mixed inventory models involving variable lead time with fuzzy lost sales, Int.J. Prod. Eco. 76(2002) 1-12.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[9] L. A. Zadeh, Fuzzy sets, Information and Control. 8(1965) 338-356.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[10] M. Saleh, R. Oliva, C.E. Kampmann, Pal I. Davidson, A Comprehensive Analytical approach for policy Analysis of system dynamics models, European Journal of Operational Research. 203(2010) 673-683.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[11] P.P. Angelov, Optimization in an intuitionistic fuzzy environment, Fuzzy sets and Systems. 86(1997) 299-306.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[12] P. M. Ghare, G. P. Schrader, A model for exponentially decaying inventory, J. Industrial Engineering. 14(1963) 238-243.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[13] R.B. Misra, Optimum production lot size model for a system with deteriorating inventory, Int. J. Production Research. 13(1975) 495-505.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[14] R.E. Bellman, L.A. Zadeh, Decision making in a fuzzy environment, Management Science. 17(1970) B141-B164.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[15] R. P.Covert, G. C. Philip, An EOQ model for items with Weibull distribution deterioration, AIIE Trans. 53(1973) 23-332.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[16] S.Banerjee, T.K. Roy, Probabilistic inventory model with fuzzy cost components and fuzzy random variable, International Journal of Computational and Applied Mathematics. 5 (4) (2010 a) 501-514.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[17] S. Banerjee, T.K. Roy, Solution of a probabilistic fixed order interval system : a general Fuzzy Programming Technique and intuitionistic Fuzzy Optimization Technique, Global Journal of Finance and Management. 2 ( 2 ) (2010 b) 257-294.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[18] S.De , A. Goswami, A replenishment policy for items with finite production rate and fuzzy deterioration rate. Opsearch. 38(4) (2001) 419-430.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[19] T. L. Urban, An inventory model with an inventory level dependent demand rate and relaxed terminal conditions, Journal of Operational Research Society. 43(1992) 721-724.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[20] Yuh Ouyanga Liang, Kun-Shan Wub, Chia-Huei Ho, Integrated vendor-buyer cooperative models with stochastic demand in controllable lead time, Int.J. Prod. Econ. 92(2004) 255-266.</div>\r\n','Inventory, Fuzzy sets, Natural idle time, Intuitionistic Fuzzy Optimization.  ','Sujit Kumar De  ','329-354    ','YES','IJICM_2013_V3N1_4.pdf','International Journal of Inventory Control and Management','45','74','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',5,'skdemamo2008.com@gmail.com',' Department of Mathematics, Midnapore College, Pin-721101,West Bengal, India',' https://doi.org/10.58517/IJICM.2013.3104','pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1223,' Challenge and coping with stress by entrepreneurs',' Entrepreneurs are defined as individual who change certain conditions in order to create value around perceived opportunities, whether within an existing enterprise or as the new ventures. Despite such challenges, entrepreneurship is becoming an increasingly popular career choice and is generally accepted as an area where stress can be expected. Stress is a result of expectations, greed, desires and ambitions; when there is a discrepancy between these and the outcome effects to achieve success is experienced. The paper aims to examine the challenge and coping of stress as experienced by entrepreneurs. Different challenges and implicating effective coping strategies and understanding the connection between the entrepreneur and the venture, depends on the entrepreneurs perception of stress and their ability to moderate the relationship between chosen coping strategies and the performance of the venture. The implication of this study has benefit not only to the entrepreneur in increased awareness but also to stakeholders such bank, insurance agency and family members, who gain better insight into possible venture failure based on the entrepreneurs ability to maximize the effects of positive stress and to minimize the negative stress impacts upon the venture and upon the entrepreneur.','','Entrepreneurs, stress, challenge, coping,','Kamana Tripathi',' 171-178','NO','','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','19','15','2014-06-03 06:41:23','E',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1226,'Wave Mechanical Analysis of Quantum Dots Materials for Solar Cells Application ','Spatial confinement of electrons in semiconductor nanostructures leads to remarkable changes in their quantum states. Quantum dots are quasi zero dimensional systems which are practical realization of the familiar concept of particle in a box. The quantum dot solar cell concept is proposed as a scheme for increased solar cell efficiency. These are alternative of conventional tandem approaches to higher conversion efficiency. In this paper, a wave mechanical theory of physical process of Q-dot in nano media is presented and increment in the conversion efficiency of Q-dot solar cells is discussed. The theory is based on the consideration of particle in a box. The problem is solved with Schrodinger wave equation under boundary condition of box. ','','Wave Mechanical Analysis of Quantum Dots Materials for 	\r\nSolar Cells Application\r\nWave Mechanical Analysis of Quantum Dots Materials for 	\r\nSolar Cells Application\r\nWave Mechanical Analysis ,Quantum Dots Materials ,Solar Cells ',' Reeta, N.D.Kaushika and V.P.Singh ','55-62  ','YES','05 ITAS 6-1 (1).pdf','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','73','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1227,' Study of life Satisfaction and Perception of Happiness among Villagers','The present study aims to investigate the life satisfaction and perception of happiness among villagers belonging to different caste groups i.e. - General, OBC and SC/ST. Data were collected from 240 subjects (General, OBC, and SC/ST). Two open ended questions were asked for eliciting villagers concept of satisfied and happy life. The result of content analysis of happy life projections revealed a quite similarity among the villagers belonging to three categories.  Villagers were concerned with personal needs and agriculture needs. Social, psychological and community needs were not frequently emphasized. All three groups of villagers were concerned with personal and agricultural needs. Village prosperity and need for achievement as well as dependence were the needs which were not emphasized frequently. The villagers belonging to general category were emphasized more psychological needs while SC/ST subjects emphasized dependence more in comparison to the subjects belonging to remaining categories.','','happiness, life satisfaction, villagers, caste groups. ','P.S.N.Tiwari, A B Singh                                                                 ','157-164','NO','','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','28','46','2014-08-01 10:52:18','E',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1228,' Enhancing Entrepreneurship Among Rural Youth','Entrepreneurship has been defined as any attempt at new business or new venture creation, such as self-employed, a new organization or expansion of the existing business by an individuals or an established business. The present paper is an attempt to give a birds eye view about the entrepreneurship as an alternative occupation options for the rural youth. Entrepreneurship in rural areas is finding a unique blend of resources, either inside or outside agriculture. This can be achieved by widening the base of a farm business to include all the non-agricultural uses that available resources can be put to or through any major changes in land use or level of production other than those related solely to agriculture. The paper deals with the brief description of rural entrepreneurship, basic infrastructure, domains & problems in managing a rural enterprise. To overcome the limitations, the rural entrepreneurship development programme has been introduced. Rural Entrepreneurship Development Programme (REDP) is one of the important NFS (non-farm sector) promotional programmes supported by NABARD, creating sustainable employment and income opportunities in a cost effective manner for the benefit of educated unemployed rural youth.','','Entrepreneurship, Rural Youth    ','Kamana Tripathi ',' 165-171','NO','','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','28','46','2014-08-01 10:54:11','E',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1229,'Studies on Variation of Glyco-Proteins and Vitamin-E in Patients of Pulmonary Tuberculosis ','Tuberculosis has been a serious problem since a long time. In 1880s the disease caused more than 30% of all deaths in Europe (Goldrick 2004). With the advent of Anti-Tuberculous antibiotics in late 1940s, the battle seemed to be won. Because of inadequate public health resources, reduced immune responses due to AIDS, the development of drug resistance and extreme poverty in the many parts of the world, the disease continues to be deadly (WHO 2006). This  study is about the  variation of Glyco-proteins and vitamin-e in patients of pulmonary tuberculosis ','','Glyco-Proteins, Vitamin-E, Pulmonary Tuberculosis ','Richa Singh ','869-882','YES','ITAS 2-4, 869-882.pdf','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','17','28','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1230,' EMPOWERMENT of ADOLESCENT GIRLS for GENDER EQUALITY','The empowerment of women is one of the central issues in the process of development of countries all over the world. Empowerment is an active and multidimensional process, which enables women to realize their identity and power in all aspects of life. It goes beyond socio-economic or political attributes and essentially refers to a process of becoming psychologically empowered too. It is believed that education is the propelling source of women empowerment as it enables them to boldly respond to the challenges. Like women, girls need to be empowered in order to let them become future leaders, self-sufficient individuals and role models in their segments. Adolescent girls in India face many challenges. Adolescence is a crucial phase in the life of women. At this stage, she stands at the threshold of adulthood. The influence in these foundation years not only shapes the personality of individuals but also determines the next generation of workers, parents and leaders for any nation. Empowerment of adolescent girls is a matter of social justice and recognition of their rights. This paper deals with the role of education in addressing the immediate and long-term search for gender equity and Womens Empowerment. The research work highlights the empowerment level of adolescent girls','','',' Seema dhawan',' 1-6','NO','','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','47','77','2014-08-05 05:25:42','E',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1231,' A Study of The Effect of Indigenous Techniques for Enhancing Emotional Intelligence','Emotional Intelligence (EI) is an emerging concept which involves the ability to carry out accurate reasoning about emotions and the abilities to use emotions and emotional knowledge to enhance thought. This study investigated the efficacy of a yogic package on EI of engineering course pursuing students. The sample consists of randomly selected 80 students with sound health in age group of 18-28 years. A yogic package comprised of selected Asanas, relaxation, anulom-vilom and Bhramari Pranayamas, Prayer and group discussion regarding yogic life style was instructed for 30 days. Each session was of 60 minute in morning hour per day except Sunday. Emotional Intelligence Scale (EIS) constructed by Anukool Hyde Sonjyat Pethe and Upinder Dhar was administered to measure the level of EI before and after intervention. Result indicated that yogic package was significantly        (P<0.01, df = 39) responsible to enhance the EI of participants. Controlled group t-value was not significant. It may be concluded the yoga practice could enhance various emotional competencies and efficiencies among students if it gets incorporated as a regular part of teaching and learning. Therefore, indigenous technique is very effective to enhance emotional intelligence.','','',' Surendra prasad rayal  & Jay prakash kanswal',' 7-10','NO','','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','47','77','2014-08-05 05:27:20','E',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1232,' Dynamics of STRUCTURAL CHANGES in INDIAN AGRICULTURE','The performance of Agriculture in India is important as the sector not only contributes to overall growth of the economy but also provides employment and food security to majority of the population in the country. The 11th Five Year Plan also indicates that agricultural development is an important component of inclusive growth approach. Structural reforms were introduced in India in a big way in 1991. These reforms were followed by India becoming founder member of WTO in 1994. The structural reforms and obligations of WTO have positive and negative effects on Indian agriculture','','',' V.S.Rawat',' 11-18','NO','','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','47','77','2014-08-05 05:50:16','E',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1233,' Impact of MGNREGA on ECONOMIC STATUS of RURAL AREA A CASE STUDY of Dunda BLOCK (DISTRICT- UTTARKASHI)','The paper assesses the implementation of Mahatma Gandhi National Rural Employment Guarantee Act (MGNREGA) and its various impacts in the rural areas of the Dunda Block, district UTTARKASHI. MGNREGA has a flagship program of central (UPA) government which is given 100 days job assurance in rural areas for unskilled persons. DUNDA block, UTTARKASHI (UTTARKHAND) has a backward area and in this area MGNREGA had not provided 100 days job guarantee to who are willing to do jobs under this Scheme. Irregularities are also found in implementation of MGNREGA in this area. Planning work was not prepared properly. But another picture is that its provided some amount of jobs for peoples in this area. In Dunda Block government data shown that jobs were provided under MGNREGA but this study could not found them. In many cases found that jobs were provided to real beneficiaries. And in some cases wages were not given after completing of work. Unemployment allowance which is another safe guard of this scheme not provided who want to jobs but unfortunately jobs were not provided within certain period. These papers select 05 villages (Patara, Malana, Pujargaun, Bandhu and Kalyani) and the survey study based on 250 (man and women 50From each villages) skilled and unskilled labor.','','',' Diwaker boudha',' 19-26','NO','','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','47','77','2014-08-05 05:51:10','E',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1234,'EMPOWERING TOURISM THROUGH SUPRANATIONAL TREATIES A CASE STUDY of ASEAN','The present study tries to evaluate the potential of tourism in ASEAN region and to find out the benefits of the regional alliances in the ASEAN region. Paper highlights the importance of the increased integration of ASEAN as a Community in 2015 which will bring greater benefits to ASEAN member states and the region. ASEAN first need to develop a sustainable economic structure resilient to outside turbulence, boosting their internal strength to be the nucleus of the regional integration and connectivity which can be done only with the help of tourism Industry. ASEAN had also been active in promoting regional integration and connectivity by its community building process scheduled to be completed by 2015, and by various economic co-operation arrangements with its partners, including China, Japan, ROK, India, Australia and New Zealand, among others. The economic benefits of the travel & tourism industry are now well-recognised. The means of achieving short-term gain in terms of job creation and foreign exchange earnings are well in place.  The paper envisages the importance for the creation of different alliances which can reap out the benefits to the tourism industry.','','',' Amit Gangotia  &  Rahul Thakur',' 27-34','NO','','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','47','77','2014-08-05 05:54:21','E',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1235,' FDI in INDIAN RETAIL SECTOR Prospects and CHALLENGES','Indian retail sector plays an important role in Indian economy. It is a great pillar here which contributes about 14 to 15% in the GDP. The Indian Retail Market is estimated to be US$ 450 billion and one of the top five retail markets in the world. India is the fastest growing retail market in the world with 1.2 billion people. The overall employment share of Indian retail sector consists of 6 to 9 % workforce of the country. Due to the huge retail market, many multinational companies attract here to grow their retail web and to attain maximum benefits. Through FDI the government encourage the foreign MNCs to involve in the retailing process and to supply a fair and systematic organized facilities to the consumer. Investment from abroad has also been hailed by Indian Industries. The shape of Indian retail consists more of unorganized retailers like small shop stores, kirana stores, cheap jacks local stores etc and limited amount of organized stores. This paper focuses on the challenges of Indian Government and Prospects of FDI in retail sector with an aim to provide a brief information and impact of FDI in retail sector in India. This paper also discovers the impact of FDI in retail sector through a survey conducted for the purpose of finding the effect and to reach at the conclusion.','','',' Jagdish Pandey',' 35-40','NO','','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','47','77','2014-08-05 05:55:26','E',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1236,' A Study on Attitude  of Secondary Schoolstudents towards   Environmental Constituents','The environment constitutes of air, water, land, flora and fauna, because these regulate the mans life. In this study only four constituents of environment has been taken into account. Main findings of this study is a positive attitude among all the students towards environment. There is significant difference in attitude towards environment between boys of govt. and non-govt. schools, And the understanding level of male students of non govt. school is more than male students of government schools, and female students of non govt. schools are more aware about environmental constituents.','','',' Chhavi Chadha & Usha Dhulia',' 41-44','NO','','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','47','77','2014-08-05 05:56:33','E',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1237,' Voicing HUMAN RIGHTS through LITERATURE: A PERSPECTIVE through TENDULKARS KANYADAAN','The issue of advancement of human rights has been a deep concern for the UN as well as for everyone all over the world. Since ages injustice in all forms has been done to the Dalits and women in India This paper aims to project human rights as depicted in literature with special reference to the famous play of Vijay Tendulkar, KanyadaanThe play vividly depicts the plight of a woman and the agony of a low caste boy who has nurtured anguish against the upper caste people due to suppression and discrimination faced by his ancestors since ages. In Indian context, there is still lack of recognition of ones own rights as a human being. Since, literature is a reflection of society, so it has been used as a potent tool to depict the scenario of women and their rights in modern era.  Kanyadanexplores the plight of an Indian woman and a Dalit boy who are caught in a conflict between idealism and reality. The play Kanyadaanby Vijay Tendulkar vividly describes the domestic violence against women and the anger, anguish and frustration fostering in the minds of  Dalits which is the result of their sufferings and suppressions since ages. It also highlights the plight of the downtrodden section of the society, who were  deprived of their basic rights even as a human being. Hence, literature plays an important role by reflecting society in its true picture and making the readers acquainted with the predicaments of the weaker sections of the society.  ','','',' Pooja Gupta  & Jyoti Mamgain',' 45-48','NO','','International Transactions in Humanities and Social Sciences','47','77','2014-08-05 05:57:55','E',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1238,' Techniques Used in Voice Recognition','Voice is a natural mode of communication for people. We learn all the relevant skills during early childhood, without instruction, and we continue to rely on voice communication throughout our lives. It comes so naturally to us that we dont realize how complex a phenomenon voice is. The human vocal tract and articulators are biological organs with nonlinear properties, whose operation are not just under conscious control but also affected by factors ranging from gender to upbringing to emotional state.','','communication, phenomenon, nonlinear',' Bbirnally Sapna',' 417-420','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2014-08-23 05:20:58','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1239,' Smart Antenna for Cellular Mobile Communication','The adoption of smart / adaptive antenna techniques in future wireless systems is expected to have a significant impact on the efficient use of the spectrum, the minimization of the cost of establishing new wireless networks, the optimization of service quality and realization of transparent operation across multi technology wireless networks. This paper presents brief account on smart antenna (SA) system. SAs can place nulls in the direction of interferers via adaptive updating of weights linked to each antenna element. SAs thus cancel out most of the co-channel interference resulting in better quality of reception and lower dropped calls. SAs can also track the user within a cell via direction of arrival algorithms. This paper explains the architecture, evolution and how the smart / adaptive antenna differs from the basic format of antenna. The paper further explains about the radiation pattern of the antenna and why it is highly preferred in its relative field. The capabilities of smart / adaptive antenna are easily employable to Cognitive Radio and OFDMA system.','','Adaptive Antenna; Wireless; Beam forming; DSP; Diversity',' Bhuma Naresh','421-426','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','26','44','2014-08-23 05:22:21','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1240,' Influence of Water Stress on Growth and Development of Crop Plants','Depletion of land water resources and adverse effects of global climate change are becoming crucial for future agriculture. To fulfill the food