'47','77','2014-08-26 17:28:33','E',3,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1269,' Recent Advances in PVC Thermal Stabilization with Lead Free Compounds','On application of heat and mechanical shear, polyvinyl chloride (PVC) breaks down resulting in the removal of HCl. This process can be controlled, most effectively, by the utilisation of thermal stabilizers. While the thermal stabilizers based on lead are reported to be most efficient, in several cases, are not in usage any longer in view of the fact that they are toxic. Other thermal stabilizers may be tin compounds, barium-calcium soap combination, calcium-zinc soap combination, antimicrobial organic compound and many other organic thermal stabilizers. This review delineates the basic degradation and stabilization mechanisms of various lead free thermal stabilizers which are involved in these processes and outlines some recent development in this field.','','PVC, degradation, stabilizers, PET Waste recycling, pentaerythritol.','Anjali Verma, R. K. Soni and Mukesh','63-75','YES','06 ITAS 6-1. 2014.pdf','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','73','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1270,' Antifungal studies of terephthalic dihydrazide (TPD) generated from PET waste','The degradation of poly (ethylene terephthalate) (PET) waste by making use of hydrazine monohydrate was investigated at ambient temperature and pressure. Polyethylene terephthalate (PET) waste flakes were degraded with hydrazine monohydrate at the room temperature for different periods of time. The complete degradation of PET waste with hydrazine monohydrate was investigated only in 24 hours. The end product was characterized as a mixture of terephthalic dihydrazide and its oligomers. The synthesized end product further investigated for antifungal activities with different fungi species such as Penicillium notatum, Tricoderma lignorum, Aspergillus niger and Fusarium sp.  The result shows that growth of different fungal species decreases with increase in concentration of terephthalic dihydrazide. The minimum inhibitory concentration (MIC) of the terephthalic dihydrazide has been found 200mg. /20 ml. ','','Ddegradation, Poly, ethylene, hydrazine monohydrate.','Anjali Verma, R. K. Soni and Krishna Dutt','77-91','YES','07 ITAS 6-1-2014.pdf','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','73','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1271,' CRYSTAL STRUCTURES OF RbMgCl3.6H2O AND TUTTON SALTS','The paper describe the crystal structures of two hosts in which EPR of doped vanadyl ions has been investigated and also studied through EPR in the present paper.  ','','CRYSTAL STRUCTURES','Narender Pathak and Anil Mishra','883-889','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','17','28','2014-09-10 14:35:47','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1272,'Effect of Learning and Inspection on Economic Order Quantity Model for Impatient Customers with Taguchis Cost of Poor Quality Items','This paper extends special class of Economic order quantity models with backorder to explicitly specify the Taguchis COPQ due to imperfect items and effect of learning phenomenon on percentage of defective items present in each lot, on holding cost and on ordering cost. From the analysis, we found that the annual profit will be affected by the presence of poor quality items in lot and the Taguchis COPQ in the EOQ model with backorder. From the observations it can also be concluded that one can earn more profits by incorporating the effect of learning on holding cost, ordering cost and on the percentage of defective items present in each lot considered in them simultaneously. This model gives the direction to decision-makers to take account of learning and while taking decisions. ','','Learning,Inspection ,Economic Order Quantity Model ,Impatient Customers','Bhupal Singh and Punam Sharma','93-104','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','73','2014-09-12 14:37:04','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1273,'Stochastic Modelling for Imperfect Manufacturer System with Random Machine Breakdown and Uniformly/Exponentially Distributed Machine Repair Time',' purpose of this paper is to investigate the deteriorating items production model with random machine breakdown and stochastic repair time under the effect of flexible manufacturing system where the unit production cost is the function of production rate. The model assumes that the machine repair time is independent of the machine breakdown rate. In first part of the model it is assumed that the repair time is uniformly distributed while in other part of the model it is assumed that repair time is exponential distributed. Classical optimization technique is used to obtain the optimal solution.','','Stochastic Modelling, Imperfect Manufacturer System','Punam Sharma and Bhupal Singh ','183-200','NO','','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','39','72','2014-09-12 14:45:29','E',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1275,' An Inventory Model for Decaying Items with Partial Backlogging','In this paper, an inventory model for non-instantaneous decaying items with linear demand along with the effects of inflation has been developed. In this model deterioration rate is taken as two parameters Weibull distribution function. In this model shortage are allowed and partially backlogged.  Numerical example with sensitivity analysis is also shown. ','','Non-nstantaneous,Weibull,shortage','A K Sharma and Kavita Sinha',' 105-114','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','73','2014-10-07 13:51:43','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1276,' Effect of Inflation for Decaying Items with Stock and Time Dependent Demand on an Inventory System','The purpose of this paper is to investigate an inventory model for deteriorating items with time and stock dependent demand rate. The environment of whole study has been taken as inflationary. Shortages are allowed with partially backlogging. Backlogging rate is taken as waiting time for the next replenishment. Numerical illustration and sensitivity analysis is also discussed. ','','Time and stock dependent demand, inflation, Backlogging','A K Sharma, Kavita Sinha',' 201-212','NO','','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','39','72','2014-10-07 14:18:15','E',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1277,'MHD FLOW OF A VISCOELASTIC (MAXWELL MODEL) DUSTY FLUID THROUGH A POROUS MEDIUM INDUCED BY THE MOTION OF A SEMI-INFINITE PLATE MOVING ','In this present paper is concerned with the MHD free convective flow of a visco-elastic (Maxwell model) dusty fluid through a porous medium induced by the motion of a semi-infinite flat plate moving with velocity decreasing exponentially with time. The expressions for velocity distribution of the dusty fluid and temperature distribution are obtained. The effect of Visco-elastic parameter (0), magnetic field parameter (M), permeability parameter (K) and Prandtl number (Pr) on velocity distribution of dusty fluid and temperature distribution are discussed graphically with the help of the tables. ','','MHD, free convective flow, Maxwell model, dusty fluid ','Santosh Kumar Srivastava and R. K. Khare','115-123','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','73','2014-10-07 14:26:20','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1278,'EPQ Model with Price Dependent Demand and Backlogging Under Imprecise Environment','In the present work, a production model is considered, with selling price dependent demand under imprecise environment. Today, when market trend has changed to such a large extent, it becomes imperative that we take demand depends on selling price. Shortages are permitted with complete backlogging. In this model, finite planning horizon has