cating the formation of free radical intermediates during the course of reaction. The most probable reactive species, in Ru(III) catalysed oxidation of amines, is assumed to be Mn(HSO4)2+ ion. Though it is known that Ru(III) in aqueous acid media exists in various forms[1-3]. [Ru(H2O)5Cl]2+ is considered to be the reactive catalytic species in the present studies because a reaction of RuCl3 takes place in a few seconds from [Ru(H2O)3Cl3] to [Ru(H2O)5Cl]2+ while its conversion to [Ru(H2O)6]3+ or Ru3+ (aq) takes place in several months[4]. The fractional order dependence in both [RNH2] and [Ru(III)] indicates the formation of the (tert ruthenium amine) complex, which has been confirmed by Lineweaver Birk\'s reciprocal plots of 1/k\' versus 1/[amine] and 1/k\' versus 1/[Ru(III)] and also by the shift in the absorption maximum of Ru(III) from 203.4 nm to 288.6 nm. ','','n-Butyl amine, Isobutyl amine, Sec butyl amine, Dimethyl amine, Trimethyl amine','Munesh Kumar,Dinesh Chandra Agarwal, Deepali Rani','125-139  ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','73','2014-10-18 15:33:18','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1281,'Ouch-Ouch or Itai-Itai Disease and Need of Cadmium Removal','As other elements are the part of soils composition in the same way heavy metals are also found in this naturally. Cadmium is also categorized as heavy metal. It is also found in the soil but in a very minute quantity. High concentrations are confined primarily in to polluted soil. This review emphasizes cadmium toxicity on plants with regards to ecological, physiological and biochemical aspects. Cadmium toxicity and problems concerning tolerance are discussed. Efforts have been made to compare the relative sensitivity of various plant groups. Cadmium is a non-essential heavy metal so it is considered as pollutant. Its presence in environment resulting from various agricultural, mining and industrial activities and also from the exhaust gases of automobiles. It may help in interdisciplinary studies to assess the ecological significance of metal stress.','','Phytoremediation, contaminated soils, chlorosis, cadmium, heavy metals, Detoxification; Cadmium ','Reshu Chaudhary and Pushpendra','141-146','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','73','2014-10-11 04:01:40','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1282,' Kinetics and Mechanism of Bromohydroxylation of Cinnamic acids in situ By Sodium BromateSodium Bisulphite reagent in aqueous Acetonitrile medium','The kinetics of bromohydroxylation of cinnamic acids with HOBr, produced in situ from sodium bromatesodium bisulfite reagent has been investigated in aqueous acetonitrile (60:40 V/V) medium iodometrically over the temperature range 303K to 318K. Under the conditions [HOBr] << [CA] the plot of log [HOBr] versus time was linear indicating a first order dependence in [HOBr]. From the slopes of such plots, pseudofirst order rate constants (kobs/s1) have been evaluated at different initial [CA]. The plot of log kobs versus log [CA] was linear with a slope equal to 0.35, indicating the fractional order dependence in [CA]. This indicates the formation of an intermediate adduct between CA and HOBr, which could be a fourcentered cyclic encounter pair. This fact was further supported by linearity in I/kobs versus 1/[CA] plot with finite intercepts. This adduct is supposed to decompose in the rate determining step to yield the products. Addition of acrylonitrile to the reaction mixture did not show any polymerization, thereby ruling out the possibility of a free radical mechanism. 	The rates were unaffected by added Na2SO4 indicating that the reaction may be between two dipoles i.e. CA and HOBr. In this study HOBr has been well established to be the effective bromohydroxylating species. Based on the foregoing discussion, product analysis and stoichiometry, a plausible mechanism for the bromohydroxylation has been proposed.','','Cinnamic acid,Acrylonitrile,Sodium bromated, Sodium bisulphate etc','Munesh Kumar,Deepali Rani, Dinesh Chandra Agarwal,',' 147-158','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','73','2014-10-11 04:05:24','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1283,'  Analytic Continuation Formulas and Recurrence Relations  for the  Srivastava Karlsson Triple Hypergeometric Function  .','The present paper carries ahead my previous studies [9,10,11] of the  the Srivastava Karlsson triple  hypergeometric function   (see Srivastava and Karlsson [6]) in which I have deduced some analytic continuation formulas and recurrence relation for this function.','','Srivastava Karlsson  function  , analytic continuation formula, recurrence relation, hypergeometric function.',' Lalit Mohan Upadhyaya',' 341-347','NO','','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','34','51','2014-10-12 08:01:56','E',1,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1284,' A Note on an Incomplete Lauricella Function of Matrix Arguments with Statistical Application','In the present  paper an attempt has been made to define the incomplete Lauricella function   of matrix arguments for real symmetric positive definite matrices and following  Exton [4, section 7.1.1, p. 291-221] it has been utilized to give the corresponding  matrix generalization of a generalized beta distribution given in the said section of Exton [4].','','incomplete beta function, incomplete Lauricella function, generalized beta distribution, matrix arguments.',' Lalit Mohan Upadhyaya',' 785-792','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','30','53','2014-10-12 08:10:18','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1285,'A COMPARATIVE STUDY OF KINETICS OF OXIDATION OF PHENETOLE AND Di-n-Butyl ether by   ion in acidic medium',' The Ag (1) catalysed oxidation of phenetole and di-n-butyl ether by   ion was found to be first order in   and zero order in each substrate. Various energy parameters have been calculated. The salt effect is found to be negative. The rate constant is found to be increased with an increase in the concentration of H2SO4 e.g. - [H+], The reaction was found to be suppressed by allyl acetate, A redical mechanism has been proposed and corresponding rate expression is derived.','','Radical Mechanism, ethers.','Monika Sharma, P.K. Sharma',' 159-173','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','81','2014-10-18 16:13:37','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1286,' Challenges in Research and Higher Education System','In the last few decades there had been a thrust on the development of human resource as an important resource. This recourse, besides material resources, contributes substantially to the richness of a nation. In order to exploit this resource there had been a quantum change in the recent past, in the system of education in India. India placed with the advanced countries and the largest exporter of technically trained manpower in the field of software engineering and information technology. Education remained at prime positions in our country since ages. After independence, there was exponential growth in the number of universities, colleges and the student enrollment. However, modern era of science and technology added new dimensions to the meaning of research and education. ','','Cadmium, Heavy Metals, Phytoremediation, Contaminated Soils, Chlorosis  ','Reshu Chaudhary, Pushpendra and Reena Kumari','175-179    ','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','81','2015-01-05 16:55:18','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1287,' An Inventory Model For Perishable Items With Lost Sales And Time Varying Demand','In this paper, we developed a two-warehouse production model under the fuzzy environment. Demand rate is time dependent. Production rate is demand dependent and greater than the demand rate. Inflation is also taken into this consideration. Shortages are allowed and partially backlogged. The model is developed in both crisp and fuzzy sense. All the costs are taken as fuzzy triangular numbers. Numerical examples for both the models and sensitivity analysis are illustrated this model.','','Inflation, shortages, preservation technology',' Vineet Kumar, S.R. Singh','227-236','NO','','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','39','72','2014-10-21 16:02:32','E',4,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1288,' SCOURGE OF NAXALISM IN INDIA: SOCIO-ECONOMIC PERSPECTIVES','The present paper aims to discuss the origin and rise of the problem of naxalism in India. We have discussed the various causes of its origin and the ongoing various government initiatives to curb this menace. An analysis of the other related phenomenon from the ideological point of view has also been done to arrive at certain conclusions in the paper.','','',' Amitabh Bhatt',' 224-240','NO','','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2014-11-04 10:01:19','E',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1289,' ','','','',' ',' ','NO','','International Journal of Education and Allied Sciences','22','24','2014-11-04 10:01:40','E',7,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1291,' Bio-Chemical investigation of Echinops cornigerus   ','Echinops species are medicinally important, so we take unexplored species, Echinops cornigerus. Seven components Betulinic acid, Olenolic acid,  &#946;-amyrin, Luteolin, Lupeol, Apigenin and Apigenin-7-O-&#946;-D-glucoside are isolated first time from Echinops cornigerus and identified from their physicochemical data.  ','','Echinops cornigerus, Betulinic acid, Olenolic acid, &#946;-amyrin, Luteolin,\r\nLupeol,Apigenin and Apigenin-7-O-&#946;-D-glucoside\r\n  ','  S. Negi,  D. Singhal, H.V. Pant, H. C. Joshi, R. Dhoundiyal & A. K. Gupta  ',' 180-187    ','YES','ITAS 42 03.pdf','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','81','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1292,' Vibrational Spectral studies and thermodynamic functions of 6,7 Dimethoxy 1,2,3,4 tetrahydroisoquinoline-3-carboxylic acid hydrochloride molecule','Investigations of FTIR absorption spectra (4000400 cm1) and FT-Raman spectra (40050 cm1) of 6,7 Dimethoxy 1,2,3,4 tetrahydroisoquinoline-3-carboxylic acid hydrochloride molecule are presented. The vibrational spectra are analyzed assuming CS point group for the molecule and in term of fundamental and their overtones. The thermodynamic parameter have been calculated using vibrational frequencies and the effect of temperature on thermodynamic parameter have also been discussed','','Vibrational Spectral. and thermodynamic functions ','B.S. Yadav, Richa Sharma',' 189-203','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','81','2014-12-26 17:11:28','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1293,' FTIR, FT-Raman, and molecular structure investigation of   5-chloro-2,3-dihydroxy-pyridine: A combined experimental and theoretical study','In the present work, the experimental and theoretical vibrational spectra  of 5-chloro-2,3-dihydroxy-pyridine(5,2,3-CDHP) were studied. FTIR  spectra of (5,2,3-CDHP) in the solid phase was recorded in the region 4000400 cm-1 . The structural and spectroscopic data of the molecule in the ground state were calculated by using Hartree-Fock and density functional method (B3LYP) with  6-31+G(d,p)  basis set. The scaled values have been compared with experimental FTIR . The observed and calculated frequencies are found to be in good agreement. The mulliken charges and van der walls radii for the compound 5,2,3-CDHP is also discussed.','',':  5-chloro-2,3-dihydroxy-pyridine, FTIR and FT-Raman spectra, Vibrational frequencies, HF and DFT.\r\n','Vinita, Jayant Teotia, Seema, M.K.Yadav',' 205-221','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','81','2014-12-26 17:13:58','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1294,' Synthesis, Characterization and Spectral Studies of Noble Heterobinuclear Complexes of Transition Metal Ions and their Biological Activity',' Some noble heterobinuclear complexes of transition metal ions with bis (salicylaldehyde)malonyl-dihydrazone in the presence of 5-nitroindazole Cu(II) / Ni(II)- chloride of the type [ML1 M`L2 Cl2]  or [ML1FeL2Cl2]Cl, where M = Ni(II), Cu(II) and M\'= Mn(II), Co(II), have been prepared. All the complexes have been characterized by IR, UV vis and EPR spectroscopy, elemental analysis, magnetic moment and molar conductance measurement. Spectral studies and magnetic moment measurement in DMF suggest the covalent nature of the complexes, except the [ML1FeL2Cl2]Cl complex which is 1:1 electrolyte. An octahedral geometry is proposed for M` and square planer for M for the heterobinuclear complexes. The low value of magnetic moment and overlapping EPR signals are due to spin crossover since both of the metals have unpaired electrons with same molecular symmetry. The lowering of the magnetic moment has been discussed. The biological activity (antifungal and antibacterial) of the represented compounds has been studied.','','Heterobinuclear complexes, Malonyldihydrazone, 5-Nitroindazole, Biological activity.',' Vinay Phogat, Subash Malik',' 223-230','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','81','2014-12-26 17:16:10','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1295,' Molecular polarizabilities of tetraphenylporphyrin and their derivatives','Tetraphenylporphyrin, abbreviated TPP or H2TPP, is a synthetic heterocyclic compound that resembles naturally occurring porphyrins. Porphyrins are dyes and cofactors found in hemoglobin and cytochromes and are related to chlorophyll and vitamin B12. The study of naturally occurring porphyrins is complicated by their low symmetry and the presence of polar substituents. Tetraphenylporphyrin is hydrophobic, symmetrically substituted, and easily synthesized. The compound is a dark purple solid that dissolves in nonpolar organic solvents such as chloroform and benzene. The molecular polarizabilities of tetraphenylporphyrin and their derivatives were calculated by using semi-empirical                 function method and Miller and Savchiks methods. The results were compared with the molecular polarizability calculated using the Lorentz-Lorentz formula. It is observed that there is a reasonable agreement between the theoretical and the experimental values.','','Polarizability; Tetraphenylporphyrin,   function model.','R. P. Semwal and Vivek Rawat',' 231-237','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','81','2014-12-26 17:17:57','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1296,' Effect of Time Value of Money on an Inventory System with Partial Backlogging ','We discussed an inventory model for decaying items with inflation induced demand over a finite planning horizon. The demand rate is assumed to be a function of inflation; shortages are allowed and completely backlogged. The stock is assumed to undergo deterioration as soon as it is produced. The effect of inflation is also considered. Holding cost is taken as variable. Optimal solution for proposed model is derived by minimizing the total cost. Results have been validated with the help of a numerical example. The whole research caters to put forward some aspects of an inventory model with some real world considerations and market deliberations.','','PET waste, Aminolysis,   Antifungal agents, MIC',' Anubha Goyal, S K  Soan',' 239-248','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','81','2014-12-26 17:20:11','E',2,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1297,' Learning Problem Solving Between Students (Girl & Boy)','Research proposal: The goal of this article is the survey on the comparative the learning problem solving between students (girls and boys).\r\nMethodology: In this study to measure the survey, a standardized questionnaire is used. Size of sample were 168 students in academic year 2012 that to be referenced to the schools of Iran in Qom city.\r\nFinding: The comparison frequency distribution scores pre-test and post-test indicate that the most of students in experimental group are in high (43%) and very high (44%) range of scores. Frequency distribution in control group show that the most of students are in very low (25%) and low (61%) range of scores. Maan Witney U test indicate that Experimental group has higher mean score in comparison with Control group in development of problem solving scale (p=0.000<0.01) which is more than 99 percent confidence level.\r\nResult: This study was conducted in the city of Qom in order to find the result of promote problem solving in students (girls and boys) & (Experimental and Control Groups) questionnaire was used as research instrument. This instrument was collected from the sample data of 168 students (boys & girls). Further the hypotheses were analyzed with statistical sample and finally conclusion of the analysis is given.\r\n','','Learning, Problem Solving, Experimental& Control Groups, Students, Pre-Test & Post-Test','Sedigheh Sadat Moein, Nafiseh Khodamoradi',' 121-130','YES','1 Sedigheh Sadat Moein & Nafiseh Khodamoradi.docx','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','42','82','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1298,' Psycho-Social Environment and HIV/AIDS in India','The present study attempts to review the current state of knowledge on issues relating to the psycho-social environment in which the HIV/AIDS epidemic is breathing in India. A well known but little understood fact is the complex relationship between psycho-social environment and the spread of HIV/AIDS. Information, education and communication efforts and behavioral change strategies about practicing safe sex cannot produce the desirable effect if these efforts are not contextualized within the risk behaviors. In this context some of the social factors are poverty and socio- economic- status, mobility of the Population, HIV Surveillance in injection drug use, young population, evaluation of knowledge and awareness, discrimination and human rights. Depression and other psychological effects were also found in HIV/AIDS patients. So, it is very important for the rehabilitation professionals to recognize the major social and psychological issues that appear at different stages of HIV/AIDS infection.','','HIV/AIDS, Psycho-Social Environment',' P. S. N. Tiwari, Preeti Shahi',' 131-138','YES','2 p s n tiwari preeti shahi.docx','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','42','82','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1299,' Law and cooperative Movement in British India ','- ','','- ',' B.S Gautam ',' 139-152','NO','','International Journal of Education and Information Sciences','42','82','2015-02-03 11:22:26','E',11,'','',NULL,'pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1300,' A Study of Axial Viscosity Variation on Non-Newtonian Flow of Blood in an Artery with Mild Stenosis','The objective of this present mathematical model is to investigate the axial variation of blood viscosity caused by accumulation of red cells with mild stenosis for the blood flow through an artery using Power-law fluid model. The expressions for dimensionless resistance to flow and wall shear stress have been obtained. Effect of stenosis size and axial variation of viscosity in blood flow is also discussed graphically. All the flow characteristics are found to be affected by the presence of stenosis and axial variation of viscosity of blood. Graphs are obtained by using MATLAB.','','249-258','Stuti Gupta , Mukesh Gupta ,S.P. Singh ',' Blood Flow, Blood Viscosity, Power-law fluid, Resistance to flow and Wall shear stress.','NO','','International Transactions in Applied Sciences','44','8