it as quadratic dependent on the frequency of advertisement and time. The shortages are allowed at the end of replenishment cycle and partially backlogged. A permissible delay period is allowed by the vendor to buyer. An allowed trade credit period works as an incentive tool for the buyer and as a promotional tool for the vendor. Three different cases based on allowed trade credit period are discussed in the model. Numerical example for different cases and sensitivity analysis with respect to different system parameter are presented to illustrate the model. The convexity of the total cost function has also been shown with the help of graphs.','','Deterioration, Permissible Delay,\r\nWeibull Type Demand, Shortages,\r\nPartial Backlogging, Inflation',' Abhinav Goel, Mohd. Aftab Ali','167-190','NO','No file','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','78','125','2021-09-03 03:39:50','E',4,'aftabkhan307@gmail.com','Department of Mathematics, Shri Venkateshwara University, Gajraula','','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1439,'A Literature Review on Simulation Models to Deal with The Multi- Echelon Inventory Control System','Inventory management is a key lever in supply chain\r\nmanagement. The ability to manage inventory, businesses can\r\navoid high inventory levels, while providing a high level of\r\ncustomer care. With the current increase in the complexity of the\r\nsupply chain, multi-level inventory management has become a\r\nchallenging and interesting area of research. In particular, the\r\nintegration of the entire system, which allows you to manage the\r\ninter-dependencies between the various parts of the supply\r\nchain. Today is the day, to solve the problem of multi-level\r\ninventory control; by means of analytical models is not enough\r\nanymore. Many researchers have developed simulation models\r\nto overcome the limitations, a mathematical model representing\r\nthe dynamic behavior of the various parameters that are\r\ninvolved in the multi-level inventory systems. In this article an\r\noverview is given for the use of modeling in order to create a\r\nmulti-level inventory management decision. Classifications of\r\nthe different simulation models of multi-echelon inventory\r\ncharacter of the systems that are used in the literature are also\r\nidentified.','','Simulation, Multi-\r\nechelon inventory\r\n\r\nsystems, Inventory\r\ncontrol, Supply chain\r\nmanagement','Sandeep Kumar','191-206','NO','No file','International Journal of Operations Research and Optimization','78','125','2021-09-03 03:44:19','E',4,'drsk79@gmail.com','Department of AS & H, Dewan V. S. Institute of Technology, Meerut','','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1441,' A TWO IDENTICAL UNIT STANDBY SYSTEM WITH GENRAL LIFE-TIME DISTRIBUTION AND CORRELATED WORKING AND REST-TIME OF OPERATOR','The present paper deals with the profit function analysis of a two-identical unit Standby system model with the concept of working and rest-time of the operator (different from repair facility). The working and rest-time of the operator are considered to be random variables having their joint distribution as bi-variate exponential. The failure time distribution of operative unit is taken as general whereas  the repair time distribution is taken as exponential. The system model is analyzed by using the regenerative point technique. The graphical behavior of MTSF and profit function have also been studied.','','Redundant System, Regenerative Point Technique,  Reliability, MTSF, Availability',' AMARDEEP SINGH AND ALKA CHAUDHARY',' 127-136','NO','No file','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','63','116','2022-07-11 07:57:08','E',1,'amrdeep.stats@gmail.com',' MEERUT COLLEGE MEERUT','','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1442,' Model for Deteriorating Items under the Effect of Inflation and Trade Credit.   ','In this paper an EOQ model for deteriorating items is developed with the rate of demand as constant. Shortage is allowed with partial backlogging. This model aids in maximizing the total profit by finding optimal selling price and time. Some numerical examples have been carried out to illustrate the model and its significant features. Sensitivity is also given with respect to different parameters to study the effect on total profit.    ','','Deterioration, Shortage, partial backlogging Trade credits.   ','    S. K .Shon and Satyarth Prakash Maurya    ',' 25-40      ','NO','No file','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','62','109','2022-07-25 11:40:39','E',1,'sksvishnu@gmail.com',' Department of Mathematics , Vardhaman College , Bijnor   ',' N/A   ','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1443,' Order level inventory model with Weibull distribution Deterioration and Shortages under Trade Credit','In this paper an order level inventory model for deteriorating items has been developed.  Deteriorating rate is taken as two parameter Weibull distribution. Holding cost is taken as time dependent. We consider the situation that the buyer is asked to pay the entire amount of contract to the vendor in advanced before the delivery of goods. Moreover, discount is considered by the retailer if the entire purchasing cost is paid by the buyer in advanced. EOQ models are developed with full numerical illustrations, convexity and sensitivity analysis for decaying product under different conditions. ','','Deterioration, Time dependent holding cost, Trade credits',' S. K. Shon and Satyarth Prakash Maurya ',' 105-116','NO','No file','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','62','110','2022-07-16 12:10:58','E',1,'sksvishnu@gmail.com',' Department of Mathematics , Vardhaman College , Bijnor.',' N/A','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1444,' An EPQ model for deteriorating items with exponential demand under inflation','In this paper a production model for deteriorating items with exponential demand under inflation has been developed. Production rate is taken as demand dependent. The deterioration rate is taken as a two-parameter Weibull distribution. The main aim of the study is to minimize the total cost. Results are illustrated with numerical example and shown with graphically. Also the sensitivity analysis of various parameters is discussed.\r\n\r\n','','Deterioration, two-parameter Weibull distribution, inflation',' S. K. Shon, Satyam Kumar Sharma',' 117-125','NO','No file','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','62','110','2022-07-16 12:16:19','E',1,'sksvishnu@gmail.com',' Department of Mathematics , Vardhaman College , Bijnor.',' N/A','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1446,'<p>\r\n	Sutra-based Methods for Multiplication, Square, and Cube Generalization and Rationale</p>\r\n','<p>\r\n	P. Swm Bhrat Kria TrthaJ continued the Bharatiya tradition of discussing various alternative methods for multiplication, squaring, and cubing in the book &quot;Vedic Mathematics, &quot;where he elaborated on these methods is using the stras. This paper first focuses on generalizing these sutra-based methods, otherwise discussed as the cases with illustrations only. The rationale for these generalized forms is attested to in each case.</p>\r\n','<div>\r\n	[1]. Brhmasphuasiddhntah: Tr. V. D. Heroor, Chinmaya International Foundation Shodha Sansthan, Ernakulam, Kerala, India (2014), ISBN 978-93-80864-198.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[2]. Gaita Kaumud Part I: Ed. Padmakara Dvivedi, Sarasvati Bhavana Text 57, Banaras, India (1936).</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[3]. Gaitasrasagraha: Tr. Padmavathamma, Sri Sidhanta Kirthi Granthamala, Hombuja, Karnataka, India (2000).</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[4]. History of Hindu Mathematics: Bibhutibhushan Datta and A. N. Singh, Vol I, Bharatiya Kala Prakashan, Delhi, India, (2001), ISBN 81-86050-86-8.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[5]. Llvat Part I: Tr and Ed. A. B. Padmanabha Rao, Chinmaya International Foundation Shodha Sansthan, Ernakulam, Kerala, India (2014), ISBN 978-9380864-18-1.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[6]. A Modern Introduction to Ancient Indian Mathematics: T. S. Bhanu Murthy, Wiley Eastern Limited, (1992), ISBN 81-224-0371-9.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[7]. Pagaitam: Ed. Kripa Shankar Shukla, Department of Mathematics and Astronomy, Lucknow University, India (1959).</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[8]. Vedic Mathematics (VM), Swami Bharati Krishna Tirtha Ji, Ed. Dr V. S. Agrawala, Motilal Banarsidass, (1981).</div>\r\n','Indian contributions, Vedic mathematics, sutra   ','    Shriram Chauthaiwale   ',' 1-8    ','NO','1. Shriram Chauthaiwale-N.pdf','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','82','129','2023-07-18 12:49:06','E',1,'vedicganit.shriram@gmail.com',' Lecturer (Rt), Amolakchand College Yavatmal (M H)   ','','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1447,' Vedic Conversion of Auxiliary Fractions into Decimal Values ','<p>\r\n	Swami Bharati Krishna Tirthji (1884 &ndash; 1960) has shown the easiest way to convert the fraction whose denominator ends with 1, 3, 7 or 9 into its decimal form in a single line, by converting the fraction into a small auxiliary fraction. The same technique has been used in this paper for the fractions whose denominator is ending with 2,4,6,8 as well as 5. In this way, decimal conversion of any fraction whose denominator is a number ending with any of 1 to 9 can be easily done.</p>\r\n','<div>\r\n	[1]. Magical World of Mathematics by Shri. V. G. Unkalkar Vandana publishers (Nov. 2019).</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[2]. Vedic Mathematics by Shri. Swami Bharti KrishnaTirth, Motilal Banarasidas publishers(1994)</div>\r\n','Reciprocals, Auxilary Functions, Prime Numbers ','  Vishwanath Unkalkar  , Komal Asrani  ','9-13','NO','SodaPDF-converted-02 ITMSC 141-converted.pdf','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','82','129','2022-12-17 14:53:47','E',1,'unkalkar@yahoo.com',' VidyaBharati,SSUN,JKMS,  2 BBDNIIT,Lucknow ','','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1448,'<p>\r\n	Modern Mathematics and Its Fulfilment in Maharishi Vedic Mathematics, the Mathematics of Consciousness</p>\r\n','<p>\r\n	Science studies patterns of the structure and behaviour of the natural world. Mathematics is essential to science because it studies the abstract properties of those patterns, which do not exist in the physical world but rather only in the consciousness of the mathematician. The nature of these patterns and how they are structured in consciousness is the purview of Maharishi Vedic Mathematics. The applied aspect of Maharishi Vedic Mathematics is the practice of the Transcendental Meditation technique, which enlivens the consciousness of the mathematician and supports the qualities of consciousness necessary for research in mathematics. We indicate directions for further research in the study of these areas.</p>\r\n','<div>\r\n	[1]. Calinger, R., ed. (1982). Classics of Mathematics. Oak Park, IL: Moore Publishing Company.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[2]. Corazza, Paul. (2015). Addressing The Problem of Large Cardinals with Vedic Wisdom. International Journal of Mathematics and Consciousness 1, 66&ndash;89.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[3]. Gorini, C.A. (1997). How Maharishi Vedic Science Answers the Questions of the Unreasonable Effectiveness of Mathematics in the Sciences. Modern Science and Vedic Science 7, 181&ndash;190.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[4]. Gorini, C.A. (2017) Geometry for the Artist: An Interdisciplinary Consciousness-Based Course. International Journal of Mathematics and Consciousness 3, 1&ndash;32.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[5]. Hagelin, J.S. (1987). Is consciousness the unified field? A field theorist&rsquo;s perspective.&rdquo; Modern Science and Vedic Science1, 29&ndash;87.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[6]. Maharishi Mahesh Yogi. (1975). On the Bhagavad-Gita: A New Translation and Commentary. Penguin Books.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[7]. Maharishi MaheshYogi. (1996).Maharishi&rsquo;s Absolute Theory of Defence. India: Age of Enlightenment Publications.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[8]. Nader, Tony (2015), Consciousness Is All There Is: A Mathematical Approach with Applications. International Journal of Mathematics and Consciousness 1, 1&ndash;65.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[9]. Nidich, S.I.; and Nidich, R.J.(1989). Increased academic achievement at Maharishi School of the Age of Enlightenment: A replication study. Education109, 302&ndash;304.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[10]. Nidich, Sanford; Mjasiri, Shujaa; Nidich, Randi; Rainforth, Maxwell; Grant, James; Valosek, Laurent; Chang, Walter; and Zigler, Ronald L. (2011). Academic achievement and Transcendental Meditation: A study with at-risk urban middle school students. Education131, 556&ndash;564.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[11]. Orme-Johnson, D.; Dillbeck, M.; Chalmers, R.; and Farrow, J., eds. (1976&ndash;2020). Scientific research on the Transcendental Meditation Programme, Collected Papers Volumes 1&ndash;8. Fairfield, Iowa:MUM Press.</div>\r\n','Modern Mathematics  ',' Catherine A. Gorini,and Susan Runkle  ','15-20  ','NO','3. Catherine A. Gorini1, Susan Runkle2 (1).pdf','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','82','129','2023-07-18 12:49:17','E',1,'cgorini@miu.edu',' Maharishi International University  ','','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1449,'<p>\r\n	Diary of Swami Bharati Krishna Tirtha Ji on Vedic Mathematics: A Review</p>\r\n','<p>\r\n	Vedic Mathematics, an ancient discipline of knowledge, remained dormant for centuries, now witnessing a revival thanks to Swami Bharati Krishna Tirtha Ji, who followed the Indian legacy of expressing thought processes, concepts, ideas in the sutras format. Swami Ji applied this format for the subject &lsquo;Mathematics&rsquo; first time. Hence, his diary is an invaluable treasure and is of historical importance. In the light of above thoughts in the literature of Swami Ji, the Vedic Mathematics may be benefitted to the disciplines for teaching and learning of Mathematics in schools and higher educational institutions. In this Paper, the diary from January 1, 1951, to December 31, 1951, of Swami Ji on Vedic Mathematics has been reviewed in the context of disciplines namely, arithmetic, algebra, geometry, calculus, coordinate geometry, astrology, etc. The authors elaborated on all the 16 sutras and 13 up-sutras to cover mentioned topics and the corresponding page numbers of the diary.</p>\r\n','<div>\r\n	[1]. Kansara, N.M.,Vedic Sources of Vedic Mathematics, Journal titled &lsquo;Sambodhi&rsquo; in Vol. XXIII, (2000).</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[2]. Kapoor, S.K., Practice Vedic Mathematics, Lotus Press, New Delhi(ISBN 81-89093-82-7), (2015).</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[3]. Puri, N., Ancient Vedic Mathematics band 1, 2, 3, 4 &amp; 5 Maths of smiles, Spiritual Study Group, Roorkee (1990).</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[4]. Tirth ji, Swami Bharti Krishan Maharaj, Vedic Metaphysics, Moti Lal Banarasi Das, Delhi (1978).</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[5]. Tirth ji, Swami Bharti Krishan, Diary of Vedic Mathematics onwebsite vedicmathsindia.org from 01-01-1951 to 31-12-1951,(1951)</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[6]. Tirth ji, Swami Bharti Krishan, Vedic Mathematics,Moti Lal Banarasi Das, New Delhi (ISBN 978-81-208-2173-6), (1965)</div>\r\n','Ancient, Vedic Mathematics, Sutras, Up-sutras  ',' Rakesh Bhatia, Shivraj Singh, Dinesh Kumar Sharma  ','21-28  ','NO','4. Rakesh Bhatia1,Shivraj Singh2, Dinesh Kumar Sharma3.pdf','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','82','129','2023-07-18 12:49:31','E',1,'rakeshbhatia106@gmail.com',' Maharaja Agrasan University, Baddi Solan Himachal Pradesh  ','','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1450,' The Implementation of Vedic Mathematics to Algebra:  Factorization ','<p>\r\n	Vedic mathematics is an intriguing, expedient, basic sensible and vital piece of our antiquated Indian culture utilizing customary math, which finds its starting point in our Vedas particularly &quot;Atharva Veda&quot; and is predominantly dependent on 16 standards called &quot;Sutras&quot; and 13 Sub-Sutras. Applied to pretty much every part of science. The fascinating part with regards to Vedic mathematics is, you can generally look at your computation and know whether you are correct or wrong in couple of moments and that makes it more charming. Here, talk about a few utilizations of Vedic mathematics in one of its field for example Polynomial math and perceive how it saves a great deal of time and endeavors in tackling the issues.</p>\r\n','<div>\r\n	[1]. Goel, A. (2006), &ldquo;Learn and teach mathematics&rdquo;, Authors Press, Scholarly Books, New Delhi.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[2]. J.T. Glover: &ldquo;Vedic mathematics for schools Book&rdquo;, Motilal Banarsidass Varanasi(India),http://www.mlbd.com.</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		[3]. Jagadguru Swami Sri Bharati Krisna Tirthaji (1986), Vedic Mathematics or Sixteen Simple Sutras from the Vedas. Motilal Banarasidas, Varanasi(India).</div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		[4]. Rajesh Kumar Thakur: &ldquo;Advanced Vedic Mathematics&rdquo;, Rupa Publications India Pvt. Ltd.</div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		[5]. Rajesh Kumar Thakur: &ldquo;The essentials of Vedic mathematics&rdquo;, Rupa Publications India Pvt. Ltd.</div>\r\n	<div>\r\n		[6]. Vedic Mathematics: Sixteen Simple Mathematical Formulae from the Veda. Delhi.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n','Sutras, Sub Sutras, Algebra ','  Pankaj Tiwari1 , Aradhana Dutt Jauhari ','29-34','NO','SodaPDF-converted-05 ITMSC 141-converted.pdf','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','82','129','2022-12-17 14:57:17','E',1,'tiwaripankaj9716@gmail.com',' Galgotias University, Greater Noida, Gautam Buddha Nagar ','','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1451,'<p>\r\n	DEVELOPMENT OF TRIGONOMETRIC FUNCTIONS IN ANCIENT AND MEDIEVAL INDIA</p>\r\n','<p>\r\n	India has a rich tradition of Vedic trigonometry. The knowledge of trigonometry was necessary for the study of the motion of planets etc. in mathematical astrology. Vedictrigonometry was known as jyotpatti-ganita (The last chapter inGoladhyaya andconsists of the 25 hloka),in ancient days. Hindu mathematicians were usedthe JyotPattiganita to solve the astronomical problem. And nowadays trigonometry is an essential part of mathematics. Hindu mathematicians introduced and usually employed three trigonometric functions namely jya, Kotijya, and utkramajya. This article explores the approachable mathematical method behind the development of trigonometric functions as well as the method of interpolating the three basic trigonometric formulas.</p>\r\n','',' Vedic, jyotpatti- ganita, mathematical astrology, jya,kotijya,utkramajya)\r\n  ','   Dr. Ajay Kumar Saini  ',' 35-42  ','NO','SodaPDF-converted-06 ITMSC 141-converted.pdf','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','82','129','2023-07-18 12:49:41','E',1,'drajaysaini290@gmail.com',' Dept of mathematics C.C.S. University, Meerut,   ','','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1452,' Learning Vedic Mathematics Gives an Edge to Young Aspirants  in Competitive Examination  ','<p>\r\n	Vedic mathematics is the name given to the ancient system of Indian mathematics that provides all mathematical operation and calculations in faster way The purpose of the present study is to study the effectiveness of the Vedic mathematics in terms of students learning mathematics in competitive examinations, students find difficult to solve the aptitude questions effectively with very less or small time durations. A sample of 60 management students (BBA) studying at IMS Noida were selected randomly and divided into two groups namely experimental and control group. The students of experimental group were taught square and square root through Vedic mathematics whereas the control groups were taught through traditional method. The study revealed that the mean score of experimental group is greater than the controlled group (score was compared using t-test) which proves that Vedic mathematics is more effective than conventional method. Through Vedic Mathematics, students would be able to solve lengthy calculations within fraction of seconds and also understand the intricacies in the way the number system works thereby strengthening your fundamentals. This will not just improve your speed and efficiency but also ensure that you save a lot of time during those vital hours of the examination.</p>\r\n','','Introduction, Vedic maths sutras, T-test, Methodology\r\n  ','Mini Verma  ','43-48  ','YES','SodaPDF-converted-07 ITMSC 141-converted.pdf','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','82','130','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',1,'mini.verma@imsnoida.com',' IMS Noida, Sector 62 CCS UNIVERSITY  ','','pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1457,'Justification for Aryabha as Value of Pi Ratio    ','<p>\r\n	At the age of 23 Aryabhaa wrote the book titled ryabhaaiya (AB) in which 33 verses under the caption gaitapada  pertain to mathematics. In the 10th verse of the chapter he stated the relationship between the circumference of a circle and its diameter which leads to the approximate value of Pi ratio as  = 3.1416. This paper discusses a possible method adopted by Aryabhata for the said values of the circumference and diameter by extending the relationship between the length of a side of an inscribed hexagon and the circles diameter stated in the previous 9 th verse.</p>\r\n','<div>\r\n	[1]. ryabhaaya of ryabhaa: (With com of Bhaskara I and Someshvara), EdK. S. Shukla, INSA,</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	New Delhi, (1976).</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[2]. Geometry in Ancient and Medieval India: T A Sarasvati Amma, Motilal Banarsidass Publishers</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	Pvt Ltd, Delhi, (Ed 1999).</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[3].  (, , ):  , ,  , 2009.(In Marathi)</div>\r\n',' ryabhaa, ryabhaaya, Inscribed polygon, Pi ratio     ','Sanjay Madhukararao Deshpande and Shriram Chauthaiwale      ','49-52    ','NO','SodaPDF-converted-08 ITMSC 141-converted.pdf','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','82','130','2022-12-17 15:14:27','E',1,'vedicganit.shriram@gmail.com',' Dept. of Mathematics, Bhavabhuti Mahavidyalaya, Amgaon (MH)      ','','pending',NULL,NULL,'subscription',NULL),(1458,' Mathematical Operations in Vedas   ','<p>\r\n	The Vedas are ancient religious and philosophical scriptures that originated in India. The term Veda is mostly used for four canonical Vedas : 1. gveda(V) 2.Smaveda(SV) 3.Yajurveda (YV) and 4. Atharvaveda(AV). Although the Vedas are not exclusively dealing with mathematics but many mathematical data and other mathematical methods are contained in Vedas. We have found enough examples that the is of Vedas, not only knew the addition and multiplication of smaller numbers but also of large numbers and they were well acquainted with following six mathematical operations: addition, subtraction, multiplication, division, square and square-root.</p>\r\n','<div>\r\n	<strong>Original Sources</strong></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[1]. Atharvaveda , Swami Dayanand Sansthan, New Delhi,</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[2]. Brhmasphuasiddhnta by Brahmagupta , Indian Institute of Astronomical and Sanskrit research, New Delhi,1966, Vol.I</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[3]. gveda. Swami Dayanand Sansthan, New Delhi,</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[4]. Smaveda, Swami Dayanand Sansthan, New Delhi,</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[5]. atpatha Brhmaa, Ed. A. Weber, Chowkhamba Press, Varanasi,1964</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[6]. Taittir&icirc;ya Sahit, Anand Shastri Dhupkar, Aundh, 1945</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[7]. Yajurveda, Swami Dayanand Sansthan, New Delhi,.7</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	<strong>Secondary Sources</strong></div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[1]. 24. Witzel,M.,&quot; The Development of the Vedic Canon and its Schools: The Social and PoliticalMilieu,1997, pp.257-348, (available on http//www.people.fas.harward.edu/~Witzel/canon.pdf)</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[2]. 9.Gupta, R. C. Six Type of Vedic Mathematics, Gaita Bhrat&icirc;, Vol.16,nos.1-4, pp5-15</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[3]. Bag, A.K. Mathematics in Ancient and Medieval India,Chaukhambha Orientalia, Varanasi 1979,pp.1-344</div>\r\n<div>\r\n	[4]. Bose D. 