\n	Zadeh, L. A. Fuzzy logic, Coumpter, 1988;21(4); 83-93</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	Zadeh, L.A. Fuzzy sets as a basis of theory of possibility&rdquo;, Fuzzy sets and systems.1978;1 ;3-28.</p>\r\n',' Sustainability, carbon emission, inventory, stock dependent, stock, price dependent, shortage, \r\npartial backlogging, preservation, environmental',' Surbhi Singhal, Akshika Rastogi, SR Singh and R.B. Singh',' 1-15','YES','Akshika ijicm.pdf','International Journal of Inventory Control and Management','88','136','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',5,'akshikastats@gmail.com',' Department of Statistics D. N. College, Meerut','','pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1485,'<p>\r\n	An EPQ Inventory Model with Green Techology and Multi Variable Demand under the Shortages and Volume Flexibility</p>\r\n','<p class=\"TextGaramond\" style=\"margin-left:1.0in;line-height:110%\">\r\n	<span lang=\"EN-IN\">A hectic life makes fitness difficult, especially if you consume chemicals. Knowing this fact, we have analyzed an economic production inventory model for deteriorating items. The manufacturing model is developed with green technology in order to produce eco-friendly products. The volume flexibility is taken into account. Multivariable demand rate has been taken into consideration which is dependent on selling price, green degree and green preferences of the customer. In response to the growing green preferences of customers, manufacturers should increase their investment in green technology. It is allowed to have shortages and all backlogs are fully backlogged. A closed-form solution has been provided for the optimal values of the green degree and replenishment cycle. In addition to analyzing the volatility of the system numerically and sensitivity-wise, the model can also provide some managerial insights in favor of the manufacturer to maintain customer satisfaction and increase profit.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n','<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Schrady, D. A., &ldquo;A deterministic inventory model for repairable items&rdquo;, Naval Research Logistics Quaterly, Vol. 14, No. 3, pp. 391- 398 (1967).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Nahmias, S. and Rivera, H., &ldquo;A deterministic model for repairable item inventory system with finite repaire rate&rdquo;, International Journal of Production Research, Vol. 17, No. 3, pp. 215-221 (1979).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Fleischmann, M., Bloemhof- Ruwaard,&nbsp; J. M., Dekker, R., Van Der Laan, E., Van Nunen, J. A. E. E. and Van Wassenhove, L. N., &ldquo;Quantitative models for reverse logistics: a review&rdquo;, European Journal of Operational Research, Vol.103, No. 1, pp. 1- 17 (1997).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	El Saadany, A. M.A.and Jaber, M. Y., &ldquo;A production/ remanufacturing inventory model with price and quality dependent return rate&rdquo;, Computers and Industrial Engineering, Vol. 58, No.3, pp. 352- 362 (2010).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Alamri, A. A., &ldquo;Theory and methodology on the global optimal solution to a general reverse logistics inventory model for deteriorating items and time varying rates&rdquo;, Computer and Industrial Engineering, Vol. 60, No. 2, pp. 236- 247 (2010).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Singh, S. R. and Saxena, N., &ldquo;An optimal returned policy for a reverse logistics inventory model with backorders&rdquo;, Advances in Decision Science, Article ID 386598, 21 pages (2012).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Singh, S. R., Prasher L. and Saxena N. &ldquo;A centralized reverse chaneel structure with flexible manufacturing under the stock out situation&rdquo;, International Journal of Industrial Engineering Computations, Vol. 4, pp. 559- 570 (2013).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Singh, S. R. and Saxena, N., &ldquo;A closed loop supply chain system with flexible manufacturing and reverse logistics operation under shortages for deteriorating items&rdquo;, Procedia Technology, Vol. 10, pp. 330- 339 (2013).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Singh, S. R. and Saxena, N., &ldquo;An integrated inventory model with remanufacturing of secondary material under shortages&rdquo; Proceedings of 3rd International Conference on Recent Trends in Engineering &amp; Technology, pp. 354- 359, Elsevier, India (2014).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Hartley, R.V., Operations Research&ndash;A Managerial Emphasis, California: Good Year Publishing Company (1976).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Sarma, K.V.S., &ldquo;A Deterministic Order Level Inventory Model for Deteriorating Items with Two Storage Facilities&rdquo;, European Journal of Operational Research, Vol. 29, pp. 70&ndash;73 (1987).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Kumari R., Singh S. R. and Kumar N., &ldquo;<a href=\"http://scholar.google.co.in/citations?view_op=view_citation&amp;hl=en&amp;user=cYeizvkAAAAJ&amp;citation_for_view=cYeizvkAAAAJ:j8SEvjWlNXcC\">Two-warehouse inventory model for deteriorating items with partial backlogging under the conditions of permissible delay in payments</a>&rdquo;, Int. Trans. Math. Sci. Comput, Vol. 1, No. 1, pp. 123-134, (2008).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Singh S. R., Rathore H. and Saxena N., &ldquo;A two warehouse inventory model for deteriorating items with shortages under inflationary environment&rdquo;, Proceedings of&nbsp; 3rd International Conference on Recent Trends in Engineering &amp; Technology, Elsevier, pp.&nbsp; 385- 391, India (2014).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Chiu H. N. and Chen H. M., &ldquo;An optimal algorithm for solving the dynamic lot-sizing model with learning and forgetting in setups and production&rdquo;, International Journal of Production Economics, vol. 95, no. 2, pp. 179&ndash;193 (2005).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Kuo W.-H. and Yang D.-L., &ldquo;Minimizing the total completion time in a single-machine scheduling problem with a time-dependent learning effect,&rdquo; European Journal of Operational Research, vol. 174, no. 2, pp. 1184&ndash;1190 (2006).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Jaber, M.Y., Goyal, S.K., &amp; Imran, M., &ldquo;Economic production quantity model for items with imperfect quality subject to learning effects&rdquo;, International Journal of Production Economics, Vol-115, pp.143-150 (2008).</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Singh S.R., Jain S.&nbsp; and Pareek S., &ldquo;An imperfect quality items with learning and inflation under two limited storage capacity&rdquo;, International Journal of Industrial Engineering Computations, Vol. 4, pp. 1- 12 (2013).</p>\r\n','Inventory, EPQ model, green technology, multivariable demand, shortage, deterioration, volume flexibility ','  Subhash Chand Garg  and B. S. Kalra ',' 127-140  ','YES','Chp 01 Subhash Chand & BS Kalra.pdf','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','83','132','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',1,'schand.cbse@gmail.com',' Department of MathematicsMeerut College, Meerut ',' https://doi.org/10.58517/ITMSC.2022.15202','pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1486,' Inventory Model for Imperfect Quality Deteriorating Items with Carbon Tax Regulation','<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Emissions of carbon are one of the primary causes of global warming. Several countries are currently working on reducing carbon emissions. For many countries, carbon taxes and cap policies are the key mechanisms used to accomplish this goal.&nbsp;To deal with this issue, a sustainable economic production quantity (SEPQ) carbon tax and cap model is considered in order to control carbon emissions. Based on carbon emissions and defective rate, we present an integrated single-vendor single-buyer inventory model for deteriorating items with imperfect quality. Screening has been done on the produced units to find the imperfect units, but the screening rate is below or equal to the production rate and greater than demand. A secondary market buys the defective products at a discount price. In order to reduce work-in-process inventory and carbon emissions, the study aims to increase throughput times. We also examine the effect of carbon tax regulation on the potential emission reduction from the developed deteriorating item model.&nbsp;Results from the application of a numerical example and sensitivity analysis confirm the impact of carbon tax regulation on reducing carbon emissions.</p>\r\n','<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Singh, S. R., Kumar, N., &amp; Kumari, R. (2010). An inventory model for deteriorating items with shortages and stock-dependent demand under inflation for two-shops under one &nbsp;&nbsp;management.&nbsp;<em>Opsearch</em>,&nbsp;<em>47</em>(4), 311-329.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Hua, G., Cheng, T. C. E., &amp; Wang, S. (2011). Managing carbon footprints in inventory management.&nbsp;<em>International Journal of Production Economics</em>,&nbsp;<em>132</em>(2), 178-185.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Wahab, M. I. M., Mamun, S. M. H., &amp; Ongkunaruk, P. (2011). EOQ models for a coordinated&nbsp; two-level international supply chain considering imperfect items and environmental impact.&nbsp;<em>International Journal of Production Economics</em>,&nbsp;<em>134</em>(1), 151-158.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Singh, S. R., &amp; Singh, N. (2013). Green supply chain model with product remanufacturing under volume flexible environment.&nbsp;<em>Procedia Technology</em>,&nbsp;<em>10</em>, 216-226.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Toptal, A., &Ouml;zl&uuml;, H., &amp; Konur, D. (2014). Joint decisions on inventory replenishment and emission reduction investment under different emission regulations.&nbsp;<em>International&nbsp; journal of production research</em>,&nbsp;<em>52</em>(1), 243-269.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Qin, J., Bai, X., &amp; Xia, L. (2015). Sustainable Trade credit and replenishment policies under&nbsp; the cap-and-trade and carbon tax regulations.&nbsp;<em>Sustainability</em>,&nbsp;<em>7</em>(12), 16340-16361.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Hovelaque, V., &amp; Bironneau, L. (2015). The carbon-constrained EOQ model with carbon emission dependent demand.&nbsp;<em>International Journal of Production Economics</em>,&nbsp;<em>164</em>, 285-291.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Sarkar, B., Ganguly, B., Sarkar, M., &amp; Pareek, S. (2016). Effect of variable transportation and carbon emission in a three-echelon supply chain model.&nbsp;<em>Transportation Research Part E: Logistics and Transportation Review</em>,&nbsp;<em>91</em>, 112-128.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Jawla, P., &amp; Singh, S. (2016). A reverse logistic inventory model for imperfect production process with preservation technology investment under learning and inflationary environment.&nbsp;<em>Uncertain Supply Chain Management</em>,&nbsp;<em>4</em>(2), 107-122.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Bazan, E., Jaber, M. Y., &amp; Zanoni, S. (2017). Carbon emissions and energy effects on a two- level manufacturer-retailer closed-loop supply chain model with remanufacturing subject to different coordination mechanisms.&nbsp;<em>International Journal of Production &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; Economics</em>,&nbsp;<em>183</em>, 394-408.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Tiwari, S., Daryanto, Y., &amp; Wee, H. M. (2018). Sustainable inventory management with deteriorating and imperfect quality items considering carbon emission.&nbsp;<em>Journal of Cleaner Production</em>,&nbsp;<em>192</em>, 281-292.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Kung, K. Y., Huang, Y. D., Wee, H. M., &amp; Daryanto, Y. (2019). Production-inventory system for deteriorating items with machine breakdown, inspection, and partial backordering.&nbsp;<em>Mathematics</em>,&nbsp;<em>7</em>(7), 616.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	Bai, Q., Jin, M., &amp; Xu, X. (2019). Effects of carbon emission reduction on supply chain coordination with vendor-managed deteriorating product inventory.&nbsp;<em>International Journal of Production Economics</em>,&nbsp;<em>208</em>, 83-99.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	&nbsp;</p>\r\n','Inventory, Deteriorating items, Carbon emission, Imperfect production process, screening process',' S.R. Singh and Rinki Chaudhary',' 1-14','YES','No file','International Journal of Inventory Control and Management','85','138','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',5,'crinkichaudhary67@gmail.com',' Department of Mathematics C. C. S. University Meerut,  Meerut-250001(U.P) India ','','pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1487,' Impact of Green Design and trade credit with preservation  Technology for deteriorating items with shortage under  inflationary enviornment. ','<p>\r\n	The phenomenon of deterioration is a common phenomenon. However, it could become a major challenge for the business. An investment in preservation technology is by far the most influential move towards dealing with deterioration proficiently. Additionally, it is noticed that the demand pattern of many products is relevant on its availability and usability. Thus, considering demand of the product to be stock-dependent and selling price dependent is a more practical approach. Further, in case of deteriorating items, it is observed that the longer an item stays in the system the higher is its holding cost. Therefore, the model assumes the holding cost to be time varying. Hence, the proposed framework aims to develop an inventory model for deteriorating items with stockdependent and selling price dependent demand and time-varying holding cost under an investment in preservation technology with the effect of inflation and green design. It is observed that the formulations of different inventory models are done with unrealistic assumption that the retailer has to pay all the cost at the receiving time of the items. But usually the supplier allows a certain time period to settle the amount. So in this paper an effect has been made to combine all the above mentioned factors together to may the study closer to reality. The objective is to determine the optimal investment in preservation technology and the optimal cycle length so as to minimize the total cost. In this model shortage is fully backlogged. In this model I determined for minimizing the average total cost under the influence of inflation and time value of money. Numerical examples&nbsp;are used to illustrate the proposed model and a sensitivity analysis is carried out to study the effect of different parameters.</p>\r\n','<p>\r\n	A.A. Shaikh, L.E. C_ardenas Barr_on, A.K. Bhunia, and S. Tiwari (2019). &ldquo;An inventory model of a three parameter Weibull distributed deteriorating item with variable demand dependent on price and frequency of advertisement under trade credit&quot;, RAIRO-Operations Research, 53(3), 903-916.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	A.A. Shaikh, L.E. C_ardenas-Barr_on, and S. Tiwari (2019). &ldquo;A two-warehouse inventory model for non-instantaneous deteriorating items with interval-valued inventory costs and stock dependent demand under inationary conditions&quot;, Neural Computing and Applications, 31(6), 1931-1948.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	A. Khanna,et al. (2019). &ldquo;Optimizing preservation strategies for deteriorating items with time varying holding cost and stock dependent demand.&rdquo;. Yugoslav Journal of Operations Research 1-14.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	A.K. Bhunia, A.A. Shaikh, V. Dhaka, S. Pareek, and L.E. C_ardenas-Barr_on (2018), An application of Genetic Algorithm and PSO in an inventory model for single deteriorating item with variable demand dependent on marketing strategy and displayed stock level&quot;, Scientia Iranica, 25(3) 1641-1655.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	A.P. Tyagi, R.K. Pandey, and S. Singh,(2014). &ldquo;An optimal replenishment policy for non instantaneous deteriorati