 and shortages are allowed with partial backlogging, the occurrence of shortage which is a natural phenomenon, and the backlogging rate is exponential decreasing function of time. This study also assumed a production model with random rate of deterioration, probabilistic demand, and partial backlogging under volume flexibility. The probability density function of demand is negative exponential rate, which is a function of exponential distribution. Holding cost is a non-linear function of time. Numerical validation through illustration. This proposed study further can be extended with inflation and stochastic backorder rate.</p>\r\n','<ol>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Schweitzer, P. J. and Seidmann, A. (1991):</strong>Optimizing processing rates for flexible manufacturing systems,<em>Management Sciences, 37, 454-466.</em></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Silver, E. A. (1990):</strong>Deliberately slowing down output in a family production context,<em>International Journal of Production Research, 28, 17-27.</em></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Moon, I., Gallego, G. and Simchi-Levi, D. (1991):</strong>Controllable production rates in a family production context, <em>Production Research, 29, 2459-2470.</em></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Ramesh and Jayakumar (1991):</strong>Measurement of manufacturing flexibility a value based approach, <em>Operation Management, 10, 446-467.</em></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Gallego, G. (1993):</strong>Reduced production rate in the economic lot scheduling problem,<em>International Journal of Production Research, 31, 1035-1046.</em></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Silver, E. A. (1990):</strong>Deliberately slowing down output in a family production context,<em>International Journal of Production Research, 28, 17-27.</em></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Khouza, M. (1995):</strong>The economic production lot size model under volume flexibility, <em>Computers Operations Research, 22, 515-523.</em></li>\r\n	<li>\r\n		<strong>Sana, S. (2003):</strong>A stochastic EOQ policy