r the years, the employment of fuzzy logic systems in intelligent transportation systems, particularly autonomous vehicles (AV), has been on the rise. Due to sensor faults, chaotic, different kind of traffic, and changing weather conditions, we have to face navigation uncertainties, which in turn make driving challenging. Existing methods, such as Type-1 Fuzzy Logic Systems (T1FLS) and Type-2 Fuzzy Logic Systems (T2FLS) lack the granularity needed for highly dynamic, real-time applications in AVs. T1FLS assumes precise membership functions, which oversimplify uncertainty, whereas T2FLS provides additional flexibility through membership function uncertainty but falls short when confronted with higher-order, dynamic, and non-linear uncertainties. Type-3 Fuzzy Logic System (T3FLS) is gaining popularity in recent times. The shift from T2FLS to T3FLS is mainly due to better approximation capabilities and uncertainty handling capabilities. T2FLS is generally an extension of T3FLS. By utilizing its hierarchical uncertainty representation, T3FLS can generate more precise and reliable outputs for critical tasks such as collision avoidance, path planning, and speed control. This paper proposes a novel T3FLS framework designed specifically for decision-making in an autonomous vehicle in dynamic collision avoidance. The proposed system uses Explainable Artificial Intelligence (XAI) to enhance transparency and trust in AV operations, ensuring that the decisions made by the system are transparent and understandable. Together, these technologies fill the gaps that previous systems could not and make the way towards safer and more reliable autonomous driving. Such systems are what will be highly important to the development and deployment of moving into a world where autonomous automobiles are a modern part of transport.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n','<p>\r\n	1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Xu, I., Haque, M., &amp; Fu, S. (2024). <em>Driving the Future: AI in Transportati