Research and Innovation in Social Science, pp.5749&ndash;5756.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:1.0in;\">\r\n	<strong>19.&nbsp; </strong>Kumar &amp; Joshith (2024). <em>Vedic Mathematics for Sustainable Knowledge&hellip;</em> offers a comprehensive review of sutra applications</p>\r\n','Division, Urdhva-Tiryagbhyam sutra, Vedic Math, Arithmetic, Algebra   ','  Kavita Kumari 1, S.R. Singh2, Rashmi Yadav3* ',' 259-272  ','YES','kav paper with doi.pdf','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','99','162','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',1,'rashmi.y94@gmail.com',' Dept. of Mathematics, CCS University Meerut ',' https://doi.org/10.58517/ITMSC.2025.18211','pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1553,'<p>\r\n	Using Reference Pricing in Tribal Communities (SC, ST, OBC) and Comparison of Health Literacy among Females and Males in East Medinipur</p>\r\n','<p>\r\n	This paper investigates the mathematical modeling and empirical assessment of <em>reference pricing</em> as a cost-containment tool in health care delivery for marginalized communities (SC, ST, and OBC) in East Medinipur, and compares levels of health literacy between females and males within these groups. Using a cross-sectional household survey (n = 720) stratified by community and gender, we apply descriptive statistics, hypothesis testing (t-test, chi-square), and regression modeling to (a) measure the impact of implementing a reference pricing scheme on out-of-pocket (OOP) expenditure and service choice, and (b) test for statistically significant differences in health literacy scores between genders. Results show that reference pricing&mdash;modeled as a cap on reimbursement for selected services&mdash;reduces mean OOP by an estimated 18% (p &lt; .01) without large reductions in utilization, while health literacy scores are significantly lower among females than males (mean difference = 6.3 points on a 100-point scale; t = 5.12, p &lt; .001). Policy implications and limitations are discussed.</p>\r\n','