th awareness differences between male and female populations in rural Bengal. <em>Health Promotion Journal of India</em>, 11(1), 29&ndash;38.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	11.&nbsp;&nbsp; Pradhan, M. (2016). Public health policy and tribal communities: A review. <em>Indian Public Policy Journal</em>, 4(2), 92&ndash;104.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	12.&nbsp;&nbsp; Saha, R. (2022). Impact of economic background on healthcare utilisation in East Medinipur. <em>Bengal Economic Review</em>, 18(1), 72&ndash;84.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	13.&nbsp;&nbsp; Ghosh, T. (2018). Cost-effective health interventions for poor households. <em>Health Economics Insights</em>, 13(4), 115&ndash;124.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	14.&nbsp;&nbsp; Mishra, N., &amp; Tiwari, S. (2017). Understanding health literacy and its determinants in rural India. <em>Journal of Community Health</em>, 42(3), 543&ndash;552.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	15.&nbsp;&nbsp; Das, A. (2020). Role of community workers in improving health literacy among SC and ST groups. <em>Public Health Outreach Review</em>, 6(1), 33&ndash;39.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	16.&nbsp;&nbsp; Roy, B., &amp;Kar, P. (2021). Impact of awareness programmes on women&rsquo;s health behaviour in tribal villages. <em>Women and Development Journal</em>, 9(2), 101&ndash;111.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	17.&nbsp;&nbsp; National Sample Survey Office. (2018). <em>Household health expenditure in India (Report No. 574)</em>. Ministry of Statistics &amp;Programme Implementation.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	18.&nbsp;&nbsp; Chakraborty, P. (2019). Health inequality among backward classes: A district-level analysis. <em>Socio-Economic Studies of India</em>, 12(3), 144&ndash;156.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	19.&nbsp;&nbsp; United Nations Development Programme. (2020). <em>Human development report: Health and equity in South Asia</em>. UNDP.</p>\r\n<p style=\"margin-left:.5in;\">\r\n	20.&nbsp;&nbsp; Sinha, V. (2021). A comparative analysis of health-seeking behaviour in East Medinipur. <em>Journal of Regional Health Studies</em>, 8(2), 58&ndash;66.</p>\r\n','Reference pricing, health literacy, tribal communities, SC/ST/OBC, East Medinipur, out-of-pocket expenditure, gender comparison, regression analysis.  ','   Niranjan Kumar Mishra, Nabarun Sahu  ',' 272-284  ','YES','Dr Niranjan paper 2 with doi.pdf','International Transactions in Mathematical Sciences and Computer','99','162','2026-02-17 16:47:49','E',1,'nirkm1983@gmail.com',' Department of Mathematics, RKDF University Ranchi   ',' https://doi.org/10.58517/ITMSC.2025.18212','pending',NULL,NULL,'open',NULL),(1554,'<p>\r\n	Polluting behavior of small-scale industries in India</p>\r\n','<p class=\"Abstract\">\r\n	<span lang=\"EN-US\" style=\"font-size:10.0pt;line-height:150%\">Despite contributing significantly to output, employment, entrepreneurship, and exports, India&rsquo;s small-scale industries generate excess pollution in the same line of production where medium and large-scale units are relatively less polluting per unit of output produced. Widely dispersed small scale enterprises pollute air, water, agricultural fields and public drainage system in the neighboring areas with potentially harmful consequences. Some of these pollutants are highly toxic. This paper shows how excess pollution of the small-scale industries results from the intrinsic nature of the production process that this sector employs, the nature of the market that these industries cater to, logistic and financial hurdles that these small units operate within including the limitation of space and back-up infrastructure, inputs and technology used, human and skill factor, and waste disposal practices. The paper makes a reference to the polluting behavior of small-scale units operating in food processing industries, paper mills, tanneries, chemicals and pharmaceutical industries, hosiery units, foundries, battery recycling, glass manufacturing, brick manufacturing, cement, ceramic, asbestos, mining, cutting and polishing units. The paper concludes with a section on the anti-pollution regulation in India relevant to the small-scale sector and the challenges faced in enforcing the regulations in the context of development.<o:p></o:p></span></p>\r\n','<p>\r\n	1.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Agarwal, A. (2002). Water pollution problems posed by small industries: a case study of India and China. Water Sci Technol. 2002;45(8):47-52.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	2.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Anjanappa J., Climate Investment Advisory Group (CIAG), &amp; Tyche Investments. (2025).&nbsp;Decarbonising MSMEs in India; opportunities and challenges. SSRN.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	3.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bhanarkar, A.D., Gajghate, D.G., Hasan, M.Z. (2002). Assessment of air pollution from small scale industry. Environ Monit Assess. 80(2):125-33.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	4.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bailey, M. L., &amp; Mayes, K. (1996). Cleaner Production Case Studies. In Clean Production Environmental and Economic Perspectives (pp. 231&ndash;253).</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	5.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Central Pollution Control Board, Comprehensive Industry document-edible &amp; Vanaspati industry (1993-94).</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	6.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Agarwal, R. N., B. N. Goldar, and D. B. Gupta, Water pollution abatement and industrial growth: the case of Indian distilleries, paper presented in the workshop on &lsquo;Environmental policy and industrial development in India&rsquo;, Institute of Economic Growth, Delhi, January 1994.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	7.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Central Pollution Control Board, Parivesh, 1(3), Delhi, December 1994.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	8.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Government of India, DCSSI. (1997). Study of Energy Efficiency Gaps &amp; Potential for Energy Conservation in Small Scale Ceramic Tableware Units.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	9.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Government of India, Ministry of Science and Technology (1994), Technology in Indian water and effluent treatment plant and industry..</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	10.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bhardwaj, A., Kumar, S., Singh, D. (2023). Tannery effluent treatment and its environmental impact: a review of current practices and emerging technologies. Water Quality Research Journal, 58(2), 128&ndash;152.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	11.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Central Pollution Control Board, Pesticides industry: status, Delhi, 1993.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	12.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Central Pollution Control Board, Waste water management in pesticides industry, Delhi, 1993-94.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	13.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Johnson, P.A. (1995). Agricultural and pharmaceutical chemicals. In: Kirkwood, R.C., Longley, A.J. (eds) Clean Technology and the Environment. Springer, Dordrecht.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	14.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Bhasi, A.B., Gurtoo, A., Shouri, P.V., Zakkariya, K.A. (2014). Regulatory compliance motivated manufacturing issues in Indian small and medium scale pharmaceutical enterprises,&rsquo; International Journal of Research in Business and Technology, Techmind Research. 5 (1), 564-569.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	15.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kotwani, A., Kapur, A., Chauhan, M., Gandra, S. (2023). Treatment and disposal practices of pharmaceutical effluent containing potential antibiotic residues in two states in India and perceptions of various stakeholders on contribution of pharmaceutical effluent to antimicrobial resistance: a qualitative study. Journal of Pharmaceutical Policy and Practice, 16(1), 59.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	16.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Tay, JH. (1996). Cleaner Production for Electroplating Industry. In: Misra, K.B. (eds) Clean Production. Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg.Centre for Science and Environment, &lsquo;Economic powerhouse, but pollution potential barely accounted for &ndash; CSE puts the spotlight on India&rsquo;s small and medium scale industries,&rsquo; workshop report, press releases, May 27, 2022, New Delhi, cseindia.org.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	17.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Adam, W. (1994). Lead astray: the poisonous lead battery waste tread,&rsquo; Industry and Environment, UNEP, France.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	18.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Government of India, DCSSI. (1997). Study of Energy Efficiency Gaps &amp; Potential for Energy Conservation in Small Scale Ceramic Glassware Production Units.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	19.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Central Pollution Control Board (1995). Comprehensive industry document &ndash; ceramic industry, Delhi.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	20.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Central Pollution Control Board (1992). Comprehensive industry document on lime kilns, Delhi.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	21.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; National Institute of Small Industry Training (1996). All India study on ice cream industry, Hyderabad.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	22.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Ghumra, D. P., Agarkoti, C., Gogate, P. R. (2021). Improvements in effluent treatment technologies in Common Effluent Treatment Plants (CETPs): Review and recent advances. Process Safety and Environmental Protection, 147, 1018&ndash;1051. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.psep.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	23.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Pandey, R., Deb, S. (2006). CETPs and pollution control in small scale industry in India. The Indian Economic Journal, 54(3), 152&ndash;171.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	24.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dasgupta, N. (2000). Environmental Enforcement and small Industries in India: Reworking the problem in the poverty context. World Development, 28(5), 945&ndash;967.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	25.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Dasgupta, N. (2000). Policy implications for environmental improvements in India&#39;s SSIs. Small Enterprise Development. 11. 15-27.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	26.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kumar, P (2019). Environmental Practices in Small and Medium Size Enterprises in India.</p>\r\n<p>\r\n	27.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; Kumar, V. (2022